text: the aroma is of peat , caramel , nuts , and chocolate . i really like the uniqueness of this aroma . the taste has more caramel than the aroma . overall , this is a really , really good scotch ale .  the only thing slightly disappointing about this beer for me was the mouthfeel seemed a bit watery .

even the airy foam atop this beer has pungent , dry , fruity hop characteristics.. as i find out as my nose and lips accidentally come in contact with the crown . aroma pleases with juicy hop aromas.. not overwhelming and no alcohol detectable . a nice brown sugary malt presence here balances.. unexpected but nice . some apple aromas as well as something spicy like yeast .  it had a light feel on the palate with mild carbonation .

summit horizon red : a : appearance is exceptional , great amber-red color to it with exceptional clarity ! nice 1 '' head that develops yet depletes half-way through .  thin mouthfeel , this is the achilles heel of the beer .
a : dark cloudy copper body with two fingers of off white head . good retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is ok. fairly light body , more than i 'd think it should be at this abv .

filled growler at whole foods - dfh snifter pours amazing , heavy looking brew with a nice fat head .  a- blackness with a espresso colored head s- coffee beans ground soaked in licorice coffee and dark chocolate really bold t- straight up coffee and espresso with bitter chocolate and a slight tang finish m- medium carbonation and a bit watery for the style d- i drink 3 cup of coffee a day who am i to judge ?

) aug. 15 2008 @ hop cat ba / brewery grand opening event , served in tulip glass . opaque black , creamy tan head , beautiful bubble suspension after pour , wow ! looks thick smells of roasty heavy malts , dark fruit , smooth and creamy , mmm taste is of thick heavy bitter chocolate , hot alcohol , rich and smooth , compared to keg this is way mellowed , not as harsh and easier to drink , amazing ! , raisins , chocolate , slight coffee , earthy peat , mm mouthfeel is oily slick , smooth , creamy , viscous , a sipper for sure - delicious !  this is almost as good a stout as they come . i like guinness extra stout better because it has more bitterness . but this stout is smooth and easy to drink with a nice bitterness . if you are looking for a stout to bring to a party this is a good one because it is not too bitter . almost everyone i have served this to has liked it .

pours out a rich and dark amber/auburn colour with a big eggshell white head that is big and frothy and has staying power .  tastefully good as well.with the same taste of chocolate milk with a hint of hops and lots of malt.i could have this one for breakfast lunch , and dinner.what ya mean i 'm a raging alcholic.i beg your pardon.this is one tasty beverage , one that will put a smile on your face all day long .

served from bottle into a duvel tulip glass this beers appearance is highly impressive .  smell is of old corn/rice and skunk . pew . taste was horrendous . a skunky malt liquor flavor mixed with sweet rice/corn adjunct . maybe it went bad on it 's journey from the carib-bean ? looks like i should have gone for the sam light that was also in the fridge ...

very poor and lazy design with 3ded fonts . extraordinary head towering above the glass , great retention , surface memory , and frothy lacing .  the mouthfeel is just average . also , carbonation is lacking enough to make this feel sticky .

this brew pours with a deep amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing .  the rye is evident , as is a tangy almost sour note along with the bread . a little over-carbonated ... i found it slightly distracting and that it may have affected my enjoyment of the beer 's complexity . light-bodied and very refreshing . while i have little to no experience with beers of this style , i enjoyed this one and i believe that its a great refresher during the summer months .

a big fluffy tan head with good retention looks quite nice . some nice lacing is left and the head is very persistent . good looking pint .  m : slick mouthfeel with a medium amount of carbonation that can be prickly at times . body is medium and has a bit of resiny stickiness to it .

the nose is extremely complex -- clay soil , caramel , butter , farmland , and fresh aromatic hops are all in there , along with some more elusive intangibles that are conjuring up all sorts of images of rural europe for me . on the tongue , the caramel sings out with a spritzy edge , the hops keep it interesting , and the butter moves to the forefront , but what really does it for me is a slight sour twist towards the end -- reminiscent of those flemish ales that ive recently fallen in love with ( such as duchesse de bourgogne ) . this says to me , `` drink with food !  mouthfeel is perhaps a bit thin for the style but not bad .

smell : strong coffee , roasted malt , sweet molasses , and some sweet dark berry aroma at the end . very small amount of alcohol towards the end .  m : the feel is slightly creamy but on the lighter side of medium bodied . could be a bit thicker here ... d : if you like coffee beers i could see someone drinking good amount of these .

original rating date : october 19 , 2008 pours dark copper , thick , creamy head . strong lacing down the glass .  this is a great beer . the aromas are sweet and malty , with hints of caramel and vanilla . this beer has a nice , smoky flavor with hints of toffee and vanilla . this will definitely be going on my `` favorite beers '' list .

smells amazing . chocolate and some buttery , boozy notes emerge with warming .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . flavor is a hospital antiseptic . said to be an ipa , i understand pigs fly too . looks bad , smells bad , tastes worse , higher abv is hidden . waaay overpriced at $ 10.45 for a 330ml bottle from colonial spirits acton , ma .

aroma is a big mix of roasted grain , alcohol , malt sweetness , slightly burnt toast , coffee , chocolate , raisin , and cigar tobacco . unfortunately this did n't taste as good as it smelled . my expectations were raised by the aroma and then i felt a little left down as i did n't get the same complexity on my tongue .  carbonation a little higher than i expect in the style but still manages to be exceptionally drinkable .

hard pour gets a beautiful head to rise up , just a little more than two fingers worth of off-white frothiness . smells phenomenal . a bouquet of citrus hops , with a little bit of floral and maybe piney for good measure . so nicely balanced , just a little bit of bitter and the rest is flavor . the alcohol would probably catch me a buzz after just a couple , but it certainly weighs in a little lower than some comparable ipas , which is nice .  drinkability : mouthfeel is a little thin , but this is a very solidly crafted stout , up there with the tops in style .

appearance : pours a crystal clear dark orange color with a huge 3 '' + fluffy head that lasts a long time .  not too complicated , but a pleasant experience overall . goes down quite easily ( in part because of the low carbonation ) .
smell is piney , citrus , caramel , spices , very nice , reminds me of the holidays , neat cinnamon-hop aroma .  the mouthfeel is less crisp then i had hoped .
fruity nose classic ipa ( not the barleywine as is sometimes said ) .  medium bodied , highly carbonated .

sm : brilliant mix of cream , coffee , chocolate , and nuts . a light strength aroma . rich and complex . the alcohol does come through unfortunately , which jabs into the otherwise well-executed balance . it 's quite well built , though i do n't think its abv is warranted .  m-medium bodied with slightly more carbonation than i prefer in a porter .

deep , dark , almost black in color , pours thick with a thin thick foam .  medium bodied , it seems a little flat at the beginning , but there 's sharp carbonation at the finish , which is a little watery and silty .

pours into my new belgium globe with very dark brown body that looks almost black in the glass . thick creamy tan head tops the beer and looks stable enough to stick around for the duration .  slightly sour , a bit thin , highly carbonated . quite drinkable .
clear reddish amber with a rich firm tan head .  m -- light carbonation . good body with a lightly soft mouthfeel .

had this out of a bottle poured into a snifter ... a : jet black with a very small head , decent lacing ... s/t : smells and tastes like creme brulee .  it seems to light and over carbonated for a stout .

it pours with a clear amber body topped by a medium thick off white head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass .  thin on mouthfeel medium orangish-amber with a 1 finger offwhite head that leaves a respectable amount of lacing . taste : broad caramel maltiness with a warming alcohol changes over to a restrained english hop bitterness . notes : a nice esb , although the abv is much higher than say , honker 's ale . drinkability ranks fairly high but the alcohol content is above that of a session beer .

color was a little hard to see as it was fairly dark in the bar but appeared to be a very deep red , that while really dark was no opaque . slightly off-white head that left excellent lacing on the glass . not sure if it was the branded oversized wine glass or what but this was probably the second best looking beer i 've ever seen .  mouthfeel was slightly thin with a very tasty caramel taste on the tongue . the finish was semi-sweet , slightly dry , very nice for the style .

the aroma is a beautiful butterscotch malt and caramel experience , like candied hops . there is a hint of some apple but all in all i would say this smells more inviting than it tastes .  a little thin , flavors do n't linger or expand much .

pour was exceptional . the head rose faster than expected , and shot over the top of the mug - but it did n't overflow .  light bodied though , almost watery . in a way this is an ipa-light - some similar desirable flavors and aromas , but less bitterness , less alcohol , and lighter bodied .
comes out of the tap looking brown and alive . absolutely perfect lacing . one of the best looking beers i 've ever had the pleasure of admiring .  mouf & gt ; meh . okay . average .
nutmeg , cinnamon . enjoyed !  mouthfeel is light and carbonation fades to almost flat .

wow , the smell is the absolute best part of this brew - strong on the citrus . when first tasting dreadnaught , i picked up more piney hop taste than the smell indicates . the more i drank , however , the citrus hop flavor came through . i paid $ 8.99 for this bomber and it was worth it ( although pricey for an everyday beer ) .  body was very light and thin .

smell is exactly what you 'd expect , with a strong earthy espressor aroma and some chocolate notes , with a bit of sweet maltiness in there .  i found the body to be a bit thin carbonation medium to low .
the pour is absolutely beautiful on this one .  it 's light on body , and not especially interesting - but as fruit beers go , this was excellent .
pours a beautiful light honey color , having little to no head kept it from getting a better score .  the body was medium to medium light .

the smell is great , roasted barley , choc , some hints of caramel , delicious . taste is fantastic .  the mouthfeel was the only thing that detracted from the beer in my opinion , as i found it to be a little to watery for my personal preference .
on draft , served in a tulip glass . a : pours very dark , almost pitch black with a nice tan head .  m - a little watery for the style , but not objectionable .

it left a medium brown head of about an inch that quickly receded to surface skim , and thick , but ephemeral lacing . i know everyone says it 's black , but it 's really the darkest shade of brown possible ( you can see this in bright light ) , and opaque ( even in bright light ) .  the only thing i felt was it could use a little more carbonation to balance the tart flavor and make it more perky .

it pours a pretty red color , crystal clear , slightly malty nose & it has a smooth taste .  not too complex- makes for easy drinking , as does its texture . carbonation level seems low , though as an earlier commenter noted , it is actually just very fine .

poured a dark golden orange to light amber in the glass ... yes , almost the color of the jewel amber . lots of beautiful bubbles in the pour reminding me of a guinness that end up creating a full 2 finger craggy beige head that melts to sticky lace .  though this is a red ale of stormy garnet and the menu states it is `` brewed with 20 % honey malts for a touch of sourness '' ( honey = sourness ? it is not merely that this red ale tastes bad ; it is absolutely offensive . of the lowest evolutionary order . the entire beer is corrupted by spoilage and should n't be served publicly .

smell is amazing ! you can pick out both beers , which is the goal of black and tans . prism hits the nail on the head , because in the beer , you can pick out the lemony hops of the pale ale and it goes very well with the licorice aroma of the porter . carbonation is right on , not too much , and at a very natural level . it brings something else to the table , and yet it works for the style .  this beer was skunky ... skunky like a becks . and i couldnt find any other component of this beer redeeming enough to get over that skunkyness . my encounter with this beer started out ok ... it has a pale yellow appearance with a medium amount of head . taste exhibited becks ( or maybe even becks light ) levels of skunkitude , again with a bit of clove chasing after it to apologize . definitely not recommended .

this brew pours a small head of dark brown colored bubbles and an opaque black brown colored body .  m : medium to light body with medium to low carbonation . would have preferred a bigger body by far .

stunning appearance . pours a clear reddish brown with a big and tight tan head .  average feel for the genre i 'd say . it 's pleasant in sips and gulps and a few of em would be just as enjoyable as one .
frothy tan head .  m - the mouthfeel is a little light , with little carbonation .

overall , a seemingly pleasant ipa , that tastes wonderful at first , but then bites back too hard and dies flowery . still pleasant on the nose and eyes and foretaste though .  m- thin and smooth with almost not carbonation feel . kind of has the texture of a flat soda .
enjoyed from snifters and beer a gift from the brewer himself ... ap : deep dark body , roasted brown head , awesome retention .  m - a little on the thin side .
very sticky and lacing all the way down the glass . looks fantastic .  m- light in body and light to medium in carbonation .
black with a glorious creamy beige head with great retention and lacing .  medium bodied and a bit sticky in the mouth .
clear brown color with a strong pillowy off-white head .  mouthfeel : thin body and medium carbonation overall : a nice geuze , a bit too watery for my liking though .
beautiful ruby red color .  mouthfeel is a bit light , to me , for the style , though it seems appropriate for the flavors that this beer brings to the palate .
aroma : incredibly aromatic , rich bitter chocolate , fresh roasted coffee beans , smoked oak chips , burnt caramel , woody .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

pours a sparkling orange tinged gold , topped with a huge four finger pillowy white head , constant streams of carbonation bubbles , leaves thick puffy webs of lacing .  thin bodied , and just sufficient carbonation , but i suspect the growler is at fault much more than the beer .
dark , dark brown body sits below two generous fingers of frothy tan head that lingers until the very end of the glass .  m honestly its way too light of a mouthfeel .
looks really viscous and is extremely dark . excellent cascading head .  a little too thick on the tongue , but nice .

bright transparent golden hue with a two inch frothy white head . lots of bubbles and good lacing . perfect appearance .  the mouthfeel has average carbonation and ismedium bodied yet feels a bit thin at the same time , as it falls off the toungue quite quickly .
terrific lacing up the glass !  mouthfeel is sticky-sweet and dense .

lovely scarlet/violet color . perfectly clear . nice big bubble , white foam on top .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with likely carbonation . that , and the over carbonated pour make this beer a something i would not recommend .

a big , thick , creamy , dark-tan head forms on top of an opaque black body .  a fairly light bodied beer with near champagne carbonation ... a bit too much for me , although i know many like this in their wild ales .
light copper with a thick , mousse-like , sticky-as-hell head .  mouthfeel is pretty average , as is the smell ... i ca n't think of anything distinctive about these characteristics .

330 ml bottle , a : pours golden orange with an extremely long lasting rocky white head with nice belgian lace .  lighter body than i thought it would be with with very low carbonation..the weakest point of the brew . easy drinker for the abv and ignoring the mouth feel , a nice brew .

big aroma full of treacle , vanilla , oak , and hints of raisins and bourbon . an acquired taste , but very good .  the body is thin and slightly anemic . a little more carbonation and body would carry this really unique beer into the stratosphere .

12 oz bottle cloudy , dull golden amber color with a massive , creamy light brown/off white head . very dense and foamy , the head hangs around forever and leaves a lot of lacing .  a bit thin , but a very good stout flavor develops in the mouth . i 'd have preferred a bit fuller body .
very nice and clean aroma , even with the `` funk '' .  the mouthfeel was thin with a slightly dry aftertaste .
put it under bright light and it looks magnificent in my flute !  body is a little thin .
pours a copper/red color , nice big fluffy head to it that sticks around with a lot of lacing .  mouthfeel : pretty thick and a little syrupy . i 'd actually like a little more carbonation .
a - dark ruby with tan head . gorgeous lacing .  the taste is fantastic , but the beer is a little thin and a bit hot ; not a good session beer , but great type of brew to have after a long day .

pours a thin layer of dark tan head over a crystal clear gorgeous dark amber liquid .  this beer was purchased at cyclone liquors , in ames , iowa . the beer was very dark in color and tasted very well . i drank the beer warm and i think it was a good beer . i would try this beer again if it was presented to me . it had a very nice sweet taste for a german dunkel , which i am not a huge fan of .
wish this tasted half as good as it smelled .  mouthfeel is rather thin and average .

poured into a pint glass , this turned out to be a really beautiful beer . it was an amber color with a thick off-white head that persisted throughout the time it took me to drink the beer . there was an amazing amount of lacing .  too carbonated , the mouthful of liquid seems to almost crumble right away .

s - smelled like delicious spiced pumpkin pie with clove and spiced apple undertones . this is an excellent beer .  m : i feel that this could have used a little more body and less carbonation , but overall ... not bad .

appeared orange-golden with a monstrous , and i mean monstrous , frothy head and excellent lace retention . this is a beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel - a bit too carbonated which overrides the wonderful taste at first .
it settles slowly in a dramatically lumpy fashion leaving a tremendous amount of chunky and webby lace .  mouthfeel is grainy and oily , body is medium to thin , carbonation is sharp .

s - i really like the nose on this one a lot . healty dose of peppercorn with some complimentary citrus , something i usually do n't go for . the winner is a great hot chili burn on the backend of the nose from the chili pepper . really excited to try this one .  m light body for the style , but not unpleasant .

a- nice burnt orange coloring with a decent head and great lacing s- unbelievable aromas ... the tropical fruits are just amazing . you could mistake this for a glass of juice . t- kind of a letdown from the smell , but really the smell set the bar ridiculously high . this is definitely one of the better iipas i 've had the pleasure of tasting .  being from the adirondacks i quickly likened this to adirondack brewery 's bear naked ale , yet a lager version , and a bit more wheat-filled . the mouth-feel is nice , but nothing special ( not flat , not too bubbly ) . in short , its a dandy brew- we all enjoyed it and thought it was pretty cool to have something that is only currently available in growlers from the brewery ( spring seasonal ) , drink up !
looks like a ton of carbonation . golden , cloudy . great looking beer and i 'm excited to taste my first jolly pumpkin .  this one was surprisingly thin in body .
i love how the smell changes over time . got ta give 3f props for the phenomenal smell , tho .  the mouthfeel was medium with a syrupy sweetness on the palate .

appearance : clean , clear golden body . very nice looking .  the mouthfeel i found oddly watery ... but still fairly full bodied at the same time . carbonation was fairly mild - maybe that lended to the `` watery '' sensation .

pours an almost transparent golden/light copper with an amazingly fluffy 3 finger head from an extremely gentle pour .  m : full bodied and creamy , the slightest touch of carbonation and a smooth , somewhat watery finish .

( s ) - very aromatic . very dynamic & layered . again , a good taste that followed suit to the smell . great aroma . lends itself more to a better drinkability score due to a lower abv than alot of strong ales out there ; thicker than most too , but it fits it well . this might benefit from further aging , but its great now .  good carbonation , which i appreciate . minimal complexity to this beer .

appearance : very dark , as the name would suggest ... but some brown tinge . quite a nice head , with moderate retention and nice lace .  m. thin to medium body with a somewhat biting carbonation . ends fairly dry .

aroma is great . i really get a spicy sage aroma on this one . a sweetness from the herbal notes really plays perfect with this one . really a perfect nose . taste is spot on too .  hate to say it , but the bottle/case i have is absolutely awful . other than a hint of coriander spice all i got was an overwelming sourness that made this one of the few i had to pour down the drain . they obviously put wayyy too much orange peel in their mix . if you can get past the sourness it is par for a wit bier course . i 'm hoping this was a bad/expired batch because ... .as far as mill street goes imo , stick to the coffee porter ...

guinness looks wonderful . poured into a glass , it 's pitch black but has dark ruby edges in the right light .  it was pretty smooth for stout and for for the alcohol content . i tried it with a few other beers .

a : pours a clear copper/amber with two fingers worth of creamy off white head . it had a great cascading effect during the pour , so much that it looked like a nitro can pour .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with thankfully a burst of carbonation near the end , making it a little less watery than it initially presents itself to be .

a - poured a slightly hazy amber-straw color , with a big , fluffy , two-finger head . took several minutes to dry down to a thick cap , which left nice rings of lacing down the glass . very pretty .  the mouthfeel is thinner when compared with other stouts , merely decent .
looked great on the pour . hazy apricot with a thin wispy head .  low carbonation . a bit coating , but not to syrupy/thick .

big foamy head , a mix of burnt malt and thick coconut in the aroma & # 8230 ; very aromatic . nice clash of burnt malt that strays to slightly to the acidic side and the mild sweetness of the toasted coconut . very interesting and yet another beer i wish i had with dessert though this would have been better with the sweet potato pie .  mouth feel is sharp and crisp , with a high carbonation level .

i love the smell of this stuff , there is n't a better smelling stout in the world , even if its from a can .  perhaps a bit thin for the style , which i suppose makes it a good pale ale for summertime quaffing .

the bourbon alcohol flavors are too over-powering in this beer . i 've tried at least three bourbon cask aged stouts and this is by far the worst one . atlanta brewing company created a delicious bourbon cask aged stout a couple of years ago , as a 15th anniversary celebration . brooklyn brewery 's black ops , is excellent . each previous example had sophisticated accents of roasted barley , toasted caramel and light chocolate , which blended perfectly with the , just above subtle , flavors of delicious bourbon . the boris , tastes like a slightly acidic stout , where someone poured and mixed bourbon , directly into the glass of beer .  slinky and a little thin , but ok .

huge off white head eventually settling to a half inch and tons of thick lacing . strong steady carbonation , perfection for this strong style considering lasting head on a barleywine is a rare happening .  it pains me to trash a beer , but this brewery needs a swift kick in the pants . i ordered this to give the brewery a second chance , since the white cloud ale i had the day before was patently awful . after a couple sips , i took it back to the bar and told the bartender , saying i wanted to try the local beer , but could n't drink it . no lager is intended to be a sour beer . he added that it 's sort of an acquired taste , but happily replaced it with a real beer . i could n't finish either of these sour beers ( and not like it 's brewed intentionally with brett ) . whoever the new guy is , he needs to clean up the brewery and get back to basics with brewing .

poured from a 12oz bottle , into a 16oz glass mug , color was a beautiful hazy golden , with a huge 3 finger+ fluffy head .  mouthfeel : i 've always thought this was a little off ... not quite enough spine to offset the sweetness .

a - black brew with two fingers of frothy light brown head . lacing is pretty thick in decent rings .  i could drink this one all night long . just the right amount of sweetness with a little more than expected carbonation . pale yellow in color , lemony aroma.very clean with little aftertaste . easy to drink and very enjoyable . will definately drink again .

appearance/pour : nice dark amber with a surprising stream of carbonation rising from the glass bottom etch . head which dissapates to a nice ring with small foamy clusters . thick lacing and a dense sound while pouring- sounds thick .  m & # 8211 ; thin , refreshing , light , plentiful , smooth carbonation .

and lists it as a strong pale ale aroma : grapefruit flowers on a sugary base . mouthfeel : medium body , a bit oily overall impression : nice and easy , a bit boring maybe , but thats more about me than the beer .  the beer feels just a bit thin on the tongue .

great pour , huge amount of foam , thins out to lace the outer edge of the beer . dark brown in color , yet the beer itself is light , meaning not as thick as you would expect it .  mouthfeel : a little slick , thinner on the palate than i expected drinkability : a fine porter , would definitely drink again .

a : pours a beautiful bronze with ruby highlights . this beer looks fantastic . s : smell is of juicy citrusy hops , with an abundant dose of pale and caramel malt .  body is on the thin side of medium and the finish is both mildly astringent and slightly bitter .

pours a deep black with a tan head .  mouthfeel is a little thin and alcoholic with low carbonation . overall this beer has a nice balance of flavours but i feel the barrel presence is a little bit too subtle and the mouthfeel a bit too thin to prevent a higher score .

citrus hops dominates the smell . citrus and pine are the taste that stick out . a good beer but there are so many better ipa 's out there .  mf : the carbonation is n't quite as spritzy as i would hope to go along with the huge sourness , the body is light d : this is a great lambic .

aroma is very hoppy . mainly floral hops . taste was not as bitter and flavorful as i was expecting , based on the smell . the floral hops and honey are present as well as some citrus fruits . overall , i was a lot more impressed by the smell of this beer as compared to the taste .  m- low carbonation , medium-body .

aromas were the strong point for this drink . deep blackberry aromas mixed with bready , wheaty textures . although nice and light for a summery day , its strong blackberry taste ( albeit weaker in comparison to the blackberry smell ) did not really make this too refreshing or crisp .  the beer is somewhat oxidized , but still highly drinkable very light bodied bitter , true to the the style . this is a prime candidate for a session beer . at 3.8 % abv , it 's alcohol content makes this a clear choice for something that could literally be consumed all day long , starting with your pancakes !

pours a deep dark brown with three fingers of khaki head .  mouthfeel - this seems a bit watery for my liking , and a bit light too , it does n't take away from the beer too much though luckily , still great . the carbonation seems pretty good , maybe a bit overcarbonated .

a : pours a clear golden with a massive frothy , rocky head with great sustain .  m - not as thick as i 'd like it to taste considering how rich the smell is . d - very drinkable , with the lighter mouthfeel it 's easier to forget how much you 've had .

appearance- beer pours clear and golden with a half finger of creamy white head with ample lacing on the sides of the glass . carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as if this were a pilsner . very nice on looks at least .  m- seems a little thin , but nicely carbonated .

very dark brown with garnet highlights and a giant , fluffy , dark tan cap .  the carbonation is unfortunately at a distracting level , but the feel is strong enough otherwise to not hurt too much overall .
this is one attractive looking beer . clear amber color with little carbonation .  pretty average mouthfeel overall .

poured from a 550ml bottle into a weisse glass . a : this is really interesting . thick , creamy , almost beige head that disipates slowly and good stickiness . the color is red when held to the light , but almost a chocolate brown away from direct light .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is light , as is the body .

a viscous pour and a deep black color , on top a beige head which collapses almost instantly . one of the most beautiful beers i came across .  very light bodied , but carbonation seems too low to me .
very pleasant complexity that is worth lingering over .  the carbonation is moderate high . i think it is a bit high for the style but the carbonation does not take anything away from the beer .

appearance : black as the abyssal depths topped by a hearty dark brown head that 's thick , frothy and slightly rocky . it sticks around for quite some time before settling down to a smallish layer of foam and then finally a ring of bubbles .  in my opinion , flying dog brewery has created a great seasonal , smooth-tasting beer with very little bite or after taste . i would definitely recommend it to any self-respecting beer drinker who might be having an end-of-summer party this or any october .

a truly profound smell . has all the plums and figs of a dickens novel .  good carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is spicy , yeasty , hints of sweetness that gets buried by the yeast . lingering yeasty aftertaste .

crisp . ( t ) - has a rather tart profile with some serious pineapple & grapefruit citrus up front . ( m ) - a tad higher carbonation level than you would expect from the style , but it really is not too bothersome . really crisp because of it though , with really potent citrus .  m : flat , slick , and that 's it . not quite watery , but pretty close .

there is the overpowering scent of nutmeg , cinnamon and some other christmas seasonings . the taste is about what you would expect from the smell . the cinnamon and the nutmeg dominate so much that it almost fails to taste like a beer .  it was a little thin .

a - pours a gorgeous bright and translucent dark copper color with some nice golden and slight amber hints . very good retention . almost perfect looking beer .  3.0 m : medium body . smooth , but not creamy .

a - black with a huge coffee colored head s - smells delicious - very sweet , chocolate malts . the most balanced smell to a stout i have had the pleasure of knowing .  mouthfeel : both the carbonation and body are on the higher end of the light range .

pours a murky brown/dark copper with brighter highlights when held to the light . a three-finger sticky and frothy tan head crests the top of my tulip glass , but stays together . the head lasts a long time and leaves thick sheets behind .  mouthfeel is quite viscous , with not a lot of texture . feels full and a bit flat . could use more carbonation to cut through the smokey flavour more .
pours a gorgeous dark caramel in the glass , with a nice thick tan head .  m : feels alright . average .

pours a light amber color with a massive bright white head that just keeps growing and growing , the lace on this beer is incredible it coats the entire glass . gorgeous looking beer .  my first tripel style beer , i spit it on my counter . the flavors of fruit combined with a bitter aftertaste left one bottle down the drain , and three still sitting in their case . anyone near me is welcome to the other three . while i am confident in the quality of this product , this style is definitely not for me .
smell has a great malty dark fig aroma . very warm smell . taste is also very malty .  the drawback on this beer is the carbonation - it 's too heavy . sparkly but with a nice dryness in the finish .

in honor of the black wych appearance - dark . black . dark as the light on a moonless night .  the nose is caramely and very malty . a little too carbinated for a traditional barleywine but lines ones gut like the best of the bunch ! being a sucker for barleywines i have to give this beer high remarks .

this beer sure looks good , but it sure aint of me . stone ris pours an oily thick pitch black witha huge brown head . as the head disapates , it leave so great lacing .  body is light and the carbonation is lively , a bit too much for my preferences .

it pours a beautiful clear coppery-brown with just a little head .  but there are hints of dark fruits that seem to disintegrate on your tongue , slight astringent alcohol tate/smelll this is defiantly a very drinkable brew .

the pour is ebony in color , the head inconsequential in size , the structure patchy clumps of large bubbles , the color a light chocolate .  while the champagne-like extreme dryness may put off some , i think it makes the beer truly unique and tasty as opposed to unblanced .

the overall aroma is pretty sweet smelling and i enjoy just the smell of it . did i mention this smells really good ? taste - scotch flavor with a malty flavor to it . overall - it 's a beer that smells better than it tastes .  and this is a surprisingly warming , earthy-tasting beverage for a `` summer ale '' -- i would n't mind opening up one of these in midwinter either , except in that it lacks body . it 's in the mouthfeel that the summeriness stands out .

the most delicate looking head i 've ever seen , pillowy and white , thick and longlasting . beautiful .  medium bodied with carbonation that was a little too high and too coarse for my liking , but it did n't turn me off completely . my only issue was the carbonation .

pours a dark brown with hints of red at the edges , crackling four finger light tan head settles to a finger tall , and remains all the way through , leaves temporary sheets of lacing that fade ( probably due to the abv ) .  the mouthfeel was a little on the watery side but i did n't feel like it ruined the experience .

a- body is a nearly transparent dark copper hue that is served with the perfect 1/2 finger foamy white head . the head has perfect retention the whole way down the glass .  m - a little thin-bodied and watery and a little low on the carbonation .

smell takes a little while to come out but once it starts to warm and the head retention leaves it 's very pleasant . initial blast of earthy hops matched with an almost smokey characteristic and roasted malts w/ fennel seed .  ran into the maui brewing company while killing time until our dinner reservations were ready . there was a very slight bitterness in the aftertaste but was well hidden in the passion fruit sweetness . found the beer to start like any average golden ale but the aftertaste was what i really liked about it sorta like an ice tea aftertaste .

pours a beautiful hazy light orange with a frothy white head that leaves droopy horizontal strips of lacing down the sides .  the beer seems to thin a bit in the mouthfeel . very clean beer for a triple , slightly thin in the mouthfeel , but that helps give this beer a nice clean dry finish .
poured a dark mahogany with a big light brown head that left some lacing .  lowish carbonation and a slightly thin mouthfeel .

s - the nose on this one is as good as it gets . t - just wonderful - almost as perfect as the nose . this outstanding beer 's only downfall . d - great . tons of booze and heat on this one , but the outstanding vanilla and coconut flavors allow me to drink as much of this as is available !  toward the end of the drink , the beer felt almost flat .
pours dark , great head , and it retains it thru the glass .  smooth and to the point , bit of a sweet aftertaste in the sweet sticky beer way .
pours copper hue , with a nice , long lasting , white head and lively carbonation .  light , decently carbonated , and quenching for the desert dweller .
outstanding imo . a : normal , yellowish/orange .  it also takes a hit because while it looks thick , it feels a bit thinner than it should be .
pours a fascinating brownish black with little foam . very appealing to the eyes .  m : thinner and crisper .

a : thick and black , dark almond head ( more like a thin disk of residual bubbles ) s : strong note of alcohol , bitter dark chocolate , coffee m : very alcoholic feel ; initial taste of a dark stout followed by the heat of a liquor akin to scotch .  m - this is the weakest part of the beer . medium body with a little too much carbonation .

a : black , opaque , with dense creamy tan head s : mild to medium nose , more spritzy carbonation than anything , slight roasted malt evident t : decent black saison , definite bubblegum and yeast taste , not as clean as i 'd like , somewhat metallic-sharp taste in body , almost reminds me of an average tasting extract homebrew m : medium bodied , good roasted malt but sharp , metallic bitter finish that makes it slightly unbalanced in taste o : not what i 'd expect from goose island for balance and representation of the style  the carbonation is nice throughout . thinner than expected also .

a - solid black brew that allowed not even the slightest bit of light to peep through ; medium brown head that was retained throughout the session and left a nice coat of lacing s - smell of alcohol was certainly present and the aroma was mostly that of whiskey , with a whiff of coffee scent t - the flavor profile was more balanced than the aroma suggested , with whiskey and coffee as the most prevalent characteristics , though there was a hint of chocolate m - smooth texture with a somewhat sticky finish d - overall easy drinker , but the whiskey flavor lingers a little too long as a result of the sticky finish .  the overall feel is dry , like it should be , but unfortunately , it 's also a touch chaulky , which is pretty unfortunate .
a - huge head , really fluffy . beautiful amber color with appealing haziness .  m-a bit watery for my tastes but the taste makes you forget about it being slightly thin .

s : great honey nose , the hops do n't get in the way , sweet herbal notes , some cinnamon . t : the honey notes are good , sweet malt with an earthy grassy hoppiness . nice flavour , but kind of obliterates the great honey taste .  mouthfeel : the body is oddly thin , and crisp .
apppearance was a dark black color with a medium frothy brown head that dissipates fully .  nothing special here .

i `` stole '' a proper beer glass in the hotel bar ... a : it pours yellow to golden with a large creamy head that leaves great lacings when it dissipates .  m- thin to medium in body . highly attenuated with a soft carbonation .
poured black , with a brown head .  medium bodied and dry .

11.2 oz bottle poured into duvel tulip a : perfect . billowing tan head barely contained in this glass . settles to leave full layer of fine tan lacing . as you sip the soft foam coats the side of the glass in sheets not patches .  4.5/5 m : crisp , medium body .
it pours a dark , coppery amber with a frothy , persistent , off-white head .  carbonation seems spot on .

very interesting bouqet-smells very much like a moscato d'asti frum the muscat grapes . also floral , sweet honeyed bready malts , and fresh ( not roasted ) nuts in the nose . medium to full-bodied and viscous , this could present a cloying sweetness after a while and as such is not a session beer , but definitely something unique and worth trying .  a malty mouthful without much carbonation . resiny flavors fill the mouth but do n't obscure the big malt . this one is quite drinkable with an interesting mix of flavors that rise out of the basic malty sweetness .

a - dark as night with amber hue creeping in with the light . thick head that lasts the entire time drinking it slowly and leaving very nice lacing .  nice floral hops and malt starchiness in the finish . it 's a drinkable beer . heavy in the stomach .

tasted june 25th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - deep copper , one finger off white head and some lacing s - lots of alcohol , very hoppy , pineapple , pine , grass , very yeasty , sweet malt , sugar , high octane everything , flowers , grass and tons of everything awesome t - really sweet up front and than a wall of bitter . this is a great ipa . i am starting to be a big fan of yulesmith final thought - 8 % + abv and only $ 7 a bottle . this one is worth it and if you find this on tap somewhere , please email me  mouthfeel was week and its not complex at all .

appearance : black like the back ground on this page smell : chocolate , coffee , malts and cookies taste : not as heavy as u think it would be taste like it smells butit is not a strong taste mouth : thin and creamy no carbanation drink : dont really like it that much i usualy only have one or two of these when i go out to eat .  mouf & gt ; nice , nothing special drinkability & gt ; sure thing

s- large amount of aromatics here ! strongly grapefruit in character , citrus of oranges and lemons behind that , notebook paper , and minute hops profile . t- the grapefruit is a tease . i prefer to smell it to be honest , but that wo n't last forever . the hops become distracting towards the middle , but it is no where near the annoyance of a hop bomb .  if you aerate the beer in your mouth , it really releases the co2 . it would do well as a beer to server with medium to strong cheese .

pours a pitch black , with a solid 3/4 inch head that has serious staying power .  a little lighter and less sweet than many `` real '' belgian beers , and a little thinner in the mouthfeel department .
black with a solid 1 finger tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was fine but that doesnt make up for much .

allspice cinnamon and nutmeg all very strong a beautiful smelling ! t-the spices hit upfront with an impressive strength .  m - crisp and bitey , high carbonation - the bottle overflowed when i opened it .

reviewed 11/16/2008 ( tap @ the stables , st. louis , mo ) : very cool presentation in a kasteel glass with a castle on the stem of the goblet-like glass . pours a very dark blood red body , with a lasting frothy pink head .  parching on the tongue . almost no flavor : slight sweetness up front , trace of bitterness on finish . really .
it pours clear ruddy amber with a very thick and creamy tan head .  light bodied .

the smell is very nice . lots of tropical fruit flavor on this one and sweet candy .  on tap this poured as a golden straw colored ale , clear and bright with less than an inch of head . there is an apparent hoppy aroma that followed with a similarly dominant slight-hoppy taste followed by the expected bitters - very tasty . i stopped with one . not to discount its drink-ability , there are just several others i wish to try .

pours a good-looking clear deeply copper colored ale with a tight off white head . very impressive head longevity and sheeting in the glass , this has incredible looks .  m_on the lighter side with a bit too much carbonation . the carbonation is along the lines of a tripel which is a bit too much for the style . d_the light body while a flaw style wise make this fairly easy to drink .
bottle holiday wine cellar escondido , ca black as can be with a thick , persistent light brown head . perfection !  m - a little thin , sickly-sweet finish .

strong dance of raspberries , prunes , blackberries , oranges , ribes . you feel it 's still young on the nose too . t : sour taste of raspberries .  fairly thin and smooth , mild to medium bodied . breckenridge definitely delivers a vanilla porter as i would expect a vanilla flavored porter to be . i suggest toning down the roasted barley and focusing more on bittering hops .

the duchesse . i liked the aroma - sour cherry , tart , musty . i hope it does n't pervade the taste .  mouthfeel can be too fizzy if you do n't make sure to pour high for tall head . when i 'm drinking more than one beer , this is my favorite second or third , as it 's got enough hops to satisfy , is not highly alcoholic , and sells for a real good price where i live .
absolutely fantastic aroma , but let down by it 's flavours .  m : not too bad , there was a little bit of body .

pours a brilliant copper ; a vigorous pour produces only a one-inch head but a nice , tight , foamy one .  the only thing that could be improved on this beer is the mouthfeel . a bit light for my tastes , but like i said it has incredible drinkability without making you get too full too quick .

pours pitch black into a snifter . the visual is as appetizing as it 's ever going to get for a stout .  actually thought it might be bad but when i drank it there was plenty of carbonation . smell : a toasted malty smell with an almost cardboard smell . taste : very strong toasted smell but more of a bitterness then a sweetness . note : no date on the bottle but wondering if this beer had gone bad . will try another attempt at it but not really looking forward to it .
nose presents juicy flavors of dried mango and apricot with a bit of citrus and rosewater .  lighter mouthfeel than expected . d - full flavor and light mouthfeel .
look is beautiful . perfect 1/2 inch head when poured carefully into a surly pint glass .  m - moderate carbonation , medium bodied .

this ipa is perfect specimen as far as appearance . it is a cloudy gold in color with a nice foamy long lasting head that sticks perfectly to the glass .  mouthfeel works just fine , but is a little watery . highly drinkable .

bottle pours a beautiful chestnut brown with a rich ruby hue . a small tan head fades to the edge of the glass . very unassuming aroma .  the huge head tipped me off and my first taste confirmed that this beer was infected . as a homebrewer , i 'm sure to sample every beer i brew before i give it to a friend . a little qc goes a long way .

a- body is a moderately pale amber hue that pours with a nice 2-3 finger foamy white head . body is uniformly translucent and has the head has great retention with lots of lacing left all the way down the glass .  mouthfeel is smooth , crisp and almost watery , with medium carbonation and a medium body .

s : the best component of this beer , gratifying spices on top of a light roasted malt . d : good smell and its light make for easy drinking , but i would prefer more commanding flavors and spices .  the mouthfeel was quite thin with a very fine and mild carbonation .

a : this is a very beautiful looking beer . the head is absolutely amazing , with perfect color and form . the color is a very dark brown or black , depending on how much light is on it .  m - light bodied , not overly carbonated , clean finish , mild fruity aftertaste fades quickly .

pours a beautiful light honey color . have n't seen a pale lager with such nice color .  nice chewy mouthfeel , but significantly under-carbonated . the only thing it lacks is carbonation and a decent head .

there is also a nice toffee and molasses sweetness to keep the aroma balanced . there are also hints of dark berries : to me it smelled like blueberry and raspberry . it is a very enticing aroma . taste : more roasted glory , and the first sip was a shock of burnt bitterness ; the overpowering intensity , though , passed after a couple sips .  m : standard mouthfeel for a low alcohol ale .
very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel : medium and semi-smooth . bottom line : this is one of the most bland beers i 've ever had .

thick dense white head with great retention .  it states `` the deep coffee flavors are created naturally during the brewing process by dark roasted malts . '' then later it notes `` stout brewed with coffee . anyway , i 'll refer to this as a steady drinking stout because of its thinness , otherwise it 's pretty enjoyable . not particulary complex but enjoyable taste of roasted malt with coffee . abv seems pretty low as i had two with no noticable effects .
cloudy blonde coloring with good head retention and excellent lace on the glass .  the mouthfeel was medium bodied with adequate carbonation .

smells heavenly ! this thing is full of floral and citrus sharp hop notes . it smells of flowers , grapefruit , clementines , and there 's a little crystal malt and sweet cranberry which i think is a fusion of the malt and hop character .  it is light bodied and enjoyable . it has a light hops aroma and a light bodied feel to it .
i absolutely loved this bottle .  a watery texture and lighter body than i expected from the nose , with a moderate amount of carbonation .

this brew is really gorgeous . nice hint of red , obviously , but the cloudiness swirls around and give the beer a nice look . head is off-white and puffy ; almost too big even with a careful pour .  this is about my only complaint of this beer-too much carbonation ! carbonation gives a foamy/frothy mouthfeel .

appearance : beautiful murky caramel color with a hint of dried apricot . smell : amazing sweet english butter toffee with candied strawberries . very very rich and delicious . mouthfull : thick and smooth exceptional beer by another great quebec brewery .  overall , i quite enjoyed this beer . it 's got a fresh and interesting taste that makes it a decent drinking beer . deliciously fruity hops , nice malt sweetness , comes across as quite fresh . noticeable taste of apricots which i quite like makes this distinctive and something i look forward to drinking . disappointing finish however . lots of interesting things happening up front and then nada . nothing really lingers which is a darn shame , 'cause overall this beer is well worth a try . still tasty after each bottle . mmmm .
head is enormous and really nicely laces . retention is amazing .  mouthfeel is just a tad watery .

( a ) - pours a thick cloudy red mahogany color that actually briefly cascaded during the pour . left a giant foamy tan head that left tons of intricate lacing behind as it slowly dissipated .  long , super bitter piney bitterness , aftertaste almost of pine-sol but i love the hop attack . problem is that it 's too sweet and slightly syrupy , especially evident in the middle . a little harsh and unbalanced overall , big beer and it shows .

it had a wonderful , fruity , rich , creamy , almost cherry ice cream soda type of aroma.the first mouthful had a cherry , hoppytaste with a very smooth mouthfeel.then a very bitter backtaste made itself evident . definitely a slow sipping brew .  m - medium body , with moderate to high carbonation . a bit too carbonated for my liking . slightly thin , would like a bigger body from a stout . the mouthfeel is lacking , and sweet flavors of vanilla and chocolate make it too much like a dessert beer , one is all you need .
looks the part . `` glugged '' into my tulip glass and created a nice tight brown head that leaves lots of lace as i drink .  mouthfeel : body is light to medium and slightly watery .
a : huge three finger head , constant carbonation , brown oil color .  the mouthfeel is just a little light and watery .

poured this 12 ounce gem into a british pint glass and really enjoyed this smooth stout jet black appearance with 2 fingers of foamy tan colored head and retention ; this brew looks perfect , and staring at that glass rekindles an image of a british pub aroma of a sweet , biscuitty , and dark chocolate notes rich , full bodied , toasty malt , balanced with some hops which accentuate the side of my tongue , and a finish with a bit of zing that lingers on the palate .  the mouthfeel is a bit weird ; kind of a harshness on the tongue .

pours a clear amber , and a massive pillow of ivory capped this beauty . plenty of sheet lacing surrounds the volcano of head in the glass .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin and watery side though .
poured with a beautiful , thick , creamy huge , fluffy , tan head with brown highlights .  even with the earthy malt flavor , the overall feel stays on the thin side .

s : nice nose . lots of vanilla and caramel , with well integrated bourbon . this is about a 4.25 in the nose , but i 'm feeling generous . t : not as good . the second half of this beer is just unpleasant : hot , overly bitter , and astringent .  5/5 m : medium body and smooth . the lighter body makes it sit not-too-heavy , and it would be easy to partake of a few of these on a cold night .

appearance - nice copper color , cream colored head holds at a solid cap and laces quite well .  m : crisp and a very smooth , medium body , medium carbonation , finish is slightly sticky . tad too thin for my liking , but not too bad .

coffee dominates the nose and overpowers the other smells that are underneath . nevertheless , the smell is very enticing .  lightly bodied , perhaps overly so , with a passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

t : hugely ( and distractingly ) sweet . almost medicinal o : a very complex sipper of a beer that i found overly sweet . enjoyed the non-ba version much better .  m : hmmm . it may be a tad too aggressive with the carbonation .
beer pours black with a creamy brown head .  m : medium-bodied , creamy , resiny , thin finish .

smell is very sugary with a fruit and spice scent of apple butter . apple , cinnamon , clove , raisin , grape , figs , black pepper and sweet prunes are all in here . taste is drier than expected sweet but not very . good spice flavor that builds as you sip . the flavor just is n't anywhere as complex as the smell . mouthfeel is good nice drinkable belgian here that is worth a try , only problem is that there are lots better around .  m- the mouthfeel is a little lighter than expected , almost watered down .

n : cherry , honey , fig , banana , candy sugar , light funk , hints of cinnamon and perhaps some clove . o : nicely balanced and easy drinking . this makes a wonderful winter treat !  solid mouthfeel , nothing noteworthy , but nothing wrong with it .
poured from the bottle into a pint glass a - pours a brilliant off-white three finger head with great retention . leaves gorgeous lacing .  m- just average .

oz bottle poured into my pilsener glass pours a vibrant dark copper color with orange hues with a three inch slightly tan frothy head . great head retention that last throughout the beer and leaves very sticky soapy lacing clinging to the sides of my glass .  m : smooth on the palate .

very sharp and fruity hops , with a good amount of grapefruit and pineapple . the hops seem to disappear from the flavor , very surprising considering the aroma . the hops are more tea-like , sitting on top of a sweet bread-like malt base .  mouthfeel is a bit lacking . this is not a full-bodied beer , as i would prefer , but the carbonation level is to my liking for a barley wine drinkability is very good for a big beer .

a very complex and inviting aroma . the taste really follows the nose , with a sweet melange of spices careening across the tongue . it 's very complex , but unfortunately does n't smell quite as good as it tastes .  body is very thin for a dipa , medium carbonation .

perfect appearance . really smooth 2 finger ashy cocobutter brown head . dark black balled body that looks beautiful in my snifter .  m : surprisingly on the more carbonated side with a slight fizzy mouthfeel .

a- clear dark reddish copper hue with a billowy tan head that last forever and leaves tons of sticky lacing on the glass . edit : holy shit , this beer is so hoppy it turns your tongue yellow !  i first had this beer a year ago and fell in love . so i was excited to see it appear once again this fall . i find it a very easy beer to drink even for the inexperienced beer drinker . flavorful and rich with malts , a slight hint of hops towards the end . the aroma is sweet but not overpowering , you can definitely smell the sweet malt that went into this brew . i highly recommend this beer . unfortunately its not around year round but it definitely will give you something to look forward to come fall .

hard to imagine the being sweeter , loaded with caramel , chocolate , toffee , brown sugar , molasses , prune , fig , plum , cherry and apricot fruit , orange marmalade , bubblegum , candied nuts , on the hops side has pine and flowers , nothing too biting . in spite of this theres more room for more focused clove , ginger and pepper spice , quinine and earth . this forestalls the eventual onslaught of caramel , toffee , molasses , maple syrup , chocolate and so on , the orange to lemon citrus retains that syrupy and candied character . more yeastiness here with that bubblegum to banana touch . plum , fig , date , cherry , apricot , peach flavors , nice mix of darker and lighter fruits . booziness elevates as it warms , more rum notes and feels like it goes to your head faster . one glass is really all you need .  m : decent mouthfell , it has to have this considering how light it is .

oily , thick , jet black with the one finger reddish tan head expected from a russian imperial stout . head fades quickly with light lacing .  quite watery for the big flavor this one tastes and smells different from the main stream craft ipas , which is a pretty new category i 'll give it that .

beautiful red orange color . a tan head sits on top for a while . a very pretty beer . we tried it with some honey ham and then some apple pie and it was terrific with both .  a light- to moderate mouthfeel , hints of sour flavor linger at the back of the tongue after the swallow . i do n't pick up much of a hint of carbonation in the mouthfeel .
looks great with a two finger thick off white head , and has a nicely filtered copper colored body .  m : light body , watery touch , smooth with low carbonated in the mouth .

the aroma is out of this world . a very , very bready smell . heavy yeast and a cake-like aroma . immense . the taste is very strong carrot cake . pumpkin spice and brown sugar . hits the back of the tongue with authority . rich and bready , like a sugary cake .  the mouthfeel is just a touch too syrupy , though it does n't detract much at all from the enjoyment of the beer .

s : chocolate covered cherries , vanilla , mocha , amazing ! t : huge vanilla ( a little much for me ) , oak , bakers chocolate , mocha .  first sip reveals a much thinner body than i expected and average carbonation .

bottle poured into a dogfish head signature glass it pours clear copper color . a fluffy eggshell white head is very long lasting and intricate lacing across the glass .  m : the honey seems to add a little body to this , but other than that , just average .

smell : smells like a banana laffy taffy . also get some pumpkin spice aroma in there too .  this beer pours with a very pale yellow body topped by a medium thick head with some lacing left behind . not much flavor or aroma but more than you get from most light beers . the aroma was sour and bitter and the flavor was malty with a hint of bitter hoppiness .

it has a lovely roasted , woody aroma and the initial body is a full toasty , roasty malty assault that jumps quickly to a firm , dry bite and lingering hoppy finish . a beer like this is actually a good reason for my pessimism at another certain large brewer 's foreign extra reviewed in february , because this is what that could have been : firm , full and nuanced .  mouthfeel : a bit thin and watery .
d : nice big i.p.a. , best smelling i have had yet , very flavorful and the malt has been kept in check and the hops can come right through .  mouthfeel - smooth , yet a litle effervescent .

golden colored and pours a huge white fluffy head with good retention .  not too much that i can to the other reviews here . this beer was nothing but dissapointing . the label does say ipa right ? where are the hops ? i know that it does n't have to be a hop bomb but the flavor just is n't very good at all . i 've got 5 bottles left from this 6-pack . now i have to decide if i struggle though them or i just pour them out .
smell was amazing , coffee , toffee , bitter chocolate , sugar , fruit .  my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin .

the appearance was great ( and yes i know to pour 2/3 of the bottle , let it setle , then pour the rest ) but the flavor was just not up to par .  start is lightly sweet , the top skeletal in feel , the finish lightly carbonated , hops shy in their spiciness , a bit medicinal , dry aftertaste , quite drinkable but a touch different than my normal american over the top beers , and frankly scarlet i dont give a damn , im ready for a change .
overall , it sounded and smelled so good - just did n't taste good to me .  it has a medium body and a fair amount of carbonation , but again feels a bit weak .

pours a clear amber , nice thick white head forms , as it drops leaves some pretty epic lacing , settles to a nice layer , great retention . looks great , smells good , but the alcohol takes too much of it .  smoky , malty and mildy coffee-like . deep black with a thumb thick mocha head . fore is hoppy bitter then roasted barley malt follows . very much in the fullers vein as opposed to the more roasty and coffee/chocolate flavored american porters . very nice brew .

pours a deep dark chestnut brown color that is nearly opaque with mahogany edges when held to a light and a two finger frothy , soapy tan head . very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with chunks , rings and splotches of soapy lacing .  t - great pilsner , very slight hops , clean finish m - light body d - very smooth and very drinkable .

- this beer had a very exceptional appearance and a weathered pumpkin smell . very inviting beer , although there was something `` left on the field '' as the beer entered my mouth .  a bit thin , for i think i like them a bit more bodiful , but smooth and flavorful i do think this one , yes .

the smell was sweet , malty , and smokey , which i really liked .  m - the bitterness and acidic notes can be a bit of a turnoff , and its a bit prickly going down , thus not the smoothest dubbel i 've had . o - a tasty dubbel , but not my favourite .

very impressive appearance .  my first new pumpkin beer of the year . i love october ( because of pumpkin flavored beers ) . this is definitely not the best pumpkin beer i 've tried , but it 's still a very good beer . if you like shock top 's wheat , you want to try this . i ca n't promise i 'll buy another 6 pack , mostly due to price and wanting to try new things .

the smell was magnificent , and like i said i wish it had been in a snifter to catch more of these floral and citrusy aromas . outstanding .  a bit too foamy actually . last swigs : overall enjoyable . that 's cheap !

head is a bright off white , watery and light , not much retention or lacing ... outstanding aroma , very funky floral muskyness , some nice brett ... taste has some nice things going , this is a musky sour brett saison , not sweetness , makes no bones about it . crushable musky saison , well worth trying .  m : medium-light in body .
pours near black with tan head .  smooth , mellow finish , and a thin watery mouthfeel .

this beer had a beautiful pour into a tulip glass . very dark and rich , with a dark roasted tan head that was very thick and continually rebuilt itself every time i swirled the glass .  ( m ) smooth , oily , and flat . it 's a solid beer , or a solid base of a beer that could be improved only with a better mouthfeel .

light tan head for a second , poor retention and lacing ... the aroma is sweet with lots of nice sweet bourbon on the front . its a really nice smooth bourbon , makes you really want to drink it ... the taste really lets me down sadly .  mouthfeel : a little thin , medium body , low carbonation , medium flavor . underwhelming mouth .

drank on-tap at atwood 's tavern , cambridge , ma served in a stemmed glass gorgeous appearance . thick , lasting rings of lacing coated the glass .  m - this one finished a little dry , too much so for my liking , but the carbonation was nicely balanced , making it very smooth .

big hit of citrus hops right off , mostly grapefruit . pretty complex . orange and cloudy . poured with not much head that fades to not much less but still not much head .  m - pretty watery and thin .
smell is great , very complex . ripe fruits , some yeast , a tiny bit of roasty malt and a bit of alcohol .  m : somewhat thick , bread-y . but smooth .

smells great ( but nothing like a gumball imo ) . incredible . very bitter for a pale ale , or pale wheat ale , whatever . it certainly smelled good , but nothing more than the typical tropical fruit-heavy pale/ipa .  on my first stop on my michigan beer tour . the grand cru on tap was a very nice start to my tour . the first taste was wonderful , but , the flavor of the beer left my mouth looking for just alittle more .

the yeast notes are exquisite . not very earthy , mostly ripe fruit with a bit of funky complexity .  m -- slightly too watery , does n't really coat the mouth like i would hope but it washes down clean with no bad lingering tastes d -- this is it here , i think this is the beer i would use to introduce someone new to ipa 's .

pours a hazy golden color , with a huge fluffy white head . what a sight , as the head rose easily above the rim of the glass , and held there like an ice cream cone for a lengthy period of time .  could use both more body and carbonation .
a - black , inch and half of tawny head . leaves amazing lacing that should be in a museum as art .  the mouth is a tiny bit like flat soda which was the only off-putting part of this beer .

they are the best ! beautiful pour , orangish tan with a perfect beige head .  malts help to round it out a little , but that bitterness hangs around for quite a bit m : medium body with typical sa carbonation , slightly oily d/o : well , apparently zeus is known for that intense piney flavor , so it is highlighted well here .

s - chocolate and lots of it . earthy dark chocolate aroma reminds me of opening a box of cherry cordials . the aroma lingers quite a bit and stays until the end of the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is quite sharp ; a bit fizzier than i 'd like .

its been awhile since i went belgian even longer since i had a lambic beer for wich iam not a big fan but i decided on taking a chance on this pretty highly acclaimed on today and iam glad i did.first off what a pour into a tulip glass a a rosey color with a fluffy pink head that settles slowly into a creamy-like mass with globs of lace behind.a whole lot of stuff going on in the nose a little funk and iron to go along with the sour cherry and vanilla just alot to take in , the flavors are just so much rolled into one starts off big and nearly puckering sour but is stopped abruptly by a cedar wood dryness and iron/metallic note.a nice vanilla pod lends itself well as it melds nicely between the two extremes of this beer.this is a doozy and makes me think more about a style that i didnt care for much before but maybe i havent explored it enough , it might be my beer phase i go into exploring the fruit lambic style .  taste : a bit thin for a porter , almost to the point of being slightly watery .

a - brilliant clarity , orange tinged gold , rocky white head , effervescent s - spicy lemon/lemongrass esters , low sweetness , hay , earthy , t - very perfume-like , flowery bitterness , tastes sweeter than it smells , which brings out a fruity character ( apricot and pear ) , peppery , aftertaste is alcohol and spice m - somewhat boozy and astringent , dry finish , high carbonation is very creamy d - pretty good american take on a saison , just some minor miscues this is not as boozy or astringent as the first sample i had of this beer .  the mouthfeel is slightly buttery but leans more towars a syrup-like feel . carbonation would be greatly appreciated and add a very unique feel for this beer .

s - sweet raspberry , cherries and candied sugars . t - very sweet , like a slightly sour cherry soda , there is a bit of raspberry and light malt .  i wish the mouthfeel had a bit more viscosity ... .but i say that about every stout .

a- beer pours a slightly hazy oranghe-red with a nice foamy white head that stays around for a while before settling to leave some very nice lacing .  t - again , bicuit and nut . nice and malty , virtually no hop bite , but tasty none the less . d - i have had this a ton in the past , but i only just got around to getting another one for the purposes of reviewing .

smell was outstanding . malts , and dried fruits , raisins , prunes , etc , very complex and really builds the base for the beer . very , very nice . no bitterness to speak of and a lingering toffee sweetness at the end . overall an excellent doppelbock , right up there in my top 3 .  m : somewhat thin body , slightly watery ; could do with more carbonation also .

a : pours black with milk chocolate colored head . major milk-stout lacing and on a violent pour you can definitely end up with 3+ finger head .  smell is cocoa , touch of coffee , licorice , slight vanilla , a whiff of smoke . taste is thick creamy , dark and bakers chocolate , touch of espresso , end is dry and slightly bitter , a woody aftertaste .

acidic and fruity nose . fun berry aromas . the nose was the best part of this beer .  from the perfume river in vietnam ( no really , that 's what the label says ) , on to the beer : poured into a mug , it 's a clear yellow color with a soda-like head . this flavors in the beer do n't meld together well for me . there 's more cooked corn , a mild astingency , and a straightforward bitterness that battle each other for supremecy . even at ice cold , it took some work for me to stomach this beer . round off the edges and we might have something more tolerable .

a : pours a pale yellowish amber color with frothy white head and lots of lacing on the glass s : smells like major hops , citrus , grapefruit , some pine ... the usual great dipa scents t : tastes just like the smell , but the hops are less prevalent that i expected .  m - felt a bit thin to me .

it produced a nice , soapy , white head at about 2-fingers . decent retention that left some seriously clumpy lacing behind . this is a vibrant and inviting looking beer .  a - black on the pour with no head whatsoever s - big burnt malt and bittersweet chocolate aroma along with some bourbon , some oak and vanilla in there as well , slight alcohol , as the beer warms up , smells almost like straight bourbon , maybe more like a bourbon and cola t - big bourbon flavor right up front , lots of oak as well , some bittersweet chocolate in the body , finish is more bourbon and oak along with some vanilla , alcohol notes , long finish m - a bit too flat for my taste , full-bodied but totally devoid of any carbonation action in the mouth d - i 'm glad port put this in a 375ml bottle , because this is a sipper , treated this almost like fine bourbon sipping for quite awhile , but i could sip on this all night very interesting beer .

excellent look - copper color with a big slightly off-white head that leaves excellent lacing . looks as good as a rye beer can .  heavy bodied but also heavily carbonated . less carbonation would have been preferred as experiencing more of the beginning flavors would make for a more enjoyable tasting .
great look to this beer .  little fruityness . light to medium body , oily , light carbonation . could be a little more carbonated .

head exhibits very impressive staying power , and impressive lace . color is a beautiful dark and cloudy orange , yellowing around the edges .  the carbonation is ok ; small fresh bubbles at a decent strength .
quite a nice choice of fragrance hops . looks and smells phenomenal . taste , i just ca n't wrap my tongue around it .  medium thin body manages a bit of creaminess .

pours a pitch black color with a tan colored head that fades slowly , leaving a thin layer of foam and some heavy lacing .  m : finish stays around for quite a while , almost too long , really coats the mouth .

excellent retention and good lacing as well . looks intimidating .  the mouthfeel is light bodied with a high level of biting carbonation ( the carbonation is the only part of this beer that i 'm not too fond of ) . quite dry due to the high level of carbonation .

smell is grainy , nectarine and dried apricot frutiness , caramel , leather , damp earth . very little alcohol noticeable . overall the nose on this is great ! slightly fruity , caramel sweetness , subtle amounts of cedar and tobacco .  this brew is 5.2 % abv and my bottle looks exactly the same apart from the two silver australian international beer awards one from 2007 & the other from 2008 in the top left of the label anyways it pours a dark cola hue with a fast vanishing two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is fresh chocolate icecream and vanilla expresso , it has an average mouthfeel with tastes of fresh chocolate icecream , vanilla expresso , macadamia and it finishes with a light bitter mouthfeel , overall a nice brew that is just lacking that full mouthfeel of a stout in my mind but in saying that its very sessionable and ill definately buy this again .

a - poured a completely black with a gigantic 3 finger head .  had this during o'briens wet hop festival . pours clear orange with a white ring of bubbles . lots of caramel with some tropical hops in the nose . kind of like a fruitcake . earthy , yet citrusy in the taste . bit sweeter than your normal ipa . grapefruit and blood orange . good stuff .

s- big nose , this is got it all for a west coast ipa , grapefruit , pine , and light citrus notes . this is sort of sweet smelling , but not from the malt . o- this is the last i had from the hop box .  mouth feel is reasonably rich .

appearance- pours a crystal clear brownish red , almost cognac , with four fingers of beautifully structured soapy bubbles . the head peaks well above the rim of my glass , and compacts to a creamy , hefeweizen-like consistency . outstanding lacing leaves sheets behind . excellent .  the body is sufficient to carry the 10 percent alcohol which is impressive by itself . some spicy notes and an effervescent type of feel to it .
color is a dark brown color , wow real bif frothy head on this one .  t - tastes like a combination of pine-sol and a basic light lager m - who cares ?
there is a good strong malty and coffee like smell .  first pull provided a mouthfeel that was a little more smooth than i would have expected , just short of creamy .

a -- pours thick with pitch black color and a dark one finger head in my snifter . m -- the pour looked thick but it obviously was an illusion because this is watery and leaves a gross aftertaste d -- hugely let down by this beer , might have to drain pour it because of the aftertaste .  carbonation is n't bad , with fairly good activity after each drink . mouth-feel is a bit dry .

pours a cloudy amber brown into a wine glass with two fingers worth of frothy , white head . the lacing clings to the inside of the glass for dear life , and is quite exquisite .  it has a medium-light body and it 's pretty smooth .

dark brown color with a smooth , silky , creamy , long lasting head of white foam .  m - this is where the beer ranks fairly average for me . under carbonated and a little bit flat , would have liked it to be heavier , stickier , and have more of a bite .

poured a hazy straw colored hue with a fluffy three finger head . the retention was beyond excellent as was the very stick lacing . by the time i got to the bottom of my hefe glass , there was still nearly a finger of fluffy head remaining .  it has little to no head on it with a soft pour . this beer has a good balance of spices that is not overpowering . the aftertaste is mellow . this is one of the darker ales that i have drank but all in all i would give it another try . especially on a snowy winter day .

one of the best smelling dipa 's i 've tried . nice dry finish . o a great dipa . enjoyed this beer very much . this is a hop monster with a nice sweet malt complimenting everything .  m - a little water , but it goes down smoothly d - this is a really good beer .

overall the aroma is very nice . first sip , small tingly carbonation and average body . flavor is much less complex and rich than the nose advertised. , some toffee and fruit followed by a very clean yet somewhat empty finish .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low yet sharp carbonation .
great retention , light lace . gorgeous .  m good medium body , with a lot of carbonation , either takes away from this beer .

s : mmmmm ! banana , caramel , chocolate , pecan . twinge is a big negative . better as it warms , but not great . looked and smelled great but flavor was not smooth and a little imbalanced .  mouthfeel : it 's a bit heavy for the style .

the pour was very good and this is easily one of the best looking beers i have ever seen with its excelent head , color and champagne like bubbles .  muted roastiness and chocolate malt notes . deep black body with a decently firm and lasting thumb thick head . roasted coffee beans int he fore followed by toasted and burnt bread and some mild chocolate notes int he finish . finish is dry and coffee tinged great classic porter .
