burnt , dark orange in color , and hazy clarity poured this one . plenty of carbonation led to a creamy light tan head .  always looking for a great session beer and this one fits the bill for me . great bitter citrus aromas with just enough malt balance on the taste to keep the acidity in check . great piney hop character with a nice citrusy finish . my only complaint on this one is the price , for $ 11.99 a six i would prefer stone keep the etched bottles and give me a 4 % abv beer at a more reasonable price .

great head retention & lacing s : dark fruit , woody hop nosr==e t : cherry & herbal hops , some raisin & fig notes as well up front , plus a touch of candi sugar .  mouthfeel - rather bubbly , fairly thin .

disperses to form a nice cloud with some fingers of lace behind . great colour , great everything .  thanks to ncvbc for this great extra best by 12/31/08 bottle poured into my sniffer produced a good fingers worth of tan head that turns into a ring of lace around the glass on top of a jet black body aromas of toasted malts , coffee and chocolate with a slight funk ( i 'm glad i am not the only one to pick it up i though my nose was going ) earthiness , sweat malts , light chocolate , molasses good balance of flavors the only real complaint is it is a little thin for a stout good drinkability i could drink a few of these a night easy .

essentially , but not quite , black , it has a large tan head , creamy and long-lasting , slowly shrinking to a permanent frothy head with some nice lace .  mouthfeel- medium body with very little carbonation .
excellent , excellent , excellent bottle condition , hazy , champagne head pour .  light feel with lots of carbonation .

clear dark amber colour with a smooth , creamy light tan head . good head retention .  spicy and yeasty on the finish , this beer is medium-light on the palate with a high level of carbonation , much higher than i care for , really foaming up in my mouth .

complex , unique , and very intriguing . lots of vanilla , caramel , and pumpkin with cinnamon , nutmeg , and allspice . big and flavorful , intriguing , and easy to drink in a non-session beer kind of way .  the mouthfeel is medium but i think the beer would be better if it was properly carbonated .

appearance- pours a off-white , two-finger head that recedes to a well retained thick foam . the color is a medium brown with well defined garnet highlights .  a chore to swallow . lingers on the palate like a bad cigarette . overall : not something i 'll ever subject myself to again . there are way better means of getting trashed than this , and though it 's cheap , it 's not at all worth the gagging and self loathing .

the aroma is filled with dried dark fruits , apricots , honey , and wheat toast . overall a good beer , that will become a great beer over time .  it looks like a pale ale should , there 's some yeast on the bottom of the bottle and the head stays for a bit . i 'd rather have a bit more malt presence , it 's just too hoppy and bitter for me . drinkability , if i had to choose between this and a macro , i 'd take this . edit on 10-3-04 i 've raised my review score , since i 've either started loving the hop , my tastes have changed or the fact that this is one of the few decent beers you can get around here on a night out and i 've become more accoustomed to it .

a : excellent dark red color . very bright and enticing .  i can see why the word peat was used before in a review the mouthfeel was medium to light i will agree it needs some more body to it this is a good brew and with a little tweaking it could become world class .
pours deep burgundy/ with 3 fingers+ of sand/tan colored head . superior lacing & head retention s : chocolate & coffee ( ?  come and drink this corn syrup !
what a `` mixed bag '' this beer is ! smoooth and lovely , nice head , good lacing , and a wierd smell and taste .  mouthfeel - a little gritty , though a light body to it .

captain lawrence st. vincent 's dubbel is a great looking dubbel that tastes pretty good . a : red orange colour and a great 2 cm head that lasts very well . highly carbonated .  decent head , minimal lacing , crisp smell with just a hint of hops . the hops are more noticeable in the taste . really nice american lager . makes bud look like the crap it is . my only macro beer ( maybe amber bock , too )

the appearance is amazing . it pours really really dark brown , safe to say black . it leaves a thick lacing around the glass that is very very intimidating .  i think i 'm a bit parial to this beer for 2 reasons . it 's not by any means a `` specialty '' beer , it 's your typical lager and since it 's been around since before any of us were born it 's got a nostalgic feel . excellent beer in my books , average for most .

the beer pours a nice orange color , and an aggressive pour yields an initially massive off white head , that fades to a one finger height before lingering . an impressive amount of lacing in generated , almost enough to garner a 5 .  i think if the mouthfeel was better it would have made a world of difference imo .
appearance : black in color sporting a two finger creamy head that lasted a long time .  mouthfeel : hoppy and rough , but a bit fuzzy .

nice crispy scent on the nose..very citrusy ( orange blossoms and lemon scents ) and wheat filled..pouring a hazy cloud in my glass , some lacing , not much . this does smell like spring !  high carbonation detracts slightly .

750ml corked bottle poured into a tulip glass . ( a ) - pours a hazy golden yellow color that produced a huge 2+finger fluffy white head with fantastic retention . it is sticking to the glass in webs as it dissipated .  mouthfeel : it feels like an astringent hop bitterness , but i sure as heck ca n't taste any hops .
full concentric rings of lace and very good retention are a highlight .  m - medium/light body with little carbonation good with spicy food .
the body is as dark as night ; it is absolutely impervious to any light .  the motuhfeel is moderately carbonated and slightly watery .

i know this is a beer and should smell like one but this smells really good to me , reminds me of candy apples when i was a tyke .  the hops however tastes amazing but it needs more malt m - very light mouthfeel d - probably the most drinkable 7.2 % beer ive ever had

smells slightly woody followed by ripe fruit , but relatively lean . this beer has a great aroma , and a few promising notes , but overall disappoints .  medium bodied with medium carbonation . i only wish this average mouthfeel was supporting an average taste .

reviewed in 2004 , but at wrong restaurant : a two time medalist , this opaque black stout is boldly agressive with a roasted flavor stemming from rich uk malt . iron horse stout was awarded the top medal in the 1998 world beer cup competition in rio de janeiro , brazil , and the bronze medal in the 2000 great american beer festival in denver .  for the mouthfeel , i found this stout almost watery in consistency .
it looks similar to a darker version of a rose champagne . the nose has cherries and some pear .  slight astringent twinge . d- very good `` sessionable '' strong ale .

a beautiful site setting in the glass , this blackberry to almost brown elixir of life , the head gargantuan in size , creamy in texture , the color a light chocolate brown , the residual lace a thick clinging sheet .  it was also a little to carbonated for me in the mouth feel category .

appearance : beautiful hazed orange with honey lemon corners . a huge 3 finger off white crown with loads of retention and lace . the crown is really frothy and gets nice and dense like whipped cream after you let it settle and repour a few times .  mouthfeel - very enjoyable borderline complex character .

brillient , copper penny colored pour with a full , thick head of near white froth that retains and laces very nicely . just the way i want my ipa to look .  crisp taste - not heavy as expected ... hints of smokey , woody flavors - has the appeal of a coffee porter ... mouthfeel is average .

pours out an opaque black with shimmering brown at the edge of the glass . thick , creamy , off-white head and thick lacing as well .  smooth , nice , a little thin maybe . not a ton of carbonation at the end which leaves it a little watery .
it poured amber in color with a creamy-brown 3+finger head that lasted quite a while . it left gobs of sticky lacing all over my glass .  way too thin in the mouthfeel category , however .

the smell is really where this beer shined - a rich aroma of nicely roasted barley - coffee and chocolate predominated as well as a milky lactose aroma . this beer fell flat on the taste ( or maybe that 's just in comparison to the nose ) - it started off sweet , but never really delivered on all the flavors i had smelled . still , kudos for the nose . i probably wo n't be purchasing this again .  taste is dominating by anis with some candi sugar . body was above average and alcohol was well hidden .
aroma is very pleasant . sweet .  m : a touch thin .

the head very slowly fades to a 1 cm cap atop this impenetrably black brew , leaving beautiful , copious lacing everywhere . perfection in appearance .  ) my only qualm was the the body seemed a little thin .

nice tight eggshell head . nearly brilliantly clear .  a medium to full body . possibly a little too thick ( syrupy was mentioned earlier by easyr which sums it up well ) as it took me a while to make headway down the glass ( unusual for me ) .

boozy aroma with vanilla and oak apparent , notes of toffee and coconut , roast and chocolate , faint licorice and figs . great texture , full without being heavy , moderate carbonation that provided an airy mouthfeel , a bit of astringency from the kilned grains and wood , slightly sticky .  the feel is smooth , suprisingly light for a beer that seems so heavy . while i feel that this is one of north coast 's better efforts ... though none are really bad , i do wish that it had a bit more body .
pitch black with a cocoa colored head . tons of lacing .  thin , oily body ... definitely needs some more heft .

when it finally does begin to recede , huge chunks of rocky foam are sticking to my glass . surprisingly beautiful to look at .  smooth , medium body with a palate almost entirely made up of bitter , herbal hops ; perhaps trace notes of biscuity malt can be detected , but they are virtually non-existent . finish is long , dry , and bitter , and leaves you wanting more , which leads to a great level of drinkability , especially for a hophead .

huge , billowy head of marshmallow fluff is perfectly `` belgian '' - big foamy clumps of lace are all over my glass .  the only real flaw for me with this beer is that it 's a bit thin , but that 's a bit nit-picky and did n't detract at all for me from this wonderful beer .

the body is a nice burnt gold color and is slightly hazy , but the carbonation is clearly visible . its topped off with a nice thick white head , and is very bubbly and frothy but doesnt last long : there is some mild lacing too .  color and mouthfeel are average for the style and fine .

'' in the glass , beer is a dark mahoghany color , very attractive .  so we have another german pilsner . i 'm still amazed that there are so many of these . i 'm still unable to get passed the grassy flavor of these . i just which they 'd add something else to mute that flavor down a bit . then again that would change the style and it would n't be a pils anymore . anyhow this brew is clear yellow with an earthy natural aroma and taste . the style just is n't for me .

drank in a american pint glass from a 12oz bottle . appearance - golden brown with a foamy white head .  now i understand the meaning of the word `` swill '' . i have an enormous amount of respect for european beers . avoid . trust me .
great retention and lacing .  m - average mouthfeel . carbonation on par , but a very thin feeling brew .
the beer pours amazingly dark reddish purple with a creamy purple head of 3 cm foaming up easily .  a tad thin .

pours out like chocolate syrup , fills the glass pitch black with a very dark tan head . billowing foam despite a very cold serving temperature , thick chunks of lace , crazy retention .  decent palate , a little thin like the others in the series , but fairly smooth .

this one gushed out an extremely creamy , frothy off-white head with a suprisingly long and stable retention . the bottom was also very appealing , golden orange-yellow hue that was opaque and reflective .  mouthfeel i kind of like the mouthfeel to this one . the carbonation isnt bad , and it goes down smoother than most .

brown to copper towards the edges with a huge off white head that falls slow and never completely goes away while clinging to the glass . as the edges fall away , thick ringed sheets of foam . this is one damn good lookin ' beer .  feel is also a bit thin and fizzy .
i had this on tap and have to say was extremely impressed by its beautiful golden color , and fine head .  m : lightly carbed , thin , slightly oily , tannic finish .
smell is excellent and unique . predominate smell i get is apricot .  m - medium body , not a lot of carbonation .

poured into an imperial pint glass . color was a dark amber with a slight reddish tint to it . head was initially 3 fingers , but dropped down to 1 , and consisted of off white foam , almost like a meringue that clung very well to the sides .  mouthfeel was a bit thick , and it was not quite as carbonated as i would have liked .

pours from 21 oz bottle to pint glass , a deep , dark , caramel-color with a straw colored two-finger head that seems to grow with time rather than dissipate . frothy lace definitely persists .  hmmm . drank this because a chick bought a pitcher and the service was terrable . it 's like club soda with a twist of beer . not much color , not much flavor . not bite of hop . not really much to say about this stuff . it 's pretty popular with girls ...
a : beautiful two inch creamy head . incredible creamy yellowy orange color with micro rising carbonation .  m : the body is light but sugary and grainy with a moderate carbonation .

a - pitch black with a carbonated type head that fades quickly s - fruity , chocolatey , roasty , and malty t - huge dried fruit on the forefront followed by massive chocolate and roasty accompaniment . different then most ris , but a pretty good example .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and resinous , this is really the only fault i can find .

best by date of 5/3/11 a : standard pour yields a billowy 2.5 finger light creamsicle colored head with very good retention . lacing is patchy and spotty with nice cling .  mouthfeel : bubbly and light body . the mouthfeel is a little peculiar and affects my experience .
nitro-can encouraged frothy tan head , superb retention , some lace , almost opaque hue .  the only fault is that its a little thin bodied but that 's what makes this brew dangerous .
i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . great head , fine bubbles that stuck to the glass the whole way down .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent .

a- really nice big belgian-style head on top of a fizzy , slightly hazy , light straw colored body . looks lovely in a belgian tulip glass .  a : pours a dark brown with a two finger head ; burnt orange around the edges of the glass when held to light ; lacing is excellent s : smells of caramel and coffee ; very earthy aroma t : tastes like a bitter coffee initially , but the sweetness of caramel and honey slowly creeps in m : i think its a bit too watery and the carbonation does not seem right d : two in a sitting is nice ; i 'm generally not a porter fan , but i enjoyed this beer

aroma was outstanding . rich and full with dry , whole grain oats and sweet , cereal-like notes ( kind of like sticking your nose in a box of quaker oats ) . drinkability however was quite good .  mouthfeel is on the thin side for a stout .
aroma is lots of banana and lemon , very nice and assertive .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .
great looking beer .  the mouthfeel was about what i expected going in , but i thought it might a little over-carbonated . the aggressiveness of the carbonation was a little distracting .
s - delicious blueberry scent which overpowers just about everything else .  the body is medium with decent carbonation .
poured nice gold color with a generous stiff white head .  m- low carbonation and very low mouthfeel .
this is beautiful , and refined . man , the nose really had me going , but the taste did n't follow through .  the mouthfeel is a bit overcarbonated for the stle but not bad .
appearance : very dark with a thick foam head with good retention . very good lacing .  m. a bit acidic d. overall a nice iipa .

looks absolutely fantastic , deep impenetrable black body with coffee coloured head , aromas full of coffee and chocolate and heavy dark roast malts with some fruity notes and a little hop .  pretty thin mouthfeel i guess , but overall its a great balance of flavor and drinkability , something i would definitely buy again .

a : beautiful clear rich copper color with creamy tan head . m : smooth o : a very aesthetically pleasing beer . really beautiful to look at and smell .  carbonated but not overly so . on the lighter side of medium bodied , i 'd say .

head is enormous and very thick and creamy .  this is a man 's beer . none of this flowery wine swilling critique lingo . light color , smell and mouth feel , who really cares . outstanding dry & hoppy flavor without sweetness . when bought in the 30 pack , cost is about 50 cents each . the best macro being produced !

smell : strong citrus aroma boasting orange , pineapple and sappy resin . they really knocked it out of the park in the smell , what an inviting and pleasing scent . has west coast written all over it . overall : a pretty impressive brew from cisco brewers .  this feels thin for some reason . carbonation is good and proper .

smell is awesome -- the smoked pork hits you first , followed by hints of raw sugar , honey , apples or pears , and black licorice . first few sips have an element of 'burnt'-ness to them , but once you get used to it , it 's quite pleasant . there 's almost a saltiness to it , with some background flavours of coffee , chocolate , and strong malts .  mouthfeel too prickly and astringent but medium body is appropriate for style .

poured from a 750ml bottle into my troubadour tulip glass . a dense and enormous mattress of foam tops the ale almost like a merengue . a sudsy lattice-work of lace remains in the glass even after it is empty .  the only knock here is that it was a little thin . m = is it possible to be creamy and watery at the same time ?

brilliantly clear with a nice 1 '' head - amber/copper in color . looks great .  feel seems to be about medium in body , but slightly watery , with a lingering semi-bitter dark unsweetened chocolate/coffee bean aftertaste .
s : it smelled very malty with hints of doughy white yeast and whiffs of ripe white ( apricots and pear ) s fruit and sweet citrus ( mandarin oranges ) .  mouthfeel is on the light end .

the smell on this beer was very nice . bold citrus flavors dominate and are light and bright .  tart and dry feel , but not overly so . lower carbonation detracts a little , really the only flaw in my mind .

a : pours a deep , hazy plum body that resides beneath a three-finger head of creamy pinkish-tan foam ; good retention and tons of lace . probably the best-looking barleywine i 've seen . beautiful .  mouthfeel : this was my one issue with this beer . it loses carbonation quickly , and with not that much to start with , it is kind of a bummer . a little sticky as well but the taste makes up for a bit of this .
great retention and generous lacing . lovely looking porter .  mouthfeel : this is the one downside of this beer ; it 's just a bit thin .

a bit of lacing & zero head retention , really dragged this score down s : pumpkins & pumpkin pie spices , cinnamon , allspice , & nutmeg t : pumpkin , cinnamon , nutmeg , dryness & brown sugar up front . spices start to dominate as this warms , cinnamon & nutmeg especially , plus some squashy/pumpkin notes as well . finishes warming with nutmeg & cinnamon mf : medium bodied , fairly low carbonation & a nice warming sensation , expected a bit more malt depth though drinks pretty easy , the abv is well hidden , but lacks the total package of say , an ichabod , but i would certainly grab a sixer of this during the fall every year  i thought the mouthfeel was a touch watery but the whole packaged seem very much an alluring strong-lawnmower , early evening session beer .

it smells like a a big pile of hops . there are also some alcohol esters and actually a decent aroma of biscuit-like malt . t : hops dominate .  tingly in the nose which is common with sour ales but this is n't sour at all t. sweet with dried fruit , malty m. has a biting quality , a bit to carbonated .

pours brown with ruby hints . there are two healthy fingers of head ( boy , is this a live beer ) and the retention and lacing are top notch .  an e-mail from the brewery indicated that twins lager is not the same beer as hauenstein , just with a different label . schells tells me that the twins lager uses a different recipe and yeast than the hauenstein , but a side by side comparison leaves me wondering why they would go through the trouble . i have always liked `` cheap '' beers . the beer drinkers of olden days wanted it cold , crisp , and cheap . but for afternoon lazing back and swigging , there is certainly nothing wrong with a cold bottle of twins lager . twins lager might be `` twice as refreshing '' as the label purports , but , boy would it be a treat to drink an original recipe fitgers again !

750 ml bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a cloudy corn silk hue with a pillowy cloudy white two finger head . super sticky on the sides with a head that sticks around forever .  boosting the carbonation would help .

a- pours into my pint glass a light mahagony with a finger of bright foam . this trails into a lacing pattern that reminds me of a coral reef , quite beautiful .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . flavor is sour apple cider without the expected hops from a bitter , one has to question if this bottle has gone bad but after reading other reviews apparently it has n't , even though it has n't been brewed since 2006 .
s : the aroma is fantastic . natural lemon scent and orange zest , mostly lemon .  m - sort of dry but hops represented well in this brew .

a beautiful looking beer that has a very appetizing aroma , but its flavor does n't meet expectations .  there is little ( hardly any ) carbonation here , and the mouthfeel really does n't pack a punch at all .

s - beautiful wet hopped aroma with a citrusy and piney profile that is extremely fresh . there 's also a bit of bread and caramel malt present .  m/d - mouthfeel is nothing special , the steely hop bite takes a bit away .

aroma : very light malt aromas appearance : huge foamy head , light brown in color . very dark brown , with ruby highlights , almost opaque . clarity is very good in the highlights .  shockingly light carbonation feel . i think the mouthfeel is off from what it should be .
dissipation takes it 's time but leaves fantastic lacings .  mouthfeel : low carbonation , light-medium body , slick texture . a bit flat all in all .

a - clear red orange body with two finger for frothy tan head and excellent lacing s - a little pine and a little citrus .  m : medium body but the finish is not as crisp nor as clean as it could be .
the beer poured a molasses black colour with a light brown head that quicklt disappeared .  mouthfeel was a little thin , that 's my only complaint .

a- pours a very hazy yellow-orange with a thick white head that lasts a long time and leaves lots of lacing . exactly what this style should look like .  seems a bit thin , with very soft carbonation .

pours with an outrageously massive head , a dense , simmering mass of eggshell brown rising over the rim of the goblet like a souffle . what a visual feast !  thanks jpm30 . clearly sour taste that sweetens as you drink it . vineous and slightly rich , wood only detactable before the taste buds are overpowered.. great after salty fish . a slightly milder alternative to a cantillon , overpowering the mouth but not for the entire day .
s - classic belgiun smell.. sweet dark fruits.. caramel and brown sugar . t - pretty bland and tart .  m : light but slightly creamy body .
it looks gorgeous , black with a creamy tan head .  feel left me a bit disappointed , however , as it was thin -- too thin for this big of flavor .
aroma is nice : lightly caramel with a tangerine citrus hop character . does smell nice though !  the mouthfeel was light but a bit chewy .

still a bit of haze but not anything like a hefe . the beer looks great in this glass !  this beer has a flavor i really like m- pretty thin and bubbly , almost reminds me of a bmc feel o- one of my favorite tasting pale ales .
nola brown ale , draft a big thick rocky head , deep ruby red color when held to the light . a nice looking beer .  m : a bit thin , i was kind of expecting it to be a bit more viscous .
bottle to a tulip pours a clear red body , and by red i mean excellent vibrant red . has a fizzy white head that doesnt stay for the party .  nicely carbonated .

the aroma is both unique and memorable , with a cornucopia of fruitiness : pineapple , mango , strawberry , and starfruit . the hops taste grassy and resinous , but the highlight is the tropical fruits derived from the yeast ... excellent stuff , even though it 's not the most cohesive-tasting flavor profile . a crafty anniversary beer..complex , tasty , and original . kudos , real ale .  mouthfeel is somewhat disappointing . if we 're talking about banana bread here , then it should be thicker , like bread .

a- a dense golden/honey color . a nice spongy two finger head with great lacing to the end .  m/t : light to medium body , watery and a good amount of carbonation . however with the light body , low bitterness and virtually zero aftertaste , i could session this beer .
a deep mocha head emerges from the bottom of the glass to form a nice half inch layer . exactly the appearance a big stout should uphold ; textbook .  medium bodied fairly low carbonation .

750ml a : really looks great with red notes . the amber color really makes this look appetizing .  tastes like , yeah , tart blueberries ( probably artificial blueberries ) . just sweet & weird & sweet ... really tough to finish one . much like a cheap , too-tart wine cooler .

appearance : creamy froth deep dark brown , nearly ebony color smell : deep dark roasted coffee and subtle dark chocolate and some nice cinnamon spice aroma taste : a heavy dose of black coffee , zero alcohol burn , lacked power though , you have to like coffee to liek this beer . mouthfeel : light bodied for a stout drinkability : a solid stout and interesting pumpkin pie aspect  i did notice after a while that it has been pulled from tap that it acquires a lack of a better word , a buttery taste that really dos n't go good with anything . i do like this beer and i 'm not bashing it . the buttery taste in my opinion did not take effect until thirty or so minutes after pour . i do keep some in my fridge . i have shiner before to make burgers with , which turned out great . good beer for beer lovers .

the aroma is strong with floral hops and some spices ... very nice . the taste is a little too empty ... you can definitely tell it is a wheat beer with the sweet perfume floral characters .  slightly under carbonated for my taste but not really a flaw .
very nice and original beer - more body would have been better but still a great treat from a great brewery .  m : relatively light though not particularly carbonated .

poured a hazy gold-orange with a 1.5 inch frothy white head and cascades of tiny effervescing bubbles that traveled from the base of the glass to the bottom of the cap . sticky rings of lacing were revealed as the head slowly receded .  drink this on tap at city beverage in durham . i like the color and mouthfeel , though a bit thin for a heavy beer aroma is slightly sweet and complex spices taste is toasted barley , spices , and slight caramel with little head . drinks easy for a heavy beer

oh , man ... the aroma on this is , perhaps as the name implies , heavenly . almost a perfect balance in the nose -- fruity , pine needles , grapefruit . and this one goes through three `` hoppings , '' kettle , hop back , and dry hopping ... awesome . the flavor is just about perfect . a fine balance of hop flavors , including a nice grapefruit bitterness and a light bready undertone . but , as a whole , this is a very drinkable beer ... and quite delicious .  i think that the long trip from greece to williamsburg , va did n't treat this beer too kindly . pours and looks like the standard heine-clone . taste was rather flat .

solid brownish black with a massive and thick mocha head that has outstanding retention and leaves lots of lacing all around the glass .  not as sweet as oscura , but the mouthfeel reminded me of it . it is a little light in the feel for an imperial but ample carbonation maybe to much .

the aroma is of chocolate milk , or maybe the chocolate chips used for cookies .  as a swallow i think the first thing i notice is that this is a tad light , but still serviceable in mouthfeel . a nicely balanced apa if not a little thin . im still pleasantly surprised !

it 's one of the prettiest beers i 've ever seen ! deep , dark brown with a hint of ruby when held up to strong light . a tan frothy and foamy lasts and lasts , leaving waves of sticky lace on the side of the glass ( artful ) .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with no carbonation .
a very nice brew that started with an absolutely great black color with an outstanding head and lacing .  the mouthfeel is light with a decent amount of carbonation .

just about perfect for a true winter beer .  m : the feel is creamy and medium bodied . rather light for a ris and that really detracts from the beer in my opinion . the mouthfeel is lighter than what i come to think of when i thik of a ris .
a fairly large ( nearly two finger ) head of light brown foam sits atop . an ominous looking brew .  m_slightly below medium bodied and very effervescent .

a - clear ruby brown with a thick white head that has excellent retention and fairly decent lacing .  s : candied pineapple , yeast , and hops well balanced t : a typical ipa taste with accents of pineapple ; yeasts and hops , well balanced m/d a bit thin , carbonation too small and too much , abv on the high side and quite noticeable good beer

appearance : i 'm a huge fan of this beer 's appearance . it is mildly dark in colour with a deep rich , ruby read colour that really glows when held up to light . it pours with a nice dense , slightly rocky head .  m : very smooth , but seems pretty thin in terms of the body of the beer .
smelled great ! t : was a bit disappointed by the taste .  mouthfeel is lightly carbonated , a little thick ( like a dark lager ... blech ) , and generally mediocre .

this beer pours a slightly cloudy golden orange color , with a thick , fluffy light yellow head . the head fades very slowly , leaving a thick cutrain of lace .  not sure what they used for malt , but very sugary at first . the hops comes in and stays with you . almost like an ipa with the first snoot full of hops . i suppose they have to keep winning people over cause of the whole inbev deal . king of beers , so i am not surprised .
clear copper colored beer with a large , cream colored head . head retention is good , with nice lacing .  m - slightly thin and sweet .

a- pours dark black . one of the prettiest beers i 've seen .  it 's viciously acidic , but tasty . i like acidic ... i 'll drink straight malt vinegar . this is fizzy alcoholic pomegranate juice with nothing to resemble beer to my palate . i would n't hold `` not tasting like beer '' against a legitimate ale beverage , which i 'm sure this is , except that i like beer , and i do n't like this .

appearance : this brew pours with a wonderfully thick head . lacings are plentiful and surface spiderwebbing is consistant and lasting . color is indeed a reddish amber . excellent first impression .  very light mouthfeel .
the appearance is nice and perfect to style : pale orange in color and crystal clear .  the mouthfeel is fairly overcarbonated and dry .

aroma : very sweet and pleasant smelling . a little fruity with banana 's the predominant smell ( in terms of its fruitiness ) .  mouthfeel is medium with a thick body but too much carbonation for a barleywine .
brilliant cloudy , fuzzy , bubbly orange appearance with a perfect 1/4 inch puffy head and a pleasant hoppy aroma .  m - heavy , with little carbonation .

smell has a strong piney grapefruit aroma , the grapefruit really shines through as the star , the aroma kind of reminds me of the 1260 triple ipa .  m- thinner than i would like and overly fizzy from too much carbonation .

bottle and served in my expedition snifter ( along side of the 5 & 8 ) : a - very dark with some ruby highlights and the best head of the three with a good creamy lace upon the glassware .  m- a little light and watery , but not awful . makes for easy drinking .

pale golden-amber , brilliantly clear and bright , this is a beautiful beer . two fingers of head settles down to a thin disc that retains very well .  mouthfeel is surprisingly tingly and sharp from the tiny carbonation and i suspect a hop i ca n't discern in either the aroma or taste . mouthfeel is unfortunately a little weak and thin for style to my mind .

appearance : dark black color , with big chocolate brown head , medium carb smell : chocolate , with malts , and some wood taste : bitter dark chocolate , coffee , alcohol , and roasted malt mouthfeel : dry , slightly bitter , rich full body drinkability : a drinkable imperial stout , the high abv is moderately masked .  average body and carbonation .

serving type - 22oz bottle appearance - very dark tan , black , great 3 inch thick creamy head smell - coffee , cocoa , mocha , hops , chocolate , malts , barley , smells amazing taste - as the smell prepaired me , very strong mocha coffee taste .  mouth : such a light and watery mouthfeel that it becomes distracting pondering the feel when you should be appreciating the tastes . drink : the nearly too-light mouthfeel is redeemed by the drinkability of this brew .
appearance : a wonderful amber color .  m - ok and average .

honestly , a fantastic looking beer .  this is n't the fault of the brewer so maby it had great head . the main problem with this beer was infection . i 'm sure it was an infection because when i sniffed it i thought for a second maybe i was at the movies about to dig into a 12 dollar medium popcorn . past the buttery flavor i could taste blueberry almost which i 'm sure was n't intended either . it 'd be interesting to taste one from a different batch .

this beer has a frothy , three finger thick , almost rocky pale white head that sits atop a body that is brilliantly clear and a pale straw color . the color is about perfect and the head is one of the longest lasting and best ones i have seen on a macro-lager .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .
smell : oh baby can you say citrus hop bomb ? loads of grapefruit and a touch of lemon .  mouthfeel : this beer has adequate body , but i would like a bit more texture .
beautiful dark color , with good mapping down the sides .  m= a little thin . boring mouth on it .

appearance , was this beers strong suit , poured a nice amber , with a frothy meringue-like head , that left broken puffs all the way down the glass , smell was rather vague , sweet malty aroma , dried fruit perhaps , taste waspleasant , rather weak , unsweetened tea-like taste , very light , and slight hop dryness , but a nice beer on a warm day , as it is here right now , mouthfeel , is light bubbly , smooth .  the mouthfeel was lowly carbonated .

served in the `` new '' sam adams lager pint glass , the beer pours dark , dark brown ( might as well be black ) with an inch frothy brown head . head retention and lacing are both pretty good .  definitely a little too carbonated for my taste - the mouthfeel was a little too creamy , masking the flavor .

this beer proves that looks are n't everything . pours an utterly marvellous cloudy yellowish gold under a stupendous off-white head that grows and billows into spectacular cumulous clouds of foam on top of the liquid . this head lingers long and leaves very nice lace . ca n't really ask for more in a wheat beer 's appearance . the mouth starts off prickly , but goes flat like magic even before you can swallow . after the beautiful vision , the reality was quite disappointing .  had a typical pilsner mouthfeel .
this amber ale pours with a clear amber body topped by a thick head with lots of lacing left on the glass .  m- average medium bodied beer o- great take on a saison style beer .
appearance - i really like this one , a rich caramel color and moderate foaming taste - hmmm .  mouf & gt ; sudsy .

appearance is beatiful dark dark black with a fluffy , pale yellow head that laces nicely .  mouthfeel is a bit watery not much body to it , but on a hot day like today , i could take plenty of these guys down .

tremendous head and a deep , dark brown body . the lowly brown ale usually isnt going to win beauty contests , but this is about as good as one will look .  m : a light-medium feel to it and kind of syrupy .

s- smells of dark caramel , roasted malt , charcoal , and a light smokiness . t- quite astringent .  m : earthy with a little grapefruit at the begining and a little pine at the finish . light carbonation .

a - beautiful amber body with intense white huge head and sheets of lacing remaining for an insane amount of time .  i almost gag every time i take a sip of this . tastes like day-old miller high life with some bread , chocolate , and coffee mixed in . it looks like cola , and at first it smells like oh , say , a bottle of old milwaukee . if only it tasted even half as good as old milwaukee . please , for your own sake , stay away .
pours clear deep amber body topped by mid-sized creamy beige head with excellent retention that sticks to the walls and never fades away .  mouthfeel is smooth , but almost unpleasantly so .

app : nice copper color , tight white head smell : minimal hop aroma . some malt notes taste : med body , nice carbonation ... just boring to drink mouthfeel : nothing new or different than other sn beers drink : average ... good , but there are other beers i would go to first 2008 version a : nice copper color with tight bubbles and a good foamy head .  a : solid black , modest lacing even at the beginning , but once the beer was gone so was the lacing s : malty , chicory , lingers nicely t : dominated by coffee ; bitter stout ; the oak comes through nicely ; not very complex m : casked , so it does n't really buzz in the mouth overall , a really good beer , but not as complex as i was hoping ; still , very worthwhile

the smell is as excepted sweet and more sweet . hints of flowers and something a bit citrusy . wow ! the taste is sooo much bigger than the smell and really does n't do it justice .  m. a little too sticky , it feels syrupy , but without a sweeter taste it fells a little off .

this beer looks great in my mug with a great black body and a thick coffe colored head .  mouthfeel is full and seems overcarbonated for the style , but overall has the typical heavy/slightly syrupy mouthfeel characteristic of wheat beers .
opaque pitch black , moderate brown head . '' apart from the looks and the aroma : very disappointing .  mouthfeel is fine - it 's a very light lager .

below average head retention , but the aroma more than makes up for a lackluster appearance as it brims with bold espresso and sweet chocolate notes . one of the best-smelling coffee beers i 've had recently , and the malt backbone is nothing to scoff at , either . overall , brewhouse coffee stout is amazingly aromatic , but could use a few tweaks here and there with regards to the appearance and mouthfeel .  body is ok , nothing special but not bad . very boozy finish .
beautiful , beautiful honey color with a thick , but not creamy , head .  m : light bodied and well carbonated .

appearance is dark brown/red , with a tan pancake head and nice lacing .  m : the body is not as thick as i was expecting . it on the thin side as far as stouts go , but drinks very smoothly . i would have liked a thicker body , but that 's just being picky .
pours a cloudy garnet hue with a thin but persistent head . leaves an incredible lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is a little thin , though .

beautiful amber brew with dark caramel and red highlights . nice foam , and lingering carbonation in the mouth .  the beer poured hard but the carbonation ended up being low and the mouthfeel medium .
poured - beautiful dark color .  the bier finishes quickly but is not overly dry . the malt department is a little thin for me but damn well done !

and while it is not terrible , it merely passes as ok. the look is deep and black , and of course the cascading head is beautiful .  mouthfeel the beer is slick on the tongue with strong carbonation . the body is a little lacking , medium-light .

pours a dark chestnut brown color that is completely opaque with a two finger frothy , pillowy yellowish beige head that has very good retention , only slowly fading into a lasting cap . sporadic spots of lacing left behind .  feels quite creamy at first , almost in a draft-stout kind of way , which struck me as odd . would rather it be crisper and a bit more carbonated , though .
bomber poured a clear dark reddish brown nearly black with a lasting brown head .  do not know if this was an aberation , but this caused a lower score in mouthfeel .

the bouqet is powerful , with bubble gum , circus peanuts ( the candy ) , bananas , caramel , toffee , honey , flowers , and a hint of the big alcohol that awaits . drinkability suffers due to the huge abv . this went well with a salty , deep blue cabrales from spain .  finishes with a sweet malt taste m- medium bodied with decent carbonation , not as full for an octoberfest as i 'd like but still good d- very drinkable and easy to use to introduce others to a seasonal beer

really lovely to look at .  the taste is metal , sweet malt and finishes a nasty bitter . this is not a beer to be revisited unless it is on tap . i need to quite trying these imported green bottled beer . i do n't think i 've had a good one yet . on tap is a different story since kegs should n't get light damage . of course then there 's temperature . . .

hazy yellow body with short white head beautiful voluptous peach aroma . very juicy . simple and juicy , no bitterness or sourness .  pretty weak mouthfeel , it 's a bit watery . i 'm enjoying the flavour and aroma quite a bit but the mouthfeel is a bit weak . but lacking in mouthfeel .

appearance : poured a milky orangy and yellowish hazy color , typical of hefeweizens , especially authentic german ones . yielded a huge 3 finger creamy head that came right out of the glass but maintained its shape is it was thick and creamy .  mouthfeel was the only thing i was n't too keen on- felt a little spritzer-ish .
it has a really nice , spicy aroma with a solid grain backbone .  the body is rather thin though .

s : very complex and aromatic , dark fruits , like figs and raisins , some dark sugar is there as well , with a bit of port wine and grapes . t : taste is of a medicinal , dark fruity brew . very complex , though the flavour did n't really come through until the beer was at about 60 degrees , so serve this one a little warmer than usual .  m : medium-full bodied , zero carbonation , silky . d : lacks the warming feeling that is usually related to a winter warmer .
a : guinness just looks great in the glass . good contrast with black color with a creamy white head .  m : over carbonated - fizzy .

head leaves a serious amount of lace on the glass . really a great looking pint of beer .  mouthfeel was a bit heavy and undercarbonated , but that may have been more of the fault of the bar i was at , and not the beer its self .

really nice , dark golden color . really substantial , bone-white head that has little recession .  the head vanished quickly , but the carbonation level remained high . the aroma was overwhelming sour cherries ... mouthwatering sweet aroma that shows a huge proportion of cherries used in this brew . definitely on the sugary sweeter cherry beer side .

my favorite part of the beer was the aroma . it had this very intense chocolaty smell that while sipping was very pleasing to the senses .  mouthful mouthful is okay . has decent carbonation , but i 've had better as far as carbonation goes .
appearance is good - clear chestnut color with a pretty good cream colored head that sticks around awhile .  mouthfeel : there is a lot of bitterness .
appearance : this one pours a very dark mohogany with an incredible red hue . great head rentention very frothy .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

the appearance is beautiful . a bit darker than i 'd expect a golden ale to be , but it looked great .  taste is more of the same ... some wild floral flavors , hints of citrus ... seems like the dominant flavors have switched from the citrus to the floral characteristics . i like it , for sure , but could use some balance . i 'm not a big fan of the bitter taste left in the mouth ... but it 's still plenty drinkable . a definitely above-average ale , but not the best .

great appearance : solid dark black with some brown amber colors in the light .  this is a seasonal brew , do n't know if it is offered everywhere or if it was given adequate time to chill before serving so i 'll reserve final judgment for later .

bottle into a pils glass pours a clear , deep copper orange with a one and a half inch off-white head which holds up well throughout from lots of carbonation release . it also leaves some nice looking sheets of lacing down the sides of the glass . ca n't ask for a better looking beer .  m : still a bit watered down , but again , it 's better .

the nose was the winning feature for me . it was a stunning coffee and chocolate explosion . it almost reminded me of a warm bowl of oatmeal with mocha covering it . it was a little too bitter and i really tasted the alcohol .  mouthfeel : typical red stickyness drinkability : i love this beer .
the smell is divine with fruits and spice and honey , and a little malt . although not a belgian champion it 's still a fine tripel .  mouthfeel is thin for a stout imo , but not bad .
it pours a burnt orange color with a large cream colored head and great lacing .  mouthfeel was my only complaint .
s : pumpkin exactly as it would smell in fresh baking . a nice blend of cinnamon and spice present .  m - lots of carbonation maybe bordering on too much .
poured into a standard snifter at about 55 degrees f , 1-inch head , light lacing , deep beautiful cloudy magenta .  thin to medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

a- pours orange-amber with a massive , foamy and creamy head that retains amazingly , gives duvel a run for its money . the cloud is as big as the head of others .  no sediment at all when bought fresh . this really brought out flavors you could not taste beforehand . a wedge of orange or lemon is a nice touch also . best served a little warmer than most beers . goes really well with food . a beer you could drink all night especially during a good bar-b-que .
wonderful looking ale .  mouthfeel a bit thin .

great color , substantial head on pour . beautiful appearance .  it 's a black colored beer with ruby edges . fairly nice nose , with a variety of dark fruits , as well as a bit of chocolate and coffee . really nice nose . flavor is fully packed , loaded with dark fruits ( blackberry , plum , cherry and currant ) , as well as some notes of dark chocolate , coffee and a light hint of alcohol . i like it .

appears a ruby dark brown with a beige head and lots of thick , sticky lacing .  a - it was still cascading when the glass arrived to the table ... settled into a deep , deep brown body with a brown head ... the head was creamy yet bubbly and it retained as one finger tall ... sheets of lacing were left s - there was a lot of chocolate in the nose with some subtler coffee notes ... dark fruits were present as well as a noticeable hop presence t - again , the chocolate presence was throughout the entire beer ... it tasted like bittersweet chocolate ... the dark fruits came out in the middle ... i would say dates were most prevalent because there was a nice , sweet caramel note throughout ... the coffee flavor showed up briefly at the end as well as the hops ... it did n't leave a bitterness on the palate though m - light bodied ... this was indifferent for me ... you would think the nitro would have added some body , but it actually came across as watered down o - the description said this was an homage to yard 's brawler ... i believe i had three of these one night ... the chocolate flavor is nice and it 's all around ... there are other players that join in the flavors ... you ca n't beat 2.6 % abv , talk about session ! ... my only complaint is the watered down mouthfeel
poured at the rock bottom brewery prior to seeing the blue man group . beautiful honey gold color ... poured with no head .  the mouthfeel is a bit too watery and perhaps a bit chalky .

a perfect looking stout .  this beer poured nicely with a creamy white head , giving off nice citrus aromas . the flavor was shocking , however , reminding me of kool-aid orange flavor , and with almost as much sweetness . i could n't distinguish any hop bitterness , though it could have used some to balance out the excessive sweetness . this beer tastes as though all the yeast were filtered out , and then orange kool-aid added post-fermentation

on initial pour this is one of the finest looking brews i 've ever laid eyes on .  it was my first fruity beer . it kinda tasted like an apricot . i was expecting most of a fruit taste like wine , but no . and i liked the picture on the bottle . and since it came ithaca i just had to try it . over all the beer was worth it . it 's good . : )
sampled on 4-7-09 pours a clear deep red/brown , with a huge , foamy , clingy , off-white head that leaves crazy thick lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium , slightly watery .
pours out a beautiful amber color with a wonderful fluffy white head .  mouthfeel is a little too tingly for me with the carbonation .

appearance : crystal clear orange-brown body with randomly-placed shades of red . very nice head retention on the whole and lots of web-like lacing .  this was my first encounter with pumpkin ale . i must confess that i could not finish the bottle . i had the distinct impression that the beer was trying to taste like something and not quite getting there . fearing the latter , i tossed the bottle after about five sips .

pours a light , burnt orange , very clear . the beautiful amber-orange gives it an amazing radiant quality , looks delicious and refreshing . also great for the beach , on a deck or patio watching the sun set to match the color of this gorgeous beer , especially since it will go great with chips and salsa .  aroma of fresh fruit and a bit of must , faint barnyard . taste starts with blackcurrant , very dry , moderately sour . hints of vanilla . finishes with more fruit and some mustiness . complex . would love to see it age .

sweet malts , wheat , maple syrup , and barrel aged booze in the nose . wheat & sweet malts with a hoppy backbone . boozy on the way down , leaving your throat tingly .  nice golden color with plenty of carbonation . the head of foam was really thick and creamy , but it dropped down to a this lace in about 15 mins . at first i was n't crazy about the taste , but about 3-4 sips into the beer i changed my tune . it is not like any beer that i typically drink , so i did n't what to expect.interesting brew , i would buy this again .

on the nose , fresh fruits , cherries , peaches , green apples , pears , simply amazing . a bit twangy and just on the border of being chewy , but not quite . dry and a bit laid back ; decent yeasty body with some reserved sugar , candy cane offerings . sticky as it warms , sort of a bubble gum palate and a bit rustic .  m-medium carbonation with a fairly dry finish o-listed as a pale lager ?

smell is of bourbon , wood , malt , brown sugar , toffee , and dark fruits . overall , this is a fantastic beer with very complex aromas and flavors . i am really glad i was able to try this one .  mouthfeel : a bit thinner than expected , but not bad .

smell is on the sweet side but hoppy as well , sweet bubblegum scent , weed , juicy citrus and a malt punch , great scent . taste is enjoyable , alot of different things balancing sweet and hoppy in that order with the above mentioned scents going into the taste without the weed .  in the mouth , it 's rather average , with light carbonation .

the aroma is decidedly tart and funky , with some citrusy hops . complex and enticing . the flavor is dry and yeasty , with some interesting phenolics bordering on burnt rubber .  m - a little harsh , not as smooth as other ipas .

achieved a very impressive tan head . the appearance was the best thing about this beer . wow , overhyped ?  creamy flavor does not carry over into the mouthfeel ; light bodied beer without much carbonation .

appearance perfect looking . the frothy , sticky head is everlasting .  nothing to write home about when it comes to mouthfeel . kind of a club-soda feel to the beer , tingly . though there seems to be a strange `` romanian roulette '' effect where every sixth beer is kinda soapy .

$ 5.00 / 750ml bottle county market grocery store stevens point , wisconsin appearance - a haze of golden yellow to a pale orange with a lasting frothy white head . very much carbonated as a constant flow of tiny bubbles speed to the top if the beer from the side and bottom of the pint glass .  dare i say it seems a bit on the thin side . the meatiness in the flavor is not backed up by the body . not bad , but just a little disappointing ... this is a fine stout .

first pour yielded about 6 fingers of creamy/frothy hybrid head with ( unfortunately really good retention and lots of lacing .  i can feel it in my cheeks . it does n't have any off aromas specifically , but it definitely has the acidity for it . undrinkable , i 'm pouring it out .

poured into a pint glass ... appearance-maybe the best head i 've ever since on a hefeweizen . considering many hefeweizens bodys look similar this is getting a 5 . frothy 3 finger head that i 'm enjoying just sit there and watching the bubbles slowly pop .  refreshing when ice cold , pleasantly balanced when it warms a bit .

the classic appearance is the widget induced/nitro-draft style , which produces a paler , more uniform head with typical nitro bubbles ( tighter ) . it was almost foamy and left a nice lacing on the glass from the four pulls i took . this is what a stout beer should look like , imho . perfect . the dark , almost black , appearance of the guinness is beautiful .  the carbonation is surprisingly strong for the style .
it pours a dark brown to almos black color with a huge fluffy tan to light brown head .  the mouthfeel is sort of watery , but it 's alright . this drinks very well .
poured a snny yellow with an impressive bright white head that stayed and stayed- rendering a lot of uneven side lacing .  this beer has a fairly heavy body , a bit too much for my tastes .

pours a beautiful dark brown with a slight ruby hue on the outer edges , nice thick microfoam head that leaves nice lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied to me . could be a little thicker on the tongue .

the smell is quite pungent . i can smell the glass from a foot away ! sweet caramel malts are picked up in the nose , but are nothing in comparision to the huge hops assault . it is very hop foward ( understatement ) . this is easily one of the most unique and bitter beers i have ever had . the hops oils make it quite slippery and oily going down .  it has a pretty high carbonation .
pours to an absolutely gorgeous deep golden/brownish-gold color with a decent amount of rich foam .  the palate is somewhat thin for the style but it 's still smooth .
a- this one pours out an opaque black as night colored body with a small coffee colored head on top .  m - thin with medium low carbonation d - not a bad amber .

body is significantly darker than i 'd expect out of a typical hefe , but not to the point that this should be called a dunkel ; kind of a thickly hazed tarnished bronze , with weird , grainy chunks of yeast . massively fruity , spicy , and complex . it 's nice to see japanese brewers stepping outside the box a little . sadly most of the other flavors from the nose are very subdued here , though the cidery sweetness remains . drinkability : this is one of those beers that 's more fun to smell than it is to drink , but it 's still pretty good . worth whatever exorbitant price i paid for it in nagasaki , but not as enjoyable as the pils .  m - thought it was a little flat , but not bad .

poured from the 22oz bomber into a belgian duvel glass . appearance- beer pours a clear brown with red hues with a finger thick cap of irish cream foam .  m : carbonation is a little weak ( especially since i poured moderately , and received an aggressive head ) leaving a mouthfeel thatis not strong enough for me to consider it cask-like . a little watery ... d : all things considered , i really enjoyed this beer .
impressive looking beer .  carbonation is a bit low for the style .

pours a gorgeous , deep garnet red - almost burgundy - with a large , rocky , creamy-tan head which dissipates slowly leaving heavy lace on the glass . not much for smell - faint floral hops and maybe a touch of sweet yeast .  i also find it a little thin .

a half inch of rich , russet-colored head temporarily lays upon a very dense cola brown body .  ill start this by saying i am not a lager drinker by any means . the smell is very summery with hints of citrus and the taste is very malty . the taste is very rounded and balanced . nothing is too harsh or overpowering it all just sort of settles around itself . would drink again !

330 ml bottle consumed at a certain way , on to the beer : it 's black with a some hues of ruby red . the head formed on top is extremly thick , is tanned in color , and still holds on top until the last sip . did i mention is shows some rings of lacing ?  mouthfeel is decent , this beer seems to foam up in your mouth .

the aroma is absolutely wonderful ... full of freshly crushed green , leafy and sweet hops . nice . the carbonation is mild to moderate . pleasantly surprised by this one..i thought this was going to be another average pale ale , but this very enjoyable .  m- medium body that was slightly under-carbonated . with more carbonation , all the flavors would bite that much more .

a - golden and slightly hazed with coppery highlights and a foamy , cushiony head that jets to the surface and clings to the glass like glue as it subsides . head retention is fantastic , and would be even without the aid of the etching at the bottom of the glass . fantastic .  m-explosive carbonation . tough to gauge the feel over the bubbles . a bit too carbonated for me .

boozy for sure . notes : the nose is pretty friggin ' great . the palate feels thin for the style and the flavors that it 's supporting .  very good light lager . hints of barley and hops , with a smooth slightly dry aftertaste . this brew had a short lived white foamy head and lower than normal carbonation . i would highly recommend this to any light beer drinker .

the nitro definately makes this beer look great . otherwise , it 's a pretty average ale .  i 'd love to try this on cask , if only to taste it more directly without all the carbonation dancing across my tongue .

aroma is tremendous . dark , rich , malty sugars . drinkability is horrid , just alcohol and thickness . cloying . i hope to get to review a better bottle at some point , as i can tell the flavors are there , but this bottle was not something i enjoyed .  in the glass , the elderberry dominates . the taste just off , sour in a nasty way , more like rotten fruit than any sort of pleasant tartness which might be expected from the berries . we gave this a decent try to see if it would get better , but in the end just could n't drink it .

s - if you like coffee , this is actually really nice . great roasted coffee and espresso aromas , along with a little unsweetened cocoa and vanilla .  body is light and a bit watery , not too syruppy at all .

pours a cloudy yellow with white high lights . the head is astounding . it is enormous and when the dust settles it remains a nice lacing .  m : crisp feel at first , mellows gradually before eventually becoming a little sticky/gummy . light-medium body .

a big , beautiful whack of tropical fruits on the nose - pineapple , passionfruit . superb . the tropical fruits are still there on the palate but perhaps a little more resinous than i was expecting .  t : bitter chocolates and cold black coffee .mmmmm m : a bit thin in the mouthfeel , slight warming in the finish which i found dry .
very nice ! the taste is more pronouced citrus fruit and pine that slowly reveals the malty backbone of fresh baked bread .  the body is pretty light though and clean .

thick brown head with moderate retention . excellent lacing throughout .  its sucks to know that in a different format this could be so much more . body and carb is okay , but by this point i 'm already at the meh stage .

the aromas are very fine and intense i was very impressed ! !  i was not a big fan of the mouthfeel of this one . i 'm all for thick imperial stouts , but somehow this one was much more syrupy than i liked , it felt a little to sticky sweet in my mouth .

poured a beautifully clear , clean amber golden color , with a huge 3 finger , frothy , white head . lacing was incredible on this one , totally covered from the top to the bottom of the glass when finished .  the taste is also very floral and hoppy , but its a smooth onset of flavors , doesnt smack you like other ipas , which ca be good or bad . the flavor doesnt last as long as other beers in this catagory . overall a pretty good beer , i think most peple will enjoy this one .

pours a beautiful crimson/brown color with a fluffy two finger head - as i move the beer around the head remains as one and sticks together , unwilling to fade away .  smell was sweet , with a citrus hint and strong english ale smell . initial taste was interesting , and i was n't sure about whether i would like it . by the end of the bottle , it had become one of the best beers i 've tasted . i would n't recommend it for any parties , but in small groups of like minded people i would say good call . very drinkable beer . looking forward to trying more from the brewery ( if i can find it )

glass : chimay goblet temp : cellared @ approx 45 degrees bottling date : 04-23-08 pours an exceptional clear golden amber color . minimal head that retains a light lacing all the way down .  the taste is also fresh but a with bit of watery mouthfeel .

i look at these two next to each other and woder if i have not walked into a paint shop and someone mixed my color swatch perfectly ... the aroma is fantastic . it has all the elments of a wonderful malt bomb , and just enough hop remnants to keep it interesting .  m : average , nothing of note .

creamy khaki foam tops off this american porter , the surface has a light sheen to it , forming uneven crags and peaks that push above the rim . sticky lacing is left all around , clumped in almost cartoonish 3-d . cola ruby color in the light , with slow trails of carbonation .  the only complaint i have is that the texture left much to be offered . overall i great beer .

pours a white zin looking pink . rosey orange color with a large white tuft . retention is a persistent layer of tiny bubbles that deposit themselves all over the glass . nice .  the only detraction i can fin is the below average body .
pours a pretty almost crystal clear pale orangish yellow with a nice two fingers of white foam topping it .  mouthfeel was ok .

this beer smells amazing . t : very roasty , lots of coffee , lots of chocolate , some sweetness in the background .  mouthfeel is on the thin side , but not bad . crisp , clean , pleasant in the end -- not overwhelming , a little tart .

a : poured into a tulip , leaves 3mm head throughout the session , light brown or burnt meringue in color . simple , but effective lacing .  under carbonated and somewhat thin bodied , there is a coffee flavored finish that is truly amazing .

immense multi-layered head with frothy , large bubbles at the base and fine meringue top . lasted for ever , leaving beautiful lacing behind .  flavor is more of the same with enough body to keep the brew honest . good mix of sweet and bitter and a weaker mouthfeel that allows for more on a warm summer day .

500ml swing top , vintage 2006 a - pours dark brown , nearly black into my snifter . when held up to the light the faintest brown hues shine hrough .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with low carbonation and is a bit watery .

s- smell is absolutely perfect . sweet , floral tones with a huge aromatic pineyness . t- taste is milder than expected from the ipaesque nose but good none the less .  the only thing i was not pleased with with this beer was the mouthfeel .
very impressive lager appearance .  it was watery with no carbonation , and had a bitter aftertaste . but it had good flavor and decent body , and was fairly clean and easy to drink .
gorgeous dark burgendy like ribena syrup . redy brown highlights , good head retention but minimal lace .  the carbonation is heavy and it adds harshness to the palate . medium-full body .

immense aromas hit the nose . plums and lilacs begin the assault , followed by maple and vanilla syrup and a touch of smokiness . this is a very complex ale , as most dfhs are , but the complexities do n't mask the big abv as well as their 120 minute ipa , imho .  drinkability - taste is pretty good , stays consistent throughout , isnt too thin , and has a reasonable abv so overall this would be a good beer to have a few of if you options are limited .
s - good smell , lots going on .  m - takes a major ding here for not having much carbonation . it has a medium body , but the lack of bubbles make this seem borderline watery .

exquisite aroma . lime zest , clover honey , white grapes , earthy yeast , ripe granny smith apples , and a spicy component of white pepper and coriander . taste opens very citrusy , with lemon pulp and lime zest notes but honey drenched summer green apple hints balance nicely . a hint of coriander underneath and a pleasant yeast character make for a complex and very tasty experience . excellent saison by any standards .  very carbonated feel on the tongue .

at long last i was finally able to snag the great westy 12 , pours a deep brown with a suprisingly thin head that was gone pretty quickly not leaving anything behind.whoa the aromas are just incredibly complex and rich , some almond and raisin almost a cinnamon bun type aroma to it , just awesome.flavors are more mellow than expected , i get some star anice and raisin up front with some mellow orange tinge in the lngering finish.i like the `` 12 '' better than the `` 8 '' but i have had some better quads but still a pleasure to drink for sure .  the mouthfeel is a bit harsh with the 8.0 % alcohol , but i have found very few tripels that can hide the alcohol content .

appearance - gold honeyed color in a belgian glass . extremely high effervescence yields 3 fingers of foam instantly . the soft bubbled head recedes unevenly to a thin solid cover .  taste : mirrors the smell , but the flavors are weaker than their aroma counterparts because of a thin mouthfeel .

the aroma of berry funk with a hint of crust that smells delicious . the appearance is rich pinot wine color with a white head and tons of berry sediment floating on top .  ) i would like a little more bready/chewiness as the mouthful feels a tad more thin than what i 'd prefer for this style .

rich with oak and dark malts , the aroma is a mine of chocolate , malted milk , coffee , molasses , figs , vanilla , walnuts , caramel , spiced with plenty of caraway , anise , tobacco , and floral hops . increasingly smoky as it warms , and very interesting ; the akavit is not subtle but well-incorporated with the base malt aromas . tangy and earthy on the palate , with a crisp caraway entrance and a long , luscious chocolate finish . juicy and rich yet sharp and bitter , this one balances coffee , citrus , licorice , oak , and red wine and yet it is n't quite as complex as the nose led me to believe . possibly an excellent match for game , assuredly for chocolate and blue cheese .  mouthfeel lots of fizzy carbonation , lighter bodied , finishes dry . the high carbonation combined with a thinner than usual mouthfeel really did throw off the beer making the flavors less prominent than i feel they could have been had the aforementioned two things been toned down a bit .

brilliantly clear light copper hue . creamy , dense well retained head . beautiful in appearance , but lacking in all around flavor .  as readily available as bud , and a whole lot better . a great fall-back session brew , which is good with a meal , or having several at a baseball game .
the nose was sweet , dominated by roasted malts , chocolate , treacle and burnt toffee , very pleasant indeed .  palate : medium body , thinner than expected actually , but goes down smooth .

a - black ad pitch .  t : wood chips , obviously , tastes like a sauna smells , charcoal , molasses , savory like breakfast sausage , soy sauce , real sharp sweetness that 's broken down by hops lurking in the background and that 's absent at the finish m : medium body , very low carbonation , i 'm surprised this was n't the cask ( it was n't but they did have it ) , dry bitter charcoal finish . the mouthfeel was a big drawback for me , it was very flat , considering this was the draft veraion .

the beer has a golden color with a hint of orange and features a wonderful malty aroma that is crisp and rich . the flavor is also crisp with some malt highlights and a pretty bitter aftertaste , and overall is heavier than i expected ( i was expecting something like a brewpub blond from this since they also offer a pale ale ) . my last swigs still get that great malt aroma wonderful ! !  feel is smooth and well-carbonated though a bit on the thin and watery side . medium-full body , not too heavy . leaves a nice sticky coating around the mouth . a bit thicker and less bitter and it 'd be great .

smell : the wonderful aroma starts with the smell of concord grapes . holy hell , this liquid smells amazing . its like a huge fruit salad mixed with brandy and raisins ! taste : so does it taste as good as it smells ? well , the taste is of plums , raisins , and maybe prunes .  the mouthfeel is just a little light for a tripel style . just a little watery and fairly light on the tongue .

wow ... the nose on this is excellent ! tons of roasted malts , coffee beans and dark chocolate . very nice ... the taste is n't quite as profound as the nose , but it holds up well . i am really glad i had the chance to try it ... after all , it has been on my wants list for some time .  m - nothing special . just a regular lager thing .
really quite nice and the flavors are very detectable .  texture is smooth but only slightly fizzy , leaving a slightly sweet fruity finish .
dark-brown/mahogany color with a full creamy tan head and good carbonation which leaves sheets of lace .  nothing spectacular in terms of mouthfeel , but i 'll buy it again .

just great . t : similar to the smell but with bit of smokiness .  the colour is a light straw , probably the weakest colour i have seen in a pale lager , the head is very pleasent and has some serious glass cling ... the aroma is very skunky when first opened but quickly disappears and the taste is highly sweet malts on a thin body , very nice for dining , not a stadium brew ... i first reviewed this brew in march of 03 , approx 10 monthes ago .

bottled april 22 , 2009 poured into a pint glass amber with a very thick white head . very good retention and lacing .  have you ever canned tomatoes ? if you have , you should be familiar with the smell and flavor tomatoes have when cooked . this beer had an overwhelmingly strong odor and taste of spicy stewed tomatoes . it was too strong to drink . i know this is not normal for this beer from the other reviews of it i have read ( and the style does n't allow for many strong flavors ) , but it was only days past the best by date and had been stored in a refrigerator . there was also some floating particles in the beer which i also assume is not normal , pilsners typically being filtered . i will come back and rerate , but i 've been told by some fellow raters that i should take this beer into account for my rating .
pours a vibrant and dark golden orange . totally clear with a slightly off white head that is sticky and thick .  mouthfeel was ok ; about the same as urquell .

this does throw a great looking pour into my glass .  it smells of rotten banana peels , rotten apples , and molding compost . the flavors are very sweet and kind of medicinal . it leaves a clove laiden aftertaste behind , making you think you just had an artificial banana milkshake . i just do n't understand what two brothers was going for on this one .

great retention and great lacing , too .  this is a very good pumpkin beer . picked a 6 pack up at the local market , came home on a chilly night here in rural mi , and my girlfriend and i finished the whole six pack . lots of pumpkin taste , beautiful color , and an overall great seasonal choice . i would n't drink it in warm weather , but on this cool fall night , it hit the spot . i could see picking this up in the future to bring to a bon fire , or to enjoy while i hand out candy on halloween . cheers !

pours a deep brown with ruby highlights into a tulip . creamy off-white/light khaki head leaves excellent lacing and retention .  initial taste of a sparkling mouthfeel with a puckering sour cherries that coat the mouth incredabily . the palate duration is average . medium body .

the medium amber-copper beer shows bright clarity while building a dense froath of lightly tanned foam while leaving broken patterns of lace behind . a very classy look .  less fizzy than anticipated in the mouth .

the head poured out at 1.5 fingers and stays that way forever in a rocky , creamy form that just refuses to recede . gorgeous appearance .  nice dark brown color with fantnaztic lacing ! smells choclotly with coffee . tastes even and thick with cocoa sweet caramel flavors continuing thru . good for its class this porter represents well , its much better than its younger brother . would drink again .

a - a beautiful pour . deep amber with an inch of off-white head . as the head slowly goes away it leaves great lace and ends up in a creamy , bumpy layer on top of the brew .  i wish the carbonation was a little more noticeable in the mouth .

the look is awesome : clear golden color with a great head and excellent lace .  a : dark reddish copper ; flat head ; strong carb ; not much lacing s : strong raspberry aroma , very inviting ; occludes other smells t : expected sweet -- it is n't ; the raspberry dominates , but it 's quite sour , draped over a wheat-beer-like base ; i must confess , this tasted terrible to me ; it tasted like nothing else i 've had , so i do n't think this is something against the genre m : good carbonation redeems the experience a bit overall , a terrible beer , for me .
this is one of the best smelling beers i have ever had .  i like a little heavier of a mouthfeel than this offers , but the lighter feel is not surprising considering the crystal appearance .
the color is pitch black . head is large , creamy , and dark tan .  it is about a medium mouthfeel , with almost no carbonation .
the beer pours a delightful orange/amber with a heavy off-white head .  mouthfeel is fairly thin but not unpleasant .

it has a great thick fluffy dark mocha colored head perched upon a jet black body . the head was still present a good 5 minutes after pouring .  mouthfeel is a bit too thin , especially in view of the heavenly head and ample lacing .
excellent retention . something you could stick your finger in and feel the foams welcoming grasp .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with medium to high carbonation .
appearance- clear , dark , copper-colored ale with persistent , cream head . full carbonation . lots of lacing .  m : um . it was carbonated and did n't leave any odd off flavours on the palate .
bottle poured into a tulip glass . brilliant clarity . thick white crop of foam with good retention and moderate lacing .  a sticky medium body with good carbonation . a bit too sticky for me .

pours a hazy light blonde colour , with a very fine bubbled and retentive white head . really its absolutely spot on for the style .  the taste is awesome m : medium bodied , perhaps a bit too heavy , with decent carbonation , not the best , but is good enough for an apa .
pours out an apricot color with a good deal of carbonation in the body and a huge , creamy head with dimples all along the top .  the body was light and there was not enough carbonation .
750ml bottle ( cork & cage always cool ) purchased at carmel mtn . fruit in the nose , sweet apricot perhaps . slightly musty , too .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but thats a minor complaint .

clear straw with a dash of red thrown in , the luscious billowing head practically crawls down the side of the glass like spider webs getting torn from a window .  s - some grassy hops paired with caramel malt t - slight hop bitterness resolving into some serious roasty malt , but then it 's all gone fairly quickly with just a hint of woody bitterness m - quite light with just a hint of carbonation on the back of the tongue ; the slight bitterness endures for a whlie d - quick drinkable , though the excessive roasty malt will probably get in the way ; little to no alcohol warmth nice drink ; did n't expect it to be as dark as it is - listed as an american porter , but it 's almost a supercharged brown ale .

a : aptly yclept schwarzbier ( blackbeer ) -- dark opaque black with a frothy head and a ruddy hue around the edges . i like the way this looks . s : not much at all .  first off , great pics , great blurb on the back , just fantastic presentation . this beer is belgian to the core , color , nose , taste . there 's an abject fizziness to the brew i could do without , reminds me of shasta in the summer of my youth , a memory i did n't need to dredge up . taste is sweet & light . barring the cost , this is the kind of beer i could drink all night . this is a solid beer , but not the hellion i was expecting .
