in the very bottom of my glass , i can see rust colored highlights coming through . the head is creamy looking and a very inviting light brown that makes me think of `` mocha '' for some reason .  the mouthfeel is thin , however , and it 's over-carbonated .
had awesome retention and never showed signs of totally leaving .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied .

; save water , shower with a friend . i got a full , finger 's worth of deep brown head with good retention . color was a deep , dark brown with ruby highlights and ne-quality clarity .  rated as a stout the mouthfeel is a bit thin , the carbonation is a bit high , and the finish is a bit less than one would expect .
smell is dark fruit , roasted malts , vanilla , oak , and a touch of coffee/chocolate .  mouthfeel is light , and carbonation is set at medium .
the smell is wonderful , but what happened in the translation to taste ?  light bodied for what i was expecting , but then it does n't claim to be a porter or stout .
pours a dark brown colour with a frothy thick tan head .  some hop aroma and flavour , a little to light in the body for my liking .

very still with incredible lacing s - dry roasted malts , sugar and bread , a touch of spice t - earthy roasted malts , dry corn , very malty with a mild hop finish m - nitro tap gives a creamy smoothness that makes it super sessionable o - really great !  alex dumped this on this ! ... pours an ugly apple cider color , murky medium brown , not much carbonation ... the aroma is terrible , generic wood , rotting pears , and vanilla . ca n't stand this ... the taste is dry hopped wood ; a piece of wood that was drenched in dry hopped water . this is ugly , and smells and tastes terrible . skip
the aroma is sweet fruits and some spice including coriander , orange peel is present as well .  mf : a bit thin , light body , medium to high carbonation d : another winner from sierra nevada .

poured a deep dark reddish-brown into my guinness pint glass , and the tan head reached the top . beautiful .  active carbonation to form lacing but it does n't feel on the heavy end of the carbonation spectrum .

aroma is full of floral notes and hoppy sweetness . gummy ... lavender ... spicy ... oh so nice ... smooth on the palate ... a smallish touch of burn on the way down the throat . more balanced than i was expecting ... a nice sweetness up front and a good bitter back-end .  m : medium light body with medium high carbonation .
just when you think you have seen it all when it comes to beer appearances , this one comes along . strangely fascinating looking beer .  but a little watery .

the appearance is the best attribute of this beer for it is a nice amber-brown and has a steady head that leaves rings of lace .  mouthfeel & drinkability : lighter bodied and less bitter than most other ipas , which makes for quite easy drinking .

brilliantly clear , tawny copper hue . pitted , steadfast ivory white head . persistent , massed lace trails .  the nose of the beer is strong and gives off a nice floral hop aroma . the flavor is sweet and semi-tart with fruity tastes . behind the sweet fruit , there is a slight but smooth alcohol presence . the earthy hop bitterness comes in at the end and fades away with the semi-dry finish .

s - toffee , cocoa powder , nutty , then as it warms sweet citrus oil , green pine needles . slabs of caramel mix with alcohol vapors and fill the glass with a robust sweetness . t - starts with a mix of semi/sweet chocolate , sweet toffee malt , then an undertow of hops rush in with mint and citrus . the aroma is so good it 's hard to explain .  mouthfeel : a bit thin the only thing i can say i 'm disappointed about here just seems watery i even recall the original munich formula having more body but hey sturdy carbonation excellent o-fest .

serving type : 16oz bottle appearance : pours a darker cloudy orange colour w/ a 1 finger head . plenty of lacing the whole time while drinking .  m : a bit overcarbonated , dry , thin , light-medium bodied .
pours with a big foamy white head . fades to 1/2 finger and has great retention from there .  m - the hops lingered a bit too long and had a metallic feel at times .
slight visible carbonation , a very nice looking brew .  decent carbonation , a little thin on the malt profile for the style .

the most beautiful foamy head i 've ever seen , and it lasts forever in the duvel glass , sitting atop a gold so intense it almost glows .  i am starting to view the boston beer co. as a-b or miller taking a stab at the craft market but still wanting to appease the masses rather than being strict to beer styles . a big dissapointment for an apa

smell : by far the most enjoyable aspect of this beer . the smell is incredibly complex with a strong prune backbone and hints of everything from lemon to chocolate . i like smelling it more than drinking it .  m : medium body and high carbonation .

it poured a beautiful copper color with lots of bubbles coming up from the bottom of my beer-clean glass . the beer had abundant head that agressively stuck to the side of my glass and slowly and inconsistently faded , starting from the middle of my glass . this beer really was quite attractive .  ( i actually do not care for this sweetness , but the beer still has great flavor ) m : nice carbonation , but the body is a little weak .

smell was very enjoyable with lots of wheat , lemon , banana , and hints of honey . thumbs up . t : followed the nose nicely with touches of wheat , lemon and banana that are felt in the tongue as soon as you sip the beer . the good smell and taste made up for the weak appearance .  if you closed your eyes and smelled this you would think your smelling a good octoberfest beer due to the scent of carmalized malt and faint hops . has a carmel toasted nut flavor on the tounge and finished dry . i like the fact that this irish red is a little more bitter than most red ales but still not overpowering . tongiht i will be reviewing 4 of hook and ladder beers as i bought a gift pack that came with 3 bottles of 4 different beers . the beers i got were backdraft brown golden ale pipe and drum irish red ember amber ( a type of black and tan made with their backdraft brown ale and golden ale ) . try these beers if u can find them they are good

just unbelievable . on the palate the beer is very good , but does n't blow my socks off . very nice beer from stone brewing .  m - decent body with a bit more carbonation than i 'd like from this style .

aroma is `` off the chain , '' as the kiddies say nowadays . rather than compete and muddle all these scents meld into a unified aroma of awesome . perfect .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin and harsh from the acidity and carbonation . also finishes quite dry with little to no bitter .

earthy , weedy , hoppy , piney ! a real west coast ipa . love it ! not for the faint of heart hop haters , but awesome for hop lovers ! definitely interesting with tropical fruit hints in this one . mouthfeel : deliciously crisp and oily .  m - light body , with a carbonation level that is probably too sharp for the style .
from a bottle , chilled , it pours a pale gold color with some haze , along with 1cm of white bubbly head that sustains nicely .  malty and corny .

pours out very clear straw color with plenty of carbonation and a rich frothy white head that lingers and laces , truly beautiful .  slight hint of the hop flower but the malt dominates , sweet , crisp , fresh and pleasing to the senses with the start lightly sweet , satisfactory malt presence , and top light to middling in feel . this is a style where i like the lighter body , as it lets the flavoring hops shine through , quite quaffable , a damn fine session beer me thinks , and i thank royalt for this bottle .

awesome looking brew . s : wow , what a nose on this beer . sweet smelling with fruity esters along with some spiciness as well .  m-its a little undercarbonated but the balance of the sweetness with the malt and subtle hops make for a relitivly complex october beer . d-easy to drink and very nice to have this time of year , easy to session .

aroma exhibited a very nice floral hop bouquet . light and sweet with a hint of spiciness . this beer smells excellent and is not overpowered by the hops .  m - smooth and thick , but hard to hold onto . unpleasant taste does n't do it well .

firstly , i dont know if the nitro can should be listed alongside the on-tap version , because they are completely different , as the on tap version is far superior than the widget-can . anyway , if kept well , the pour is the classic we have all come to know and love .  m : mouthfeel is decent , goes down reasonable smooth even with the slight burning sensation .

appearance- one of the best looking belgian pale 's i have seen . a large 2 inch big bubbled head which 1/4 inch remains until the last drop is consumed . excellent lacing stuck to the entire rounded wall of my glass .  the body is surprisingly light with moderate carbonation , helping to make this very drinkable .

s : a typical fff piney , citrus hop parade hits you strong up front , with delicious burnt cocoa , cinnamon , and brown sugar following . an epic nose that promises much . t : unfortunately , the nose can not keep it 's promise . there is still some malt left underneath , but it is just not coming through like it does in the nose . as a huge fan of toasty porters and stouts , it ; 's kind of a let down for me .  unfortunately , it is basically flat , with a heavy mouthfeel . overall , this beer would be unbelievable with good carbonation .
huge tropical fruit aromas on this one -- passion fruit , mango , pineapple and bubble gum . creamy , with a good warming alcohol finish .  m- very carbonated and light for a lager .

a - pours black with a creamy tan head that dissipates fairly quickly to a thin , but dense , covering . good amount of lacing left behind .  mouthfeel is a bit fizzy , and another beer where bottle-conditioning would have a positive impact .

a- very good looking . best retention i have seen for this style yet .  much like the ingredient list on the back , there are scent of malted barley , malted wheat , hops , and yeast which gives it an almost caramel scent . starts out making you think this will be a heavy tasting beer with its malted ingredients like a stout but instead it finishes rather light . drinks rather smooth as the malted ingredients really hit the taste buds . finishes rather clean smooth . a decent beer with a rather interesting drinking experience .
a : moderate pour yields 1.25 fingers dense tan head with superb retention . a beauty .  mouthfeel is about average for an ipa .

it was truly beautiful , and left something more than lacing , almost a vanilla milkshake looking coating on the glass .  the mouthfeel is a bit watery and cool in texture , it goes down nicely and is a little bit better than water .
perfect lacing . very good retention .  mouthfeel was unremarkable .

if this beer is to live up to its awesome appearance ( and awesome name ) , it needs to be much more robust in all departments , especially mouthfeel .  drinks a little heavy because of all the sediment but feels watery and thin on the palate . adequate carbonation but not incredible lively .
pours a dramatic thundercloud of head , beige/tan and mountainous , rocky .  m : thin , do n't take that the wrong way though but easy drinking .

a- black beer into ayinger glass , huge head with infinite retention , probably 4 fingers on average . nice light mocha color and a ton of lace everywhere .  has a very light mouth feel , which makes it a more-then-one beer .

the smell has that fruity scent that just says dfh in my mind , must be the local weather . lots of subtle scents here and i am sure i am not picking them all out .  mouthfeel is a little thin and aftertaste is a little too much ... like the brew has gone stale , although i know it has n't .
pours a lager-yellow , huge creamy white head that dissipates down to a film leaving very much lace . nice looking beer .  m : a little thin in body d : good .

the nose piques my interest in this brew as the aroma is highly reminiscent of a belgian triple with strong esters of alcohol , yeast , and caramelized sugar . entry is muted until the midtaste takes over by blanketing the tongue with a thick coating of honey . my numbers reflect my overall impression of this brew ... nice appearance , great nose , overpowering honey midtaste & finish .  take this beer for what it is ... a nice `` treat . '' it 's not something you will want to drink all night long . but for a nightcap , or change of pace this beer fits the bill . the vanilla taste is not overpowering , it 's there , but not so bold and overpowering that it seems fake .

appearance - deep muted red , like the embers of a fire almost . the head is light beige in color , extremely dense and creamy like melted marshmallows on hot chocolate . the lace is a full blanket all the way around the glass .  the mouthfeel is decent , but could be a bit more robust to support the flavors .

single bottle from town & country liquor , on to the beer : slghtly murky orange amber color in my pint glass , the head sticks well together on top and is thick . great retention .  i got this beer in the beers of the world gift box for christmas . immediate taste is a lil sharp and bready with a hint of citrus in the smell . it was not an out of this world experience , but it is a very light and enjoyable beer for everyday or get togethers .

stamp directly on top of the white , generic cap announces : bottl 2008* a dark caramel body with a significant amount of sediment floating around that were actually dark in appearance . topping all of that is a nice , creamy white head that sticks around for several minutes . very cool look .  presentation 11.2 oz ''ceramic '' bottle with blue foil over the cap no date on bottle . pours with a think creamy head that dissipates as quickly as is rose . light brown with a hind of deep red . a smell of caramel and alcohol , taste is more of the same with a slight earthiness to it . finishes cleanly .

the appearance is a deep coffee color , heading almost to burgundy . the light tan head is large and resistant , preventing me from quickly getting into it .  m- a little thin , but not too bad . nicely carbonated , with a slight bitter hoppiness at the tail end .

s : very nice smell here with wood tones in the nose and some great hop/malt balance .  but it has quite a few pros : this beer is intended to be consumed with food . if you want to have chinese food with a light drink then this one is just what you are looking for ! it 's a typical lager : crystal-clear blonde , discreet taste and weak aroma . i usually do n't drink lager beers but this one i can have by the barrels while there 's food on the table . this beer is what you want to drink when you do n't want to drink !

this beer poured an opaque black with an exceedingly abundant head .  i 've always liked this beer , and if they beefed up the abv and gave it a little more body , it would be the perfect porter . why grant 's beers share these characteristics i do n't know , but if they ever did beef 'em up a little , they could truly be a contender .

a : pours a pale lemon/lemonade color with a hazy body full of carbonation and bubbles . head has good retention , about 2 fingers thick , with beautiful lacing .  t & m : for a doppelbock a little thinner bodied than is usually expected .

like nocturnum , my favorite of the delirium family , this beer has nice white fluffy head . the beer pours orange/gold , and the head lasted through the entire glass .  the middle is kind of hoppy , but somewhat thin . the finish is dry and quite hoppy . a decent light beer .
it pours a pretty orange-amber color , and is crystal clear . a huge two+ finger , pillowy , rocky , bone white , head .  mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .
appearance- deep brown-caramel colored pour . leaves wonderful lace streaks and patches . almost the entire glass was caked with lace after i was finished .  this is a bit thin , but still great .

pours thick and pitch black , no light can penetrate this . has a nice sized brown head that fades to medium ring that leaves an awesome lace .  i have had ipas that went down a bit smoother but this one is n't bad it still goes down good but with just a little more carbonation and bite .

this one sure looks like an ipa , pouring a nice copper color with a huge head that leaves nice sheets of sticky lacing on the side of the glass .  mouthfeel was very thin for the style , but added to the higher level of drinkability .
the brew pours a slightly darker golden color with a huge , creamy , rocky white head that sticks around for a while .  mouthfeel is a bit light .

a : pours a yellowish orange color , like apple juice with a little fizz ; head is huge and rocky , foamy and thick , like something out of a bubble machine ; yeast sediments sink to the glass bottom upon pour and settling s : everything you 'd expect from a belgian strong ale ( dark or light ) , with complex , sweet dark candied and dark fruit aromas ; however , there is a hint of dry , hoppy citrus and bitterness just underneath the heavy sweetness ; definite booze smell as the beer warms t : the first flavor is alcohol , but not in a sharp , unpleasant way ; it 's there , but tempered with the great and significant sweetness only found in belgian strongs ; great maltiness ; sweetness ranges from tropical fruit flavors to bits of caramel , vanilla , cloves and banana ; m : smooth and heavy up front ; warm , tingly on the tongue ; finishes with a surprising and welcomed touch of dryness that finishes in a refreshing and crisp way ; amazing ! maybe i 'm just an american , but this one 's damn good .  surprisingly light mouthfeel makes it a fairly easy drinker for a 9 % er

aroma of a quad / stout mix with the figs , plums and spices plus a hint of grape hi-c infused vanilla . full bodied , viscous without being cloying , chewy . the alcohol is amazingly restrained , not even the inherent warmth you 'd expect at this abv level .  mouthfeel : light/ medium body with excessive carbonation that somewhat hinders the flavor .

it smells awesome , everything works together and you get something else every whiff no issues here t much more booze then the nose , more toffee , smoke , and fruit with some burnt brown sugar , still very nice but without as much balance m enters silky then the bubbles make it feel creamy , quite thick and the flavors linger , the heat lingers too and that 's my only complaint in this area o for a big fresh barley wine i thought it was pretty good , the barrel agings there but not overpowering and its oh so mellow i was hoping this one would suck so i would n't need to buy a couple of them to age , pretty expensive but this would be amazing after some time , pretty mellow considering the 13.8 % fresh i can only imagine this 5 years down the road  medium body , maybe even a bit thin .

a dark body that exhibits a reddish tinge when held up to the light , with thick lacing spiraling down the side .  the only downside of this beer was the mouthfeel , which was fairly flat and watery , probably due in part to the low % abv .

appearance : pours a deep black with hints of red and a thick beige head that will not dissipate . this is one of the most enticing beers that i have ever seen .  a really really long aftertaste in the nose .
head retention is outstanding , and the glass is coated nicely . great looking beer .  a little less carbonation and this probably enters `` special '' territory .

aroma is rich and complex : sweet , sticky maltiness rich in caramel , accompanied by a ripe fruitiness and a good deal of citrusy hops . i do n't detect any oakiness .  yack ! i 've had this lots over the years , but this time it got a major problem with butterscotch . aroma smacks me down wth that butterscotch - ugh . but , somewhere in there is some malt and a little chocolate , good malt . flavor is butterscotch - blaaahh . ca n't finish it . draft lines are clean here too . no more , pleeeeze

smell is mighty fruity with loads of banana and some vanilla .  smell : balanced scent with undertones of both malt and hops ; predominant smell is faintly sweet yet mainly grainy aroma . taste : well-balanced flavor , neither hops nor malts are predominant , the combination of which is apparent throughout the beginning and middle , dissapating for a clean finish . drinkability : refreshing and palatable , the quality of yuengling speaks for itself . definitely a beer that can be enjoyed regularly .

2009 batch 2 a - pours a nice beautiful red that is a cross between a tomato and an orange . a nice pinkish 3 finger bubbly , foamy head that goes does down to about 1 finger . beautiful .  light-medium bodied with crisp high carb .

aromas are deliciously grapes , plums , candied sugars , and lots of fresh mild fruits .  ordered this one in a taproom and was vary pleased . this beer is solid , as one might expect from north coast . it 's is as good as any pilsner i 've had . it drinks easy , has a hint of subtle fruit flavor , and smells very good . it also pours very nicely from the tap with a fluffy head . i 'd pick this one again on draft and might pick it up as a favor for a host when a house guest .

bronze coloured with a big head and marvellous slightly citrus , very herbal nose . hops dominated with a very distinctive lemon rind flavour to the fore .  does smell a little like `` beer , '' as my wife would say . so sweet on the tongue . slight raspberry tartness but it is like drinking raspberry sorbet after it melts . it is still trying to recover from the sweetness . a good once in a while beer . sorbet beer , i tell ya .

drank from a gouden carolus goblet a : black as darkest night -- - i held it up to a light , and nothing passed through . if dark beers scare you , do n't go here ... otherwise though , it is a thing a beauty .  there is a very little carbonation factor in this beer .

a : fantastic clarity , golden , and a relentless head , a 3 millimeter head is still visible after 20 minutes , leaving rings of lace in its wake .  im stoked i can try a beer from this brewery even tho it is a collaboration but ive got nothing but good things to say about mikkeller and heard good reviews on these other two so looking forward to it , it pours a very light honey hue with decent carbonation that leaves a one finger head with sporadic lacing , the aroma is floral hops , apricot , bananna and a nice belgian yeasty aroma too , it has an average mouthfeel for the style almost syrupy and has tastes of yeasty bread , citrus and of course a pleasant floral hop finish with the alcohol well hidden , this is definately an easy beer to drink and if it didnt cost $ 18 ( aus ) i could drink it all night .

pours a deep orange copper hue into my chalice glass with an off white head forming thick and even with fine detailed lacing .  i picked this lager over the ale 's offered , due to the miserable heat wave here in no . cal . it was an appropriate choice . saaz hops seemed to be prominent with good malt base . a nice refreshing beer . nothing spectacular but very acceptable when in the mood for this style .

from a bottle , poured into a pint glass a - deep black color with a mocha head .  body is medium , and perhaps errs to light every once in a while , which does n't help the flavours as much as it could .
great retention and great lacing .  m - smooth going down , a bit thin , finishes dry .

had this one just a few minutes ago , and i have to say i 'm was very impressed . gorgeous presentation especially in a decorated glass german stein .  m- a little too carbonated for my liking , that makes this beer have a little `` sting '' to it ( especially if it is served too cold ) .
great looking pour for a white ale .  easy drinking but it has a different mouthfeel , it almost leaves a film in my mouth .

half inch of dense creme colored head . brown in color with an orange glow when held to light . good lacing and a welcomed layer of retention after settling .  its perfectly balanced and not overly done . m very medium , which i find most all stone beers to be and i dont really complain about . the carbonation is present and isnt overly aggressive or submissive .

a deep mahogany appearance with thick lacing on the sides gave this a beautiful appearance . i emailed the location and i guess what makes it unique is its cross between a red ale and a stout .  all of the good notes that a belgian has , with some american notes such as a much higher rate carbonation , more citric fruitiness . the high carbonation almost makes me question whether or not it 's natural , but i doubt stone would rape this brew with added co2 like the macros do .
huge four fingers of bright white , soapy head .  it feels very thin in the mouth , close to water .

nose : an absolutely great floral hop aroma consumes the nose . very nice ! it has a fantastic aroma , a great hop bite but a low ibu and low abv . one word : impressive .  mouthful : somewhat over-carbonated but generally decent mouthfeel .

a - dark , rich copper color , clear . large head that reminded me of fluffy meringue .  beer/brewery - old fezziwig ale/boston beer company ( samuel adams ) city/state- boston , massachusetts style winter warmer abv 5.9 % ibu 27 date 10 dec 2011 serving type 12 oz bottle glassware pub glass appearance mahogany in color with a thin head with a brownish white color aroma- fruity and winter spices , all spice , clove and nutmeg i think taste pumpkin pie without the pumpkin , a lot of clove , also has a bit a of a bitter ( non hop ) after taste mouthfeel very light and bland ob feeling conclusion other than the after taste this is a great christmas beer , not quit a winter warmer as they abv is a little low , but still a good flavor to think of around christmas .
very nice scent , potent citrus and floral hops .  light body with a very active carbonation .

the foamy white heads even offers a nice lacing as it recedes ever so slowly .  could use more malt or residual sweetness but for a regular american coffee stout it does the trick mouthfeel is a touch thin and watery but there is a bit of creaminess from the nice carbonation that keeps this one going .

a - wow , the gentlest of pours brings forth a beautiful ( slightly clouded due to my misjudgment ) light orange brew with the most ridiculous pillowy head i have ever seen , four fingers to start , sticks around for what seems like forever , and leaves great lacing s - pear and apple , along with a little cut grass , lemon zest , lots of yeast , clove and pepper t - smooth maltiness , slightly tart , with a lot of green apple , a little fresh hay , some yeasty goodness .  the reason behind that tenacity turns out to be that it 's a bit overcarbonated . there 's a great nuttiness in the flavor here that i 'm seeing as chesnuts , but it could be the power of suggestion , and a little bit of roast . tasty , but just a tad too gassy .

poured out of the bottle into my samuel smith 's pint glass a jet black in color with a nice 2 finger tannish-brown head that settled to about one finger after a few minutes .  mouthfeel if very alive and crisp at first sip . maybe a bit overpowering on the carbonation .

500 ml bottle poured into a stella challis a - creamy , foamy 2-finger head . cloudy , dark-apricot orange . rings of foam stay on the glass as the glass is drunk .  i found that the beer smelled and tasted rather skunky , unlike most other beers that i had tasted and was deeply disappointed by it . it felt ok in the mouth and looked very nice in its green bottle but was not worth my time .

on tap at the pub ... the body is bright dark orange , but totally clear , very cool . an off white head leaves a thin cap , with great lacing , stellar ... the aroma is really successful in that the citra hops come across as orangey and sweet but they are literally cut but the balance of the other hops which reigns it in with some nice bitter pine .  it 's almost too sticky and thick to be pleasureable , kind of like a toned-down bourbon county stout . i 'm not a big fan of the finish , which comes off like sweet wort of a stout ( oily and a bit thin ) . m : very thick , with some relief , but then a lingering silkiness .
looks great . almost pitch black body with a massive tan head that is both dense and puffy . head retention is excellent and lacing is substantial .  m : medium mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

the smell is strong of both a carmel brandy and a little alcohol is evident . the alcohol that was apparent in the scent is not in the mouthfeel , which is very nice .  the mouthfeel is medium with some sharp carbonation .
a : attractive drink on the pour , looks like a lighter , creamier guinness pint from a good tap . huge head and flowing bubbles .  feel is thin bodied overall , but well bodied for the style .

had this at a recent ba gathering at milly 's , and brought a growler home . this is a beautiful beer : as black as can be , with a thick coffee-colored head .  this is the least impressive quad from the trappist breweries ... do n't get me wrong , it has a similar taste profile , although not that perfect as a westy 12 or a rochefort 10 , dark fruit , plums , candy sugar , but i did n't like the mouthfeel on this one . too much sparkling going on ... pretty funny thing is i just absolutely endlessly adore the la trappe quadrupel oak aged batch 1 version ... so so so much better then the regular one , especially when the oak aged version , bottled this summer , is coming around fantastic ! i like their dubbel more too .

pours a very dark and opaque brown , almost black , very thick brown head forms , settles to a big thick ring around the glass , lots of sticky lacing , about as perfect as a stout can look .  m : thin mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .

smells fantastic . spicy , fruity and different . really intriguing . tastes similar to the aroma -- some malty , almost candy-like , sweetness underneath , but with a strong bitterness taking centre stage .  the mouthfeel is larger light with a very , very slight fizz .

fosters lager pours a crystal clear light golden color with a beautiful thick foamy head that rides way above the lip of the glass and stays .  ( m ) - this is where the beer starts to fail in my opinion .

a - very nice lacing left by a frothy white head with strong stamina on top of a copper colored and translucent body . i even witnessed the bartender pouring some head away .  m : mouthfeel is a bit thin , considering how robust the initial flavor is .

aroma : sweet candy like roasted chocolate , burnt marshmellow , citrus and spicey hop arma . smells so good ! appearance : clear , dark brown with ruby highlights . this beer kind of dissapointed me becasue the hop aroma is supposed to be a lot more intense . i was expecting a burst of hop aroma which was n't really there . this is a well brewed beer and very tasty .  mouthfeel : thin yet flavorful .
excellent lacing . a great looking beer .  good carb , but feels a bit thin and watered down in general .
the best looking beer in the world , & one of the tastiest .  mouthfeel is fairly carbonated , a bit sour , finishing dry and crisp .

a : pours a cloudy dark brown that barely lets any light through ; fat 3 finger-width head , sticky lacing s : floral winter spices -- nutmeg , rosemary , sweet flowers t : wheaty , slightly funky tartness ; tastes of flowers with a small hint of rosemary ; not much honey , little bit of raisins ; finishes with a sharp boozy bitterness .  i 've never had this in europe because there are too many good beers over there to risk the experiment , but does it taste better over there ? anyway . the carbonation is nice and the golden hue is lovely . but the smell and the taste are the real reason i drink a beer and this one fails . sorry . i would prefer any american macro brew to this and i will drink alum for the buzz before i 'll drink those so this must be a bad beer .

a : pours amber color , small white head , slight lacing down the glass s : smell is very citrusy , slight malt background t : taste is also very citrusy .  the feel is a little odd . it does n't seem to be too carbonated , but the bubbles sting like sprite against your lips .
i like the flavor and am very impressed by the aroma it offers .  lively carbonation is a bit excessive , but the body is quite smooth .

frothy head retention and lacing is outstanding .  12 oz bottle poured into weizen glass , only glass i could get at my buddy 's house a : great pale golden color , light head with decent retention , great clarity s : great floral aromas t : not a pale ale that is actually an ipa , not overly bitter and slight maltiness m : good carbonation , could be a little thinner o : great pale ale , not just a copy of other american pale ales .

very little head to speak of , thin collar of dense white bubbles s : deep notes of dark chocolate , carob , molasses , and a hint of coffee . the flavors are very mellow but well integrated . t : the taste does n't translate into being as good as the smell suggested , the smooth chocolate is there , but turns into a slightly sharp flavor by mid palate and has a slightly metallic finish .  magic hat usually disappoints me , not that their brews are n't good , it 's that some of them just are n't tasty- till now . magic hats roxy rolles is right up there with ithaca 's cascazilla and troegs hopback amber . a definite seasonal must have for me . great ! ! !
nothing wrong with the way it looks . clear and golden , great head .  very basic but very good m= average carbonation and average weight .

pours a dark brown black with a medium cream light brown head that slowly goes to a thin film that laces the glass .  mouthfeel - foam is scarce and small bubbles and light caramel that fades quickly . slightly thin .

as soon as i opened the bottle , i was smacked with a heavy hoppy smell , easily reminded me it 's an ipa i 'm dealing with . s : an amazing combination of hops , pine , citrus , maybe some grape . t : interesting , with the token ipa hoppiness being the most notable aspect of it all . d : daunting at first , especially for me , not a huge fan of ipas , but i have to respect this beer . the dynamic flavor-smell combinations are remarkable , and though it 's not my favorite , the never-departing flavor may be the reminder that it is something to be reckoned with .  m - surprisingly , its a bit thin and lacks carbonation .
looks like a magazine beer ad . beautiful clear , light , orange-amber color .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and the carbonation is too light in my opinion .

`` mad bitch '' has an great look . upon pouring it creates a beautiful white head that lasts for the duration of the drink . the beer is an opaque , honey color that is incredibly appetizing .  m : medium body with a sticky quality when it enters the mouth .

browning 's bourbon barrel imperial stout pours a very nice , pitch black into a snifter with a small , light tan head that leaves lots of lacing behing .  mf- raw resinous and sticky , becoming oily , medium carbonation , slightly astringent , dry and grainy in the finish d- well rounded ipa , but not the best around .

pours a rich golden orange , excellent clarity , good carbonation , topped by a level one finger slab of snow white foam .  this review is from notes in my `` travel journal . '' obviously the beer is now `` retired . there is some berry in the attack . the flavor smoothes out to leave a clean finish . it is a very drinkable beer , but not what i normally seek out .

it had an excellent , crisp citrus kind of scent to it . very sweet , very unique . i did n't love it , but appreciated how different it was .  bought this over a month to two months a go and decided to give it a go . it is an ipa so it does have a nice bright orange to copper color . the taste and the smell are sweet and fruity , the only bad thing i have to to say about it , is the taste of tea is very lacking . i cant pick it up but , other than that i wish that stone , ishii and baird made this more as a yearly offering , cause its really good

from notes a - good dark black body with a medium brown head s - delicious sweet chocolaty bourbon t - dry smoky bourbon and vanilla . o ( d ) - tasty , great smelling . a 6 oz bottle split 4 ways can make it difficult to judge . but very enjoyable  i think this batch was contaminated . so , this review only applies to the specific beer i drank . it had a floral hop finish . so , that extra ester punch made it deviate too much from the pale ale style . so i ca n't say i liked it , i 'd try again and find a better batch .

the nose is bursting with scents of fresh-squeezed oranges , pineapple , guava . good full-bodied ipa with plenty of carbonation zip . i expected more of a fruity-tasting ipa , but this one is herbal , earthy , and spicy .  m : dense and creamy with low carbonation .

a : very dark brown color that does n't allow you to see through .  had to give it the maximum points for appearance , because even out of an imported bottle , it looks just right . comes in with an alcohol bite that 's almost like an imperial . pertty nice taste , though , and if you had some , i would n't refuse .

pours a deep chestnut brown , with a layer of foamy white goodness on top . laces amazingly . the more beers i try from this brewery the more i realize they sure know how to make a beer look good .  cons : the low carbonation level does hurt many factors of the beer , but it is such an exquisitely brewed offering , it 's only a minor issue .
superb retention .  the mouthfeel is light carbonation , somewhat on the watery side , but very drinkable .
smells rich and sweet with a nice peaty smokiness to it . overall it 's nice .  m - a little strong on the carbonation for my taste .

has a really nice fluffy one finger tan head that sticks around . lacing covers a huge portion of the glass .  very pleasant indeed . great hop character . this is a fairly balanced ipa . hard to say , it might just be because this particular bottle is more on the room temp side , but i would like more effervescence . a good beer all in all . i will be sure to drink it again , only a little colder and faster . more drinking , less typing ... .
a unique looking beer .  m : thinner than i expected , pretty fair amount of carbonation , once again a little more reminiscent of a porter than a stout .

amazing mix of bitter hops , tropical fruit , pine , etc , etc . really amazing ! taste follows suit -- -an assault of hops and some light malt . very nice , but nothing i 'd want to have more of one of . had a touch of heat from the 10 % abv on the finish . overall a really good brew -- -glad i tried it finally .  maybe a touch too much carbonation .

belhaven- twisted thistle ipa appearance- dark mahogany brown with a huge thick head .  the mouthfeel is the only thing i think could be improved here and it very well may just be that i am having it from a growler .

a : light brown pour with a good light tan head that leaves lace on the glass after about 1-2 fingers of head .  this beer has a lot of flavor for a light . too bad its not a good flavor ! nothing impressive at all here . i 'm not sure what they are putting in this beer but its not worth the 7.99 they are charging for a six pack . i would recommend pabst blue ribbion over this any day !

the smell is phenomenal , with loads of tropical fruits , pineapple , passion fruits , grape , mango and green apples . this boquet is really amarillo , and everything amarillo can be . any possible malt-notes in the nose is totally subdued by this awesome onslaught of amarillo !  a light , medium in body . extremely active on the palate ; too carbonated , that really takes away from this hop-filled wheat 's pleasanty flavors .
very inviting . as the bottle says ... dark and dreamy . leaves rich foamy rings and walls of lacing .  not bad at all , really , although a bit thin for the most part .

a 5 finger head shot up the glass as bubbles cascaded down the sides like a waterfall . left a massive three finger head after it settled .  mouthfeel was ok , not too thin , right amount of carbonation .

the aroma is very good , with some slightly tart chocolate-covered cherries and lots of caramel malts and toffee as well .  the mouthfeel has a little bit more carbonation than i would like a brew of this calibre to have , thus the 3.0 .

poured a medium copper hue with a huge chunky white head . there was very good retention and sticky lacing .  as with several anchor offerings , i feel the carbonation is a bit overdone , but is n't powerful enough to be overly distracting .

11.2 oz , 2007 bottle a : deep brown , not quite black under a nice sized tan head . excellent lace and retention .  the taste is ok. it seems a little flat coming out of the can compared to the tap . nice clean finish , no lingering aftertaste . definiteley a session beer if drinking from the tap .

smell : smells nice and tasty , with chocolate and molasses notes . very little hop aroma , but still strong enough to balance the brew .  pours a three finger light tan head that fades quickly to a ring leaving a little lace . dark cloudy amber color . light carbonation and light bodied . caramel nose . starts balanced but then a caramel flavor that stays to a clean finish . a tasty wheat . $ 2.49 for a 500ml bottle from john 's grocery iowa city , ia .

750ml , 2009 ( ? ) vintage pours pitch black and completely opaque with a one finger frothy beige head that slowly fades into a lasting ring . sporadic rings and spots of lacing are left behind .  t- roasty , sweet malts , coffee and dark chocolate m- starts off nice and creamy and full , then towards the middle loses a bit of it 's body and seems to get watery , only to return with a solid finish .

lovely hue , a truly good bright ruby red , with a collapsing , but pleasantly silky head of yellow white . it 's a really lovely looking american red ale , absolutely what you want from the style .  m - the feel is not terrible .

aroma is wow ! bacon .  had some fruity and clove flavors but was covered up due way too many hops for the style - not to mention that it was bitter . i barely finished it . other reviewers liked this beer and seemed to have a much different experience than i did which leaves me to believe that they have consistency problems or maybe they use different formulas for each location ? btw this one was sampled at the brewpub near the fleet center .

the retention was downright insane and it essentially sat there like whipped cream . beautiful looking beer .  i 've been waiting to try this one for some time now and it was well worththe wait ! i could smell it 's fruity aroma as soon as i opened the bottle , it has a nice dark cloudy amber color to it that is topped with a nice thick head . it goes down very smooth and just warms up your mouth , and you can really taste the spices in it .

incredibly complex aroma , a deep strong dark with dirt , sour grass , tart apple , a cornucopia of spices . perfect touch of the rustic .  body is fairly thin , but that is expected for the modest abv .

appearance- pours a slightly hazy pale gold into my glass , a rough pour results in four full fingers of well constructed bubbles . after about 8 minutes , the head settles leaving behind webs of sticky lacing and a creamy , whipped topping . it 's messy and uneven , and leaves a burning bitterness that even i find unpleasurable .  the mouthfeel seems a bit week and flat , but it 's not bad .

reviewed 11/21/2009 ( bottle , goblet glass , 53degf , office @ computer after dinner ) : pours a strong purplish red color body , with an average sized dark pink head , lasting .  if i had to log a complaint , it would be that this stout is too thin and less of a cream offering . however , it is full of flavor and easy to drink despite being 6.5 % abv .
a : pale straw , great carbonation , crystal clear , and a lovely full head .  the body was a bit too thin for my tastes in this style .
pours with almost an amber tint with a lovely fluffy head , almost like a belgian pour .  mouthfeel is a little on the thin side .
appearance : a dark tan head sits atop a black-brown body . long lasting and nice to look at .  m : full bodied but way too over-carbonated .
pours a deep , opaque mahogany , almost black . there 's a 3-finger cafe au lait head with a moderate amount of layered lacing .  too much carbonation for this style ( -1.0 ) .

330ml bottle poured into tulip dec9 2010 a super hazy golden orange with tiny suspended particles being move around by a shitload of bubbles . a gentle pour leaves a massive 3 finger head that forms a dome over the top of the glass and just sits there for a while ever so slowly falling to a thick film with a island in the middle that looks like a little brain s a little yeast and pineapple with some other fruits i ca n't quite place and some booze t what i smell but with a little more booze , some cereals and a nice little blast of hops .  m-medium body and syrupy with a grainy tough texture . strong carbonation and a slightly messy carbonation in the finish .
incredible retention and ok lacing s- sweet and hoppy .  ; very sweet ( perhaps overly ) m : a bit syrupy overall , a fantastic barleywine style ale .
the aroma is quite nice - banana , bubblegum , wheat , chocolate , coffee , and maybe some citric hops .  mouthfeel is medium with more carbonation that i expected due to no head showing up .

appearance : orange/amber body with a nice two finger head .  poured from bottle to tulip glass a : brilliantly clear pale yellow color with huge 3+ finger head that fades very slowly n : nose of a light belgian type wit with some light malts , touch of spices , toasted quality , touch of yeast t : starts with more malts and toasted quality , pretty light otherwise , a touch of light fruits and banana , slight earthy marzen quality , no spices m : very light and somewhat watery f : finishes dry and very crisp with a fading earthy marzen taste , would make a good session beer final thoughts : its a very light tasting oktoberfest/marzen .

appearance : shakespeare stout pours out nearly black with a full 3 fingers of mocha colored head . retention is very good , and lacing is very abundant .  bittersweet finish . kind of think and syrupy on the palate .

clear copper with orange accents , forming a large , pillowy peaking light beige head atop fine bubbles . moderately strong carbonation .  m - nothing special just went down really easy ... .it was n't bad tasting ... .i was surprised how quickly i finished it because it went down fast .
pours a rich , opaque sable with a nice thick tan head .  a little more carbonation may have helped this one with its texture . just a tad thin , becoming a little dry but not crisp in the finish .
huge 3 to 4-finger tan/beige head , slowly recedes to thin but relatively constant layer . great webby lace .  light in body and fairly thin on the tongue . smooth and lightly carbonated .

deep , shiny gold/light copper with good , medium creamy head , that lasts a few minutes , medium white sticky lacing , hugging the glass a good while .  m : light-medium body with an oily mouthfeel , and a dry and resiny fade overall , not a bad beer , though it does stray from traditional belgian dubbels in a few aspects : not as sweet or yeasty as the classic belgian examples , a little hoppy for the style , and its too light .

a : a clear light copper bear with a nice foamy creamy white head . the nitrogen really adds to the appearance .  wow this has to be one of the worst ideas in beer history . trying to cross a pale ale with a belgian and what you got is something that is a distant cousin to both . instead of leveraging the style 's strengths this beer doubles down on their worst attributes . a very hoppy tatse that fights like a strong ale . not a fun beer and a true shame that it might discredit weyerbacher 's other great beers .
a : deep solid golden yellow brew , 3 '' of billowy off-white head sticks around and coats the glass with webbing . moderate carbonation visible . quite appealing .  medium carbonation .
probably the prettiest lacing you will ever see on a glass . effing beautiful .  light to medium bodied , carbonation seems to be at the right level .

poured into a shaker pint glass at cellar temp results in a nice frothy tan head that slowly sinks to a thin cap , lots of lacing .  lacks hops . lacks malt or any toasting . crisp , dry , clean , even a little bit bitter and metallic .

aroma smacks you . good and hard . hops and oak would be an obvious statement . my notes indicate an amazing floral and woody perfume aroma . initial flavor is upfront pine and sweetness .  mouthfeel is a bit of a problem for me . the carbonation level is also a factor , making it hard to enjoy in gulps .

a-pitch black with a nice tan head that thins s-chocolate , red wine , licorice , and black pepper . strong and complex ! possibly some ginger in there too .  m - a little thinner than i thought and more carbonated than i would expect .

this porter pours with a dark brown to black body topped by a thick , light brown head with a good amount of lacing .  the taste is sweet and smooth , with a hint of hops but the most prevalent taste is of lemon . finishes with a very refreshing aftertaste . i would defiantly suggest this beer to even non craft beer drinkers .

s : nose is pleasantly funky , mild barnyard with notes of hay and grass .  the body is is a serious letdown , nowhere near rich/full enough and it crosses the line into watery . the carbonation is appropriately subdued , and does n't overtake the lackluster body .

appearance : poured with a huge fluffy white head that lasted forever . the beer is a clear golden color with a few bubbles rising , but the head sticks around anyway . there is a whole bunch of lacing left on the glass after the head falls .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light but overcarbonated .
nice nose ! great complexity .  like drinking sour grass , probably the best way to put it m - low carbonation , slightly astringent d - not very drinakble , i had to leave a third of it

bottle provided by mike , drank into my hill farmstead glass ... looks great , a dark clear peach with a big bright white head . looks awesome ! ! ! ... boring aroma of light toffee and hops , generic .  ) it has very low carbonation witch makes the mouthfell very average with about that of a tap bud lite , only a little tingle from the carbonation .

robust cherry smell that is fantastic . taste is almost all cherry , wheaty malt underneath .  this beer poured a dirty blonde color , with a haziness that made me suspect that i would n't enjoy this beer too much . aroma was malty , and flavor was a sweet maltiness with only a hint of hops . this was n't what i was expecting from an american pale ale , and i really did n't enjoy it . i may have gotten an old beer , but there is no date code on this beer , so i have no way of knowing its age and it gets what it gets ... most of this one is going down the drain .

big fluffy cap of beige foam makes a nice stand and keeps itself steady for a good while before dismantling itself to a heavy skim and lots of thick lacing .  m - exceedingly bitter . needs to be a little creamier for this style d - not a session beer .
poured pitch black with a healthy , khaki-colored head .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and syrupy with a bit of sharp carbonation .

( served in a tulip glass ) a- this beer has a dark opaque brown body with a mousey thick creamy head that last and lat . s- this beer has a very clean smell with a faint hint of dark roasted malt or prunes and as it warms quite a bit the notes of brown sugar and alcohol come through .  m : very thin mouthfeel however strong carbonation makes overall body light but full .
a clear copper ruby when held up to the light with brilliant head retention and honeycomb lacing .  it is a bit thin , bordering on watery with adequate to slightly low carbonation .

the nose ... wow . i get bubble gum and cotton candy , with a strong citrus and floral hop character . this smells fantastic ... eeeh ! ! it 's not a bad thing , just strange . i think it 's too aggressively hopped and unbalanced in the taste department for my tastes , but still damn good .  wtf did they do to this beer ? this is the first time i tried it since they put in the new brewhouse and i 'm not impressed . this used to be a wonderfully drinkable beer with orange and subtle spice flavors that made it quite refreshing . now its just overloaded with phenolics and all you can taste and smell is cloves . i ca n't get past the phenolic flavors enough to even finish a bottle . just horrible .
hazy/cloudy straw yellow coloe . great lacing .  tastes pretty amazing really . watery on the tongue but ends dryish .

appearance : pours an incredibly rich , thick molasses/mahogany . you 'll be hard pressed to find a better looking beer than this .  mouthfeel is just ok-nothing too incredible but quite drinkable especially at the 6.5 % abv .

chocolate head over a pitch black pit , some sweet lacing ... some mild anise and roasted malts tingle the nose , also a hint of acetone in there .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and somewhat tannic , but the overall effect is quite interesting .

the beer itself pulls a pitch black into the glass and lets no light through . darkness is right . head retention is decent , leaves a perfect lacing behind .  m : medium to full body but needs more carbonation .

this is , not too surprisingly amber , poured with a nice fluffy head and some lacing , would be perfect , except that the head did n't retain too long .  i always drink my high life out of cans ! it looks like beer , smells like beer , and tastes like beer ... to keep it simple . this is my go-to macro , and will always be as long as miller keeps it the same ! prost !

looks like a pretty standard witbier to me . nice and cloudy , has that ideal golden color .  this beer is not awful but it is not good either . if use to be better , i think , back in the days before aluminum cans and pull up tabs . beer is fizzy and gives a good head and that is about the only good quality it has .

pours dark mahogany with a thick tan head .  the taste is very good , it could use a bit more body but the flavors are great . tons of chocolate and roastiness dominate the profile but there is also some caramel and hops . the bitterness is at a great level in comparison to the sweetness , especially for the style . the guy below me has it right : not quite edmund fitz or blake butte but this one is one of the supeb examples of the style .

very pleasant . t : this is too light for the style .  picked up a few of these `` oil cans '' at a local liquor mart . this is the only place i 've seen them . i like the regular fosters occasionally , and have fond memories of it from various parties and times in life . after looking at the color , noticed that the can said `` caramel coloring added , '' so nothing real to go by there . i liked this , i guess , but the drinkablility was hampered by a fakey sort of bitterness that did n't hold a candle to the fuller 's and young 's of the world . kind of caught in my throat . i pick up the regular if it 's on special , but for a real bitter , this ai n't it .

poured into an imperial pint glass a nice deep garnet color with well defined half finger off white head atop , good richness and definition to the color.aromas of cinnamon and clove mainly , i could tell right away this was gon na be a more heavily spiced winter warmer.heavy cinnamon , clove , and nutmeg on the palate , not crazy sweet just spiced to the hilt , some faint toastiness underneath the spice does come thru after awhile as well some alcohol sweetness.much like their pumpkin ale the winter warmer is too spiced up , i do like this better than the pumpkin beer but it 's still not great by any means .  m : a bit light in the mouth , but it kind of coats your mouth as well .

smells creamy/milky with rich , almost sweet coffee , chocolate , kaluha , cocoa , and a touch of green hops . absolutely divine . the flavor is roasty with burnt/charred malts , coffee , chocolate , and a medium bitterness .  ambrosial start , lots of malt , the top skimpy in feel with the finish having a delightful hop spicy bite , the carbonation moderate and the aftertaste droughty and long lasting .

a - it 's impossible to score higher , beautiful beer ... thick fluffy white head that resembles the frothed milk of a latte , dark gold to light copper , carbonation rains towards the head ... such a beautiful looking beer .  reminded me a bit of bmc with a bit of syrup added for sweetness . the taste is more of the same with a quick malty dryness at the end that seems to say , `` ha ! had you fooled..you thought there was about to be something pleasant here , did n't you ? in fact , this may get sacrificed to the kitchen sink . as i always say , in total fairness to the brewer and his ( or her ) intentions , this may have its fans , but it most assuredly is *not* for me ...
poured black , with clear mahogany highlights , with a large mostly lasting light brown frothy head with good lacing .  mouf & gt ; easy , average .

big , meaty chunks of yeast floating around in the ebony liquid . has a giant , thick head the color of chocolate milk .  the body of the beer is actually approaching medium and the carbonation is not overly fizzy as many macros are .

this beer smells so good ! sweet with almost a balsamic vinegar quality . great . tart , sour gets me in the back of the mouth .  my first taste of it was great , however it lacks in the balance of the malts , and has sort of a over roasted taste . altogether though , this beer in my opinion is the best of the coors brand and i would recommend for something new . not a everyday beer though .
this smells amazing ! t - the taste is good , not great ... yet .  there was a very light mouthfeel , but an extremely dry , crisp finish .
served in a pint glass , it pours dark brown with some tinges of ruby red in there when i hold it up to the light .  m-medium carbonation . medium body , slick .
d - the smell is excellent , the rest is mediocre .  the mouthfeel is a little lacking in carbonation too .
this beer black and entirely opaque with a thick and persistant off-white head with flecks of tan in it - very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel is okay , no carbonation to speak of .

my beer poured a dark , murky , opaque mahogany color with a gigantic , creamy tan head that took forever to fade and leaves chunky lacing down the side . my foam looks like a root beer float it is so solid and creamy looking .  mouth feel : a bit thin on the palet , or maybe the aroma and taste make you expect more in the way of mouth feel .

outstanding retention and lace , strong carbonation . looks beautiful in the glass and the lace is breathtaking , but the flavor just falls short of expectations .  it must be said that this beer is a bit astringent on the palate and a bit thinner than i would have liked , but it is still rather drinkable .

s - the aroma initially reminded me of kentucky monk ( a very fine compliment ) . nice stuff .  mouth feel is thin pretty characteristic of bbc 's beers which makes this a really drinkable session stout with a lot of flavor .
a really nice looking pour .  a rather thin aqueous body with less carbonation than expected , but otherwise nothing wrong with this brew .
pours a beautiful slightly hazy amber color with a large two inch off white head . excellent retention and some great lacing .  the mouth was a bit oily but not unpleasantly so .

2009 vintage poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 3/4 finger cream colored head with good retention . clear reddish copper liquid is beautiful s : herbal and earthy hop aroma .  it is slightly watery on the palate .

pours a crude oil black with a phenomenal caramel tan mocha head that is incredible , the cake laced froth will coat the glass throughout the session .  m : starts off creamy , but i 'm pretty quickly struck by how watery this is . the carbonation is decent , but i find this surprisingly thin .
this beer looks great , clean and clear , good carbonation and head .  m : fairly thick , carbonation seems a tad high .

i got this beer from the local gas station and thought i should try it because im a big fan of seasonals . the appearance is great just like every other goose island .  mouthfeel is ok , but too watery and thin feeling for my tastes . drinkability is quite good , the only real flaw i found was the weak mouthfeel .

a : very lively , clear , beautiful orange/light amber color , borderline perfect head .  mouthfeel : high carbonation gives the impression of a thinner mouthfeel , and the carbonic acid and alcohol bite knock this one down a little in the mouthfeel rating .

pours an opaque black with tight tan head .  a-garnet with small ring of foam s-raisin , pancake syrup , faint vinager t-assertive sour front , sour cherry , some malt sweetness , dates m-medium , with average carbonation d-very tasty !

the aroma is intoxicating , deep and bold arabica coffee notes upfront that is fruity and intense . high quality cacao , molasses , pepper , cherry wood and a wallop of alcohol ... really outstanding . the flavor is a letdown from the aroma , with a broad sweetness that kind of smothers the coffee and roasted notes , some cherry and plum notes in the background and an alcohol bite finishes things off . an incredible aroma almost makes up for the cloying sweetness .  under carbonated .

a : orangey amber cloudy beer with a huge 3 finger cappucino head that settles to peaks and valleys veery slowly , great lace throughout .  not too many micro 's that come out with a light ale . hats off to them for bringing this to market to allow folks who are used to drinking american mass producted swill to move into a easy drinking michigan micro brew . lighter than sam adams but more flavor then the bud and miller 's of the world .
appearance is great . a very nice looking stout .  the beer really lacks in body . carbonation is great . overall this was a good beer but the body creates a void .
smells great ! ! !  taste/mouthfeel : this beer is slightly oily , with a very limited carbonation .
pours very dark brown color with a 2.5 finger dense tan head with incredible retention , with some very nice lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is thiner but still good .

s- hops are floral , citrus , and a sweetness in the background that 's a sweeter peach and apricot .  a wonderful beer . one i have had before , and thought it would be great for the new year . it 's dark brown hue and brownish colored head was delightful . the taste of cocoa and hops pleased my nose . the roasted flavors were soothing , but left a little bit of an after taste .

this is the only barley wine i have every tried , and chances are it will be the last . some people love this stuff , not me , not my taste buds .  light copper color with a large head s. malty with a slight resiny hop smell t. more bitter than sweet but well balanced with roasted malt m. a little to acidic and carbonated for my tastes d. a good lighter amber ale that i can heartily recommend
deep brown that looks reddish when held to the light .  mouthfeel is very dry with almost no carbonation .

incredibly clean , with absolutely no imperfections in the malting or hops . extremely delicate . the flavor is incredibly clean .  cake/nutty malt up front with a huge , thick spiced tea hop flavor headbutt with the swallow . not just season 's best , but saranac 's best . i usually find them to be just an average brewery but this stuff is nice .
pours a thick black with a large mocha head .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .
this stinks like simcoe , cascade , and centennial - if i recall . good shit .  m- smooth , but a tad thin . carbonation is good , as is the thoroughly smooth finish with a tad of warmth .
looks fantastic ! the head leaves plenty of lace after a couple of minutes .  m - a little thinner than i imagined , though based on the aroma , i might have been expecting a double ipa .

absolutely fantastic aroma . t & m : sweet chocolate , citrus hops , and toasted black malt all make their appearance .  incredibly light with cereal grains , very grainy taste , hops are nowhere in site . there are way better summer beers out there .

the colour is pitch-black ; the two finger head is pale beige , airy and uneven . massive amounts of lacing .  i always look forward like most do the annual stone anniversary brews.poured a rich deep amber with a tight and sticky one finger off white head , big hops in the nose with a mix pine and herbal/leaf , there is a gummy , fruity-like sweet note as well.the mouthfeel is a bit sharp i will say it crashes down the gullett at first , it does begin to smooth out after a few sips but still seems a bit harsh.no holds barred hops hit the palate up front with big pine and big herbalness , a healthy does of sweeter alcohol gives a slight burn along with a bit of dark fruit.very good but seems like it something that should sit for awhile , still another fine one from stone .

this beer pours with a lot of carbonation - almost too much - an absolutely massive head barreling over the top of the glass a la snow-cone .  mouthfeel is way more thin than the head and lacing made me think it would be . very quaffable .

s : i thought i died and went to heaven the first time i smelled this beer . caramel and toffee aromas dominate with some hints of berries .  just some `` laying down '' advice : had the extreme plesure of six-year bottle conditioning tasteing , in which years 4-5 were exceptionally good . year 3 was quite good , with anything under that seemingly `` young '' tasting . after year 5 the qualities that make it a stellar barley wine were fading .

wonderfully hoppy scent with a citric , floral edge . notes of toffee and orange in the aroma . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but overall a nice , easy-drinking harvest ale .  mouthfeel is soft and a little heavy .

poured from a 750ml bottle into a spiegelau tulip . appearance : pours a clear medium amber color with orange highlights and a fluffy 3 finger off-white head . excellent head retention and nice lacing .  perhaps another way to explain the feeling would be a textured shandy . noting the high praise this saison received , i have trouble fathoming such a bad experience .

appearance- deeper colored golden pour with a full inch plus rocky head with a good 1/4 inch of staying power . great looking beer .  4/5 m : surprisingly thin side of medium , slightly tongue numbing , spritzy .

the aroma is the best part , but it goes down smooth and tastes nice .  nice carbonation , but this comes off as a little thin . this should be more drinkable considering its thin body , but as this is a stout , the thin body is a bit of a turn off .

a : what a great looking stout . deep brown color with an extremly silkey 1/2 '' head that slowly disipates into lacing s : roasted malt t : grain sweet ness and roasted malts m & d : mouth feel was medium and dry .  m : the thinnest , lightest imperial i can remember , but the intensity doesnt have to be overpowering .

fruity and floral , very nice . t - slight malt at first taste , but the bitterness of the hops kicks in and lingers .  flavour is better than expected- a little woody and slightly spicy , with a thick strong maltiness . i 'd like the hearty body on this one , were it not for the turbocharged carbonation .

odor : rich citric aroma , tangerine , slightly lemony , floral backbone , some red fruit in there as well , pleasant and mellow . consistency : big carbonation , too much for my taste at least , it is straddling the line between gentle and tingly , no doubt that it gets in the way of the flavor a bit .  do n't brewers taste the beers they brew after they 're done ? how many sips does it take to get stone juxtaposition to the center of my sink drain ? i think this beer is really spent burnt coffee grounds blended with colgate toothpaste in a bottle .

this beer pours a nearly perfect copper color with a voluminous , tan rocky head . the head slowly fades until a loose layer of foam lays atop the beer , which displays excellent clarity .  a touch lightly bodied , with an oily , but thinnish and passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

dark brown with a light brown , foamy head that stays through the entire pint and leaves a nice lacing .  thanks walter a-a nice rich amber , good head , some lacing that turned into a small bubble ring s-a slight bready smell , some citrus ( makes me think of citra hop ) slight sweetness and then tart t- close to the same as the smell , there is a slight tangyness in the middle of the drink , it 's a good thing m- it 's moderately lively not as much bite and tingle i was expecting , a clean wet finish o/d- overall i really like this , it 's not the craziest ipa but it 's more than just decent , drinkability , i can see myself finishing this growler , this is a tasty beer and one i really like

bottle states brewed on the banks of the mighty st. vrain bottled on date printed on the label 09/12/07 , drank 11/16/07 poured from a bottle into a pint glass nice two fingers of foam billowy and thick , lacing all the way to the finish . the mouthfeel was on the thin side with a tad too much carbonation for my liking overall this beer very solid style wise , it would make a good session beer , but i was turned off by the high carbonation and thin mouthfeel .  an american classic . good fall back beer , or one to enjoy when a less complex brew is desired .

smell : the best part of this beer in my opinion . extremely complex ! i smell the chocolate and coffee but i am also overwhelmed by the super sweet heavenly smell of vanilla . taste : i was so happy that the taste was so refined , understated , elegant and smooth . drinkability : love it love it .  the carbonation and the color were good , but this did n't make up for the off taste and smell .

a delicious aroma of coffee , and bready malts , and a flavor which delivers with a nice hop bitterness at the finish .  the mouthfeel is light , but hey , its a light beer ! for drinkability , again , one of the beers that could probably never offend me .

a tall , tan , thick head that lasts .  remarkably good . but pay attention : almost 10 % alcohol , but you hardly remark it . it does not have that much body , but it surely has a delicate taste . i 'm a bit more inclined for brown beers , but this one is really good , and not brown at all .

a : rather mild amber color , nice sudsy bleached-white head , globs of wonderful lace as thick as frosting on the glass paired with vibrant bubbles .  lowish carbonation and a light , smooth mouthfeel .

aromas of lots of different berries ( strawberies , blueberries , blackberries , and raspberries ) . i would get a different berry every time i sniffed . the berries were done nice ! good thing i like all the types of berries in this one .  m : very carbonated .

pours a clear yellow with tons of head and lots of lacing . not typically a fan of the pale yellow look , but this one had an amazing head and great retention .  smooth mouthfeel with a moderate amount of carbonation and just a little watery in the finish .

a - pours black with a nice light-tan head . looks great . sticks fairly well to the side , just about as good as a porter could .  it is a little light in body but i 've noticed that porters and stouts are generally lighter from a can .

pours a truly awesome blood orange reddish tan color with a tan head .  had this on tap when i was being introduced to the lager style of beer . it 's smell is very specific to the beer and is appealing if you are craving a medium-bodied lager . its has a malty intake and a bit of a spicy , hoppy after taste . it goes down smoothly but the taste tends to stick around and interfere with ordered food . it is very drinkable but as stated , but be careful when drinking this with food .
this has a nice hop smell right out of the bottle . with smells of carmel , malts , and a sweet smell .  mouthfeel : heavy , chewy , slick , low carbonation borders on flat .
fantastic stuff t- it 's ... really bitter ?  heavy mouthfeel .

a - pours very dark red , foams high but dissipates quickly . has a very nice cream/coke fizz coloured head and a great ruby red hue in light . very attractive beer .  taste some roasted chocolate flavors . flavor lingers on the tongue after each sip . not quite what i would consider a savoring beer , but tasty none the less . i could drink this beer around the fire in the winter or after raking leaves in the fall .
the color was near black to black with light tan head . the lacing was exceptional , straight rings from the top to the bottem .  feel is a bit coarse , but just a bit .

pours an absolute , dense black with a healthy sized brown head .  nice aroma of hops but i would hope for a bit more being a hops lover . the celebration ale , from the same company , seems to hit the spot more than this beer but still worthy of a place in the fridge and still better than many micro beer ipa ii . sierra nevada seems to me to be the only mass beer company that brews excellent beer for `` mass beer '' prices .
a : pours a wonderfully bright golden/orange color .  carbonation is fizzy on the tongue where it should be soft and creamy .

pours a light honey with a beautiful white head that has levels of plateaus and some sheets of lacing along the sides of my imperial pint .  mouthfeel was somewhat on the thin side , but still quite acceptable .

the smell is surprising sweet with peaches and apricots on top of the big citrus hop base . this is an interesting dipa though i wish the flavor measured up to the unique aroma . still worth trying .  finishes dry with nice mocha notes & a touch of charred grain mf : very oily & smooth as all hell with low carbonation & nice stickyness .
smells amazing . the pine and citra form a wave of hoppy goodness .  the silky smooth mouthfeel was fantastic and carbonation was spot on .

s : holy hops ! strong citrus and pine hop aroma , sweet and fruity , not very bitter smelling . t : follows the nose , tropical fruit and citrus hops dominate , followed by piney flavors . o : this beer gives me a rock-solid .  mouthfeel : amazing . creamy and smooth , thick .

2010 bottle had a ton of suspended sediment in a burnt orange body . wow , aroma is the big winner here . pumpkin pie with crust as it warms ; some clove came thru as well , and even somewhat herbal . pretty authentic pumpkin flavor - vegetable/squash quality , and good amount of spices , incl cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove - but not overpowering . decent volume of malty sweetness / richness ... touch of campfire as it warms . outstanding drinkability - this is the most aromatic and flavorful pumpkin ale you can buy at this level of abv .  a - opaque for sure ; not quite black , but very dark brown ; 1/2 '' tan/light brown , creamy head that diminishes to a thin layer pretty quickly ; lacing here and there , around the glass s - very nice aroma going on here ; notes of roasty malts , dark chocolate , hints of milky sweetness , and nice qualities of gingerbread too t - dark chocolate , vanilla , cinnamon , and ginger come first ; milky sweetness lasts from start to finish that is reminiscent of espresso ; slight bitter finish with roasted coffee beans and ginger as well m - medium to full bodied ; slight dry finish ; some carbonation that feels nice on the tongue ; can feel some warmth from the 9.2 % abv ; texture is very milky , creamy , velvety smooth o - i just ca n't get over how exceptionally smooth this beer really is .

great nose of banana , passionfruit , cloves and green apples .  m - they got the `` rick creamy '' part right in the description . the beer has moderate carbonation and has a nice creamy feel to it . it 's incredibly creamy and smooth and fits the style well .
very clean aroma of bourbon and some licorice .  m - the mouthfeel is fantastic . creamy , smooth and light with a perfect amount of carbonation .

smell is very floral and fragrant , wow , fantastic . as it warms , you get more classic nw hops , pine and citrus .  m : really a standout porter . carbonation is perfectly dialed in and gives a very subtle tingle on the tongue .

smells like a rich and fruity tripel and is very inviting . as far as taste , the hops kick in first and are then followed by a slight hint of the tripel .  m : great , chewy and resiny , full-bodied and robust , with a smooth finish , compared to the rest of the sip , just what i 'm looking for in a double ipa .

smell was deep with plenty of sweet chocolate aromas and bitter grains .  the mouthfeel on this ale was great , and i think the mouthfeel of just about any beer is enhanced by cask conditioning . it had a nice thick feel on the tongue .
it smells great , a little like their nut brown ale , which along with the oatmeal stout are two of my favorite beers .  mouthfeel : full bodied , chewy , carbonation is spot on .

s : this is seriously the best part of the beer . the smell is a pronounced chorus of woodiness , vanilla , chocolate , and booze . is this nirvana ? t : starts out with a creamy chocolate taste which is followed by a sharp stab of flavor and alcohol burn on the tongue . d : overall a very impressive beer .  it has a wonderfully creamy mouthfeel that makes each sip a pleasure .

s- great smell like a realy fruity white wine , dark raspberries , some of the cereal grains come through , no hop aroma . it doesn ; t over power though .  the texture is likewise decadent , being somehow both silky and creamy .

excellent . sweet and sour fruits cominate the taste , but caramel malts creep slowly in , along with alcohol , honey , and even some wood . the feel ends up pleasantly sweet and smooth .  fairly light in body for such a big beer , drinkability is good . the mouthfeel was amazing thanks to the silky , rocky head which remained throughout the entire glass .

a nice smell . t : malty and roasty .  bordering on chewy as you work toward swallowing . carbonation was excellent on tap , just enough to contribute to a dry and clean finish despite the initial sweetness of the beer .

s - spicy , fruity hops . pepper and lemon with some floral hints of jasmine and a bit of basil . the hop character is fantastic , especially in the nose , and the bitterness is neither harsh nor overwhelming , but rather refreshing .  huge bodied and full ( again , suggesting iipa classification ) . this is a beauty on cask .

smell- the jasmine is def . present in the nose of this one , along with fruity , citrus , hop notes . taste/mouthfeel- starts out with a nice hop presence but then fades quickly drinkability- very easy drinking beer , having it with some food helps the overall taste of the beer too .  m : so good i ca n't get enough . nice thickness with light carbonation and a good oily texture make this a delightful treat for my mouth .
