poured a nice golden color with a dense rocky head pronounced piney and citrusy aroma , along with an earthy spice to it . huge hop bouquet . this beer seemed a little thin and light bodied for an ipa .  has that totally coating feel like a warm thick cask draught , just almost oily in its feel and velvety ( aside from the alcohol ) . really like this about this beer .

i 've always like tryign various fruit beers ... .and this one was certainly one of the better ones that i have tried . the raspberries are extremely prevalent to both smell and taste , but not to the point of being overwhelming .  perfect mouthfeel for a beer of this kind with controlled carbonation and appropriate body .

what struck me first was the phenomenally fresh smell . the roasted malt and slightly bitter hops hits your nose and just stays there , begging you to take a sip . while the beer is great , the taste did n't quite live up to the smell . a bit thinner than expected and a bit less complex than i had hoped .  first sip is velvety smooth textured average body with minimal carbonation .

decent lacing left behind . s - wow , great aroma here . immediately there is a lot of pineapple and coconut aroma making it clear that this has been barrel aged . lots of stuff going on here .  and even so , it is still incredibly smooth , and the alcohol flavor can not be detected . the body is huge . one of the thickest beers i 've had the pleasure of eating . very good stuff .

has a very dry champagne-like smell ripe with musty cherries , smells like they 've been sitting in a dank barrel for a while . very appealing smell . overall medium body , slightly tart , cloys in a big way .  m - this is one of my favorite parts so far about this brew . moderate amounts of carbonation that whirls around your tounge and warms it in the process .
unique and quite nice aroma . taste is medium sweet upfront mixed w/medium hop bitterness .  m : medium viscosity , very smooth and creamy on the palate , with low carbonation .

s : the smell is quite amazing and complex in my opinion . there are some light hops initially noticed . overall , it is very pleasant . t : after the very satisfying smell , the taste was sort of a let down .  mouthfeel is full bodied and smooth that feels pretty creamy on the tongue .

smell : thick , sweet , treacly , appetizing taste : smooth , bitter , slightly sweet . not as sweet and deep as the smell hinted at .  m/d - the mouthfeel and drinkability are exceptional . this is a simple brown ale that i could knock back one after the other .

good retention and lacing ... the aroma is pretty nice , sweet candy wheat , honey , floral finish ... the taste really is disappointing , borderline bad . pretty disappointing for me after such a great aroma . i ca n't recommend this .  m - thick , very smooth and very viscous with little carbonation .
smell- very fresh malts give a whiff of roast , toast , and even some plums .  mouthfeel . amazing , thick rich and seems sweet but comes together .
has a solid malt flavor with a huge hop aroma . i could use a tad more bitterness but that is just a personal preference .  starts with roasted coffee flavor , mouthfeel is incredible smooth .

a : almost totally opaque , thin tan head that generates late and dissipates quickly , not much lacing s : smells like a campfire is the best way to put it , some light hops and malt , but mostly that charcoal mesquite , wow t : again , the campfire , but a little more subdued , some chocolate notes in the middle , with a hop bitterness in the back that mixes with the rough , almost metallic charcoal character m : pretty thick , coats the entire mouth and stays with you for a while d : a true sipper , amazing for the style , but it 's so intense , i had a little trouble finishing the bottle , one would be enough for me for quite a while  taste- wonderfully intense malt , and a big bready character that thankfully outweighs any unpleasant sweetness that the malts could impart . fantastically effervescent , it rides into the mouth and over the tongue with confident grace ... all the while alive and outspoken .
overall , i really liked the smell of the beer - the flavor , not so much .  perfect silky creamy carbonation .

aroma - this is where the beer shines i feel . a great funk , barnyard , grassy , astringent blast right to your nostrils . taste - definitely follows the nose . barnyard and belgian yeast right up front , almost a brett taste , the astringency is in the back with grassy notes . great smell and decent tasting beer , i am enjoying it !  mouthfeel is very good , a light bodied beer with excellent carbonation ; it dances on the tongue and finishes smooth .

the nose is amazingly sweet .  good and special beer , cloudy , double fermentation , yeast , hops , malt and wheat are present in smell ; taste fruity , and floral like grassy and herbs ; good for mexican haute cuisine , try with pasta and salads ; mouthfeel exceptional , well balanced and litlle strong for the palate ; 96 % recommended .

aroma is really nice for a bourbon-barrel stout ... vanilla , sweetish milk chocolate , with an underlying fruitiness from the barrel . very tasty stuff ...  m : medium bodied with a good amount of carbonation . exceptional in this category . appearance and mouthfeel are certainly worth noting .
this smells promising . taste : toffee , brown sugar , caramel , dark fruits and sharp alcohol .  m- awesome thick mouthfeel on this seasonal .

i 'm a huge fan of strong , hoppy pilsners , and this is just great . tons of fresh grassy floral hops , a touch of pale malt . definitely enjoyable , regardless .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel . very smooth , lightly carbonated .

awesome hop aroma of german noble hops . smells like tettnanger to me ... pleasant , dry and crisp character . decent hop bitterness and flavor .  aroma : not overpowering , but hints of citrus-y hops well balanced with malt mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a nice oily coating of the mouth . very smooth with just the right carbonation .

remains hazy as it warns , unlike the 2010 . among the best sour aromas i 've had the pleasure of experiencing . t : fruits , oak , and brett share the spotlight . great blend of the three flavors . m : body is thin and weak , yet nicely oily . d : sessionable , even at $ 40/bottle .  perfect carbonation to it .
seems very complex , i love it . t : disappointed from the smell .  mouthfeel is damn near perfect for an o'fest , i think . impeccable balance .

a : peppery spice with citrusy fruit , somewhat leathery . a : clear golden yellow with a tight white head f : dry , with fruit ( apple/citrus ) and spice up front . o : good interpretation of saison . nice and dry with plenty of character . there 's something tangy tht decreases my overall enjoyment .  great mouthfeel .

quickly diminished head , but holds glass well ar - beautiful cascade hops aroma ! i 'm a sucker for that .  m - full body , viscous and chewy with low , delicate carbonation , very smooth across the palate with some heat from the alcohol/bourbon content .
lots of aromas , raisins , plums , maple sugar candy .  m : very soft carbonation and easy on the palate as a good session beer should be .
aroma is clean and bright . sassafras along with quiet vanilla sit beneath a strong phenolic note .  f : wonderfully thick .

sweet and very appealing like a hopslam . t - taste is a bit different than the smell and reminds me of pliny the younger . very good . o - i think this is a very fine dipa .  m : super creamy as it should be .

i just about busted a nut getting the # $ # cork off in one piece..ahh make that several pieces that did n't fall back into the bottle ... but after a long and arduos process the cork was successfully removed.. poured a dark brown ... relatively clear..absolutely no head ... mouthfeel is very uncarbonated..i love the nose ... molasses ... .brown sugar ... .dark fruits ( plums , dates , even burgandy cherries ) ..a bit of oak ... just an awesome smelling beer.. the flavors are similar to the nose but much more tame ... .dark fruits ... molasses ... oak ... good taste to this ... my biggest complaint is the loose mothfeel ... very uncabonated which gives it almost a watery texture ... seems almost thin ... overall , the nose is great and the taste is very good but the body leaves something to be desired..definitely worth trying ... i wo n't be buying any more though ... .  the mouthfeel is dry with a long and deep finish which is full of blackened malt and char . very very nice .
this looks like cough syrup . smells of citrusy hops , hops , and more hops .  excellent ! incredible smooth and silky mouthfeel .
aroma , port , sherry . it 's sweet but very inviting . sherry quality very present in the taste .  m : full-bodied , a very firm and brilliantly sructured beer .
a - hazy yellow , highly carbonated , soda pop head that dissipates quickly s - yep , definitely a peach beer , but pleasant .  mouthfeel & gt ; exciting ... not too bubbly . full score .

lively grapefruit , bright citrus notes abound . what a lovely burst of pineapple and fruit aromas . so very inviting . taste - resin and oily entry , coating the tongue with the expected presence of hops to the max .  m : perfect carbonation amount .
the smell is very oaky . there is a good bit of vanilla .  it 's thick , creamy , rich , and robust .

the aroma is pretty complex like any respectable barleywine , but definitely more on the malt side . brown sugar is obvious and is of pleasant company to figs , peaches , alcohol and an all-around complex fruitiness .  the mouthfeel , though , was the best part . it fills your mouth with mousse like consistency with very round edges .

brewery states they did pick up some brett recently , popped the cork off ... corked talked about brett to me , more fruit than funk . hops stay modest . mild tartness , infancy of the brett ? it does have a ghost-like funk within . sweet roasted finish , pretty much burnt sugar . not a hair short of being great , the brewery admits to some funk ... wish i had another bottle to see where it goes .  the mouth feel is perfect - not watery , not syrupy , well carbonated , and very refreshing .
delectably hoppy smell . taste is not bad , but does n't live up to the smell . it tastes thinner than i 'd like .  mouthfeel is full bodied and super smooth . very enjoyable .

really nice aroma . smells of pecans , buttery crust , vanilla and dark fruit .  you can feel how well-crafted this beer is : perfect body ... thin , but not too thin ; carbonated , but not overdone ; hoppy aftertaste , but not a tastebud destroyer .

s : brown sugar , molasses , caramel , dark rum , raisins , and a little toasted malt . t : this is nothing but sweetness and malt in your face . it 's a slow sipper , which means i ca n't handle more than one bottle in a sitting , and it 's just too damn cloying to take even that .  extreme balance and smoothness in this beer , its quite good . big full body with a champaign like fizzyness . im impressed .

up top , a cardboard-colored head recedes quickly to a wisp of foam , but is revived nicely with a quick swirl of the pint glass . the aroma brings everything the style should have : floral , bubble-gum like hops with tropical fruit , pine sap , and spiciness from the rye . still , it 's quite tasty . mouthfeel is dry and juicy at the same time , with an uppity carbonation level that fuels the aggression from the hops .  m- great mouthfeel .
t- very very nice . lots of chocolate & lots of coffee .  the mouthfeel is light , with excellent particulates that roam the mouth . a most excellent brew that i would n't hesitate to try again .

the smell is pleasing . tons of sweet banana and light belgian candied sugars . a nice belgian yeast is present in the smell , with nice sweet lemon scents . a nice beer overall , but not as clean as i would have liked to see .  matches perfectly with the thickness of the body .

it really reminds me of the nose i get off a really good heffeweizen ( spelling might be wrong , but there ya go ) . it 's a bright and inviting smell and makes my mouth water .  very nice feel in the mouth -- rich , thick , tingling bubbles , kind of evaporates on the tongue . medium-heavy body , quite a bit of honey , i get this apple quality .
wonderful . just the perfect amount of fruit mixed with the belgian wheat goodness .  the texture is just flat-out perfect and this is about as easy to drink as you can want .

it pours a cloudy golden orange color and smells delicious . the nose had hints of orange peel , coriander , hops and light caramel . drinkability was a little low though due to the over carbonation and the sweetness of the beer overall , but very good . will buy again  silky smooth on the tongue and exceptionally creamy .

deliciously hoppy nose - massive sweet fruit backed with gritty , resinous hops . extremely fragrant , and powerful . palate is less robust , with a subtle , but pleasant hop character riding over the top of a smooth , buttery sweetness . this leaves it extremely drinkable - very smooth and refreshing . an excellent and tasty little ipa .  m : the mouthfeel is dense and creamy and frothy ... and almost stout-like . excellent .
pretty tasty with a great aroma .  incredible mouthfeel .

smell is incredible . a big sugar smell is predominant accompanied by nice dark malts . there is a nice thickness to it as well , that makes it incredibly smooth . drinkable beer for a strong abv .  m : very thick , borderline creamy . superb .
the aroma is awesome . right away it reminds me of kuhnhenn raspberry eisbock with huge notes of sweet raspberries and chocolate .  mouthfeel is incredible , one of the smoothest beers i 've had .

its smell is sweet and pleasant , and reminded me of peaches . i dare say red stripe is the best smelling lager i have ever come across , although i admit my range of experience is not the widest on beer advocate .  mouthfeel : has a great mouthfeel . it has exceptional smoothness .

really fantastic nose , the raspberries shine through . good interesting beer that is cool to try to reach both the girls and the boys beer drinkers or not .  m : very creamy feeling , small bubbles , not too sticky .

i 've never actually smelt a flanders with actual fruit in the nose but this is really amazing and adds a whole new experience to this brew . simply fantastic and i 'm grateful to have had a chance to try it !  mouthfeel is a heavy but perfect . heavy with lots of lactose , light but fizzi carbonation .
s- very wonderful aroma here . very nice hop smells come from this .  m : the carbonation on this one is perfect . perfect mouthfeel .

s - excellent . yellow grapefruit , with lots of citrus , and a malt backing . great appearance and smell , no taste .  the mouthfeel is incredibly creamy , with the tastes of chocolate and dried fruit coming through .

an isabelline crown persists and leaves luxurious cascades of sandy lacing - those bubbles that stick rest atop viscous legs suggesting snow dusted mountain peaks . aroma is highly potent - it hits you from the moment the seal is popped . brown sugar , high quality aged sherry , vanilla , coconut , dense brown bread , faint clove ... the list goes on . the flavor profile closely follows the aromatics , but everything is present in a lesser degree . lots of flavors come and go - abbreviated tastes of bread crusts , licorice , and dried tropical fruit . the finish is quite nutty and hints at leather as well . almost like an armagnac it is a beer well suited to contemplation . the oak notes contribute a great deal without becoming overwhelming ( brandy barrel angel 's share i 'm lookin ' at you ) . definitely worth seeking out and sticking in the cellar ...  mouthfeel : thick , creamy and full-bodied , smooth with just enough carbonation . spicy warming alcohol remains through the finish and leaves a tingly sensation in the mouth and a nice warmth throughout .

it could stand to have a little less heat , but it was otherwise pretty delicious . again , it 's slightly hot , and seems a little less rich than the smell , but it 's still quite good . m - pretty much flat , syrupy aftertaste , thinner than i 'd expect for a 10 % brew .  the hop particles make it sticky as hell , the rim of my glass is sticky , my lips are sticky , and the mouthfeel is outstanding ! as far as double ipas go ( which let 's face it this is really comparable to an ipa ) , i still prefer either pliny or any of the alpine ipas , but this is a nice change of pace .
aromas are awesome . i can smell this for a couple of feet away .  the aroma speaks strongly of roasted grains , as you would expect from a stout , while on the tongue the beer has tremendous body .

s : some spice notes in the aroma -- cloves , cinnamon , and nutmeg -- followed by sweet caramel and vanilla aromas . there are some floral notes in there as well as a touch of sweet citrus . t : similar to the aroma , spices come up front but do n't overwhelm .  i keep tasting chocolate ice cream ... dry chocolate ice cream ... not cloy at all ... very fantastic finish and mouthfeel ... german beer ftw will buy again !

a trace of lacing & head retention s : dates , raisins , steel & port soaked raisins t : rich dark fruits , herbal & leafy hop bitterness up front . started strong , but the dryness & oakyness detracted as this warmed mf : slightlty overgassed , medium bodied & with fair balance drinks easy , but this one could use at least 12-18 more months of aging , not a bad take on the style  mouthfeel/drinkability- sublime mouthfeel , super-easy in the mouth .

a - pours an opaque golden hue with limited head and noticeable lacing s - apples , bleu-cheese , cherry pie dominate the aroma , surprisingly . citrus and grapefruit as it warms . t - very sweet , especially for an ipa .  beautiful .
this smells real delicious . t - balanced malt hop mix up front with a hint of the fruity taste the smell indicated .  it is full bodied and creamy in the mouth .

looks find s- awesome citrus hop aroma , much more aggressive than i expected from a tiny , 4 % bitter . insane ! lovely m- body is overall pretty thin , nothing to see here o- awesome sessionable beer .  5.0 on the mouthfeel with a huge creamy full-bodied mouthcoating that covers every bit .

the aroma is very nice , a heady mixture of malt , honey and alcohol . unfortunately the flavor does n't come close to fulfilling the promise in the aroma . the body is carbonated with a rather lager-ish character .  velvety mouthfeel and smoother than sinatra .
aroma : hoppy , hoppy , hoppy . awesome !  this beer feels absolutely perfect in the mouth .

a definitive malty , smoky scent with maybe a hint of apple lurking .  m : this stout has an amazing creamy mouthful like a well done milk stout without being too creamy or way too thin like most crap stouts . medium to full bodied ; a really nice medium carbonation on this one .

s : holy hops , batman ! intense , complex , and amazing . t : starts off with citrus and herbal hops , then transitions to a bit of caramel malt before finishing with a wave of piney bitterness . delicious . m : medium bodied with a good dose of initially spiky , finally smooth carbonation .  m : perfect . it 's thick without being cloying .
very sessionable , but only an adequate porter with the exception of the nose which is amazing .  the mouthfeel is where this shines , exceptional medium body and smoothness .

apricot golden body , tiny hop flecks visible and a classic ivory creamy , spritzy cap . the nose is very aromatic like a freshly prepped bowl of ambrosia . lots of ripe citrus in the nose , specifically tangerine and ruby red grapefruit . the taste is crisp , hoppy and i could tell upon first drink the mouthfeel is superb . i 'll say it , it 's overrated a little .  perhaps my favorite aspect is the full and very creamy mouthfeel .

s- wow , loads of scents starting with a spiced apple and spiced pear followed by great light sweet malt scents and of course the belgian bready yeast ... this reminded me of my trips i used to take to julian with my parents and brothers as a child , we would always go up there for some fresh apple pie and hot cider ... t- not as much as the smell , but still great . you pick up on the apple/pear , spices , light sweet malt and loads of bready yeast with a nice crisp finish .  m= smooth and crisp . feels resinous as well which is great for an ipa . d= super drinkable .

a little unusual too . overall , a unique and very enjoyable iipa .  mouthfeel is as silky as they come , the sensation over the tongue is as pleasurable as quaffing god 's nipple lactations . taste is , however , the killer here because it 's just not as explosive as the complex nose and full body could easily have supported .

a - pours an orange copper color with a layer of fine bubbles on the surface s - lots of piney and citurs hops , lemon , orange , just a totally amazing aroma t - grapefruit & orange upfront , sweet malt & a slightly bitter hop finish , a really flavorful hopbomb m/d - medium body with good carbonation , just a really drinkable beer , somehow its 10 % which you really have no way of knowing  the body is just fantastic : full , creamy and smooth .

unusual , overwhelming and lovely aroma of port wine , raisins and dried figs , hints of barnyard . i understand that some people find it cloying , but with a beer this rich in aroma and flavour , i accept the sweetness .  full bodied , heavy on the palate and full of flavor . i love it .

i 've had a few of these and this one plays up the humidor to 11 . incredible . t. the jai alai flavor is played down a bit to the predominate cedar flavor . the grassy and citrus hops are very nice with a good malt .  mouthfeel is exceptional ! this beer is smooth , silky , creamy .

bottle- color of dark orange , with a decent off white head - nose of fresh hops , pine , mint , resin , cannabis , and slight malts taste of fresh hops , slight mint , resin , cannabis , and slight malts - body is smooth , but too watery , and with low to medium carbonation aftertaste of some metallic , hops , and resin  m : medium body with a fantastic carbonation balance ! amazing here !

its smell is its best characteristic -- floral hops , malty , a hint of wheat -- really beautiful . the taste is sweety & malty , as well as bitter .  the texture on this is great . with the silky texture and sweetness , this is a good sipper , but nothing you 'd have more than 2 of in a single sitting .

the smell is great . as a chocolate lover , i really like this . smells like straight up melted chocolate . but this is really good if you like chocolate . next time i will pair it with some raspberries or strawberries , or make a damn milkshake out of it .  still i thought the aroma was alittle weak , but once it hits your mouth it is amazing .

the initial smell is awesome -- somewhat of a bubble gum and lemon mix . a strong taste of fruity malt/yeast and a very dry aftertaste , the strong feel of hops comes on towards the finish of this one .  a great take on belgium ale ; apples , pears , lemons , apricot and orange flavors nustle their way thru a carbonated full bodied swig .
a little swirl allows a bit of malt to show up , which smells simple enough .  m : the mouthfeel is perfect . full and creamy with a little grittiness in the texture .

aroma is of banana , the spiciness of clove , and actually some pineapple . taste is not as good as the smell . it 's a bit earthy , and far less of a phenolic presence than most hefeweizens i 've had .  the mouthfeel is outstanding . substantial , but not quite so thick as to confuse it with a stout .

s- smell is awesome . tons of tropical fruits pineapple , apricot , and grapefruit a bit of sweetness coming through from the malts . t- follows the nose really well . a very nice hop forward beer .  mouthfeel is exceptional . it feels good in the mouth but leaves no lasting memories on the taste buds .
s- totally amazing smell . just like pumkin pie .  the mouthfeel is fucking perfect : it 's thick and creamy .
s : a very rich banana/clove mix , just about perfect . no hops , no nothing .  mouthfeel is super creamy and silky smooth .

amazing nose of peach with a high , frothy , long lasting head with an almost soapy mouthfeel .  mouthfeel- this is an exceptionally smooth saison , with the mouthfeel rivaling that of the saison dupont , my favorite of the style and one of my favorite beers . the tank 7 is definitely a thicker beer , very complimentary to the flavors .

a : beautiful deep dark red , with a foamy , rich head s : unbelievably fragrant of cherries t : this is a sweet cherry beer . yummy .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , rich and creamy it 's quite thick and chewy without going over the top .
it has a great smell of having trouble explaining other than sweet . this is a very drinkable beer but there are many more much better .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , substantial and even sticky .

short 's nailed this one . spicy tomatoes , peppercorns , alcohol , tabasco , peppers .  mouthfeel ; very tight and lively carbonation , slick and creamy in the finish , pretty complex and admirable .

smell : lovely aroma of apples , pears , and light citrus - notably grapefruit . slightly sour smell comes in at the end . a very sour character shows up that is a bit cloying , then the beer finishes strong and unpleasantly bitter .  the mouthfeel was very very thick and creamy and not as thin as say a sierra nevada .

mmmmm , toasty , husky pale malt and plenty of spicy , floral saaz hops . a slick finish rounds out a flavor that , i have to be honest , was a bit of a let down after the tremendous nose . still tasy though ; i guess i just had some unreasonable expectations .  deliciously smooth . coating the entire mouth with a lasting finish .

half inch head and thick head retention s : straight dole pineapple orange juice or something like it ! phenomenally citrusy . t : more dole juice ! crisp bite at the front before smooth finish . o : delicious ! very unique . probably could n't have more than one but very enjoyable . the fruit juice character is pretty interesting , that 's for sure .  excellent mouthfeel and not too heavy .

smell : sweet fruit like berries , pear , and some citrus orange . strong spiciness not sure what kind of spices , maybe coriander . a bit musty , but in a good way , as it warms up it starts to smell like bread dough . overall : pretty good drinkability , the appearance is really disappointing , but the ( more important ) smell and taste are great !  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is full bodied with low carbonation , and oh so smooth .
the smell of this 2 year old beer is so rich and strong . it smells of sweet fruits and a little bit of alcohol .  bear republic really , really nailed the mouthfeel on this one .

very aromatic . t : consistently bitter from start to finish , but not overwhelmingly so . i love the scent and the hop flavors , and i can see why this beer is very appealing to others ... but it 's just not my thing .  m - smooth , silky , full body with the perfect amount of carbonation o - great brew !

smell : citrusy , with hints of spices , very powerful if you can wait a minute or so before you drink it .  t- the taste is starts out very smooth and creamy from the mouthfeel with some of roasted malts quickly followed by a nice bitter finish . m- the mouthfeel is silky smooth from the oatmeal with a moderate amount of carbonation . d- very good stuff , and not too boozy for a 9 % beer even though you can feel the warmth .

grapefruit ! my favorite aroma in beer and life for some strange reason , but enough about me ... .once i break from my grapefruit coma , i do notice pine and a little lemon rind in the background t - there is that damn grapefruit again , i just ca n't get away from it . immense hop flavor with a surprising amount of malt that finds its way through the hops .  mouthfeel is silky smooth , really nice . body fairly full and the beer leaves an impression all the way over the tongue .

smell : the smell is excellent . the bourbon comes through in the form of vanilla and a touch of oakiness . it is exceptionally tasty and smells fantastic , but i am having a very hard time getting over the mouthfeel .  mouthfeel is utterly smooth with just a hint of carbonation ... placidly perfect .

) extremely unique . outstanding ! t - sweet sugary honey and vanilla flavors up front , followed by strong herbal flavors , mint , anise , and a bit of tangy hop . m - medium bodied and slick , with a course , gritty , dry finish .  the feeling in your mouth , however is gorgeous ! smooth , silky , incredible.. so incredibly good that i actually said 'incredible ' in a french accent because it deserved such smoothness ... i 'm not going to lie , as for drinkability.. i 'm not as into this as anchor 's or even sierra nevada 's , christmas offerings this year , but it is still very drinkable to this lass .

that 's a good looking chunk of froth . huge aroma with lots of piney , grassy and citrusy hop smells . mmmmm . very spicy piney hops mostly though with some alcohol and a tad bit of malty earthy smell . this is a marvelous beer that i wish i could get my hands on again .  this beer has an excellent mouthfeel .

aroma is of espresso , burnt grains , bittersweet chocolate , vanilla , and black walnut . taste is thin , burnt , vanilla and french roast coffee ... there is nothing more .  ( not a huge coffee stout fan ) ( blasphemous i know ) the greatest thing about this beer is the smooth creamy texture that is present while drinking .
s-this beer has a nice sweet flower aroma with hints of roses and apricots .  really wonderful . the mouthfeel is the most impressive and outstanding attribute of this beer .

a - clear honey colored with very little head . s - smells of ripe cherries , raspberries , honey , alcohol , mango , citrus , brandy , apple juice , flowers , and apricots . t - tastes of cherry , alcohol , brandy , citrus , candied sugar , sherry , and honey .  mouthfeel - heavy body with mild carbonation . it 's perfect to me .

the aroma , which was really the high point of this beer , was quite terrific -- roasty malt with hints of chocolate and black cherries .  mouthfeel : delightfully creamy and full-bodied . very pleasant .

nose was wood the wonderful blending of currant . an herbal note of something meaty in the nose . funk like that of brie cheese skin and a bloody fruit . there was some mineral wood interaction with the fruit that gives it a food palatable quality , but it was quite subtle . overall i would only have this if you 're eating some sort of exquisitely cooked fish .  mouthfeel was virtually perfect .

smell was very appetizing , a rich sour cherry with a bit of roasted malt . taste was not nearly as robust , pretty much just a strong stout , a nice bit of burnt malt and coffee , coupled with a nice tartness from the cherry , but not nearly as rich and complex as the aroma had me expecting . mouthfeel was very rich and creamy , medium body .  mouthfeel : fantastic . great carbonation , no real aftertaste and washes easily over the palate .
nose : a nice profile of strong citrus notes , not overly complex , but nice . tongue : what strikes my first is just how malty this is .  the mouthfeel is full and velvety .
the smell is amazing , dense spectrum of aromas floating out of my glass .  m : great carbonation feel with a nice medium body . amazing here . perfect !

was picked up by my bro-in-law and quickly swept away to milly 's tavern to begin our pre-race inebriation . the pumpkin ale was a solid beer , and had a wonderful nose and flavor . the color was clear golden and the glass came lined with sugar and spice !  mouthfeel : exceptionally smooth and silky as can be .

wonderful aroma . warm and oaky , molasses . almost get a bbq sauce scent , very spicey like a worcester sauce . very interesting tastes in this one , unusual .  mouthfeel is what always gets me on these beers , i love the chewy creamy coats your throat feeling here .
heaps of coco in the nose . roasted malt on the tongue , but the taste is surprising fleeting .  mouthfeel : spot on in my opinion . medium to medium-lite body with perfect amount of carbonation .

smell is immensely yeasty with hints of clove , orange , and vanilla . decent nose if you ask me .  extremely smooth tasting beer . bodied is so full its nearly chewable . mouthfeel is full and round . finish is clean and very smooth .
head stays for a good while s- smells identical to apple pie .  m - perfect carbonation .
beautiful color , deep dark amber with beautiful smelling hops and some nice plumy undertones .  amazingly smooth going down ; full bodied with light carbonation .
s : wonderful nose . toasted notes with some malt character hiding behind it .  mouthfeel is heavy and smooth with a nice small bite of carbonation , wonderful .
really loved the nose .  t- pretty solid all around . very smooth , robust , and thick .

aroma : smell is incredible natural smelling apricot tones this one smells very nice , i am impressed not overly cloying and no off tones to boot . very natural smells like apricot juice , good stuff .  incredibly smooth mouthfeel , likely due to the aging .

smells great , like a sweet belgian with lots of yeast and fruit and candy . taste was unbelievably tart and dry , especially after it smelled so sweet and dubbel-ish . lots of smokey coffeey and mineral water .  the mouthfeel was phenomenal . to have a cask conditioned beer is such a treat , and i 'm glad my neighborhood bar always has one beer on cask .
s - sweet hop delight . much stronger hop aroma than doppelbocks i have had before . earthy hop aroma with a very sweet scent as well .  perfect creamy mouthfeel .

s - sweet complex dark stone fruits . cinnamon apple fig . with a bit of pimento . mild oaky hickory hop smells . although not as complex as the smells it is yummy .  mouthfeel is thick as hell and creamy , perfect for a big ris this is smooth as hell , much smoother than beers with this much ash flavor usually are .
huge sweet and bready malts rise to the nose upon an initial whiff .  wonderful full mouthfeel .

smell- lots of dark fruits off the starting line . the dark fruit aroma is huge . followed by a hint of banana esters . very inviting , but also oddly fearsome . taste- not nearly as complex as aroma let on . as it warms , it gets better , but not that extremely rich , complex blend of tastes that a lot of belgian holiday beers have . drinkability- good , but not great .  very nice full bodied mouthfeel . easily drinkable .

s- 100 % hoppy nose . d- decent drinkability . very bitter . wanted more balance .  mouthfeel was phenomenal - silky smooth and with a slight hops bite on the tongue , giving 'way on the finish to a great caramel sweetness .

it is overpoweringly fruity and has an amazing aroma . it pours a cloudy light rose pink with a huge head.you are overwhelmed by the raspberry nose .  thick with just a little bit of slickness and just enough carbonation . sly fox oatmeal stout is a solid beer with a fantastic mouthfeel ; probably something i would order again .
smell : wonderful aromas on this beer .  the finish lingers for a while , almost spicy with a slight alcohol burn m - pretty ideal for this style i thought .

smell : the smell is a wonderful mix of rich malts and strong , powerfully complex hops that are almost perfectly balanced . perhaps this flying dog may stand the test ... taste and mouthfeel : the taste is not as good as expected , but still not bad . drinkability and overall : this beer is just a tiny bit above the average ipa , but definitly nothing too seek out .  mouthfeel : very thick and very very smooth , wonderful mouthfeel .

s : fragrant molasses , baked dark bread , brown sugar , sweet , loving the nose . t : baked brown bread again , baker 's chocolate with a fair amount of roast . d : great nose , solid taste , in the end a nice effort , it needs more sweetness to be really good , it definitely has potential .  where this brew really stands out is the creamy mouthfeel . that smoothness works to perfection with sweetness , but does n't work quite as well with bitterness .

s : a pretty complex smell , though coffee beans tend to be the dominant auroma . it 's nicely accented by a faint hint of sweet chocolate . t : there 's a real bright fruitiness that i do n't really pick up on in the scent that compliments ( but not well ) the coffee flavor that is n't so much roasted anymore as it is just kind of bitter . both are underwhelming to say the least , but this taste is n't as bad as it is disappointing .  the mouthfeel was spot on and the taste was close behind .

very authentic aroma ... think of opening the cupboard to access your spice rack , then getting a whiff of fresh rosemary . d - another innovative beer with an authentic aroma and flavor .  mouthfeel was awesome . farily prickly carbonation with some slight drying on the finish due to the barrel aging .

smell : the smell really is impressive . heavy heavy coffee . good malt to support , but great coffee aromas . taste : feels like i 'm enjoying a nice cup of coffee fresh out of the percolator after waking up in a tent .  m - huge , thick , syrupy , creamy , perfect carbonation .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a darker color than golden , with a small white head and okay lacing ... s : the smell is very strongly grapefruited ... t : wow , a very potent hop flavor . the bitterness is actually quite light ... m : crisp , pretty light , and slightly dryish ... d : a really nice beer .  feel is pretty rich for the style , although it 's medium body it 's almost full really , with such a rich , smooth feel . excellent . honestly , it 's not very typical of the style at all , but i 'm not letting that change my rating .
s : pinot barrel with some dark fruit riding a wave bringing a boatload of vanilla and whiskey .  full creamy mouthfeel with a low carbonation . thick , thick mouthfeel .

the aroma is fantastic ; a huge hit of lemony citrus and grass with undertones of pale malt and yeast . excellent ; the best pilsner i 've tried .  m : nice and light , yet still has some body . very smooth , good carbonation , good residue . exceptional .

smell is incredible . only the most dazzling gets a 5,0 , but if there were a 4,75 , i 'd definitely give it to 'smell ' on this one . to my regret , while still very good , this smells quite a bit better than it tastes . definitely good , but not even close to the depth and complexity in the smell .  but the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible .
s : there are very strong aromas of coffee beans and roasted malts in the nose .  body is medium-full for style , and this is just about perfect on the way down .
notes - that wonderful smell gave me high hopes for this one .  m= perfect dryness and crispness .

smells of strong peat , as you 'd expect with the name `` islay '' , but there is nice chocolate and roast balance . sweet flavour actually . very creamy mouthfeel , very sweet .  m - creamy and rich . the carbonation is very laidback ... almost feels as if it floats on the tongue . very soft ... puffy , in a way .
this smelled like the kitchen while my mom bakes banana bread .  mouth is extremely crisp , clean with tremendous carbonation and a nice light body .

viscous notes , along with minimal head retention & lacing s : orchard fruit , grainyness , & pineapple t : peaches , pineapple , honey , boozey grain & a kiss of estery yeast & mushroom like funk .  however , the mouthfeel of this beer is phenomenal , on the tim of your tongue it tingles , in the middle it is smooth as silk , on on the edges it is a touch syrupy ( amazing ) a good beer , but not worth the price they charge for it .

exceptional smell of toffee , caramel , nutty . wanted to eat something that smelled like this . slightly bitter note on the nose . sweet with a more bitter nutty taste .  mouthfeel is outstanding . super thick and syrupy , that flavor coats the palate forever .
it smells like when i picked hops and stuck my head into a box of them . it smells so fresh it 's wonderful . the taste was rather assertive in hoppiness .  the carbonation is perfect . i love this .

the nose is nice . very nice . the nose just teases me with anticipation that the flavor never delivers .  bitter black chocolate moves into the woodiness and finishes boozy m- creamy , full-bodied , coats the mouth and boozy heat d- really impressed with this one .
smells great , but kind of disjointed on the taste and mouthfeel .  m : medium body with the perfect amount of smooth , yet lively , carbonation . truly excellent .

s - nice ! grapefruit aroma with some hints of pine fill my nose . very attractive flowery hops , with some bready biscuity malt hidden along the way . nice co2 .  the mouthfeel is absolutely perfect for a porter , so smooth and silky .

s : creme brulee ? the nose on this beer is amazing . loads of vanilla , caramel , cream , butterscotch and a tad bit of roasted malt .  the mouth feel is the richest and thickest i have ever tasted in a beer !

it smells awesome , but i 'm concerned that it 's going to taste a bit too sweet . upfront is strong bourbon , which is quite pleasant .  m : fairly full body is well-attenuated for its strength , with an off-dry finish . perfect balance imho ... just enough residual sweetness to keep the alcohol from being too drying .

s : the smell is unbelievable . tons of robust , fresh raspberries blended with a nice cherry and lemony tartness . slightly acidic smelling with a hint of vinegar . not as robust and/or flavorful as the smell led me to believe , but this is great nonetheless . mouth puckering raspberry goodness to start , followed by some lemon rinds , dry oak , and slight vinegar . it was very good , but we all thought it was lacking something .  mouthfeel- damn , this sh*t is creamy ! smooth , medium carbonation , but goes down super smooth . nice light bitterness in the aftertaste .
aroma is great . rich dark chocolate . wow , what a disappointment after the aroma . mouthfeel is nice . a shame that a beer that smelled so good did n't live up to it .  perfect mouthfeel .

smells like ... .oranges ! ! ! fresh , ripe oranges . tart , citrusy oranges . the beer has strong carbonation , a bit much for my liking ... .almost soda-like in the most extreme case . hints honey at times . needless to say , great pick for hot weather .  tiny bit of alcohol flavor let 's you know it can do some damage m : super creamy dipa , full bodied , good bubbly carbonation ( do n't know why there was n't much head though !

i do n't know if the age helped , but this smells fantastic ... deep milk chocolate ... . nice bourbon and vanilla notes ... hints of brown sugar and cinnamon ... really a great nose . flavor loses anything from the nose ... a bit of dark cherry essence rounds out the ris flavors ... fudgy toward the finish.. oak seems a bit musky/tannic.. medium body with good carbonation .  the mouthfeel is outstanding , like an expensive champagne and it finishes very dry .

aroma definitely has the jp funk , with some wet hay and mustiness , with a decent amount of light fruits - apricots and oranges . there is also a solid oaky tannin character to the nose .  m - perfect body .

smells amazing ! t - not too much smoke , bet definitely present .  all the great flavor of the bottled lhms here , but perfectly creamy and full in texture . this only further reinforces my belief that nearly every big beer should be served nitro .

holy hops . i like me some hops . huge hops and not much else to smell ... maybe a touch of some orange peel or citrus something . i was blasted immediately with the hops from the first taste and on . overall i liked it ... i would n't complain if i drank it again .  the mouthfeel was amazing . nearly full-bodied .

the smell is extremely interesting , behind the hops it just reeks of fresh peach to me . i kept sniffing the beer throughout my time with it , just because it was so much fun to get that strong of a peach smell from a beer .  the mouthfeel is freakin unbelieveable for me . unique and probably the finest mouthfeel i have felt in any belgian , ever .
despite the abrasive alcohol , the nose is still pretty damn good .  mouthfeel is heavy bodied and velvety smooth .
amber highlights s- smells of nice mild hops and a nutty undertone t- has a rich caramel taste .  full rich mouthfeel , particularly fun after back-to-backing the hansenns cassis .

okaayy ... ... the smell hooked me . i got a great smell of lots of spice ; cloves and some other i could n't i.d. , and some banana . now i 'm getting somewhere ... the taste was spicy-sweet banana and cloves , etc but not with the same intensity as weissbiers auf deutschland .  mouthfeel was creamy and exceptional . i was surprised to be able to drink the whole thing since i am not a fan of coffee at all , but this was a pleasant change of pace for me .

smells good too , obvious floral hops and substantial bready slightly sweet malt , both of which hit at the same time . this review is probably going to come out higher than it should due to the deceptively good appearance and smell .  sweet malts are offset by crisp hops together producing a wonderful balance and mouthfeel . sooo smooth !

not faux-bacos as many low-end rauschbiers often are ... but honest to god bacon . once you get through the scent , there is a wonderfully salty and sweet beer underneath , that makes you want to keep drinking .  mouthfeel was absolutely terrific .

s - huge pine aroma that is quickly and easily enjoyable . massively beautiful from the get-go , with underlying citrus notes . a perfect , varied aroma that promises wonderful delights within t - slight pine taste , bit of grapefruit , pure hops abound . d - very nice , but perhaps lacking a bit of malt balance making this a bit more difficult to enjoy .  m/d : a full body that is creamy and velvety smooth .

smelled fantastic ! citrus fruits dominate - grapefruit , lemon , orange . taste was disappointing after the wonderful smell . the smell was very sweet , but it tasted bitter and sour . actually , the taste is pretty appropriate , since it tasted like unripened fruit . this is the the first of the vertical epics i 've tried and i was n't very impressed .  this beer has an amazing mouthfeel , very full and luscious , super smooth .

exquisite critrusy , lemony aroma ; actually smells 'juicy ' . just amazing . flavour consists of traditional hefeweizen attributes with the addition of citrusy , american style hops .  m : incredibly creamy leaving a nice coating around the mouth that tingles slightly .

s : perfumy nose ( muscat ? ) with grapes and chamomile flowers , pungent , with hints of honeysuckle . t : there is a belgian yeasty estery upfront which is nice . after that the grapes really come out , particularly the gewurztraminer which i 'm a fan of since i love alsatian whites . but anyways , it 's a fun beer to delve into , tasty for sure . a marriage of northern french wine and belgian beer , it makes perfect sense .  m- feel is exceptionally clean and smooth .
s : molasses ! brown sugar ... dark fruit ... some tanginess noted . t : chocolate ... sweetness from the malt .  m : the feel is thick and chewy with a nice creamy texture .

aroma held very much of the brandy barrel aging . cherries vanilla , and some very tart notes as well . tart cherries oak and vanilla mix nicely in the flavor good caramel malt sweet backbone . amazingly complex and flavorful . really great beer is grounded due to complete lack of carbonation .  the mouthfeel on this beer is abosolutely amazing , almost like carbonated cream , it is wonderful and invites another sip immediately .

aromas are the usual wow you get from a strong barleywine , with smells including honey , honey ... and more honey . very intense . the smell is wonderful and the taste is honey-delicious , but it lacks refinement , and does n't balance out well .  this is one of the thickest beers i 've had . very heavy and smooth mouthfeel .

v=ql-n78agg_y appearance : clear golden , 1-finger head , excellent lacing aroma : hop oil , banana , lemon citrus , hibiscus , buttery biscuit , dry floral notes , hint of pine flavor : medium body , earthiness , dirt , grapefruit , pine , cup-cake icing sweetness , banana , bready malts , lemon rind , medium carbonation , mild bitterness pairings : fried shrimp brew + pairing : buttery dough on the shrimp balances this brew well  mouthfeel is perfect , my ideal belgian .

smell- by far the sweetest smelling beer i 've ever had .  silky silky smooth on the mouth , it makes it feel as light bodied but if you take the time to get a feel it 's almost medium . just fantastic . o- this is deffinitely a good saison , the mouthfeel is the highlight .

aroma is of fresh peaches , and is absolutely marvelous ; the best part of this beer . however , also plain and unexciting . good for what it is , but not anything that really excites me .  m - creamy and full in the mouth , so good , this is just what i want in a marzen .
smell is very hoppy , very floral .  m - extremely smooth .

nose is amazing ... sour cherry , earthy soil , fruit leathers , saddle leather , cranberry , pomegranate , craisins , dark chocolate ... i mean this nose goes on and on and on ! then saddle leather , peach pit , cranberry ( big time ) , raisins , dried black figs , dried berries , fresh black berries and on and on and on ... the best avery sour i 've had , and one of the best sours i 've had produced in north america ! awesome .  this was the first belgian i ever had . it has a very creamy smoothness that i really love . finishes long and dry with more fruityness .

the nose is bursting with fresh blueberries . very sweet nose reminds me of waffles , muffins , cereal with its grainy like finish . the blueberries are n't as dominating in the flavor as they are in the aroma . buttered bread , toast , tart fruity quality .  mouthfeel the best part of this beer , really smooth with just a little bit of carbonation .
the scent is excellent and strong , with a bouquet of citrus .  perfect . d- a remarkably smooth beer , although a bit mild .

great nose on this altbier . very mild fragrance , overall , but perfectly to style . perfect for the cool austin weather this time of year .  round velvety texture , excellent carbonation , and ( as you would expect ) some warming . exceptionally satisfying brew - if not my absolute favorite from unibroue , it is the one i return to most often .

this is where this beer truly shines . sweet brown sugar and candied fruits - i thought of cherries and apricot - are met head-on by the alcohol . the result is a rich , warm , somewhat medicinal elixir that was just wonderful to inhale . do n't get me wrong - it 's very nice . it just did n't quite live up to the advance billing . very nice .  all kinds of malty goodness going on here - silky smooth , slightly pinpoint carbonation .

very interesting . smells sweet but different .  m-grand canyon deep and gordian knot complex . amazingly tantalizing on the palate . while it looks still in the glass it bursts with palate stimulating carbonation with each sip . like an amusement park in your mouth ! this is a highly enjoyable and palate stimulating sipper . a mighty fine drinking brew .
s : pine and citrus hop aroma . the smell is reminiscent of pliny the elder , kind of a marijuana smell also , like green flash imperial ipa .  a great feel that has a body that replenishes itself .

loving the smell ... sweet oats , grain . - wonderful zingy porter ... nice bitter earthy hop.. and a backdrop of sweet oats and chocolate malt ... a very pleasant and drinkable porter .  mouthfeel is of a super smooth , velvetty batch . this may be one of the smoothest , silkiest brews that i have had .

there are several layers to the nose that create a great amount of depth . and finishes of with a chocolate covered apple character very nice . taste : the taste starts out very similar to the nose with very light touches of bourbon and oak but for me the beer has more chocolate than anything else very rich dark chocolate character and finishes off nicely with just a touch of apple mouthfeel : medium body with low carbonation overall : very good beer .  ideal texture for an ipa .

glass : generic goblet appearance : light copper color , thin head smell : sweet , fruity , strong sour grape , notes of cinnamon taste : light , dry , light malt profile . overall : the taste didnt quite hold up to the huge bouquet .  for the style , this is an exceptional mouthfeel .
s : peaches . need i say more ? t : lots of peach favor , with a big sour bite at the end .  the mouthfeel is full and warming , in fact , this beer is a huge belly warmer .

very nice . nose is absolutely beautiful with belgian chocolate , rich cocoa , caramel , toffee . smells like this one is going to be a whopper ... ... and sadly it 's not . finish is very clean and crisp . the nose , however , is truly wonderful so one should at least experience that .  the beer itself is pretty thick , and mixed with the lingering foamy head , it feels great in the mouth for savoring what taste there actually is .

some lacing s : pretty nice , smells wildly fruity and pretty strong . the great smell is a little too misleading .  what got me hooked was how smooth and creamy this beer was . fantastic . this beer is by far one of the richest and creamiest beers i have ever had .

the aroma is wonderfully smokey and peaty , with some dark malts in there too . great aroma and interesting flavor .  great palate , though . even when it gets warm , great warmth and sliky smooth syrups .

the beer smells absolutely beautiful . like bittersweet chocolate and espresso , with some caramel and molasses notes . this beer smells really fantastic . taste is a lot of the same .  altogether pleasing to the tongue and brain , it also had a beautifully full mouthfeel from the oustandingly appropriate delicate carbonation .
s - a lot going on but still well balanced . smells of citrus ( maybe orange ) and pine , along with some winter `` spices .  awesome mouthfeel .
the smell is amazing . coffee dominates , and while i 'm not a coffee drinker , i like the smell of it .  easy to drink due to it 's creamy mouthfeel and pleasant flavor .

the smell is wonderful . tannin , grapes , apples , apple peels , raisins , caramel , touch of cocoa , and a hint of alcohol .  silky , creamy , and perfectly textured , this mouthfeel ca n't be beat .

smells very good . taste - very sweet up front with lots of raisin and some dark almost cherry flavor . very unusual . it tastes like a funky port , frankly . a very interesting `` beer '' .  m : soft , smooth carbonation , big and viscous body , excellent finish . there 's very little more that i want from a big ris d : i drank my bottle in an hour and was craving more notes : i did n't really expect much from this beer because nh have n't really impressed me with much of what they 've done but hot damn , this was impressive !

awesome bouquet ; fruitiness and candy malts . even so a pretty good drop .  taste again where do i start ... sweet , spicy dark fruits soaked in alcohol ( raisins , currents , dates ) , toasted caramel notes , bready , some brandy / rum traces , biscuity , warming alcohol , spicy hop bitterness forces itself through the sweet maltiness , light madeira wine hints ... feel - so silky smooth ... rich and creamy ... light viscousness.. low drinkablilty for this one - a beer for savouring and sipping slowly ... overall - a phenomenal beer ... highly recommended .

awesomely hoppy nose of ripe citrus and waxy tropical notes with a good dose of pine too- mango , ruby red grapefruit , papaya , peach , grassy lemon mint . very pungent . overall , very juicy and delicious , with my one complaint being that the beer finishes a little short .  mouthfeel is perfect -- light but not watery , highly carbonated ... perfect for the style .
amazingly complex . taste follows nose and begins with dark malts and honey sweetness .  m- creamy smooth with just the right amount of carbonation and a nice , dry finish .

aroma is smack you in the face hop blast appropriate for a pnw ipa . taking dry-hopping to its logical extreme with several whole hop cones in each bottle .  t/m - well carbonated , providing a prickly yet very smooth feel as it rolls across the tongue .

terrific . tons of pepper and biting bitterness on the tongue . big letdown from the outstanding aroma . lots of citric flavor , especially grapefruit and orange , but the sweetness of the malt just does not do any justice to the balance and drinkability .  the mouthfeel on this beer is great , so creamy with just enough bubbles that make it not to syrupy .

the smell is probably the best part of this beer . sweet and herbal with a touch of honey , hazelnut , citrus of some kind . the finish is very dry . pretty cool beer .  the best part of the rwanda gatsinga coffee stout is in my opinion the mouthfeel which is extremely smooth and leaves a pleasant malty coffee-dominated aftertaste and a smile on your face .
very inviting . malt beginning just sorta slides on by without really putting down stakes .  mouthfeel is superb . great level of spice , perfect carbonation , medium body .

smell : vanilla is immediately evident , as is a woody character . bittersweet chocolate is evident , as is a tobacco richness underneath that may be coming from the tea added . this is one seriously complex aroma ... taste : surprisingly the tea flavor jumps out first , and it is very sweet , somewhat fruity , and not an altogether pleasant introduction to the tastebuds . very shocking first taste , but once you get used to it , things seem to get better . no hops to be found in this sugary bomb . '' this was a great workout for the nose and tastebuds , but unfortunately , the whole thing just did n't come together very well .  the mouthfeel is luxurious , thick , and chewy . amazing . i am impressed with this brew . flavors are great and the mouthfeel is unearthly .

as the beer warms , these scents blend beautifully . t : opens tart with assertive notes of grapefruit , lemon , bitter orange , kumquat , grass , salty brine , and oaky , lactic yeast .  m - the creamiest beer i 've ever had . wow . thick , smooth , perfect .

wow , this smells hoppy . i have never smelled this amount of hops in an ris , i get a lot of really citrusy hops , maybe some toasty chocolate under it , but the hops dominate , wish i could know when this was bottled . it is really interesting though .  the feel is super dry , tannic and superb on the palate , rough , sticky , and full ... easy to drink as this crushed by the girlfriend and i in about 15 minutes .

smell : complex nose boasts belgian yeast with a sweet apricot note and some underlying white pepper spice . complexities abound . taste : a well balanced tripel with a nice peppery spice and undistinguishable fruit presence . overall : solid , solid tripel . very fine beer .  great relaxed flavor , it has a nice sweetness to it , a good malt body ; it would be a great beer to drink while out on the river all day , as it has a wonderful flavor without having too much ( it was made with this in mind , according to one of the brewers ) . goes down extremely smooth with a great crisp , sweet aftertaste . ( had on-tap at the star city vfd brew fest fund raiser .

smells nearly exactly like pumpkin pie . this was my first pumpkin beer , and it 's not a style i 'm particularly enamored with .  mouthfeel is thick and chewy , as it should be fir a beer of this strength .

s : bold oaky qualites up front . big on the coffee as well . wow i wan na dive in . i drank the whole bomber but it was overtime . if the chocolate and vanilla can push thru a bit with time it will be a real winner .  taste & mouthfeel : smoothness is impeccable within the moderate body , big doughy biscuity malt flavour is the showcase of this brew .

what struck me first is the aroma , very rich with a mix of floral tones and sweet caramel . lace forms readily on the inside of the glass and a thin layer of head is always prevalent . the mouthfeel is particularly noteworthy , and every swig leaves a viscous coating of robust barley goodness on the tongue . many have complained about the drinkability , but i find that the 9 % abv is well disguised by the complexity of this well-rounded brew . even if you do n't take to this beer as i have , read up on the intriguing history behind the name of this brew , and perhaps convince some die hard minions of mass-marketed swill to see the merits of expecting more from a beer .  mouthfeel : perfect , just like champagne .

smell & gt ; sweet and resiny . a perfect balance of the two scents without much alcohol heat .  m : very viscous and full . smooth carbonation and a nice stickyness make the mouthfeel very complimenting to the taste .

s - mostly raspberry , which i found quite appealing . some caramel and roasted malt .  body is the best part of this brew . flavors are all in check , mouthfeel is full and fat , with a straw-like dryness at the finish . this beer is exceptionally drinkable .

smells of cinnamon rolls , predominant oak , very bready , some dark fruits , raisins in particular , some bourbon , unbelievably complex . tastes of sweet caramel breadiness with dark fruit undertones . a nice wave of breadiness follows with something slightly funky , cheesy almost . almost no carbonation , nice sweet mouthfeel , alcohol is scary hidden . a very interesting beer , lots of complexities . that said , i was blown away by the different flavors that passed over my tongue with every sip , one after another , incredibly complex . a very sweet beer and a treat , careful of the alcohol , dangerously hidden .  mouthfeel is lucious : creamy and oily , rich in the mouth , but smooth enough to want more and more .

aroma is exceptional , with a great sweet citrus smell that bursts from the bottle and makes you want to take a huge gulp . this is n't a horrible beer , and if you love bitterness , you should love it .  the carbonation is fantastic -- beer feels creamy and smooth- almost velvety .
s - beautiful dark malt and deep cherry aroma .  m- big , full body ... oily , almost syrupy with unattenuated sugars . very chewy , and it coats the mouth so well . just wonderful .

abv present , but smells delicious . alcohol , somewhat dry .  the creamy , delicious texture pairs well with the flavorful personality of the smoked porter . the dancing carbonation paired with the brews creamy-smooth feel and intense flavor essentially block dopamine receptors in your brain .

smell & gt ; mmmm ! burnt toast and sweet malt . taste & gt ; not very complex but very good . nothing exciting . drinkability & gt ; i could drink this again for sure .  m : full-bodied , silky smooth , velvety rich and downright luxurious in the mouth . these guys have this whole mouthfeel down to a t. notes : malty rich , fruity sweet , and explosively spicy , this bspa is quite enjoyable !

the aroma was fruity , but not overwhelmingly so . the carbonation tickled my tongue carrying on the light fruity taste and something else , a slight sour aftertaste i could n't identify . the body was light , not like the chewy trappists dubbels and quads i love . a little more pepper a little less sour , but not as generally pleasing as i 'd hoped .  mouthfeel is full and round .

smell- it does smell very good . i will give it that much . loads of dark and milk chocolate . one of the more chocolate scents i have set my nose upon in a beer .  smooth , creamy , almost velvet like . really enjoyable .

s : sweet dark frut nose come out followed by a chocolate toasted malt . on second whiff i am reminded of chocolate covered cheries .  mouthfeel is fantastic ... light , dry , well carbonated , and quite bitter .

s : kiwi fruit and pink watermelon with a hint of yeast , very pleasant . t : nice floral component , early on flowery with and hint of dandelion greens and grass .  m : rich and creamy . very chewy and thick . little carbonation .
that 's a good thing in my book . overall a fantastic aipa .  unbelievably smooth in mouthfeel - bittersweet chocolate and bitter roasted notes played effortlessly on your tongue .

do n't be turned off by the little green specks floating around as they are chucks of hops leftover from fermentation and help accentuate the huge hoppy aromas . pours a nice creamy golden color with slight greenish hue to foamy head . aromas of malts and hops give way to dried fruit .  so creamy and smooth it 's almost not a beer ...

awesome . the taste is again huge with cherry flavor without sweetness , cherry pits , a decent amount of sourness , with a good lactic tartness on the finish .  mouthfeel is exceptional . very smooth , great carbonation , but not enough to distract from the flavors going on .
very resilient aromatics , wonderful . taste - a brief sweet malt start goes nowhere before some serious hops kick in .  m : one of the fullest and creamiest dipas i 've ever had .

big piney and resiny hops fill the aroma , backed by a pretty sizeable maltiness . tobacco and bread come to mind . the malts may dominate the hops in this aipa , which almost always results in an iffy beer , that has you questioning the style .  the mouthfeel is great ... medium on the palate , but slick and well carbonated ... compliments the black pepper flavor perfectly .

smell - the rich , complex sugars here steal the show . in particular the raw sugar aroma was indistinguishable from the real thing .  thick creamy mouthfeel and mild carbonation . smooth silky mouthfeel is lucious .
smell : bacon ! ! again with bacon smelling rauchbiers . i love it ! ! but , it 's a bit weak .  full effervescent body , huge amounts of carbonation . an unusual beer that 's quite good .

aroma is overwhelming with citrusy peach essence of hop . so sweet and spicy , very cali . i usually sniff for 15-20 seconds but this beer merits much more nasal enjoyment .  thick rich and creamy mouthfeel . for such a rich and big beer it is remarkably smooth .

s - raisins and dates with stewed apples and a slight smoky character . strong presence like a nice port wine . currants and a touch of yeasty alcohol are in the mix . not the greatest beer ever and the carbonation is nuts , but it tastes , smells and looks nice .  perfectly carbonated , with a thick chewy body and a strong alcohol burn .

not overly complex , but interesting enough to keep your attention . d-i polished off the bomber effortlessly . really goes down nicely , and the alcohol is hidden fairly well .  m - fairly heavy body and solid flavors with moderate carbonation . the flavors are spot , the mouthfeel is amazing and its very drinkable .

s - bitter coffee , good coffee smell . this is disappointing . the nose is really good , but you do n't get much of that coffee on the tongue .  very palatable and no alcohol taste at all m - silky smooth , great carbonation .

the beer is a dark dirty orange , tons of bits of fruit float throughout the glass ... .the aroma is really nice , great notes of mango not at all overwhelming or too sweet , light pine resin on the back balances out ... the taste is a huge let down , most the sweetness is gone , light mango but a lot of medicinal/metallic/pine flavors are not great .  body is simply luxurious - rich , creamy , and damn near perfect .
s- it almost smells like a hoppier bock with plum and some chocolaty malt aromas .  mouthfeel is very soft and full bodied with light carbonation .

poured worthily into a duvel glass an orange amber with a thick white froth appearing and clinging nicely as a sip smelling of glorious flowery pine , dank indeed , bursts into bitter pine in the front of the mouth before cascading oily bubbles across just enough malt to save the day , without much abv burn , from what is otherwise a seriously bitter villain lacking a bit of nuance .  s : caramel , apple , sweet roasted malt t : tastes of caramel , some sour fruit like apple , yeast and hops bitterness/spice , some booze m : beautifully creamy and thick , but has a sharpness from the medium carbonation and booze o : drinkable for a bottle at least , this is an awesome beer .

smell is of butterscotch and very pleasing . like you are about to have a delicious dessert .  m : one of the most enjoyable mouthfeels i 've ever had in a beer ; medium-bodied and moderately carbonated , immensely smooth and surprisingly creamy . d : i thought that the taste here was good , not great ... but the amazing mouthfeel and complex flavor keep drawing me back in , and at much faster rate than that of many beers whose tastes i prefer .

s : best nose on a dipa i 've ever experienced . the alcohol is actually a complement to the hop aroma , however . this is one of those `` i wish this was an air freshener '' aromas . t & m : flavor is interesting -- some herbal and grassy hops , some notes of citrus , and a good smattering of pine . it does n't seem to be as balanced as stone ipa , but it 's still pretty tasty . the mouthfeel is very nice -- a sticky , full , and lasting feel with a long finish .  the mouthfeel is , in a word , glorious . smooth on the tip of the tongue , then seeming to evaporate off your tongue leaving a crisp , somewhat spicy finish .

aroma is by far the best part of this beer . a veritable tropical drink in this beer ! flavor does not follow through from the aroma- surprising . i detected minimal hops in the aroma , but they are there quite blatently in the flavor .  m : carbonation is explosive ( like the cork escapade ) . tickles the mouth with just the right amount of chewiness .

mmmm , that head really released a lot of wonderful aromas . pine and citrus predominate and , man , it smells good . very 'merry christmas ' , but not in the tinsel-and-cookies kinda way , but the 'i 'm some crank wandering around in a pine forest and i 'm giving presents to strangers ' kinda way . it definately ai n't normal , but it sure is delicious .  m : full-bodied and lightly carbonated with a soft and creamy texture . alcohol noticable in a nice warming effect .

devastatingly attractive . dried herb in color . brilliant nose . obviously aged and incredibly smooth on the palate but the cellaring destroyed the hop presense .  finshes warming , hoppy & bready , very balanced approach mf : chewy with low carbonation & great balance dangerously drinkable , this would put you on your butt after a couple of pints but a really nice dipa

it has a great aroma . lots of sweet malt , floral notes , and honey . it 's a little too sweet , but still good . i also get a slight undertone of cloves .  just take a sip and get lost in the nearly overpowering flavor explosion and the creamy tingly mouthfeel of this wondrous scottish ale .

the smell was amazing -- probably the highlight of the beer . it got better as the temp increased . overall , it 's a pretty solid novelty beer .  a full bodied beer that is creamy smooth and goes down really easy .

that being said the banana scent is there just beneath the other two , along with an almost dry wheaties scent.very enticing . overall : a solid , thirst quenching beer with a wonderful smell and decent flavor.it 's not my favorite in the style but i 'll drink it again for sure .  appearance : cloudy burnt orange/brown - nice head retention smell : cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkin spice taste : hops , cinnamon , coriander , nutmeg - similar to an american wild ale - very tannic mouthfeel : my favorite part very tannic , smooth - the rye dries the palate out so you 're ready for another sip or another bite of food .

nose is great on this - grassy hops , estery yeast and sugary , bready rye . very nice , everything comes together extremely well . yeast seems more tripel than saison , but compared to the smell the yeast is quite tame unfortunately .  m - absolutely creamy and delectable ! the amazing , tiny bubbled froth envelopes and contains any alcohol sharpness that would otherwise make this 8.0 % beer a bit fiery in the swallow . superb . d - the mouthfeel makes this otherwise straight-up scotch ale an incredibly drinkable beverage . but be careful ! at 8 % , this beer is like getting a two-for-one special in each pint !

the nose is heavy on the rye malt- showing a more pure breadiness with fruity tones of buttery apples , white raisin , faint cinnamon , light brown sugar , plum . the parallels to rye whiskey are awesome in this . the medium bodied palate is caramelly sweet up front with a mild bitterness that ushers in the rye maltiness- drying and spicy with lots of fruity tones .  mouthfeel is the best part of the beer .

the smell of this thing is very lively , wow , its all over the place , funky as hell , smokey banana and smoked salmon or bacon , dull lemon , musty horse blanket , soft rubber , and feet .  smooth and creamy mouthfeel makes the small tickling carbonation and otherwise heavier body very palatable . i do n't know if so much milk is my thing , but i 'm glad i tried it .

smell is of bourbon barrels , alcohol and some deep plum and cherry/chocolate on the nose . taste follows with notes of the barrel and a very lingering close ... nice.. good feel and the drinkability is extravagant given the potency , as the alcohol is present on the nose but not on the tongue .  mouthfeel : low carbonation leads to thirsty gulps .

an immense hop punch to the nose . extremely fresh , bitter hops practically leap out of the glass . further in i get notes of orange and citrus , wrapped into a pleasing sweet malty undercurrent . superb nose . t. alas , after such a superlative smell , how could the taste hold up ? it 's a fantastic smelling , `` lite '' double ipa that is easy to put down .  m- very , very thick and chewy . also quite heavy .
great balance . t : upfront a blend of caramel malt and grapefruit .  mouth-feel was velvety smooth and creamy .

massively nutty aroma , packed with roasted peanut butter , walnut brownies , and nuttella - very inviting . not terribly smoky ( more roasty ) , just a mild edge of charcoal that also lends a hint of toasted marshmallow . plenty of coffee notes as well - this is just about perfect , exactly what i want in the style . strangely , there is not a hint of alcohol in this beer - which makes this dangerously drinkable , but still , not exactly a lawnmower beer !  great bubbly mouthfeel , no aftertaste at all .

s- very delicate yet strong lemony aroma . t- great yeast character elevates the otherwise bland hop/malt balance to something very enjoyable . m- very smooth yet light .  m/d : full bodied , very smooth , velvet like .
s : a lot of good stuff going on here . dark , rich , even sort of ... tropical .  mouthfeel : perfection . the bead is neither too large nor too small .

i can also catch a slight nose of peaty scotch if i catch it the right way . fantastic aroma here .  they served it properly too - the temperature was perfect ( not co cold ) . pretty close to perfect .

smells like delicious ginger snaps , cinnamon and some clove . delicious . it has a medium body with a good amount of carbonation . definitely a sipper , but a very good sipper .  caramel , mocha , strong booze , brown sugar , raisins , figs , chocalate t-malt , mocha , booze , brown sugar , caramel , raisins figs , chocalate m-spicy , creamy , thick , barely carbonated d- pretty thick & filling .

hoppy scent is medium to intense , with a nice mix of fresh citrus and toasted , darker hop bitters . malt figures its way in to create a staggeringly intense aroma for an irish red .  m - big bodied , thick , and viscous as hell . middling carbonation fades to a really dry and herbal finish like green tea . wicks all moisture from my mouth !

o : for a beer that shares the great smells i associate with world-class english barleywines and doppelbocks , chimay grandrserve certainly disappoints me in other categories .  big , viscous mouthfeel does great things for this beer , transmitting a pretty large package ( 10 % , significant ibu count ) into an easy-to-sip package .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever tried . good amount of pumpkin . clean and delicious . lighter side of medium in body . not sure if this is a drastic improvement from regular pumking , but this is surely tasty .  mouthfeel is where this one shines , smooth as can be and perfectly carbonated , a light yet creamy quality .

this had a wonderful nose of tropical fruits , sugars , and malts , with a little herbal hop bitterness thrown into the mix as well . the taste was more of the same , fruity , sweet and delicious . this did have a medicinal , somewhat metallic , after taste though that kind of reminded me of orval .  nice touch of bitterness lingers as i contemplate the rich , full mouth feel . nice beer , much more approachable than the expedition .

smells like halloween ! very welcoming . it sure is an imperial . very crisp , sexy beer . spices are rounded , clove , cinnamon , vanilla bean , and most importantly , fresh pumpkin .  mouthfeel is astonishingly smooth and creamy for such a rich , complex ale .

heavy caramels , bourbon , dark fruits , a fruity sweetness and a touch of tobacco.. this is really a fantastic smelling barleywine . i 'd dare to say it is one of the best smelling barleywines that i 've had to date . kudos to a great bouquet . plenty of caramel malt to provide a creamy mouthfeel , king henry takes off with sweetness but not cloyingly so .  amazing mouthfeel . viscous , rich and creamy without being syrupy .

there are references to ginger , spice , pumpkin and fresh wet hops . packaging says best before march 2012 . the beer is very cloudy and the color is along the lines of pumpkin pie .  mouthfeel- soft , silky smooth texture . full bodied and rich . perfect .

aroma is great . cherry , oak , cabernet , phenolic , yeast , sour , sweet tarts ... mouthfeel is a touch awkward with carbonation at first , but mellows during the drink as it warms . dry on the finish .  really big round full mouthfeel .

beautiful beer at 6.8 % abv certainly packs a punch , a - perfect for the style , a big fluffy head fell away at moderate pace , lacing well , pours a hazy orange s - a highlight for me , big amarillo hop aroma , citrus , fruity no negatives in the aroma dept . t - a little bit less than a std dipa bitterness but still kicked liked a wild goat , beautiful flavours , crystal or other malts coming through m - well controlled and certainly right for me .  m : full body , and shockingly creamy . this brew is extremely smooth of the mouth .
the smell is very strong of hops . very floral and powerful . the taste it really dominated by hops and the bitterness at the end is quite nice .  very full and creamy mouth . damn tasty .

a - very good , very light golden orange - pretty decent head retention s - the most unique citrus nose of any dipa i 've ever encountered . upfront dried fruit basket and grapefruit blast to the senses . i can pick out the citra hops , that for sure . bitter dry , crisp finish . very , very good beer .  it seemed to just coat my whole mouth on its way down .

s - cherries , orange peel , and fresh fruits combine to create an enticing aroma . a definite yeasty quality is also present .  this beer is silky smooth with very well behaved carbonation - you 'll have no trouble taking big gulps of this brew !
