strong vanilla notes , sugar , and faint chocolate aroma..southern tier really has a knack for completely nailing the nose on their brews t - do n't know if i could drink any more than the 9oz i was poured . this is incredibly sweet , and extremely rich . a perfect dessert beer .  ( m ) mouthfeel is perfect for this beer .

s : lots of bacterial funk , acid , and dark fruit , very fragrant and pungent .  t : the taste was about average for a stout , almost identical in flavor to guinness m : amazing mouthfeel , so creamy and so smooth .

tons of banana in both the aroma and the taste . this is a very fruity beer , and i think the sweetness would not be as pleasant over a whole pint . a very decent brew though .  light in body with absolutely wonderful carbonation , this is airy , creamy and the combination of sourness and spiciness on the finish is unique .

lots of intense sweet and spicy hops in the nose , insanely floral . i prefer a more balanced beer , but for the style , this way pretty damn good .  mouthfeel was full and rich . this is a very good beer , and quite a unique one .

smell : they put some hops in this , a lot of them . pine , key lime , hop leaf , loads of bitter hop oil , hope there 's a base to catch me ... taste : surprisingly earthy , the hop leaf / european hop profile , was expecting a little more west coast . overall : a very flavorful texas beer , just a little more english than american in taste , like a english double ipa .  had an appropriate lower level of carbonation that many ris can not compete against . rich and thick on the palate . very warming .
aroma is nice , flavor is a bit less balanced though .  the mouthfeel is excellent .
the best part of this beer was the nice grassy hop aroma ( dry hopped with fuggles ) .  perfect in this sense .

incredibly fresh hop aroma . absolutely unbelievable . must try these galaxy hops for my homebrew soon .  the mouth feel on this one is perfect . the head retention is outstanding and just adds to that smooth , creamy , malty , citrus finish .

s : strong enticing smell of toffee , vanilla and butterscotch . t : much the same as the smell .  smooth and thick ( of medium thickness ) , with small abrasive bubbles ( in the best possible way ) . wish i had let it chill a little longer to see a greater range of flavors as it warmed , but still a nice experience .

when i first opened the bottle i could smell the cherrys right away . it was a very sweet smell which suprised me that the beer was not as sweet as the smell . very nice appearance .  mouthfeel - very smooth with a rich body and muted carbonation .

s - amazing nose ; delicious notes of chocolate , slight coffee , and super smooth oat , with roastiness present but generally transformed into the aforementioned dimensions . it reminds me of the smell of instant caf mocha , prior to the addition of hot water . ) finally , there is an appreciable hop that comes in at the end and lingers , providing herbal and vaguely floral notes on the finish .  the mouthfeel is what really sets this apart . having had very few english cask ales , i do n't know if this is gold standard , but it is the best mouthfeel i 've had on this style beer .

`` hello , my name is coriander and pepper '' says the aroma in a pleasing fashion . a bit heavier and sweeter than i would like hurts its drinkability , but the great aroma and pleasant flavor make this a very nice beer .  my favorite thing about this obviously the sweet rich malt character which adds to a very nice body for a beer of this alcohol content .
well , the label says brewed with peaches and pecans and you get tons of peach on the nose . and it 's a real peach smell too , not the kind in gummy candy .  mouthfeel very full and smooth .

the sweet malts balance this very nicely . m & d : medium body beer , nice level of carbonation , makes for a semi-creamy mouthfeel . just an outstanding ipa .  it 's as smooth as silk - perfectly suited as a dinner and desert sipper and easily the best porter i 've had the pleasure of tasting .

750ml bottle with cork , like their local series . smells of the local 1 , champagne , cork , lemon meringue or orange marmalade , some tropical fruits or pina colada , wet vegetation . surprisingly , i taste the hop in the flavor more than the aroma . a unique hop . corky . kudos for making a dry and hoppy saison , and getting it to texas ! worth trying .  perhaps there is similar inconsistency here , and i will be wowed by the bottles i brought home sometime in the future ... mouthfeel is by far the best characteristic , supple , creamy and light .

very inviting , to say the least .  appearance : amber , clear carbonated , medium head smell : alcohol , grapefruit , and citrus taste : alcohol , grapefruit , malts , hops , and slight caramel mouthfeel : smooth , slightly hard finish , can feel the carbonation ... it is amazing how smooth and unbitter this beer is for a beer with its abv drinkability : i will have this again , but may be one of the few that prefer the 60 minute ipa .
very nice . t : sugar sweet ( touch of brown sugar ) along with some malt sweetness .  m : thick and rich , with a nice amount of fine , late-developing carbonation . perfect for such a big beer .

s- unbelievably citrusy : cumquat , calamondin , grapefruit , orange peal , pine , honey t- the aroma really grabs the attention here , but the flavor and slight bitterness still comes through : grapefruit , honey , cumquat m- peppery yet smooth with a bit of acid from the hops . o- fantastic ipa .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth & this is a perfect beer to sip on on a lazy pm with no kids in sight !

the aroma was spectacular , one of the best i have ever been privy to . though the look could use a touch of tinkering , the amazing aroma and depth of flavors more than made up for it . a unique and enjoyable offering unlike any other saison i 've ever had .  the malt is well back but the beer still has a nice light body . the palate is a great balance of all that and a nice honey quality in the background .
smell - smells absolutely delicious ! ! lots of fruit/wheat and some toasty nuts ... yumm , 5 for sure .  mouthfeel is perfect and this is a pretty drinkable brew .

curiously the nose offers more malt chocolate than expected , sweetens the already concentrated apricot , peach fruit scents as well as the floral dew , nicely piney , however , the grapefruit citrus lacks focus , nothing here to suggest bitter hops or aggressive bite .  very excellent mouthfeel and drinkability .

aroma is good . vanilla and raw oak . the aroma is really nice but the taste is just like being hit over the head with sticky sweet caramel and fruit - too much for my taste .  mouthfeel : on the heavy side of the medium-bodied scale and creamy smooth .

s : extremely rich and fragrant . tons of fudge brownie , boozy spirit barrel , cherry , dark fruit , and solvent alcohol . not too intrusive , but feels a little `` tacked on '' if you get my meaning .  entering the mouth , i immediately take notice of the huge mouthfeel on this . this is fluffy , powdery , quaffable , and has this charming soft carbonation that is typical of great beers . palate displays a superb spicy bitterness executed in incredible balance and harmony ( this and the mouthfeel are the 2 attractions imo ) , gentle woodiness .

s : lots to smell here , very complex . standard malt and hops smells are there along with a fruitiness : appless and cherries . the smell is very sweet .  what i really loved was the mouthfeel . very good for a lager style beer .

s- has a nice old ale smell with similarities to thomas hardy 's and the like . the smell is this beers strong suit .  mouthfeel : thick and smooth in every sense of the words -- a very pleasant experience indeed !

aroma is big sweet , multitudes of dark fruit , caramel and quiet peat moss . quadish exceptional highly complex flavor , something for everyone . sweetness not equal to the expectation from the nose . the evolution of the taste is significant .  subtly carbonated , with a medium-full body and a delightful smoothness .

s- some nice fresh fruit hits the nose immediately in the way of some fresh apple and the caramel moves in next .  a - bright golden orange color with some chill haze present , two fingers of white frothy head that leaves thick froth-lace s - not too much rye here , just hints ... hops and bready malt t - hop bitterness up front , sweet bready malts in the back , only a hint of rye in the middle ... the malt backing is about as significant as it gets ... taste 's more like a straight up ipa than most rye beers i 've had m - hops tingle the tongue and give way to very thick , chewy malts that slide down nicely ... full-bodied and very enjoyable d - this is a reeeally well-balanced beer , i just wanted more rye flavor .
aroma is fantastic , reminiscent of triple sec and cognac . an intriguing failure of a beer .  this belgian pale ale has a strong cookie-like malt character and an exceptionally smooth mouthfeel .

big on the aromatics ! perceptible alcohol is offset by a great earthy wood character . perfect for the style . flavor brings on even more fruity ( apples mostly ) malt and alcohol sweetness but it 's held in check by the equally healthy dose of hopping .  mouthfeel is really exceptional , which along with the smooth flavors is what i really like .
positives : great aroma of sweet chocolate .  thick lushious body and moderate carbonation .

s- the dry hopping really comes through nicely . it 's quite floral with just a touch of an orange juice aroma .  feels amazingly clean and fresh while keeping the flavor of charred wood and grains . smooth , creamy , full bodied , and almost a velvet nature . the carbonation is played on in the background as an overcoat . the simplicity of it overwhelms me .

an interesting double ipa with a very malty edge and bitter finish . smells of floral hops , much caramel and honey and autumn mornings . honestly it smells a lot better than the taste .  m : the feel is excellent with fine carbonation lending a creaminess that is top-tier and a clean scrubbing finish with the right balance of crispness and aftertaste . d : an fine tripel with classic light fruit flavors mixed artfully with pepper and spice and a top-notch mouthfeel compose a very good brew .

luckily , the aroma of this beer is quite good . a butterscotch maltiness was immediately noticeable and complemented perfectly with floral and spicy hop notes .  mouthfeel is really impressive . very gradual on the tongue and extraordinarily balanced .

this stuff smells great . a very unique sweet plummy/buttery smell . tastes good , too . does n't taste like 9 % at all .  again this is a beer with a very good character but i still feel it does n't perfectly balance m- incredible mouthfeel .

a : pours a cloudy orange color with good frothy white head , good lacing down the glass s : smell is awesome , smells fruity ( apple/pear ) , good spiciness in there as well . m : light to medium bodied , dry finish d : very refreshing , complex smelling and tasting beer .  not the stunner i was hoping for m- beautiful mouth feel . i sure hope this is not the `` great sculpin '' i 've been waiting for for that past few years .

smell is fantastic ! nothing but chocolate covered toffee in the nose , the lightest bit of roastiness , and a hint of nuttiness . i love it .  the mouth-feel was what was remarkable to me , very thick and creamy , i would liken it to a stout milkshake , really satisfying and enjoyable to drink .
nose was rich with fudgy chocolate , smoke and charcoal .  perfect carbonation .
medium intensity and a very smooth and mellow character .  the mouthfeel is exceptionally smooth and creamy , terrific . thanks bif for the sample .

: ( looks and smells awesome . dark chocolate color with a small tan head that does n't stick around for too long . this smelled of chocolate before i even managed to get my nose near the glass . smells like hershey 's . i really really wanted to like this beer , but it was tough to get through the bottle and i was sharing it . if only it tasted like it smelled , this would have been great .  outstanding mouthfeel ! very drinkable .
smell- unbelievable aroma ! overall- has a great aroma but falls short with the taste .  mouthfeel is big full and smooth very rich and easy drinking with a really satisfing warming in the gut .

nose is wonderful leafy green sappy noble hop over slightly sweet biscuity malt . wonderful pilsner nose . medium weight in the mouth with a good balance of hop flavor , hop bitterness and malt to the finish , where the hop bitterness really comes to the fore .  taste- for a double ipa , this beer is not on a mission to wreck the palate ... with so much flavor i 'm surprised that the malts weigh in so heavily . solid . it 's sudsy ( the name of my beloved late parakeet ) and sublime . drinkability- one real attribute about this bruiser of a beer is that the abv ( 10 % ) is completely hidden ... it 's nowhere in any of the above categories . this is more like a nectar , thick and juicy , garnering respect for each sip .

sweetish and beautiful . t : unfortunately , the alcohol flavor jumps to the front , and while it 's not quite overwhelming , it 's a large part of the flavor , which i do n't find pleasant .  super creamy mouthfeel w/o any overcarbed bite .

beautiful hop smell : floral , grass , the smell of spring basically . a little bit of bread & cracker smell . very aromatic , but not overwhelming , a smooth & even hop character . the lovely hop character is forward in the taste , but again not overwhelming or destructive to the tastebuds .  loved the residual stickiness . d- it 's remarkable how fff can make such big beers and hide the alcohol so well .

the smell is very pleasant , a combination of biscuit , pear , and pepper .  delicious . and i think what makes it delicious is not entirely a taste thing , but a feel thing . so smooth and creamy and round without any heaviness or stickiness . and it 's an appropriate textural delivery for the huge fruits here ( again , fig , plum and raisin dominant ) ; smoky cherry continues to remind of pipe tobacco ; a more general/generic smoke flavor nicely sneaks in with warming ; and there 's a milky chocolate essence entering into the flavor that i did n't detect in the smell .

s : absolutely heavenly . fresh herbal hops , minty even , along with grassy and citric hops as well . m : full , with an excellent long finish , but not overbearing . it 's wonderful . the smell will hook you and the taste will not disappoint . the brilliant combination of hops had me wishing it would never end , and even at a relatively high abv , it remains highly drinkable .  full of body and creamy goodness .

aroma is impressive for the style with some sweet citrus in the form of oranges and light grassy notes . i definitely think it gives the beer , especially the aroma , a unique character . better than i was expecting .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with a dry , perfectly carbonated finish . perfect for the style .
the best thing about this beer is the aroma imo . awesome , very awesome . beer is thin and falls flat on the flavors at first . its a good beer , just not my favorite .  creamy but thin body .

the aroma is like a fresh hop cone very nice . from what you expect with the aroma is a slight let down but that said it is nice . the taste malty to start the taste turns to a earthy hop flavor .  mouthfeel is wow smooth , and drinkability is amazingly good .

s. funky sweet spiced berry nose - lots going on here with a nice play of sweet and spicy battling it out .  body is n't the first thing you notice , but once the distraction of the sour wears off , you realize this brew is very smooth , neither tacky nor sticky , nor drying . carbonation can be swirled up , and compliments the feel of the sour in your cheeks quite well . all in all , a crazy departure from the normal dfh offerings and dang fine weissen .

smell is superior . a robust but citrusy smell that you get a hint of straight out of the bottle .  the mouthfeel is great , for the bittersweetness from the roasted malts provide the ideal amount of oomph to an otherwise creamy body .

a great aroma greets the nose , with soft cherry fruits and lots of toffee sweetness . a hint of floral & piny hops lingers in the background -- -very barleywine-line , which i enjoy . the flavor has the typical wee heavy malt profile boosted by a vinous barrel note . overall , a great special release from real ale , and probably one of their best beers i 've had to date .  in addition , there are hop oils , caramel , some sweetness and perhaps molasses along with a medium body that is oh so smooth and coats the mouth well . delicious and well balanced .
overall , not as good as smell . alcohol well hidden .  excellent for it 's style .

smell is extremely fruity , primarily peaches with some apples , oranges , and lemons coming through as well . this is a pretty interesting and unique beer for the style . a pleasant surprise .  very full body that stretches the cheeks . just such chewy hops .

this may be the best smelling pilsener i 've ever experienced . lovely complex , floral hop aroma . pleasant light grained malt in the background . overall , a superior beer .  a nice chewy , creamy malt backbone makes each sip a pleasure .

aroma- has a super strong pumpkin aroma with tons of sweetness , spice , and ingredient within ! rivals schlafly 's pumpkin aroma already ! appearance- pours a 1.5 finger head that has terrific retention . mouthfeel- medium-full bodied , medium-high carbonation , smooth , and leaves awesome amount of pumpkin/spice on the palate . overall impression- now this one breaks into my top 5 list !  some of the best damn mouthfeel you will ever get in a beer too .

sugary , carmelized , sweet smell . fruity pebble cereal is the overall smell result , very nice ! it 's smell is amazing . picking up a faint vanilla extract smell as well . delicious . it was hard to move my nose away from the smell . but , yeah ... lets get onto the taste . not as amazing as the smell , but still good . mouthfeel is creamy , and dry . while this beer may not be spot on for the style , it 's quite unique . it 's positives by far outweigh the negatives .  the mouthfeel was awesome - very creamy and full bodied .

aromas were fantastic : bready , citrus-fruit and cloves were wonderfully balanced . it was not too strong , but the aromas were apparent .  perfectly suited for sipping and just right for the flavor .

rich , sweet aroma of dark fruits , powdery chocolate , and fortified red wine . easy drinking , pleasant and nicely fragrant .  m - amazing . low to moderate carbonation ( expected ) and full bodied .

rich , deep aroma , with cherry and caramel hints , laced with alcohol . wonderful burnt-amber color . harsh start , but a clean finish . not an easy drinker ... but good for sippling . overall , this is a very complicated and interesting beer .  wow . the thick and creamy mouthfeel is perfect for the winter months and so warm .
n : this is a beautiful , mouthwatering nose . smells very close to liquid pumpkin pie .  m- perfect for the style , ca n't say anything more .

quite delicious , but not quite as good as the nose led me to believe . m. thin with a good level of carbonation d. i was a bit disappointed with the taste after the incredible smell , but the mouthfeel is really what let me down here .  mouthfeel is creamy smooth , thick body , low carbonation .

the aroma seems to transcend the dopplebock style with a delightful boozy elixier : notes of dark rum , brandy , sherry and the like . currants , produce , fresh grass , and a slight hint of citrusy hops provide a great balance to the smell . this is not a beer for the faint of palate . i 'm not exactly sure how i feel about samichlaus ... one one hand , it 's an exceptionally complex , well-crafted beer that probably deserves its own style .  smooth and creamy , very soft carbonation . booze is extremely well hidden .

smell : the aroma is very good . lots of cinnamon , nutmeg , and all spice combine with the pumpkin to give a nice pumpkin-forward aroma . overall : the aroma is by far the best part about this beer .  first sip reveals a smooth and slightly creamy texture , carbonation is almost non-existent as cask ale should be .

roasty bittersweet belgian chocolate . all low notes , tiny musty . surprising spiciness accompanies the stout yet without much depth .  it 's just smooth and thick enough to feel perfect going down .

smell : a deep and delightful warm caress to the nostrils . chocolate , molasses , brandy , and oak joint together for an exquisite amalgamation . wonderfully sugary , earthy , and effervescent .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and exceedingly refreshing .
smell is rather striking and unique . slight hints of spice most likely from the chilles , with a really sweet grainy hop note .  its very smooth and velvety , very nice .

aroma : coffee and chocolate malt meld accented by a whiff of hops and a touch of smoke . nice complexity and balance leads to a very appealing invitation . overall impression : thick and creamy with a wonderful nose . unfortunately the taste just didnt live up to the billing .  the taste and mouthfeel is where this beer shines . thick , smooth and creamy with a combination of milk and dark chocolate with just a hint of licorice .

aroma is highlight of the beer , a rich , unique blend of dark fruit , bourbon , chocolate syrup and light roast . one of the better heavy seas treatments and they 've somehow managed to salvage a base beer i typically deplore with a passion .  the mouthfeel is dead-on creamy .
i am intrigued . t. malty and a bit sweet , borders on sour .  m : remarkably full bodied and smooth but it does n't have any stickiness , carbonation did it 's job , excellent .
smelled like coconut sugar pie , the nose is great . dark .  the mouthfeel is great on this one too , effervescent and full at the same time .
powerful hop aroma , lots of citrus . pleasant , but nothing to get too excited about .  mouthfeel is very thick and chewy , silky and long lasting on the palate , near perfect .

very sexy . s - great smell , definitely get a heavy does of burnt chocolate , some roasted coffee and other malts . great example of roasted scents . i would gauge that there was a spectacular effort put into tempering this brew to get these scents from the malts . i like sours but certainly not mixed with this style . very bitter as you will note from almost every review but this one had an almost sour milk character that turned me off during my dinner which was centered around beef .  exactly how i like my stouts to feel -- heavy and chewy .
the smell is outstanding - i was salivating from the roasty nutty goodness .  very big and chewy mouthfeel

huge amounts of fruitiness , candy , and grapefruit on the nose . sweet , light , and apricots also show up a bit . reminds me of some type of orange/apricot candy i 've had before but can not put my finger on it . very light , very fruity , yet tart but it is quite a curious taste . very easy to drink and although i do n't see myself buying a lot of lindeman 's myself i will highly recommend this to anyone trying a geuze !  lush , creamy mouthfeel , that really could n't improve at all .
the aroma was suprisingly good , with banana , cedar , mild hops , vanilla and ginger .  perfectly carbonated with an amazing mouthfeel .
s : pumpkin pie baby ! very nice . t : pumpkin spice , clove , nutmeg and caramel from the malts .  super thick mouthfeel .

s-what comes through first is a perfect balance of sweet caramel malt and a blast of citrus hops . d- this brew is pretty awesome . brews that emphasize the citrus/spicy hop combo are hard to come by and this one does an excellent job with it .  the first thing i noticed actually was the incredible mouthfeel .

pours dark orangey brown , slightly hazy at first , then extremely cloudy as i pour in some of the yeast dregs . the aroma is huge - sweet brown sugar and honey with floral notes , alcohol and some breadiness . flavors are very aggressive in this fresh form - a huge honey presence meets with the aggressive bittering hops and some dark fruit sherry notes . excellent barley wine , both in its fresh and aged form - a testament to the value of bottle conditioning and cellarable beers .  smooth as hell , perfect weight and carbonation .

smell is dominant dark fruit ( plum and fig ) with just hints of chocolate cake , cherries , and that leather smell . very complex . there is a dark smooth malt character and some caramel as well . i could smell this all day . taste is the nose , followed by a whiff of smoke and finishing like a rich deep red wine . my brother commented that he picked up on dr. pepper like qualities . caramel malt . mouthfeel was oily and clingy . drinkability : i know it 's a great beer but for me drinkability was just ok .  mouthfeel is sublime . kind of like a benign dreamy tingling that coats the palate evenly .

the aroma features the citrusy amarillo hops they note on the bottle along with tons of wheat .  mouthfeel is absurdly rich and creamy , silky smooth and slurpalicious . ) it 's the best feature of this brew . i mean , i like the taste , love the mouthfeel , and would enjoy having two or three of these , but that abv is on the high end .

smell is phenomenal ; coffee , mocha , vanilla , kahlua , coffee cake ... the aroma is outstanding . perhaps the best porter i 've ever sniffed . this beer is simply delicious . slight let down from that a+ aroma but minimal . tastes like the smell but with some malt and roasty notes . very drinkable .  the mouthfeel of this bastard makes the beer for me -- incredibly soft and smooth for strong ale , probably the result of the oaking .
the aroma is very roasty and has plenty of chocolate notes . smells very nice .  mouthfeel : smooth and creamy . alcohol warmth .

the smell is sweet and malty . sugar cookie , icing , cotton candy , candy corn , it is predominantly sugar , but it is many different shades of sweet . it is a smell you seldom come across in beer , and it is great . the flavor is big and bold .  the mouthfeel is smooth , thick , and creamy .
s : bold and healthy hop aroma . perfect ipa smell . t : dry and hoppy .  this has an excellent mouthfeel .

s : cranberries , some grapes and apples . good hop character . very complex and well done aroma . t : finish is slightly bitter but nothing overpowering , with a warm alcohol character that becomes a little cloying .  high level of carbonation with tons of tingle on the tongue . another excellent beer from ommegang .
the smell was delightful . sadly , it ended there .  the mouthfeel was the best part : silky smooth and creamy thick ; a perfect accompaniment to dessert .

smell - the smell was an enchanting citrus odor between grapefruit and lemon meshed with faint aromatic pine hops and a hint of grain underneath .  the mouthfeel is amazing , thick and solid with a lingering savory finish .

smells delicious . sweet raisin and toffee come through very clearly .  if you have to choose buy the triple , but as stated earlier this beer has a wonderful silky smooth mouth ... great feel for those who have an oral complex ...

it reeks of pumpkin pie without being too aggressive with it . the pumpkin pie aroma does n't dominate the taste and it actually tastes like a beer instead of some kind of pumpkin pie flavored wine cooler .  so very soft on the palette - really a unique mouthfeel , just velvety smooth .
smell : fantastic , lots of citrus , pine and bubble gum . it is decently balanced but could use some more malt backbone .  the mouthfeel is a true hallmark of this beer .
great aroma , sweet malt , banana , spice , wheat note . medium feel , too cloyingly sweet for me  mouthfeel is rich and creamy .

the nose is very complex , a mix of fruity , spicy , earthy and oaky tones . black licorice or anise also comes to mind . there is also a drying , acrid presence . drinkability of this one is lowered by the fact that i do n't really enjoy this old ale . i was really excited when i opened the bottle and i feel let down .  m - perfect . exactly how a dipa should be .
the smell is strong pundget and fruity , sweet and tangy . overall , pretty good .  extremely satisfying in this regard .

bubblegum , banana and cloves . smells just like i 'd like a hefeweizen to smell . the taste does n't live up to the nose , however .  mouthfeel is about perfect , and the body is about perfect for a bock style .

the nose is deep , thick , prodigious coffee and some raisiny dark chocolate notes , and roasted dark sweet grains .  very light carbonation and a perfect body for a porter , combined with what i have already mentioned , makes this a very drinkable proposition .
the smell is exceptional . it smells like candy the mouthfeel is really smooth , and not very thick .  mouthfeel : truly phenomenal creamy medium body with the slightest touch of syrup likeness .
the dry-hopping gives it a fantastic smell , citrusy and piney .  mouth : velvety good . nice water . sweet , full , but not thick . medium to full bodied .

very fresh and clean smell , hardly any yeast aroma .  mouthfeel : true german feeling on this beer . medium viscosity , rolls across the palate smoothly and is perfectly carbonated . great overall feel and authenticity .

poured into a de molen sniffer . smell : great nose , full of dark chocolate , slight sour cherry , bourbon and vanilla taste : great taste as well , this beer is very complex and still very balanced . the smell and taste are wonderful , for me it seems an attempt of the molen to produce their own cuvee delphine from struise .  ( m ) - this is ridiculously smooth despite its hop dryness and woody bite . great carbonation level and balance .
very double ipa , and enjoyable . taste is more subtle than i was expecting , bitter hops all the way through .  mouthfeel : perfect mouthfeel .

s ) pumpkin pie ... this really has it covered . this is spiced , but not over the top , which made me very happy . a very nice balance of pumpkin and beer . this is quite smooth . nice finish and aftertaste . o ) i have n't really had many pumpkin beers , but i 've heard good things about this one , so i finally gave it a shot . i 'm really glad i did .  there 's a fair amount of carbonation that you feel in the swallow .

i am smelling a creme brulee desert right now ... i do n't think i could tell the difference from the real thing . exceptional . there is a touch of courseness in the back of the throat from the abv and bitterness .  m : the best part of the beer . very creamy while still having a touch of that hop thickness you want .
pleasant overall unlike some other fruit beers .  one of the best mouthfuls ever !

an amazingly rich and creamy nose with strong aromas of toffee , cream , and roasted marshmallows . body is very good . drinkability : whatever hesitancy i had after seeing how it looked following the pour were overcome by the amazing aroma . a solid , flavorful drink that i would kill to try on cask .  the mouthfeel was creamy and medium-bodied with light , soft carbonation .

the aroma is very deep -- anise , fennel , mocha , coffee and a burning alcohol nose -- awesome . really a marvel . strange .  the mouthfeel was outstanding , felt like a cask beer , rich , creamy , smooth .

the aroma was like a big hop garden bouquet with a little sugared pixie dust spread all over . i was ready for the taste and ready to be blown away , but was not .  this is a big , complex , full bodied beer . the huge amounts of malts in this thing are chewy and even feel like they stick to the teeth some .
smells very nice . very peppery with spicy yeast , bananas and pineapple .  m : creamy and delicious . everything is dead on here .

very unique . i could tell from smelling it that it was going to be sour , but had no idea the extent of sourness .  it is dense . the mouthfeel is warm even though it was chilled . it is excellent as it warms in the glass .
aroma is wonderfully thick , gravity holds it in check . flavor collapses the experience , tremendous letdown as the scent gave much promise .  medium bodied , excellent mouthfeel .
a nice balance .  the mouthfeel is perfect for the style ; adequately carbonated and finished silky and creamy .
smells very tasty .  the mouthfeel is smooth and nicely done . excellent carbonation drinkability is good as well .

sour cherries , fresh-pressed apple cider , mild marble rye , yeasty esters and a faint touch of alcohol . complex and rewarding . effervecent and envigorating without overwhelming the tongue . much lighter than the appearance would lead you to believe and it resembles many other belgian-style ales in this regard . maybe not everyone 's cup of tea but i find it to be immensely drinkable and the alcohol is hardly noticable . quite good .  the mouthfeel on this is exceptional , so smooth will alcohol masterfully controlled .

big malty nose with hints of very dark caramel malts and lots of fruity yeast esters . light toasty wood aroma and some chocolate as it warms up .  the first thing i notice upon the first sip is the awesome mouthfeel on this one .

it smells distinctly like pineapple cake . i mean you get the sweet pineapple and a really bready smell underneath . probably my favorite smell in a beer ever , different than the norm for an apa . definitely does n't live up to the smell but i enjoy it . the carbonation level is good and there is n't really a harsh aftertaste . there certainly is n't anything off-putting , and i would recommend it to anyone , at least for the sake of smelling it .  the mouthfeel is thick and rich with a nice amount of bubbly to round it out . the taste is full , many-layered . . . wonderful . a little vineous though .
smell : very , very fruity ! it smells almost as good as a lady .  mouthfeel is perfection . perfectly carbonated and very refreshing .

majestic sniffs . taste is equally multifacited . one of the maltier versions i 've encountered , laid out in a doughy , bready fashion . this is a very fine hefeweizen  the mouthfeel on this beer is almost perfect . a nice smooth drinkable beer .

a - deep gold color s- amazing , citrus , grapefruit , & bubblegum aromas t- bitter hops ( grapefruit-like ) with fruity undertones . m - dry to the finish o- i was impressed that brewers were able to capture strong complexity for such a bitter , hoppy brew . overall i felt that the bitterness was way overpowering , leaving my mouth dried out .  keeping with the chocolate milk theme , the mouthfeel is fantastic .

amazing smell ; right in line with what i expect from stone .  the balance here is seriously excellent though , and the mouthfeel is probably the best i have encountered in an ipa , period . truly a creamy elixir , perfect carbonation .

the nose is deep bready malt goodness with a hint of brown sugar ... very nice . the taste , however , falls short of the wonderful nose , a crisp light/weak malt with thinnish mouthfeel , semi-sweet with low key hops behind it .  mf : it has a thicker mouthfeel than i expected , and it was wonderful .

a lot of lacing s : sweet smell , slight floral . definite floral hops t : rough up front , then a slight hop/malt taste .  this has been sitting in the cellar for about a year and i am convinced it has the absolute perfect mouthfeel .

there is a lot to this scent , but it is surprisingly balanced , pungent sweetness and hops with subtle funk . good stuff , but it 's a shame it does n't match the glorious scent . mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth , but a bit watery .  mouthfeel - wonderful body with great carbonation and just beautifully drinkable .

smell : strong coffee notes over roasted malt . fairly straight forward but the limited dimensions it offers are good in their own right . taste : fairly waterly coffee rinds .  it 's definitely thick , but it does n't feel anywhere near as syrupy as it looks . o : this beer has a great appearance and mouthfeel .
s : earthy tart wheat , lots of honey , sweet toffee , and a nice floral hop/heat combination . bit-o-honey candy comes to mind .  m - wonderfully full bodied , sticky , smooth . delightful .

very very unique beer , the nose right off the bat informs you of it . rich aroma of the carmel malts used , very heavy scent , but goes along nicely with the character of the porter . really good on a cold day in warm house kind of beer .  great mouth feel on this one . no hops or bitterness present at first , but bitter in the finish .

wonderful , rich , and inviting aroma consisting of bourbon , oak , roasted malt , vanilla sweetness , and some chocolate and coffee . a complete aroma if i ever smelled one , without being over the top or too powerful with bourbon and alcohol sting . subtle , yet rich and complex . a fine tasting beer with a mellow bourbon and vanilla accent throughout , though the base beer still shines through : a rich , chocolatey , somewhat smoky porter . smooth drinking , though full and rich , subtle yet delicious -- really a standout .  silky smooth thick bodied with a perfect amount of light carbonation and a ridiculously long lasting , balanced tart and sweet aftertaste .
smell is of fresh hop , so fresh.just layers of vegetal , cirtusy hops with a slight hint of pine and pale malt .  the moutfeel is exceptional - full bodied and thick with appropriate carbonation .

aroma is tremendous citrus , grape fruity , resiny hop smell . the real hopheads would truly enjoy this beer , those looking for a little balance wo n't really find it .  first gulp of this was outstanding.. nice creamy , mouthfeel to it that just bombards your mouth with sweet , delicious beer flavor .
aroma : pine and floral hops . big hop profile . overall , a decent brew , but nothing extraordinary .  mouthfeel : a smooth sugary viscous mouthfeel that is balanced nicely by the carbonation .
a complex , sweet smell with notes of chocolate , honey , bananas and a slight spicy note hiding beneath .  wonderful body .

aroma is of hops , sugar and vanilla . this beer is mostly sweet and overly oaky with an almost cloying finish that has very little hop bitterness .  mouthfeel is perfect - smooth and velvety without being clingy or cloying .

how many citrus fruits are there ? this one has aromas of all of them -- i 'm picking up kumquat , grapefruit , lime and tangerine ( piney rind ) at the very least . all those citrusy hops i smelled are seriously restrained in the taste . from classic to extreme , from belgian to beefy american , from populist to just plain weird , dogfish head 's got it all . i 'd be their bitch in a heartbeat .  m : absolutely wonderful ... smooth & creamy .

lightly spicy with some typical weizen-like notes of clove and yeast . this is quite a fruity smelling brew with alcohol esters being fairly pronounced . for a beer that smells quite deep and intense with character , the flavor falls a bit short and is not nearly as complex . as the brew warms up , some chocolate grain notes become evident .  full bodied with creamy carbonation and a lingering sweet licorice finish .
smell - aroma was bery pleasing with a definite berry aroma .  m - perfect . it 's velvet on the tongue .
definite beer geek cologne going on .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is outstanding . it sparkles just enough to give the palate a good tickle , but not so much that it scrapes away all of its flavor .

s : roasted malt is very prevalent and dominates right away . lots of great stuff going on in the aroma . t : as in the nose , sweet roasted malt is the main characteristic .  it 's wonderful . alcohol tingles a little in the mouth and it 's certainly present in the aroma but buried 'neath the fruity yeast . expertly woven into the beery fabric of this brew .
smells interesting and fun . the taste is floral and spicey .  light carbonation , rich smooth mouthcoating sensation from the oatmeal .

the aroma is a fascinating combination of sweetness , oatmeal , wheat , and roasted coffee grinds .  mouthfeel is intensely smooth and velvety , creamy and luscious . lactic milk sugar contributes a boatload of palate-smudging heft . although it 's not one for sessioning , it has a sublime quality that makes you savor every sip .
absolutely lovely . very inviting .  mouthfeel : deliciously smooth with a nice , crisp finish . the high alcohol content gives it a nice warmth as well .

it pours like a big , english old ale . smell- fat and sweet , it 's a beautiful display of wood and chocolate covered cherries ... but more like the liquid that surrounds the cherries . notes of old leatherbound library books and rum soaked dark fruits abound .  a bit astringent . fantastic , full body with a very creamy feel -- pretty impressive .

smell : wow , mazing ! roasty , dark chocolate , very coffee forward , sweetness . taste : very good , nice and roasty . overall : very good beer , i would certainly want to have this again .  mouthfeel : excellent light and crisp mouthfeel which is perfect for this style .
great smell good apperance .  nice caramel aftertaste held on the tongue by the thick mouthfeel . creamy thick mouthfeel and modest carbonation .

the aroma on this beer is perfect . absolutely no off smells and wonderfully balanced . as one would expect in an imperial , it has the requisite dark and roasted malt smells , but delightful hints of chocolate and raisins add to the aromatic complexity .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and smooth . an excellent feel .

aroma packs in big notes of freshly-brewed dark coffee . nutty caramel notes and an earthy hop presence are in the mix as well . surprisingly , this beer did not overwhelm me with coffee , but despite the excellent balance the nose is still dominated by the bean . overall , i was expecting a bit more from this highly-touted coffee stout .  mouthfeel is very delicious with some creamy notes but some nice crisps and sharp grassy hop notes .

very addicting aromas . thick chocolatey dark fudge , coffee accents , with heaps of dark fruits thrown in and integrated almost perfectly . sweet malty aromas lay behind the sheen of fruit and lend towards caramel and vanilla . this is a very dry stout that lingers for a long time that i find slightly displeasing . damn good stout worth drinking if for only the smell .  mouthfeel is great . just the right level of thickness here .

aroma is as good as it gets ; fruits , flowers , grass and everything in the yard makes this smell like a spring day ; impressive . medium to light bodied , its taste is interestingly hoppy with a lot of fruits , but the bitterness is not prominent , and it is well balanced by an underlying sweet maltiness which increases its drinkability a lot . for the sake of comparison , this was on a small tasting with alpha king and arrogant bastard ; the taste is better on the other two ; but drinkability and aroma are better here .  a festive arrangement with great depth mouthfeel : really nice - creamy and complex drinkability : good
really delightful . very nice aroma sits about halfway between a brown ale and a porter .  full bodied and silky .

citrus notes are bright and festive in the nose , enticing . t : the nose is somewhat deceiving , this is a bitter bomb .  the alcohol is kept well in check allowing the finish to cascade over the palate with a ton of character and wonderful texture . strong , long finish .

really great smell on it . can definitely smell the hops coming out . lots of earthy , dirty , grittiness to it .  initially the softness of the carbonation and the sweetness of the fruity flavors makes it like a sweet soda ( can anyone remember tahitian treat ? again with the yeast character and the near rancid presence ( the brett i presume ) , yet the overall soft flavors and soft feel are greatly appealing and enjoyable . the light , fine and bubbly carbonation brings an element of childhood fun to the drink ( how about fizzies , anyone remember that ) as it brings a tickle to the nose and tongue . light overall feel and great softness . soft and light and tasty ( again in a soda pop manner ) .
great smelling brew ! taste is of funky , pungent malts , dark fruits again , plenty of yeast , spices .  the mouthfeel is velvety and thick .

small amount of lace around the edges s : roasted coffee and dark chocolate hit the nose first . very sweet smelling , as well as the presence of alcohol t : initially it was more bitter then i expected from the aroma .  m : a great , great medium body , that grazes you at the tail with sharp carbonation .

just great smell . taste : 3.5 a little one dimensional . it has an amazing aroma , but doesnt match with taste . overall , would enjoy more with tweak to malt content , but for a one off beer , still quite enjoyable . recommend trying .  very smooth and rich taste though and perfectly balanced . wonderfull to drink though think it should be drank as i do n't think that more age makes this one any better .
t-disappointing given the great smell . some bitterness in the finish , but overall very bland and boring .  thin in the mouth but heavy on the tongue . perfect for the style and the season .

the aroma , oh the aroma of clean fresh blueberries was awesome ! ! : a cooking note , it makes a great smelling pancake addition to your mix .  m : an incredibly thick body and big , foamy carbonation . i love the way this feels .

black raspberry desert chocolate . slightly smokey and tart in the back . vanilla , fudge , and chocolate . d : described as an `` experimental '' beer , this one is definitely unique . worth a try as i 've never experienced a prominent chocolate raspberry taste in my imperial stouts before and i think i like it !  fantastic mouthfeel .

aroma is mostly complex stages of hops , it 's easy to believe there are 10 varieties , there 's the big american c hops character combined with the refined english ones . very relaxing to sniff on and ultra-complex , like a touch of vanilla on fresh citrus ( grapefruit ) . in mouth this dances on the tongue , nice effervescence , creamy , full-bodied , complex malt sweetness and an obvious balancing yeastiness . this is a delicious big generous beer . tasting this with my buddy martint , we came to the conclusion that given the choice to pick only 2 beers from a same brewery to have an infinite supply of , hotd with fred and adam would probably win over quite anyone .  the taste is a rich velvety malt with an amazing mouthfeel and a fully satisfying richness .

definite lactose on the nose although emphasis is placed much more firmly upon the strong roasted and baker 's chocolate qualities of the beer . once again , lactose shows itself with a vaguely milky start and a kiss of sugar at the finish ( along with bitter chocolate ) .  m - perfect for a porter .

nice . d - i 'm coming to the conclusion that i 'm not a huge fan of hoppy beers . but this is nice . while i ca n't say i 'd like this all the time , i 'd definitely like to revisit it .  smooth grit with comfort .

it feels odd to categorize such a beer as a stout . the aroma is very tame first tiem around , as it warms it become beautiful and fragrant with mocha , coffee , coconut , and lactose together .  nice full bodied and well carbonated mouthfeel .

s - oh shit . dark chocolate , charcoal , campfire , wet ash , cigar smoke , dark chocolate coated coffee beans , birch bark , cigarettes , and a vague hint of sweet count chocula marshmallow cereal . ridiculous ! cigar smoke , woody campfires , wet firewood outside of an old cabin , gentle hints of sushi with soy sauce , and `` musty ( but pleasant ) old house '' notes if that makes any sense .  m- full , smooth mouthfeel .
smell is perfect - best smelling sour i 've ever had .  the carbonation is very low ( natch ) , the body silky smooth , and dead creamy .

aromas are just awesome ... deep rich fruits , candy sugar , plenty of oak barrel , dark bread-like yeast character , and some orange peel in the back . maple and molasses in the sweetness , with just a touch of citrus rhind hops in the finish . not overly chewy , which was nice for this strength of beer .  mouth is rich and sticky yet wonderfully smooth .

lots of apricot and sweet smells on this one .  mouth is very crisp and finishes clean , excellent carbonation . leaves a nice tingling on the tongue . drink is very good i usually would n't want an ipa for a session beer but this one i definetly would have a few more for the evening .

the aromas promise a dandy ; juicy dark fruit ester , roasted coffee , pineapple , chocolate powder and molasses , and hints of bubble gum . a silky mouthfeel , slightly oily , and a sharp carbonation that does n't bite too hard is quite enjoyable . dark fruits , plum , sweet tobacco notes and some coffee and cocoa but not like the nose indicated .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel is absolutely incredible for a milk stout .
s blackberries . light , hammy smoke . the fruit character is subtle and dry . gentle coffee note .  '' love the mouthfeel .

the aroma is thoroughly enticing , presenting notes of buttered wheat , bubble gum , orange peel , banana creme , vanilla , and a touch of spicy , organic hops . all in all , a satisfyingly complex and tasty wheatwine from the talented terrapin brewers .  m - perfect feel to this medium bodied brew .
s. tons of beautiful hop aroma - a spring day in a can .  mouthfeel is extremely silky smooth .

s : peaty , peaty , peaty . slight hint of oak back , but peat dominates the nose , entirely . t : first taste , blast of peat overwhelms the palate , nose , pores , everything .  mouthfeel is full but not too heavy .
very enjoying ! t - malt is smooth , caramel sweetness is restrained and some dark fruits show up .  mouthfeel : fantastic . rich without being syrupy . carbonation is just right .

s : striking tropical fruit , pineapple , lots of oranges , kiwi fruit , very nice . my kind of nose in an ipa . d : the nose tricked me into thinking i was going to get something great , but this beer still impressed me just going on the previous scores .  but what might be the true feats here are , on the one hand , the quality and sock of the flavors given the abv , and the insanely creamy mouthfeel on the other .

the smell is quite good : belgian yeast funk , candi sugar , orange peel and coriander . it has more of the belgian yeast aroma than most wit brews . not as heavy on the orange peel and coriander as most wits ; which i find to be a good thing .  perfect carbonation and ridiculously easy to drink .

strong medicinal smell almost a eucalyptus quality also some fresh cut wheat or alfalfa , and some small notes of tropical fruit . smell is subtle at first and as the beer warms it really opens up . best quality of the brew is the smell . taste and mouthfeel is not as exciting as the smell . not bad at all a tingly carbonation and a little on the thin side .  a faint bit of tannins in the middle of the tongue starts the finish , which is incredibly long with trailing , vineous notes of chocolate and spiced orange peel . ya it 's a bit like those warheads candies , but it 's tucked in such an incredible silky richness .

the aromas is astonishing , this is the most coffee like of any coffee beers that i 've tasted . excellent .  mouthfeel was great , it was very rich and smooth with little carbonation but it fit the stout just right .
this smells amazing . brings back memories of the cherry topping my mother used to make to go along with her cheese blintzes .  m : perfect carbonation .

i actually smell this beer about 2 feet away when opening . very citrusy and piney , a small amount of orange juice sweetness is present . a very nice extreme beer , i may be afraid to try fresh .  the head portends the exceptional mouthfeel .

the first thing that hits the nose is fresh , sweet apricots . notes of peaches and a creamy aroma come through as well . t- very sour with lactic acid . the fruit was far more subtle that i thought it would be , based on the smell . the fresh apricot flavor comes through a little more clearly as the beer warms . d- a bit of a sipper , considering how sour it is , but overall very good .  mouthfeel : it is crisp , light , and perfectly carbonated .

the smell is intense and wonderful , very unique and really lends to the overall quality of this beer .  mouthfeel - great smoothness , i was inclined to take a deep draw at the outset , very quenching . restrained carbonation adds to the smoothness .
the beer 's aroma was fantastic , but the flavor just could not back up the aroma .  medium body and a wonderfully sprtizy carbonation keeps it light and makes the tartness manageable .

it was a pretty dark brown with a sweet hops and spices scent . it was n't very bitter at all .  mouthfeel : wonderful balance all over the pallets and each taste-bud . the slightly raised abv can give cause to the minor warmth in mouthfeel .
smell : so wonderful ... the smoky peaty aroma fills the nostrils . cloying . i really did n't care for the sweetness of this beer .  it 's exceptionally smooth with little carbonation .

this is very easily the best smelling beer i 've ever whiffed . taste is very disappointing . the smell is this brews strongest point , but it is also the source of the beer 's greatest flaw .  m : very soft , finely carbonated medium body .

the first smell i picked up on was tropical fruit smells , including banana and something else ( ca n't put my nose on it ) . there was also a spiciness , and sort of a leatheryness , and a slight maltyness that i find typical of most belgians and pilsners ( pilsner malt ? there was a lot going on in the aroma , which makes me want to revisit this beer and think it through more carefully .  really coats the mouth for an excellent mouthfeel .

very inviting . t - a little bitterness as if it had dark chocolate and you can taste the alcohol . a rather large let down after the amazing scent . m - good coating , but the only tingle is in the throat from the alcohol .  the lush velvety texture takes control of your mouth .

really really strong nose - very sweet with notes of baking spices , vanilla , vanilla cake batter , pumpkin . there is also something about it that i 'm not sure i 've ever smelled before ... and i love it . t : lives up to the smell .  mouthfeel is velvety and smooth . great length on the taste .
kind of corny but this one just smells like sunshine on a hot summer day . big lemon nose gives it a lot of life .  m- the mouth feel is excellent for this beer .
the smell is of malty blueberries , you will not be disappointed .  carbonation is just right . mouthfeel is full , lush , but the carbonation keeps it clean .
smells like sweet cinnamon at first , followed by strong aroma of nutmeg that dominates any other existing aromas .  m - rich and thick , very chewy .

the smell is strong with brandy ( and seemingly bourbon ) and dark fruity sweet malts , caramel , and vanilla . very pleasant . holy shit , what this beer would be if it were carbonated ! dark fruit sweetness complimented by a smooth and invigorating alcohol presence ( 12.5 % ) , much like an imperial stout ... its damn decent right now , but so much greater in my carbonated imagination .  m/d : full creamy body with light carbonation , pretty drinkable for 9 % .

s : a really interesting mix , i get a strong strawberry aroma mixed with a heavy caramel smell . there is also a nice hop/citrus aroma in the middle , some tangerine maybe . overall a really nice beer , very drinkable .  medium bodied beer combined with very active and tight carbonation combines to create an exceptionally creamy beer .

incredibly pungent and tropical aroma . the distinct nelson hops really shine here . one of the best aromas i 've ever experienced from any dipa . an absolutely wonderful dipa . honestly , i never expected a dipa this good to come from karl strauss -- count me in as very pleasantly surprised .  m- incredibly smooth with a nice carbonation .

the smell has a great citrus/banana smell to it that captions your nose the second you pour into a glass . very satisfied with the smell . taste - the taste is very good . the smell and taste together make this an exceptional beer to drink .  mouthfeel is where this beer really shines , and makes one understand why some folks are such lager fans . the balance in this beer is amazing , with everything seemingly in the right preportion .
if you are going to have a flavored beer , apricot is a good one . it 's all about the smell and the flavor . apricots and other fruits .  mouthfeel : so smooth and creamy . very refreshing .
s. smells like christmas . hints of cloves , allspice , and roasted nuts .  very smooth and full bodied mouthfeel , with medium carbonation .

nose is `` oh my fucking god '' chocolate . this smells like a combination of the greatest cup of pure milk chocolate , chocolate milk or hot chocolate with touches of espresso , coffee , dark burnt coffee beans and pure vanilla beans .  mouthfeel is wonderful . very thick , full , coats the mouth wonderfully .

taste s not as rich as the aroma , but still excellent . slightly warming alcohol if felt but not tasted .  the taste is initially of a very light porter and with a clean aftertaste that becomes a fruit sensation on the palate . the hop/malt balance is the real achievement here and it really contributes to the supreme drinkability . the smell upon opening the bottle is not an effective contrival of the taste that this beer is hiding as it only gives you an idea of the rooted flavor that is to be unleashed , the supreme balance and sublime flavor . great bier .

smell is heavy with german hops as soon as the cork was popped . earthy and medicinal notes and just flat out green grass .  m : wonderfully smooth . nice creamy texture that does n't stick too long in the mouth .
smells delicious and this scent would be a great air freshener .  great mouthfeel .
the nose is very complex with hints of soy sauce and salty taffy .  great creamy thick mouthfeel , light carbonation .

i noticed a nice hop bouquet on the nose which suggests it was dry-hopped . maybe it was n't , perhaps just really fresh as the beer had a born on date suggesting the beer was less than two weeks old .  very rich and full bodied , smooth , chewy , all while the alcohol is hidden .
laced well . smelled freaking fantastic . toasty , dark fruits .  mouthfeel is quite amazing , therefore the 5 .

huge pepper aroma and a very pronounced and balanced flavor . thanks to the lovely folks at elysian fields today , very gracious hosts .  the mouthfeel was exquisite . tiny bubbles caress , going a little foamy , opening the flavor as it hits the back of your mouth .

the head is fluffy , off-white , and responsible , in part , for the best characteristic of this brew : the nose . the nose is a wonderful mix of allspice , nutmeg , and a bit of cinnamon , laid over a warm , inviting sweetness . it 's like sniffing a particularly delicious cookie . this brew goes down quite smoothly , and does not seem as high in alcohol as i thought it would .  the carbonation is just right here .
the aroma is really great . big hop presence and a flavor profile that screams west coast .  given the balance and great mouthfeel , drinkability was quite good .

one of the finest smelling beers i 've ever come across . very inviting . tasted much along the lines as the aroma , with the hops perhaps just a bit more apparent . quite pleasing . mouthfeel was good , with a medium body which went down nicely .  overall a really complex , fantastic stout , one i 'd be happy coming back to over and over .

the smell starts off with honey sweetness and pine resin which follows into vanilla aromas from the oak and the citrus aspect of the hops . some alcohol is present but it is n't overbearing . its like smelling a liquified custard of vanilla and orange zest .  mild-medium carbonation just enough to excite the palate . to me , this is almost the perfect mouthfeel .

this beer has the most incredible smell in the world . '' the big wafts of vanilla , caramel , and butterscotch fill the nose and is absolutely delectable . i could enjoy the aroma of this beer for hours . one bomber was enough for me , and i was pleasantly surprised .  very rich and robust brew almost creamy . again , excellent . thanks be to lou91 for the opportunity .
but overall still a nice dipa and one you could drink a couple of .  mouthfeel- the texture of this beer in the mouth is stunning and absolutely *perfect* .

overall , very nice smell . taste is fruity , quite a bit of the banana in the smell comes through in the flavor .  m : the mouthfeel is delightful . fairly thick for an ipa , almost creamy with mild carbonation .
s- banana aromas dominate with subuded peppery yeast notes .  m - very rich and thick , has a nice little burn and pop at the end from a combo of carbonation , abv and hop bitterness .
overall , this beer looked and smelled great , but has too much bite to really enjoy .  m : medium in body with a really smooth and creamy feel on the tongue .

a - typical brown color that comes with this type of beer ; little to no head retention s - wonderful aroma ; slight caramel and hops ; this is what a brown ale should smell like !  mouthfeel is quite exceptional .

in the flavor : oodles of grapefruit and lime , fresh grass , a bit of dank weed , some sweet honey and black pepper . good hop profile ; great for a pale ale . i would n't say this winter offering from ska has flavors that really gel with the season , but it is a nice little pale .  mouth feel is incredible with some good champagne bubbling going on .

s- huge floral hop aroma escapes from the glass . t- extremely flavorful , very hoppy with a hoppy grapefruit finish . d- exceptionally drinkable .  m- wonderfully creamy . the carbonation is spot on . one of the creamiest belgian beers i can think of .
s- lots and lots of chocolate here . roasted malts as well .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect on this beer .

s - the nose is quite nice , suggesting vanilla , oak , smoky whiskey , chocolate and marshmallows . basically the nose is colored like a s'more . o - it is a nice beer , but way underachieving , and almost frustrating to drink as a result .  a very smooth , luxurious malt backbone enhances the mouthfeel , but a bitter smack of hops reminds me that i 'm drinking an ipa . quite enjoyable .

rings of lacing were left on the glass as the chugging commenced - nice ! the aroma was of a fruit forward chardonnay . citrus and floral scents were immediately detectable , along with a sweeter malt characteristic and alcohol .  very thick with just enough carbonation that completely fills the mouth and leaves a bittersweet flavor lingering on the palate , and a bit of a syrupy feel on the back of the throat with just a bit of alcohol heat that is perfect for the style .

aroma is very intriguing . predominantly grapefruit , but there 's a real presence of orange fragrance in the vein of an orange-scented candle from one of those ( apologies for the terminology here ) `` girlie '' stores . very interesting . light citrus flavor upfront .  mouthfeel is where this beer shines the most , imo . creamy and rich and the carbonation is superfine , perfect . this one grew on me a bit as i got into it and it warmed up some , but still not a mind-blowingly good beer .

gives a snootful of dark chocolate and sweet dark molasses from 6 inches away , truly intense aroma . flavor is gently dominated by the chocolate , leans a little toward chocolate flavor extract , but nothing definitive .  m- really interesting . a dry feeling on the sides of the tongue and a sweet feeling in the back . really well done .

s : smells delicious . tart fruit all over the place . fairly satisfying . m : huge carbonation level makes it just a tad unpleasant , but not so much so that i dont still enjoy the beer overall .  mouthfeel was full , thick , and creamy with a rich sweetness on the tongue .

very strong baking chocolate smell - the kind that smells delicious but is really dry and ends up too bitter when you taste it . what a deceptive beer - first you notice it because it is a ris in a can , then it looks and smells great , and then it just lets down big time in the taste .  mouthfeel- light palate with great carbonation that tickles the senses nicely .
the aroma was quite exceptional . never before have i whiffed this nose of smoke in a beer .  mouthfeel : fully body , lower carbonation , love it .
complex and strong aroma of wild flowers , banana , orange and coriander .  each sip of this full bodied beer is smooth and creamy with light carbonation . this beer is so smooth it goes right down .

s : bright fruit , almonds , yeast , nutmeg , and delicate toast round out this great smelling saison . t : begins with off-dry fruit -- apricots , grapes , and lemons -- slightly acidic .  the rich , smooth , roasted chocolate flavor works well with the silky body . this is definitely highly recommended , as the beers tend to be from great lakes brewing company .

the scent on this beer is very sweet . tons of grapefruit and orange come through very strongly . also get a lot of alcohol in the nose . upon first sip , i get so much thrown at me at once . the hops are a bit overwhelming , as well as the booziness .  just a hint of carbonation on the palate - utterly smooth .

the nose really is redolent of pepe du chat , gooseberry , bright herbal citrus with a nice minerality with a touch of dry malt - very sauvignon blancesque .  in the mouth , the tiny bubbles announce and incredibly smooth and balanced beer , with a roasted , slightly sweet flavor .

plenty of other fruit aromas to go around . t : like all hop bombs for me , a great aroma but as i take a sip a mouth puckering bitterness takes over . though this is still a very bitter beer . slick and oily . it looks amazing with a great nose . just to bitter for me .  mouthfeel is as good as you would expect with an aerator . all in all , you can drink it for the mouthfeel but do n't drink it for the taste .

n : nice nose ! ( why thank you-i just had it fixed ! ) mocha , french roast coffee with milk and sugar , choco-roasted malt , brown bread , and a touch of molassas . pretty awesome in its intensity and complexity . p : slightly watery newcastle brown with some roasted malt , seltzer , and dock of the bay tones . m : medium carbonation , medium to light body , crisp , clean and fresh finish , slight lingering malt , slightly sour .  at least it was smooth and the carbonation was just right .

the aroma was simply amazing ! i was champing at the bit to drink this . very sweet smelling . reminiscent of belgian candy sugars and granny smith apples . it was n't unpleasant but i did n't expect this from the aroma . overall , an impressive beer .  creamy mouthfeel with moderate carbonation .
i love the smell of a good lambic though .  medium full bodied , somewhat creamy .

smell is super fruity sweetness , excellent complexities including wood , vanilla and a bit of alcohol . taste is an explosion of goodness . i love that barleywines come in 12oz bottles** , as that 's the size that i 'd prefer to have this style of beer in .  flavor is malty and sweet , and on the finish , bubble gum ! mouthfeel is firm , and drinkability is high .
the flavor is not quite as complex as the nose would suggest but it is still quite good . it starts out with some dry oakiness followed by dusty cocoa .  very creamy and full . very dry .

this is a powerfully aromatic ale it hits you the moment you open it . there is a strong candied fruit smell here . candy dates , pineapple , cherry , and a raw tobacco scent . about the most aromatic beer i have smelled in at least a year , maybe more . pliny the younger and three floyds dreadnaught are the only two on the same level of complexity . mouthfeel is good . drinkability is ok .  let me first say that the brugse tripel used to be one of my favorite beers . nowdays its called brugge tripel and the taste changed slowly ... but a lot of small steps make a big one and today this beer is nothing what it used to be . smell of spices and a little hops , not fresh at all and a dull taste make it just a drinkable beer but nothing great like it had in the past .
the first thing that hit me and my friend was the fantastic smell -- heavy with alcohol and woody wine overtones .  mouthfeel is good , slightly thick .
nice hop aroma right off the bat . very piney and resiney .  was pretty decent mouthfeel : smooth and crisp , went down easy drinkability : good enough on a hot day and goes great w/ bbq .

this smells just terrific . the flavors on the palate generallyh replicate the nose , except they 're not as intense and the brown sugar and chocolate seem to dominate the flavor profile .  mouthfeel : good .

a : reddish amber color , clear , no head retention or lacing s : although you get the belgian yeast banana and spicy notes , in the background you can notice the subtle blueberry aroma of real blueberries , not some extract .  hoping it 's one of those better in a bottle beers i 'm returning to give it another try . so far so good . maybe , and i 'm stretching , some neutral hop spice . this beer makes me try too hard . these hops should be hops should be ashamed of themselves . good malt base to support hops , were they present . bottle is equally bland as on tap .

appearance : good frothing and great head retention , the pale amber hue shows an active carbonation and a brilliant clarity .  taste : a wink of hops , than the shows over , a surprisingly dry finish mouthfeel : decent - nice restrained carbonation , ever so slightly creamy notes : this is the driest , and least bitter ipa that i have ever experienced .
a : pours to a frothey tan head with a deep and beautiful copper body . excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is about the only thing going for this one . medium body and appropriate carbonation .

pours dark brown nearly black with thick fluffy , chunky milk chocolate head that leaves hefty amounts of 3-d lacing as it slowly falls , damn this looks good !  mouthfeel : light-bodied but not watery . it had a nice feel to it .

an aroma of over-ripe and feremting pineapple wafts upwards to the nose , and mingles with subtle hints of grain alcohol.sweet honey melds nicely with mango and pineapple in a malt-forward flavour , with little noticable hopping . the mouthfeel is agressively carbonated , but syrupy underneath ... quite well done , i think . drinkability is decent - this is a sweet belgian strong pale , and while i think that was a slight detraction for me , its still a very well made beer .  mouthfeel is actually pretty nice , medium body and carbonation with a creamy quality .

s : quite good . vinous , and i 'll assume chardonnay-like , notes are at the forefront , with brett and lemongrass also inserting themselves into the mix .  m : crisp and clean , moderate levels of carbonation and warmth . medium body .

i really enjoyed the look and eroma , very subtle nutlike smell .  it has a canned fruit essence to it , but i ca n't pick up what kind of fruit . first couple of sips and i get a strong cherry pie filling flavor . i eat a lot of fresh cherries in the summer so i do n't automatically associate cherries with pie filling . not overly sweet but it does have a tart tang finish . a unique beer that i appreciate as well done , just not to my tastes .

quite a nice and pleasant aroma with qualities of banana , slight clove , a little phenol and a general light ( and sweet ) fruitiness with a backing of wheat . overall , a great aroma and appearance otherwise average , at best .  the mouthfeel is very nice , it 's very carbonated which works with the ginger presence , and the mouthfeel is at about a medium thickness .

upon opening the bottle , the aroma of raspberries is clearly evident . poured into champagne glasses - it looks pink/red in color with a nice foamy head that dissipates fairly quickly . initial taste is raspberries - sweet and fruity .  while the mouthfeel is actually pretty good , the drinkability suffers from this same fatal flaw .
dark mahogany color with a 1 finger , light tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with moderate carbonation .

really good . t : milder than the smell , with a taste of mostly apples and cider , creamy caramel , and a mild woody gin finish .  feel : moderate carbonation , medium body , exceedingly dry finish .
exquisite in appearance !  mouthfeel : medium-plus body . medium carbonation . some oily viscosity to the mouthfeel .
`` the cheeky ale '' pours out a beautiful reddish and slighly brown amber with a tan head .  m - good mouth feel . somewhat unique in feel .

cloudy gold with a large foamy head . head had very good retention , and eventually became a fine lace which left rings all the way down the glass . the appearance aside , this is not a very good beer .  the mouthfeel is full and nicely carbonated yet still somewhat creamy .
the aroma is great , extreamly fresh .  medium mouthfeel .

appearance black and opaque . the head is somewhat bubbly and a very nice brown color .  i did n't pick up the barrel aged at first but the body was quite full and large . worth drinking but i believe that there is better in the 8-9 dollar bomber range .

i 'm picking up in floral and citrus . hops linger in the mouth for a couple minutes and slowly fade into a nice , mellow finish .  mouth is medium bodied , but with some good tingly action on the back of the tongue , so also good .
a good looking beer that smells perfect , but ca n't hold up in the taste realm .  mouthfeel is nice , good carbonation , but seriously , ca n't get over that ham finish .

the smell is extremely vibrant and spicy reminding me immediately of egg-nog . despite being very interesting and flavorful it becomes difficult to drink about halfway through .  this beer has a high level of carbonation with a very crisp and clean mouthfeel .

s - gorgeous nose on this . roasted coffee , chocolate , toffee , caramel with a bit of a piny hop smell poking in there . still it 's an interesting brew with a complex bill . lots of malts lots of hops . still definitely worth a try ( all of their stuff is ) .  mouthfeel : smooth and medium thick , low carbonation .

s - roasted coffee , dark berries ( raspberry ) ripe fruit , dark chocolate , little bit of booze ( bourbon ? i 'm all for interesting beers , which this very much is , but i have had straight bourbon that goes down more easily .  mouthfeel - medium and smooth .
served from bottle into a goblet appearance- black color , very large brown/white very frothy lasting head .  body is on the full side of medium . moderate carbonation .

s : big yeast smell right up front . the yeast and hops work really well together . excellent nose . t : wow . d : very nice beer . still excellent beer all around .  it was somewhat thick with some carbonation , and had a hot aftertaste .

caramel and prune or fig in the aroma . lots of malty sweetness in the flavor , along with sticky fruit , but there is a graininess that is a bit astringent in there as well , though very minute . this is a pretty good beer , excepting the tiny bit of astringency .  it had a smooth mouthfeel with a little carbonation .

nose was erupting from the pour with plenty of darker malts , some dark wheats , a bit of a roasty and toasty aroma , a very slight chocolate , some dark fruits with a bit of fig , hint of booze , some toffee , and lots of dark wheat aromas . taste starts with darker wheats and malts again , a slight caramelized wheat flavor , some brown sugar and molasses , plenty of toffee , darker wheat flavors , a bit of a cola like syrup flavor but just a hint , some darker malts , roasted malts and some toasted malts , slight chocolate again , more fruits , fig and touch of a nutty flavor , hint of coffee , fairly complex , and even a hint of warming booze , that comes out a bit more on the finish but never heavy , very slightly sticky and hint of sweetness but dries slightly .  m- medium viscosity with a well integrated carbonation .
this brew is quite hazy with a golden orange body . the head produced is massive and bright white .  fairly thick body .

very nice . mouthfeel : a little thin and watery . taste : i was a little disappointed after the wonderful aroma . the flavor was very muted and somewhat watery , not unlike the mouthfeel .  very silky mouthfeeland light body , very drinkable and good .
there is a magical cascading effect within the beer as it settles . a beautiful off white head remains perfect throughout the experience lacing is awesome .  mouthfeel : medium bodied .

a - pours nice black and huge heavy sticky head .  lovely thick aromas of blackstrap molasses , dark bitter chocolate , strong coffee and deep roasted malts ... awesome aromas to this one ... lazy and flat tasting ... strange bitter almost sour taste present ... . not much in common with the aromas ... thick oily mouthfeel is great but i ca n't get by the taste of this one ... drain poured this one ... maybe a bad bottle but as is , a big disappointment ...

s : coffee ice cream cones ? like a joy ice cream cone , and a mild coffee . only beer yet to give me that . m : creamy , creamy and creamy . imperial anyone ? t : i 'll start with a heavy dark chocolate to start .  m - oily , medium body with a fantastic amount of carbonation .

cola colored perhaps . head is tan , lasts well , and leaves lacing . m- carbonation is medium-light , but dang , for a porter this has a thin body .  m- moderate/high carbonation , medium body , lager clean . crisp enough leaving a refreshing feel .
s : very citrusy and fruity upfront . some sweet pineapple escapes as well . hoppiness is evident .  the mouthfeel was decent , medium with adequate carbonation .

glorious aroma of silky dark chocolate and dark-roast coffee beans . very pleasant . the dry , slightly acidic roasty finish leads well into another sip .  this beer tastes like sheep shit . this may appeal to some people , but it 's definitely a very unusual belgian ale . i enjoyed drinking half of this beer for the experience . it 's so pungent i laughed out loud . it 's always fun to be exposed to a radically different flavor profile than you 're used to .
had a nice creamy 1/2 '' white head which has decent lasting power . lacing was somewhat spotty . beer is a reddish/brown with no visible carbonation .  medium bodied ; good amount of carbonation .

wow . the nose was so great . what happened ?  crisp and clean in the mouth , body fits the carbonation well . nothing amazing about this brew , but it 's not terrible and comes in a nifty bottle you can use for ... something ... .i guess .
s : big chocolate aroma , oak , vanilla and some booze . t : wow !  most everything else about this beer was great , looked good , good mouthfeel , but the taste .

heavily hopped with three different american hop varieties , the hop aroma and flavor are citrus-like and pungent . very strong hop aroma - primarily cascade hops , so this e.s.b . 's aroma reminds me of a dry-hopped pale ale in the pacific northwest style . overall , a satisfying ale - not exactly true to its style , but very good nonetheless .  mouthfeel : lightly carbonated and creamy .
