the smell is the best part of this beer : very hoppy and `` dirty '' . the taste is good , but i feel that it 's a bit weak compared to dogfish head 's 90 minute ipa . overall , a good ipa , but not the best i 've had .  the mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with smooth carbonation .

dark roasted malts , espresso , bitter chocolate , vanilla bean , and some black currant . very one dimensional with little complexity . you mainly get a big slap in the face of dark roasted malt , with some bitter chocolate , and coffee in the finish .  long , earthy , dry finish . interesting , somewhat unusual brew .

( a ) - pours a clear golden yellow/orange color that produced a huge foamy/fluffy white head with great retention .  on first sip you get hit with a strong citrus hop attack . from the aroma to the taste , there is just something that does n't sit well with me . it leaves an unpleasant bitter aftertaste . i love ipas and hops galore . my only guess is that the bitter citrus flavor is what threw this beer off for me .
this brew produces mounds of bright white head , which peaks easily over the top of my stein . it has a very nice golden and hazy body .  the mouth is smooth and light .

a beautiful dense white head lasts for a while and laces all the way down the glass . the color is a unique peachy-orange that is slightly opaque , and catches the light wonderfully .  smooth in the mouth with nice , crisp carbonation . nice feel , but flavor is not there .
the smell is stunning . if i could bottle this and wear it , i would . just incredible . the taste is great , but does not live up tot he smell .  mouthfeel is nice & creamy .
pours a lovely coppery amber with a dense , dense foamy off-white head .  light mouthfeel with a good amount of carbonation when you drink it .

medium amount of carbonation s : i really enjoyed the burnt caramel smell that comes from the roasted malts . there is some maltiness , smokiness , and some slight sweetness in the aroma .  m - nice light feel with a crisp finish , accentuated with a alcohol warmth .
very nice . taste : mmm .. chocolate and coffee with quite a few roasted flavors .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , slightly sticky in the front and a little dry on the back of the tongue . pretty good .

smell was delicious . nutmeg , cinnamon , holiday cheer ... everything a holiday ale should smell like . overall this beer was good . i would definitely try the 2012 redition .  m : medium-high carbonation fits the style nicely .

tasted june 22nd 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - a clear blood red , one finger tan head and some lacing s - alcohol , wine barrels , sweet dried fruits , earth , oak , french vanilla and more sweet and alcohol t - alcohol , lots of sugar , sweet malts , tons of sweet dried fruit , black cherries , wine barrels , raisins , charred oak , molasses , carmelised brown sugar and vanilla .  dark brown/amber body . it is a very smooth and a sweet sipper . some hops , caramel , candy sugar and oak . not much bourbon . i was way excited to try this and actually find it to be rather average .
no head retention or lacing huge oaky , fruitty boozey nose , beautiful t : dryness , raisins , dates , & breadyness with a slight booze presence up front .  m - medium bodied with good carbonation .

does n't quite live up to the smell , but still very pleasant and highly sessionable .  the mouthfeel of this beer ( outside of taste ) was great . great carbonation , bitter hop aftertaste , medium bodied .
its sweet , balanced and complex , pretty nice . the taste is way to strong and not good .  mouthfeel is pretty good , goes well with the style of light and highly carbonated .
very aromatic . t - chewy malts with the same fruity ester present in the nose .  m - good carbonation and it finishes clean . good light to medium mouthfeel .
smell is of citrusy hops , a bit of malt , and some bitterness .  mouthfeel is fine and not heavy .

smell is strong and at first of piney , grassy , spicey hops with some citrus not all that different from an ipa . some caramellly and toffee smelling malt and a bit of booze hits the nose as well to differentiate it . taste at first is boozy . it is supported by the hops , but they are n't nearly as dominant as in the aroma . plenty of malt sweetness is there , but some fruit flavors appear as well . overall a very good beer , but it falls a bit below the expectations set by the aroma .  a bitter spicy bite from the hops hit first . the light body and good crispness contrast the flavor pretty well .
s : chocolaty , coffee , roasted malt , maybe some caramel tones . the appearance and smell had me so excited for the taste , only to be let down by a watery drink .  it has good texture .

a- pours a deep brown with a big two and a half finger mocha head .  the same color , mouthfeel , and drinkability were there , just the hopiness , aroma , and flavor , as well as most of the bitterness seemed to have blown away .

s - mango , pineapple , yeast , apple , pear all present . yup , this is citra . o/d - aroma was lovely but the booze is a little rough .  body is right- light , lively carbonation , not cloying or excessively dry .

s - a fantastic aroma of lemony citrus and wheat with pale malts and a light bouquet of floral hops . the thing that totally makes the aroma is the wonderful funk from the brett yeast . tiny fruit esters of mango and pineapple from the yeast also play a small but delicious role . very complex and inviting . t - a bright sour funk bursts across the tongue right away bringing with it that barnyard and horse-blanket that is so good . it 's definitely a lively beer . d - i 'm really happy i 'm sharing this cause a 750 ml to myself would be devastating for two reasons ; a ) to my sobriety , and b ) to my taste-buds .  the mouthfeel is very full and hearty almost meaty- sort of flat .
a classic looking hefe , a orange/golden color with a billowy , white head .  mouth feel is completely crisp , refreshing , and clean .

s-the nose is quite rich with candied sugar , caramel , and a touch of dark fruit with ripe plums and some dark cherries t-the taste is sweet but a little watery , it brings caramel , brown sugar , and dark ripe fruits . plums and a hint of dark cherries .  mouthfeel - good feel , not too thick , kind of creamy , decent carbonation .

aroma is a sweet malt-candy smell , bready , with a note of ginger and sourness . this beer tastes almost as good as it smells .  mouthfeel was smooth , slightly thick for a pils , and with a nice carbonation bite .

bonus points for advertising their smaller drafts as 14 oz , instead of the misleading `` pints '' of many establishments . bright white head that leaves great lacing , a ring for every sip .  taste is thin and adjuncty . mouthfeel is good , thick and creamy .

very dark mahogany red . beautiful foam , creamy , beige in colour . it left a lot of laces on the glass . a taste that remains on the palate , and it is not a beautiful sensation .  mouthfeel is very light and well carbonated .

poured into an a-b flute on 1/3/12 deep , slightly cloudy honey-amber color with a two and a half finger head that is intent on having the appearance steal the show . the head is very slow to thin and leaves thick lace along the way . retention is thin by the end , but it does last the whole way and lace remains excellent .  has a medium body which is needed to carry all the hops and alcohol . low carbonation lends a nice texture without letting the flavors being cloying .

the smell is sweet , spicy , almost vinous , and very complex . each time i think i have an aroma captured it changes into something else .  mouthfeel : nice feeling on the tongue and also a good consistencty .
one of the best smelling beers i 've tried .  m : lovely long bitter aftertaste .

the spices really compliment the berry smell . very unique and inviting . the highlight of this beer is the incredible aroma . t - not quite as impressive as the nose leads to believe .  the mouthfeel is good , but obviously does not improve the flavor !

crazy carbonation & a genuine golden shimmer . a half inch of ethereal eggshell-colored head that recedes on schedule .  - well carbonated , dries the mouth a bit . nice smooth body , probably this beers highlight is the mouthfeel .

big aroma for such a little head ; bright fruits , dried fruits , plum , cherry , red grapes , slight caramel and a smooth yeasty character . fruity malt character also displays some earthy , hearty grain notes and much of the same fruits as in the nose . nice medium yeasty twang marries well with the fruit notes .  the flavor that by far took the lead was chocolate ! there 's an overpowering ( and for me , disappointing ) chocolate aftertaste in this beer . mouthfeel- smooth , no complaints here . drinkability- well , the bottle looks cool as you drink from it !

* subtle but complex aromas of dark chocolate , ripe cherries , sour fruits , currants , figs , beer bread and burnt sugar . taste is not as complex as the smell , and almost underwhelming with more dark chocolate notes , unripened dark fruits ( plums , grapes ) grain and yeast .  m : smooth and round .

pours a rich opaque sable with a fine-bubbled light tan head .  everything about this beer was pretty light - light , crisp malt scent ; light fruity taste ; light body . feel - 4.0/5.0 - refreshing , which was really nice .

a : a straight pour fills the glass perfectly with a clear medium orange-amber body and three fingers of frothy white head that just barely peek over the rim . good retention and light , sticky lace . a little lighter in color than i might like for the style , but otherwise a magnificent-looking beer .  m : medium in both body and carbonation .

the aroma of it is amazing , almost a pumpkin cider type smell .  ) mouthfeel is just nicely carbonated and light and the only reason the drinkability is n't higher on my ratings is because after a few 40 's your out of the game for a while .
s - coffee . geez .  m : good mouthfeel , its crisp , refreshing , light bodied with moderately high carbonation .
well i poured this into a pint glass and it has a good head , a pink hue and good watermelon aroma . this is very easy to drink !  carbonation done very well .

i think this is not a fully retired beer but a seasonal since this one was picked up last week in a large grocery chain ... aroma is heavy with yeast effects and fruit aromas including plums and apricots . nice light hop aroma too smelling like wood and light citrus .  m : medium body and moderate carbonation .

s : raisins and dark fruits with a mild white wine aroma .  mouthfeel was the highlight of the beer - it was almost velvety smooth . carbonation was low as per the style but if they 'd added a few more hops to dry out the palate it would have been near perfect .

when settled it left a beautiful two finger head which dissipated only slightly and remained until the very end . the body is a nice golden yellow/orange .  the mouthfeel is very nice.. feels heavy , thick , smooth , and not over-carbonated .

s : wow . the hops smell great in this one . at first it smells like that first hop addition when you are homebrewing . very aromatic and appealing . some grainiess in the background from the malts .  mouthfeel - it does have a pleasant rich/buttery mouthfeel .
one of the best smelling beers i have tried .  m : nice and thick d : not something ill try again .

s awesome whiff of freshly brewed coffee and oats . bits of chocolate are also pleasing on the nose , as this is very simple but rather enjoyable . burnt roasts add to this smooth and creamy mixture of scents .  at least its silky smooth and the alcohol is well hidden . this beer , in my opinion , is the weakest of their stout series .

smells of extremely fresh raspberries . seriously , about as real as it gets with the fruit scent and something many others ca n't accomplish . still , about good for drinkability to me . the tartness and somehow a tad too much malt make this less drinkable than it should be .  still for such a big beer it had a great body , just not sure if i would want more , until it got about 5 years on it .

very pleasant aroma t- a slight fruitiness with a hint of caramel . slight hoppiness , intially good , but after taste left something to be desired m- slightly heavy , definately not light .  smooth creamy medium body .
nose is superb -- very much pumpkin pie . delicious and a new pumpkin ale favorite !  mouthfeel is round and full , thick and sticky .

smell is intense . lemon sour acidity , pepper , lots of sweat & musk . sweet florals . earthy funk . it just seems more then a tad empty when compared to what i smelled up front .  the body is full and the carbonation is light . mouthfeel is creamy .
the smell is fruity and funky sweet . tons going on here in addition to the funkiness of the brett .  light body , good carbonation .

a - murky apple juice with and incredible pillow head ... slow to leave , chunky lace left .  m - the brew is wet at the lips but finishes quite dry . impressive . ~ unfortunately i 'm going to struggle finishing this because of the flavor .

the aroma was very fresh , like a breeze on a river , ( stunning ! ) floral hops and hints of citrus along with caramel malt ; a sweet and inviting blend . muted orange rind , grapefruit notes and a doughy malt/yeast blend were present but the bitterness that sat atop them i found unpleasant .  body was medium , and the liquid was fairly smooth overall . 3.03 rdev -19.5 % look : 3.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 3 | feel : 4 | overall : 2.5 1366

poures a deep tranparent amber in color . leaving a half finger of retention.thick gloppy rings of lace . : ( i was pretty excited to taste this after its wonderful appearance and terrific aroma .  mouthfeel is medium , clean with a bitter hop aftertaste .

appearance : slightly hazy , ruby-amber pour with a voluminous ( and tenacious ) , light-tan whipped-cream head . recedes to floating dollops ... lace everywhere !  mouthfeel : light , carbonated , crisp .

the beer looks great ! s : i get some notes of honey , grass , caramel , and light seasonal summer fruit .  mouthfeel is very creamy as expected from the nitro can , but i couldnt get past the taste that just did not agree with me .

aromas are fantastic ( pure wild ale ) . plenty of interesting aroma & flavor , and smooth going down .  m : fizzy carbonation that smooths out a little into the sip and works well with the body of the beer .

sn consistantly produces beers w/ amazing hop boutique aromas . t - flavor profile pretty much mimics the nose w/ the malts and biscuit holding the fort down so the trademark sn cascades can do what they do best . mf - creamy , medium body and goes down w/ a slick and oily feel d - balance , balance , balance . highly sessionable .  this one is crisp and carbonation is at a good level . body is n't as light as i had expected ; this one 's medium-bodied .

a : nothing to complain about here - dark black , with a mocha colored head that hung around for a while .  goes down smooth , no bite , and finishes with an appropriate amount of stickiness . carbonation is on the lower end of the spectrum . nice feel .

frothy near lace remains . the aroma is a vibrant combination of tangerine juice and zest hop nose along with mellow esters of a ripe pear nature . understated light caramel bolsters fruity sweetness . spot on and appetizing aromawise .  mouthfeel is light to medium and has a soft feel .

t - unfortunately the taste does n't just quite live up to the smell . tastes a little woody/green , with the nice smokey flavors absent from the taste . pretty good , just kind of a let down from the amazing smell . m - too thin for me . d - this is a good porter that i would n't mind drinking again , although it is not something i would necessarly seek out .  mouthfeel : light/medium with a tart , crisp finish drinkability : i really do n't crave another of these ; this certainly would n't be a lawnmower beer for me conclusion : just kind of unsorted ( also kind of an odd bitterness on the finish ) ... i tried this a year or two ago and was n't a huge fan ... now that i 'm reviewing it ... i 'm still not .

aroma of roast , ash , chocolate , dried fruits , vanilla , bourbon , caramel malts , and alcohol . taste of dark fruit , some tropical , sticky molasses , roasted malts , vanilla , and bourbon - alcohol .  m/s carbonation is fine , alcohol is n't really noticeable `` thanks '' to the bitterness overall i really do n't like this beer , but i guess it has more to do with me and this style than the beert itself .

smell is the leader of the pack , amazing scent of coffee , cream , smoke . drinkability suffers from the mouthfeel since this is the only non style rating , but i really like this porter .  m : solid mouthfeel , carbonation is pretty much spot on .

really smells nice . the taste mimicks the nose ... .nice balance between the cloves and banana notes ... also some subtle but enjoyable caramel maltiness .  an intense experience . the flavour is huge bitter hops - oily and rich with a spike on the back palette . the alcoholic warmth starts deep within the pit of the stomach and travels all the way up to the cheeks . next time i try it will be in front of a fire with a huge cheese platter .
served in a tulip corsendonk glass . a - beautiful golden with a nice airy white head .  mouthfeel is creamy and satisfying .
strong aroma of coffee and chocolate . this stout is pure blackness and even thick then disappates to thin dark brown head .  m : creamy to a crisp finish with a good carbonation throughout .
very alluring aromatically , strong bakery smell , quite yeasty , some wheat a little bit of sweet and citrus thrown in .  the mouthfeel is good - smooth with a right amount of carbonation .

apples , pears , plums , cherries , and a little bit of orange . interesting . some bubblegum/banana in here also . t- the taste isnt nearly as inviting as the smell , and is kind of a let down . d- after the smell this one sort of fell apart on me . i dont think id seek it out again .  m : medium bodied with a medium carbonation .

the smell was exceptional and exciting , with a remarkable variety of spicy tones that are too complex to describe . with great anticipation , i tried the first sip , which was heavenly . and then it happened ... a nasty aftertaste that i could n't quite place but did n't like .  mouthfeel was pleasant . a medium bodied chewiness and good carbonation .

very nice 3 finger head that was creamy with a great deal of structure . deep orange/amber in color and quite translucent . great lacing and a touch of visible carbonation . this short description is not an indication that it was n't great .  mouthfeel : nicely carbonated and good level of thickness - probably the best part of this beer .

pours a brilliant colour , reddish , orange , very clear , just amazing , thick white head , lots of lace , great retention , head never leaves , i have to give this a 5 for appearance , simply one of the best looking beers i 've ever seen .  m : silky smooth feel . i like the finish . smoothed out my palate .

aroma is powerful , though not overbearing . piney/resiny hops are dominant , yet there is also a good helping of pineapple , tropical fruit and caramel .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is well balanced with a nice medium body , leaning a bit on the heavier side . drinkability : the mouthfeel is great and there is no sign of the 7 % abv .

notes from 6/16/10 pours jet black with a lovely tan brown head crowning the top . the head lingers and sticks to the glass creating lacing art on the sides of the glass . this is one of the better dark beers i 've seen come out of a bottle .  full bodied with a smoothy , creamy mouthfeel .
the nose had a definite saaz quality to it .  m : very fizzy , light on body , about right for the style .
the smell was delightful . with a hoppy nose and a touch of citris .  the mouthfeel was full and sweet .
s - wow . full nose of citrusy hoppy goodness .  had a funny texture in the mouth and could definitely taste dried fruit but could not discern the type .

exquisite nose has brandy , oak , vanilla , dark pitted fruits , candy malts , port wine and whiskey . taste does not hold the same complexity . some tart cherries , plums , caramel , toffee , wood , vanilla , wine grapes and cognac . past prime for sure , but still an interesting beer .  the mouthfeel is really soft and creamy , as i figured cask would be .
terrific chocolate and coffee notes with some fruity hints as well .  m : crisp , clean , would call it refreshing if it tasted better .

batch 9359 packaged 9/17/09 a : pours an opaque black with a tight dark brown head which leaves much lacing on the walls of the glass as it fades to a thin layer .  maybe i could not taste the `` rare '' but this really sucked compared to the 2008 classic gueuze which is a fantastic gueuze .
wow , orange , slightly reddish , as it let 's the light pass through ... it 's beautiful . such a strong head , off-white .  buttery thick mouthfeel .

very attractive nose . taste is muddled malty sweetness up front , picking up some golden raisins and dried apples along the way .  m - good mouthfeel . a little heavier thanks to the lack of filtration .

also present are dark chocolates , licorice , spice , robust yeasts , sweet malts and some caramel that all lead to a very complex and pleasing aroma . the taste is not as complex .  medium bodied and decent carbonation .

very interesting . concrete and ginger . refreshing and smooth but a bit more bland than i expected based on the wonderful aroma . nicely mellow and subtle .  mouthfeel : thick and what you would expect from a ris .
richer . the sweetness comes through much more . i highly recommend storing one of these away to turn a very good experience into a great one .  it is pretty full bodied and creamy .

a perfect pour into an oversized wine glass with rich deep amber body a tightly formed thick white head , i could not find any reason to not give a perfect score.tropical fruity hops in the nose with a little boozy and caramel sweetness , overripe mango and pineapple on the palate with again some sweetish booze , the malt base is quite dry underneath the hops and sweet booze.a nice dipa , one of the best pours for me ... ever .  mouthfeel is heavier than i 'd anticipate . i wish i liked the flavor of this because its heaviness is spot on .

s : wow , tons of hops in the nose . a slight sweetness is detectable underneath it , but almost all hops , and in a big way . t : again , up front i 'm getting lots and lots of hop bitterness , with just a tiny bit of sweetness on the end of it . as it warms , i can get more malt and some caramel , too .  nice creaminess from the malt . probably the driest amber ale i 've ever had . usually not a bad thing , i like dry beers , but this was too much , there needs to be a little sweetness there to bring it to life . should n't be called an octoberfest and would n't try again .

a truly wonderful bouquet . taste accents of hops and light fruits , again pineapple , with a delayed afterthought of hops bitterness at the back of the throat . a tasty and sexy organic brew .  mouthfeel is about right for style , perhaps a touch undercarbed , but all else is acceptable , though it showcases a flavor profile best left behind the curtain .

aroma is right there with what i look for in a bsda : nice bouquet of caramel malts , dark fruits , belgian yeast , and maybe some candied sugar . i 'm suddenly pretty jazzed about this beer . if the sweetness was dialed back a bit this could be a great beer ... still very good , but imo just a bit too sweet .  m : mouthfeel is crisp , light-medium bodied and pretty dry .
on tap at kuhnhenn winter , solstice night two . a big nose of spices .  mouthfeel was nice and thick ; you know you 're drinking a dipa .
this beer looks like the platonic ideal of beers . light amber/orange color and a fluffy white head that dissipates slowly .  m- very smooth . medium carbonation fills the mouth a little . d- good .
one finger large off white that shows great retention .  strong carbonation . m. very bitter and the carbonation is clean and tart .
a - pours a thick 2 fingers of tan head that sticks around for quite some time .  m : light body , moderate carbonation , nice crisp body .

a - moderately vigorous pour yields an over the top , dense , styrofoam khaki-colored head . decent sticky legs , too . impressive !  the body is pleasant and perfectly appropriate for a light belgian ale . full of carbonation , relatively light in the mouth , easy to drink ; no complaints on this front ; this beer only becomes a problem when you have to smell it or taste it .
s - about 0.2 seconds after the cork popped , the air was almost filled with a rich , dry oak smell . lots of brett in there as well .  m : thick creamy mouthfeel .

a very intriguing nose , wow , minty , citrusy , lemon-grass , soft licorice notes , very pleasant even with its slight funk of oxidation . this is actually quite nice even with its funk , i could deal with a little less carbonation .  m : well carbonated and thick , fairly heavy . fits the style .
smell is just plain wonderful . it 's like an entire garden of raspberries up your nose .  m - pretty good .
smell is amazing . has a spicy fruity smell .  the mouthfeel is smooth and oily and the carbonation is alright .

bottle : poured a pitch-black color stout with a huge dark brown color ahead with good retention and great lacing .  really nice body all around ... overall - i would really enjoy this beer if it were n't for the bubblegum flavor , it 's really off putting and not very pleasant .
the smell is exceptional . tons of different scents .  m : the body is medium to full with a fairly high carbonation . this is actually one of the best things about this beer .
pours a bright , clear , light orange color with a nice looking head .  there 's big citrus/grapefruit hops , but then a nasty onion/vegetable taste . mouthfeel is fine .

it smells amazing -- a sharp alcohol bite ( it 's a 21 abv , for crying out loud ) but surrounded with sweet citrus and pine and caramel and hops .  m/d : light and smooth feel on the mouth , drinkable but not something i will ever get again .

appearance : beautiful translucent orangish copper with a thin white head . the head dissipates quickly leaving behind a white glass ring . good lacing .  the aroma contained notes of malt , hops and a discernable alcohol content of medium strength . it had a stong alcohol flavor that was very over powering the other flavors . it was smooth yet burned as it went down . truely a devilish brew !
i was much more impressed by the pour and visual of this beer than by taste or drinkability . nice puffy styrofoam cloud of a head .  m : light-medium bodied , creamy , smooth and crisp .

the smell was very promising with wonderful aromas of sweet , bready malt with banana , clove , and a banana bread finish .  this has a very creamy mouthfeel to it despite being fairly well carbonated .

great nose - big , malty , sweet . smells like barley malt fresh out of the bag . a rather abrasive malt profile - i hate to use that word , but it best describes it for me . nice flavors all the way through , but fails to deliver a big full mouthfeel as promised by the nose and malty attack on the tip . the finish cleans out fairly well .  mouthfeel is crisp and drying , as it should be .
this beer has a decent amount of hops for an apa and the nose is quite nice , but the flavor and mouthfeel do n't offer enough to really set this beer apart .  the mouthfeel is medium and creamy .
a : nearly black in color , a very dark cola color with a thick , foamy cocoa head . great retention and lacing .  firm mouthfeel , big and solid . very imperial .

glassware : tall 14.4 oz glass ( i love pouring it to the halfway point , let it sit and agitate it by swirling it aggressively just like scotch whisky ) appearance : amber brown hue on the pour , with a reddish head nose : i loved every moment of this brew , i sat for at least 2 hours sniffing on this puppy ( if only these guys aged their ale in pappy van winkle 's bourbon barrels , i can only dream ) palate : loving the booziness of it , sweet caramel , vanilla oak and maraschino cherries . all in all , a decent coating with a medium to long finish . pairings : a relatively inexpensive bahia blu robusto went very well with this drink , the hearty cedar core blends well with the sweet caramel and vanilla oak .  appropriately light in body without being too thin .

smells heavenly - a brilliant blend of maple syrup , caramel , toffee , figs , burnt sugar and bourbon . just a hint of booziness at the end . tastes a lot like it smells - however the bourbon is much more prevalent than the other flavors - you get hints of the caramel , figgy , malty deliciousness present in the nose , but they 're largely overpowered by the bourbon .  however , the mouthfeel was very nice , which lent a overall smoothness and softness to it .
quite nice . p : rather boxy and angular at first , with no discerning flavors other than a malty bitterness .  the mouthfeel was quite good , though . well carbonated and it felt good going down .

a : poured with a large , white fluffy head that was very long lasting ... never got below 1-2 fingers size . body is a beautiful , dark orange color , with excellent clarity .  i believe the bottle i got was 8.75 percent.. looked pretty good for a esl , smell and taste reminded me very much of great western extra gold.. very malty with a nice solventy sweet-like alcohol burn ... carbonated perfectly , making it halfway drinkable , still hangover juice as far as imports go.. cheers !
huge sticky head alone has a personality all its own . gorgeous golden haze pour that has no room for improvement , while in a class all its own .  this beer feels almost delicate .

the aroma was that of raisins smothered in chocolate , dried plums and cherries and some alcohol . a chocolatey start that gives way to dried fruits ( rasins and plums ) mixed with some bitterness .  the mouthfeel is notably well contoured . dark and hearty though at times cloying .

the smell is amazing . like i stated above , i 'm not big into coffee , but even this is appealing , and impressive to pull off . this porter does nothing but give off an intense and clean cafe au lait aroma , straight to the point . it 's greatest attribute is the aroma however , that is really phenomenal .  we 're okay though , as next time we get a samuel adams winter sampler pack , i 'll give her my cranberry , and i 'll have her boston lager . it 's not a bad beer , it 's just not to my liking . i ca n't even really say why . a bit sweeter than i 'd like , and just nothing that stands out and says `` i 'm great '' .

appearance : thick white foam that looks great in a frosted glass . color is very unique for a pilsner . it 's very pale yellow , almost looks like lemonade .  taste/mouthfeel : mostly hops . heavily malted finish . drinkability : a bit heavy and not quite as good as other european lagers . overall : probably the best gateway to this style .
the nose is beautiful . i get the belgian yeastiness , and something akin to peaches served with a dash of allspice . so far it 's awesome .  there 's actually a nice amount of body to this one .

for the record , fresh - this might be the mightiest tasting ipa out there . smells like mango , citrus , pine needles , pineapple , melon etc . also has a nice sweet malt aroma in the background . lots of piney resin with a pineapple/mango twang . o : overall , a finely crafted ipa . among my favs all-time and easily my top 3 from out west .  mouthfeel is light with a good spike of carbonation .

very good smell . t : roasted sweet caramel & malts .  taste is a very light malt sweetness upfront with a moderately bitter finish of good length and crispness . a pretty uncomplicated beer , good for the style , a good lawnmower beer .
very very nice . very complex .  nice carbonation and creamy mouthful .

honey and pepper spiciness , too , as short 's beers always smells great . the green peppercorns shine through upfront giving it an initial peppery taste .  mouthfeel is good all around- enough carbo to temper the bitterness , moderately thick , finishes dry . a damn shame .

aroma definitely carries a strong banana smell to it with some clove in there as well . it smells like a hefeweizen for sure , but it 's categorized as a wit here . it starts out with a good banana presence , as was seen on the nose . no surprise there .  m : fuller side of medium-bodied with moderate carbonation that tickles the tongue and throat . this aspect of the beer is really nice .
the nose is impressive . easily the most enjoyable part of drinking this beer .  mouthfeel is decent medium bodied and goes down smooth .

this pours a beautiful chocalate brown with a thick 2 inch mocha malty head reminicent of a fine stoudt . the taste is mediocre slight hints of chocolate surrounded by the more obvious coffe malt flavors .  feel is pretty smooth , nothing weird here .

s : the best smelling coffee oatmeal stout i 've smelled to date .  crisp , clean mouthfeel with flavors of dry , pale malt . at first , i found myself wanting more flavor , a la boston lager , but the mouthfeel and resulting drinkability really brought things back up for me in the end .
the color was reddish-amber and the smell was fantastic ! floral , sweet hops - strong and complex . the taste is hops up front and hops on the end - not as complex as the smell .  m - nice . thick .
smell is a beautiful bouquet of tangy/citrus hops .  feels very creamy but that does n't make the beer more drinkable to me .
a : an outstanding looking beer . dark plum color with a pinch of tannish head and amazing coating lacing . stunning .  m. medium-high carbonation , zesty on the tongue .

t - not as complex as i had hoped for , but still good . starts off with bourbon vanilla flavors with some caramel malt sweetness mid palate , then big oak flavors with a bit of spice through the long finish .  smacks-you-in-the-face astringent . zippy on the mouth like you 'd expect .
overall : well , the smell is great , one of the best .  feel medium body , pleasant texture , some drying and bitterness in the finish .

it has a massive creamy bone colored head , very large and good retention for a cask ale . decent lace trails stick to the glass .  m : medium-bodied with low and sightly creamy carbonation . there is a slight sticky feel and syrupy feel .
not a terribly complex smell , but its really appealing nonetheless .  very refreshing in the mouth , its best quality .
produces a huge , thick and creamy head with superb retention throughout the entire glass . just a beautiful looking beer .  m : the carbonation is pretty much just right , and it 's smooth .

s : this smells like heaven . endless raspberries , need i say more . it 's not as good as the legendary new glarus raspberry tart , but this beer is certainly fun and tastes great .  mouthfeel is crisp , the whole drink is refreshing due to the good carbonation .

the aroma of this beer was the highlight for me : banana , apple , belgian yeastiness , other fruits ... really great . golden yellow in color with a small ring of head at the top after it settles . alcohol comes through very nicely . sweet aftertaste is enjoyable .  m : medium body and very good amount of carbonation in my opinion .
a - a leathery brown color with a one finger offwhite head . great lacing that clings to the glass the whole way down .  mouthfeel is medium with good level of carbonation .

a nice wine scent . taste is like it smells , which is good .  taste - 3.0/5.0 - light `` summer '' type beer , prob good if really hot , some malt crispness feel - 4.0/5.0 - smooth , light , refreshing drinkability - 2.5/5.0 - would have again , if it was hot , but not enough flavor make this a go-to beer
pours pale gold with a massive crown of stiff white foam .  this beer does have a nice smooth , dry mouthfeel .

the mystery beer in my joe 's garage variety pack , poured a deep brown with dark near crimson hue when held up to the light with a large 2 finger mocha colored head.perfect 5 for me aroma wise its american big on the fruity , piney hop mixed with chocolate and earth just fantastic love the big hop profile.the same goes for the flavors big piney drier hop profile intertwined with bitter chocolate with a earthy raw nut lingering finish.a little prickly on the mouth but nothing to take away from the great flavors of the beer , damn i wish there more porters like this it is the most hoppedup version i think i have had to date .  medium carbonation .
beautiful tan head with steady retention .  lighter body and a nice lively carbonation .

a nice balanced nose with caramel malts , floral hops and a nice dose of sweetness coming from tropical fruits . the fruitiness keeps reminding me of pink bubblegum .  mouthfeel is sticky and sweet with a nice roundness and full character .

incredible and intense . t : bitter roasted malt throughout . overall , a fantastic beer .  '' m - actually a nice and robust mouthfeel , i just do n't really want to feel this beer in my mouth because it tastes kind of terrible .

it 's so cloudy you ca n't see any yeast in it , just an opaque gold glass . thick , white head that keeps a barrier of foam for the entire bottle .  good , solid creamy feel with enough dryness to get you through .

the first thing that struck me about this stout was the aroma , very complex , almost sweet , with what i thought could have been vanilla among other things . the # 1 surprise was the texture and consistency of this beer , i was expecting something much thicker , more like guiness , and boy was i surprised , a much smoother , lighter consistency with a great taste and just enough flavor to let you know you are drinking something quality without being over whelming . it took me more time to get a good overall sense of this stout then i would have expected , a compliment to the complexity of the flavor .  mouthfeel was good and thick , but was n't enough to save this beer from being a disappointment .

the spiciness attacks your olefactory senses with a vengence . aroma reminds me of some winter warmers i 've had .  i did n't want to buy this because i do n't trust twisted pine to sell me a good beer . since i am a sucker and i love hoppy beers i bought it anyway . the smell was very hoppy citrus , pine and something off i could n't place until i tasted it , butter . this beer was quite disappointing and i poured out the remaining 13 or so ounces after i finished my first glass .
eye : looks great , nice rich color-deep copper amber . also has a nice white fluffy head with good retention and lacing .  carbonation is very fine , which leads to a good mouthfeel .

the smell is bold of hops ! wow , this beer is very hoppy with enough malt to counteract the bitterness . it ends up being quite flavorful and works well .  mouthfeel - some creamy smoothnes , well-carbonated .

nose brings toffee , yeast , cherries , dried apricots , chocolate , coffee ice cream , and spices . very complex and wonderous . palate gives us sour cherries , yeast , sweetened iced tea , hints of caramel and toast , and some overall tartness . the mouth has some good , sharp peaks midpalate and the finish is a slow , deliberate fade . a very smooth and clean finish overall .  m : chewy and viscous . if anything , the aging has tempered some of the trademark trainwreck mouthfeel and flavors of base dark lord , so i 'm impressed .
stunning ruby red/black beauty with superb head retention .  nice mouthfeel .

i rarely describe a beer 's color as `` black '' , since most are actually a deep brown , but this poured like motor oil ! i got just over a finger of deep-tan head with decent retention off of my pour .  glass : new belgium globe aging notes : one year at ~60f in the dark bang for the buck ( oz* % / $ ) : 22*6.2/10 = 13.64 a : orange , white lacey head , slightly cloudy from yeast s : horse-y farmhouse brett with hints of orange t : brett dominates ( horse-stable hay , a little dung almost ) , notes of orange m : silky , coating , lingering , pleasant o : worth drinking , a little one-dimensional with the brett .

appearance : very dark brown with a thick , creamy , light tan head with excellent retention and fabulous rings of lacing . the cascade is a thing of beauty !  if there is , then this ska brew is a prime example ... this is the second time i tasted a bottle of this brew . this is an extremely clean tasting brew which is a great quality i enjoy , but where are the hops ? the malt and ( not overwhelming ) bitterness serve as great supporting backbones to what should be a wonderful hoppy aroma and flavor . as it stands , this brew is severely lacking in hop flavor/aroma and comes across as a brew which should be named `` delicate '' rather than `` decadent '' imperial ipa .
very promising . and then : the taste is a bit disappointing after that great smell . good , but not exceptional .  the mouthfeel is medium to full with decent carbonation .

smell : great aromas of licorice and chocolate . overall , the beer is a bit rough around the edges , perhaps from importation , but that is certainly part of its charm .  you do n't get much of the sweet malts you get from the aroma so it really confuses the senses and does n't make for an enjoyable experience mouthfeel is heavy and it sticks to your mouth for minutes .
nice nose of citrus and leather .  pretty much just a tingly water . very smooth and somewhat refreshing beer .

pours a luscious and very tempting opaque sable with a thick , frothy tan head that leaves a fair amount of lacing .  m- a good body to it . good weight and smooth carbonation . there is a strange foamy texture in the finish though .
big ripe banana aroma that is quite pleasing . malts can be noted as well .  pleasantly effervescent mouthfeel .
the clarity on this beer is quite amazing has some very see through character to it . head falls slowly and head bubbles all seem to be a nice pin head size .  crisp , good body overall .
golding hops , great hoppy aroma . some barley initially .  pretty slick mouthfeel .

very good smell . taste- there is a good amount of alcohol and hop bitterness on the palate for this one .  i like the feel with some prickly carbonation and moderately light feel and some creaminess from the head .
a-light amber , hefe , with creamy foam on top , lasting few minutes.appearance is big plus for this beer .  a little sticky and a very bitter aftertaste .

this is mouthwatering and powerful . t : follows the nose . though it is not as powerful as the nose imo . m/d : a full body that is low on the carbonation end .  surprisingly , the sediment was n't hard and i did n't feel a corporeal presence in my mouth . coopers best extra stout was nice on the palate ; softly carbonated and creamy . to tell you the truth , i was a bit disappointed .
smell - pumpkin , nutmeg , cinnamon , malts , brown sugar , spices . smells like liquid pumpkin pie . rather smooth and easy drinking .  m : medium bodied , good amount of carbonation .

carbonating is correct level o : the aroma is great , but the taste is way over bittered with pine .  the body of this beer suits the style with the usual level of north coast drinkability and feel to it . definitely the best feature .
i really like the nose .  smooth and refreshing , light to medium bodied with a slight tingling on the tongue .

when you first pour it , it wafts clean fruity and spicy saison notes . put your nose to the glass and everything intensifies going from mouthwatering to mindnumbing .  m - low carbonation , tiny bubbles , overall feels pretty good .

bottle poured into my terrapin brewery glass a - this has a beautiful color . it pours a golden honey color with a white head that leaves residue as you drink .  light and creamy mouth feel with obviously knocked down carbonation .
s : banana bread , spice & smoke .  m-fairly dry . medium high carbonation .
jet black ... amazing tan head .  mouthfeel is nice and thick and well carbonated . the best part of the beer .

a : this is simply a great looking beer , pours a deep rich carmel with quckly dissapating head s : slight maltiness , and , unexpectedly , some barnyard funkiness , but very faint t : starts off malty but quickly gives way to mild hop bitterness , finsishes pretty dry ( like the dry maltiness of a helles ) m : pretty dry and clean on the palate , although , disapointingly , had almost a watery mouthfeel d : pretty solid sessions lager that would be a good find on tap .  m : moderate carbonation with a decently viscous mouthfeel .

brett funkiness shows its face , but is n't as prominent as in others from similar varieties . like the smell , the brett funkiness is more subtle than others .  m : medium-light body ; moderate carbonation ; smooth and clean mouthfeel .

this brew pours an opaque black color . the head is large , and fluffy with a color of white speckled with tan .  feels slick , not very carbonated , and heavy . alcohol warming is powerfully strong . lacks balance and drinkability .
good strength and good harmony between the components . the nose is awesome , but that 's the only thing that is .  there 's moderate carbonation to it as well .

sticky lacing all the way up the glass , and infinite retention on the eventually short head .  aroma : hops . the crystal hops dominate the aroma . the malt is there , but overpowered by hops . but i do n't taste the balance that an esb should have . the hops weigh far more than the malt in this beer . notes : this tasted like a very good ipa , but did not have the balance i was expecting , for an esb . a great beer , but did n't fit the style as well as i would have liked .
refreshingly bright . taste : hoppy and full of citrus . not quite as balanced as the smell but it 's just as refreshing . the malts definitely bring some yang to the hops yin .  good carbonation .

the aroma has a unique sweet-fruitiness too it that i was not expecting . sweet dates and raisins all-over , a touch of hershey 's chocolate syrup , mildly sweet red fruits and a bunch of heat , which is also a surprise . the aroma is nice and draws you in . the malt is very smokey and fruity ... which seems like a strange combo , but it works .  mouthfeel is pretty good however , with a nice medium feel .

can holiday wine cellar escondido , ca a ( surprisingly ) better than average pour ! clear light goldenrod yellow with a large , persistent white head , and lots and lots of spiderweb lacing down the glass .  m = moderately carbonated . good .
the aroma is great . tons of grapefruit and orange . it 's perfect . wow it 's smooth .  good mouthfeel for this light body but the hops balance the feel .

now that that is out of the way , this is the first time i am reviewing one of there beers a : rich amber color , nice and clear , with a thick foamy white head about half an inch thick that retains well . plenty of carbonation rises from the bottom of the glass as well .  this is my first review and hope it looks well , even if not my favorite beer . leaves a malt taste on the roof and tongue . this is the first scottish ale i 've tried . for comparison , i love dark ales , like ommegang abbey belgium ale and founders breakfast stout . bottle serving .
very powerful sweet aroma . overall : fantastic beer , will definitely get again .  m : full body with mild carbonation ; slightly clinging .

coffee and lemon aromas , very rich and inviting . thick , thick , thick mouthfeel ... molasses , some coffee , and a dense and vaguely cherry flavor . bitter as all get out .  mouthfeel was really good for a light beer . liked the carbonation , and felt richer than it tasted .

s : big coffee and big chocolate with hints of ripe fruit , plums and molassas , very inviting . t/mf : sort of disapointed with this one , maybe it was because i picked it up at world market and who knows how long that thing had been sitting around getting light struck ( even though i picked it out from the back of the display , but who knows what goes on there ) .  it 's very creamy and goes down easy . i 'm really disappointed with this .

bam noire pours a dark brown that approaches black . ruby red highlights can be seen along the edges of my chimay chalice . fully inch of creamy tan head that refuses to die down . tons of thick webbed lacing .  m : tingly carbonation , medium body and refreshing enough .
s : crisp aroma with strong malt presence and hints of flowery hoppiness .  the mouthfeel is the pinnacle of this brew . full-bodied with a dry crisp feel .

aquired through a trade with xpimptasticx , thanks wanted to try for a while a- well , it looks harmless , it looks like a regular dipa except it had hardly any head and no lacing but ... that 's where the similarities stopped s- incredible smell : blood orange , booze , hops on performance enhancing drugs and a faint mango in there t- sweet booze , like a orange hop liqueur or triple sec .  the body is light-medium with good carbonation .

attractive , crystal clear dark bronze hue . topped by a thick , fluffy head that recedes into a persistent one fingered layer .  mouthfeel is pretty good , it has a nice full body , and a good finish .

smell : smells fantastic . sticky , sweet , grapefruity , piney , lemony with a touch of pepper on the back end . i will try again , just because it was so delicious .  mouthfeel was good , with plenty of carbonation and a nice smoothness to it .

poured from my home tap , this one looks great in the glass , with a deep mahogany-amber color and a thick , creamy , foamy , sand-colored head .  the mouthfeel is thick and oily with a mild burn going down . have a bottle of this is all i can handle , which is good because the full bottle would have me a little too buzzed .

probably the biggest dissapointment i 've had in a beer . after the terrific smell , the taste leaves much to be desired . the fruits are still there , but they taste spoiled .  ) the body is a hefty medium , bordering on the truly heavy , with a light moderate carbonation and a fairly chewy feel . harsh .
bottle , a : a dark , black , almost pernicious looking brew , with a beautiful thick tan head .  big body , low carbonation .
this fella was simply awesome . it smelled a lot sweeter than the normal ab , with the oak scent peaking through at the tail end of the nose .  nice mouthfeel for a pale ale .

looks great ! great color , small head .  mouthfeel : well-carbonated , as expected from the heady pour drinkability : low- i could n't get over the tire flavor , which is a shame because every other aspect of the beer was delightful

the haze really detracted from the appearance for me ... ... but it made up for the look with the smell . i honestly smelled this for a few minutes before tasting . the smell was very citrus like , with lots of malt and hop spice .  mouthfeel : medium to light with lively carbonation .

one of the best aromas to come around in a while for me . very decadent chocolate here ... sweet , silky ... you can really smell the cocoa nibs here . a slight hint of hop bitterness as well but this is a very chocolatey aroma . the body is a bit light , and the taste is certainly full of chocolate , but is more of a mix between a sweeter chocolate and a bitter , roasted chocolate . this marriage keeps it from becoming cloying or just being too bitter . what was a pretty sweet and rich beer on the nose was n't quite so on the tongue .  good mouthfeel and texture for a tap beer .

a very nice looking beer .  hints of chocolate up front , but quickly overrun by the massive spices . reminds me of chewing on a mixture of green baking herbs , and about as pleasing on my palate . an interesting brew to say the least , but not one i 'd purchase again .

great bavarian weizen smell of of banana and wheat that unfortunately is not backed up by the flavor which is mildly wheaty with lots of carbonation . this was an ok dunkelweizen but there are much better ones out there .  mouthfeel is quite nice and full .

the nose was spectacular . sweet tar , coffee , chocolate , sappy wood all leap from the glass . molasses and brown sugar are buried within the beautiful , rich nose . overwhelming loads of flavors battling for attention .  yeast , stale hops , a little grass , so boring with a duvel quality ... the taste is equally as bad , bitter toffee , light stale hops , way too much yeast , sour finish . pass .

and all very fresh . smells like being in the woods and breathing in a fresh , brisk , spring air in the morning after it 's been raining . it almost `` bites '' . not as complex in the mouth as it is in the nose though . m-medium bodied . i 'm not normally a fan of hoppy beers but this is so well made that you ca n't help but enjoy it .  a zesty tingle on the tongue at first , nice medium body , but the cinnamon is too much .

taste : something about the taste does n't quite live up to the smell . the taste is a weakened version of the caramel malts in the smell leading into a dark fruit plumlike aftertaste .  the mouthfeel is about right for a stout , a bit thick with low carbonation .
excellent lacing . great looking ipa .  it is bubbly on the tongue and does leave you dry . it 's smooth , but just kind of basic . it 's a very approachable stout .
the smell is loud with touches of sweetness . dead guy has a unique taste , that is over powering at first .  '' the mouthfeel is good . its quite smooth and slightly creamy .

22 oz bomber served in a tradional english pint glass this beer poured a cloudy medium to light brown , with decent 1 inch dense head that left moderate to heavy lacing .  mouthfeel is light and refreshing making the beer overall a decent session beer .

s - lots of hop presence , a strong floral aroma . unfortunately , there 's a lot of alcohol present too . i wished the hops ' taste was as present as their aroma . last but not least , the alcohol , a strong scotch like taste .  has a nice medium to full body with light carbonation .
pours a cloudy yellow with amazing white head that stays through out the whole glass .  the mouthfeel is fine . it is a low/medium bodied beer with good carbonation .

smell is absolutely fantastic ! huge , un-mistakable aroma of honey .  this is my first , of hopefully many reviews , so bare with me . once they were chilled i poured them into a pint glass and sat back with my favorite tv shows a- pours a dark red almost brownish color s- smells like your average porter , did n't really pick up on too much vanilla t- taste more of chocolate or toffee but with hints of vanilla m- pretty smooth , goes down easy without any bite o- not sure if i would buy a case of it , but its good when thrown in a variety pack

the nose is pretty interesting in this one , with a complex aroma profile of orange citrus , funk , light clove and some honey .  m-creamy and good mouthfeel d-did n't finish my 1/5 share of the bomber .
pours a solid black with nice size ( 2 to 3 fingers ) of frothy toffee colored head . wonderful sticky and frothy lacing .  nice creamy mouthfeel .

appearance : beautiful bright amber with a slight haze and thick , foamy off-tan head that leaves lots of lacing . looks like rootbeer float head .  mouthfeel- medium mouthfeel ( for the style ) . carbonation level was perfect for bringing out the bittering hops .

served in a wine glass . a beautiful copper amber color with a thick creamy head .  the mouth feel was thick and creamy ( a high gravity ) overall not a `` session beer '' but one to enjoy and move on .
overly sweet at times , but still nice . if it was n't for the mild astringent smell i 'd give it a 5 .  i liked the mouthfeel , smooth and gentle .

that settles into a nice thick lace covering most of the glass yes it 's a chocolate stout and the aromas defiantly back it up lots of sweet chocolate aromas some earthiness to it along with some hint of roasted malts flavor 's of dark chocolate are dominate not overly sweet with a coffee backbone it 's got this mocha thing going on the mouthfeel is medium to thin would have liked it a little thicker this is really one of the great chocolate stout 's especially for under $ 5 a bomber well worth the experience  mouthfeel is medium/light with good carbonation .

aroma : heavenly . roasted malt , chocolate , a hint of coffee , and i detected a hint of whiskey aroma that was very pleasant . taste and mouthfeel : slightly chewy but not quite creamy .  moderate hops with lots of body , almost chewy .
it smells great but does n't live up to the smell .  carbonation was crisp for a medium body .

the smell dances on the nose , full of floral and hops .  smooth with a creamy but dry finish . i walked away thinking that the `` smoked vanilla , coffee , and birch '' was meant to be flavor descriptors rather than actual ingrediants . all of these elemtns were way too weak to be appreciated for what other beers can do with them . call it a single , nix the mention of the adjuncts , and this beer would be alright .

s - mmm , what a good smelling beer . delicious smell , and a lot of it .  mouthfeel is medium bodied and crisp . good carbonation , but the overall trainwreck of flavor in the brew makes this one hard to take down .

this beer gives you a great looking glass ... smell- ... and a great smell ! incredible smell , might be the best smelling ipa i 've had so far . really nice batch . smells like a field of flowers and with its distinct flowery smell that might remind some of opening a pot of honey .  it has a very soft mouthfeel , a little like soda to be honest and you can barely notice the alcohol .

tons of mango on the nose . sweet and tart mango flesh with an herbal , citrusy hop note buried under the fruit . a great nose , i really like the fruit character . this was fairly enjoyable and very easy to drink , but i would n't go out of my way to try it again .  m- good carbonation and substantial body , not bad here .

pours dark clear copper with a very thick , pillowy white head .  not really much going on that i can discern m : this is one category where this beer does well with a nice light feel and pleasant carbonation d : why would i want another ?
smells great . taste . a decent iipa .  the feel was pleasantly smooth , but was unimpressed with the drinkability as seemed to reform a head with every drink .
very lovely appearance . aroma : roasted malt , oak , dark chocolate , molasses , hints of brown sugar and coffee .  mouthfeel is medium , carbonation average-high with some pleasant warming feel .

smell is very strong , very tasty , and actually has a mouthwatering , rich coffee character to it . start is somewhat sweet but very oaky and heady .  mouthfeel is thick and smooth , no watery sensation at all .
big chocolate smell , hint of coffee .  mouthfeel was real good .

above average head retention & lacing s : lemony with white pepper & orange peel t : follows the nose , also some breadyness & candi sugar , apple peels & general spiceyness up front . finishes with apple peel , lemony & herbal hops & a lovely spiceyness & just a bit of grapefruit at the apex mf : medium bodied , lively carbonation , very nice balance superb drinkabilty i could stay on this all night !  as i drink more my palate adjusts but it does n't ever really get over the off flavors m - pretty thick , not too carbonated , nice mouth coating qualities d - burnt coffee does not go down very well , plust the thickness of the beer limits my ability to quaff this completely i like coffee , i like stouts , and i like a lot of coffee stouts ( new glarus and founders breakfast stout for instance ) .

it 's wonderful . t- initial malts , some yeast , bread and biscuity notes , and strong warming alcohol .  smells of raisins , a hint of semi-sweet choc ? mouthfeel is nice , thick , syrupy & smooth ... the way i want a barleywine .

smells absolutely wonderful ... pungent aroma of hops all the way ... piney , citrusy hops and i 'm loving it ... i want to smell this all night ... terrific blend of piney/grapefuit hops and sweet malts.. thought this was going to be a hop bomb all the way which would have been fine but i 'm surprised at the balance on this one .  very rich flavor of dark malts and smoke , with hints of coffee and chocolate as well . the finish is almost all smoke , much too intense for my liking . ive used this many times in making caribou pot roasts in the crockpot . they even have a recipe on their website , which is delicious . i was informed that this beer has won more medals at the great american beer festival than any other beer , quite an accomplishment .
very heady pour . nice lacing .  mouthfeel is medium , well carbed , nice on all fronts but where it needs to be . big failure , in my opinion .

really nice nose on this . a big whiff of belgian yeast , revealing dark fruits and a faint hint of very bitter cocoa . after a few nose dives in this one i 've become a bit used to the yeast smell and richer chocolate notes are revealed as well as a faint alcohol aroma .  the mouthfeel was sticky and thick . there was tight and crisp carbonation that was nice .
s- it smells of pumpkin pie very strong spices . t- it 's a very sweet beer .  the body and carbonation levels are appropriate .

the head recedes smells great , rummy , oak-y , sugar cane , caramel , coconut , spicy , very layered and complex nose . there 's a little hop bitterness in the taste but all else is overpowered by the rum and oak taste .  m - nice average mouthfeel .

a- pours a good looking deep brown with a little light let in around the edges . a big 1.5 fingered mocha colored head leaves some good lacing on the side of the glass all the way down .  fine mouthfeel , nothing objectionable , but it 's not a stand-out lager either .

this is a fairly average offering in liquor stores round the calgary area , but it is one i can never pass up : this is a very flavourful beer by any means , though it is the most mass-produced of the scotch ales . i love the hue of amber/red glow to this beer . the colour itself is almost appetising . the aroma is my favourite part of the beer . sweet candy , or blueberry gum , rich sweet malt that evokes red licorice , candy cane , sweet bread , sourdough , and other sweet confectionaries . the taste is not as full as the aroma . this is a sweet offering from the time it hits your tongue to the time it leaves your breath : up front there are cherries and irish-red tastes . the hops are there , adding a touch of balance and grass to the finish . the mouthfeel is well carbonated , full , and heavy .  medium mouthfeel .

huge , foamy beige head that leaves several lace rings smeared down the glass . kinda like the glass is wearing a striped shirt .  i have the mom version the head was initially strong , though sudsy and it fell quickly . carbonation is plentiful from the surface of the brew come hop aromas -- minty and herbal -- and coriander . it does n't smell as though an authentic yeast was used , which fits my preconceived notions for rogue 's methods the flavor confirms my american yeast suspicions . light fruity flavors , strong hop contributions , though little spice .
excellent straw gold with a nice thick foamy white head and amazing lacing .  m - light to medium carbonation with medium carbonation .

has a clean fresh smell . very soothing . makes me think of lazy walks through a hop field in the belgian countryside .  palate : very enjoyable . great , smooth , and light on the throat . it would be stellar with cheese .

good lacing & head retention s : intense almost burnt caramel & malt & some alcohol t : smokey caramel & a little aclohol up front , then a hint of cherry & oak . finishes with dryness , a slight smokeyness & a praline sweetness mf : sticky rich body with excellent carbonation & balance drinks good , but 2 would be about my limit .  mouthfeel - explodes in the mouth with carbonation , yet maintaining a noteworthy smoothness afterwards . the body is sturdy but not overly big .

s - impressive ! i 've smelled hoppy beers from a few feet away , but this has a spicy malt boozy smell that almost fills a room when the the bottle is uncapped .  the mouth feel is pretty good and when ice cold very easy to drink .

a dark ruby-brown , not quite opaque , with a 1 finger tan head . i guess that i can get behind some smoked malt , and it is n't too strong in this one and i am sure nicely balanced , but i love schwarzbiers and this one takes what i like away from them . a nice toasty maltiness with some balanced hop bitterness , like a savory version of stout .  it is carbonated well . it is crisp and goes down smooth .

a - quite a beautiful opaque orange body with finger hight white head . s - very malty ( strange for a hefe ) , average yeast aroma for the style and very spicy and sweet aromas .  m - thick , syrupy , smooth , a bit refreshing .
s-this beer has one of the most pleasant aromas that i have smelt in a long time .  it is very finely carbonated , giving a tickle on the tongue .
pretty nice looking beer .  medium feel in my mouth with good carbonation .

a : a much darker brown than most brown ales . poured a thick creamy espresso colored head with good carbonation showing .  m : medium body , low to medium carbonation . smooth and creamy . d : something does n't quite work for me .

appearance : pours an attractive caramel sunburst with a solid 2 finger dirty butter crown that shows moderate retention and good lace .  mouthfeel : really thick and chewy . this part would be enjoyable in a good-tasting brew .
appearance & gt ; looks like an giant-sized perfect pull of espresso .  it had a really good mouthfeel .
nose reveals a unique combo coffee beans , dark fruits , brown sugar and roasting malts .  m- medium in body and good carbonation .

score : 89 appearance : pours a dark red-brown color with plenty of opaque-ish ruby highlights with three fingers of cream-colored head . excellent lacing , and the head really stick around -- if not apparent by the photo ( proprietary ) .  mouthfeel - nice body , pretty crisp .

s - easily the beer 's most remarkable feature . wonderful aroma of blackberries and blueberries with a slightly sourish tint . t - although it does n't quite live up to the aroma in terms of complexity , this is still quite good . early palate some sour dark fruits are balanced out by a moderate caramel flavor .  the carbonation feels pretty crisp .

smells wonderful . cloves , banana , caramel , fruitiness . nice comfortable warmth from the alcohol . not something i could see drinking a ton of at a sitting , but delightful as a one off .  mouthfeel is fine . medium bodied with the right amount of carbonation .

the smell is really quite wonderful ; nearly perfect . the roast and sweetness are the perfect marriage of complimentary elements .  syrupu sweetness , not cloying , with hop dryness in the blend . this is what imperial pilsner is supposed to be ? what happened to the pilsner part ?
beautiful looking beer .  mouthfeel is light bodied with good carbonation .
copper pour , good lacing and head here .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . fair carbonation .

sweet tropical notes , mainly mango accompany a major amount of hops in the scent . there was a lot i liked but overall very good .  saccharine all the way . how can you add fake sweetener to bier ? the beer is best described as diet raspberry 7 up . i already go to the gym 4 times a week so that i can drink all the fabulous beer i desire . flavors were overwhelmingly sweet , and tart . complexion was shirley temple , and body was crisp .

the nose is fantastic , being all floral spicy hop . the flavour is terrific too , delivering a spicy , sappy , resiny , sticky malt and hop elixir .  m : very nicely carbonated for this type of beer .
it 's an awesome smelling stout !  oily mouthfeel with next to no carbonation . quite thick and heavy , coating every area of the mouth .

the aroma is particularly good on this stout ; there is a lot of fresh blueberry aroma , along with nutty , chocolaty , and yeasty aromas to compliment . the beer pours with a very deep black color and a head that stays around the rim of the glass leaving a swirl on top of the beer . from the smell i expected this to be very fruity , which in it 's own right it is , however not in an alcipop sort of way . flavors that hit the tongue right off the bat are a little overwhelming but very nice to pick through .  it 's still fairly sturdy though , and carbonation is low but solid .

a : huge , creamy , tan head with insane lacing . very dark red-brown , but not utterly opaque . it certainly looks impressive . s : surprisingly neutral .  very tame malt , very little hops , and weak alcohol that 's more like aftershave . definitely not over-carbonated , the texture fits the style . actually the best element of this beer .
pours a deep brown color with a thick , brown head into my glass . great presentation here .  mouthfeel : trademark lager crispness and smoothness , light bodied and dry .
really great nose !  m - pretty thin and definitely refreshing .
guinness pours ruby black with a beautiful creamy white head that lingers for quite a while .  flavor was very strong ginger , and this made the mouthfeel quite crisp and pretty good .

the nose is very good and very belgiany . you get the nice coriander and clove smells , the nice sweet malts , the candied sugars , and some yeasty florals too .  smells sour , big nodes of orange and very tart lemon juice . there 's a bit of a funky hop in there , as well . no real spice of which to speak , nor any hint of wheat . very sour , almost cidery . starts more tart , like lemon juice , moves into a dryer , white wine middle , and ending on a more of a light , semi-sweet orange sour . a unique beer , to say the least . could benefit from a bit of something at the end , but is drinkable enough as it is .
s - incredible aromas in this beer . even if is a lambic , the smells are very fine and not off-flavours .  mouthfeel : medium thickness , almost chewy , minimal froth .

the first thing i noticed about this beer was the strong and wonderful flower aroma . quite spicy and with a very strong odor of coriander . quite a nice smelling saison in the same class as hennepin .  m - great carbonation , finishes well .

the smell was slightly chocolate . 2007 bottle 02/23/2008 beautiful smell like gourmet chocolates , an amazing improvement over the last year . this beer is a really good example of a cellar-worthy beer . 2006 vintage 01/10/09 smells malty grains , some chocolate , tastes good and probably ca n't get much better .  adequate carbonation .

smell is pretty dang good . smells like cherries and more cherries .  char davies , the artist in 1998 , made a fully interactive immersive visual/aural virtual artwork called ephemere , which furthers the work begun in osmose started in 1995 and displayed in the national gallery of canada in ottawa on june 26 , 1998. who cares ? this beer is almost close to a champaign ( and i would think that the yeast probably is champaign ) . also there is bitterness , which is nice to know that at least there are some hops to the so called beer . it is not advisable to use apples with fermenting , as the yeast creates funky flavors from apples , but this is much better than expected . although i would not want to drink this beer on a regular bases , thus low score on drinkability , i think it has a great taste like a grandsmith apples i use to eat as a kid .
overall , this beer is very sweet smelling . t : medicinal hops , somewhat acidic and citrusy .  the mouth-feel is thick almost porter-like with the cooling of the alcohol evaporation .

a-pours a deep amber ... .little head.. s-nice sticky sweet aroma of caramel is most evident ... also some mild chocolate notes ... .the more i smell this the more impressed i become ... .some dark fruitiness is there in the way of plums ... .also some very mild spicy black pepper ... t-the dark fruits lead the way here ... black cherries , plums , perhaps a little bit of raisins ... the spicy peppery impression blends nicely ... the caramel is strongly evident too and borders on cloying ... not tasting the chocolate but it is definitely there in the aroma . i was jacked up hearing this was the style chosen for this year as i have been mildly disappointed with the selections in the past five years ... this is a decent dubbel ... i immediately bought two six-packs of this when i saw it and i anticipate purchasing more .  mouthfeel was good and very drinkable ; however , it was slightly bitter ... something i was n't expecting this to have considering the malts .

first of all this is an amazing looking beer . a nice pale orange , hazy , with a huge rocky white head . great retention and that belgian lace that i love .  the drink is carbonated a little more than average as well . mf- very crisp beer with little or no after taste . one of the smoother beers around .
the scent is a wonderful molasses .  mouthfeel was smooth , light , though i do n't know i 'd go as far as crisp .
lots of sour funk upon popping the cork . great sour funkiness with sour apples and pears . also get some very floral notes as well .  m : it has a nice mouthfeel .

a very strong and pleasant aroma . tastes light honey sweetness and clove up front with perhaps a bit of orange zest fading to bready malts with trace hop bitter finish .  m - crisp and refreshing o - overall pretty meh .

strong aroma consisting of citrus bananas , cloves , vanilla and an overall strong alcohol presence . there 's a lot there . the mouthfeel is pretty full although something seems a bit off with a tangy , somewhat sour , very yeasty , citrus ( oranges and bananas ) flavor . i 've had other tripels recently that are better , karmeliet and chimay cinq cents come to mind , but this is a better beer than i original though .  mouthfeel is light ( duh ) , but not too thin , and nicely carbonated , giving it a bit of a zip , but not too effervescent . probably the best part of the beer .
s - great smell . dark fruits such as raisins and plums maybe . o - good over all .  good carbonation .

the nose has a nice strong hoppy and fruity-peachlike aroma .  the mouth is thick and malty . as far as drinkability , i have to say that i would be really happy to have one of these if i was alive 4000 years ago but for now i 'm going to have to go for something else .
simply great to look at .  body is light and crisp and finishes clean .
this beer pours beautifully with an amber-copper hue and a frothy white head of at least three fingers . excellent lacing . can see yeast particles floating in the glass .  medium mouthfeel .

ahh , maudite . a beautiful beer from a beautiful brewery . pours a dark , stained oak or cherry colour . nice , 2 1/2 finger froth head that clings to the glass .  very smooth without being too full bodied .
lots of lacing sticks to the glass as well , damn good looking beer .  mouthfeel is crisp and a little sizzly . refreshingly light bodied and clean .

fairly strong aroma and inviting . t : definitely citrus forward , although the flavors are a bit more muted than the nose lead me to believe .  full body , syrupy like samichlaus . very similar tastes and mouthfeel .

the nose is great , with notes of roasted barley , chocolate malt , and a little bit of coffee . has some creaminess as well which is very nice . the beer is medium bodied , but is a bit light on carbonation .  m/d ) very soft mouthfeel .

quite close to black with a fine textured tan head . i love the way the beer horizon ( the separation between the beer and the head ) looks . it stayed that way throughout the beer .  there 's also just a hint of citrus from the orange peel ( or orange oil extract ) the smooth mouthfeel and moderate body is not unlike that of a german hefeweizen .
appearance : very good . the beer pours with a pillowy white head and produces above-average lacing . the colour is an appealing orange-amber .  m - a fairly heavy mouthfeel with all the sweetness .

i smell a fruity and floral characteristic along with a strong citrusy hop overtone . this is a classic ipa and the brewers knew what they were doing with this batch .  mouthfeel : soft creaminess , light to medium carbonation , with a medium to full body .
i gave it a good rating for smell just because it 's so damn unique . taste is sweet malts , some hops and a bitter finish .  m - crisp and decent carbonation .

lovely , bright cherry red color ... head is large at first , simmers down quickly ... aroma : mmmmm ... .complex ! quite a rich and invigorating aroma , i postpone consumption to prolong my time drinking it deep into the nose ... really nice !  good body and mouthfeel .

what a crazy story ... a - a tall pour creates totally huge cascading that ends in a three+ finger head with awesome retention .  light-medium caramel malt sweetness up front , continued in the middle with a hint of earthy hop bitterness , finishing with a more of the same . medium mouthfeel .
aroma is excellent ; spicy and piny .  the mouthfeel is very smooth , with fine/sharp bubbles .

12 oz can into a tall pilsner - fridge - 2010 appearance : pours a dark brown , but not quite black color with orange highlights . the head is a towering 3.5 '' in my glass and shows great retention .  mouthfeel - good smoothness , a medium body on par with the style , crisply carbonated .

highly envigorated light brown head of fine bubbles that left behind a nice lacing on the pour .  m- really good carbonation , low abv and the nearly great sweet/tart balance make it actually react quite nicely with the mouth .
sweet marshmallow nose . banana/clove presence is notable . massive . sweet with spice and alcohol warming .  light body and nice and creamy . moderate carbonation .

cranberry nose with traces of brett-like peppery suede funkiness ( either from the kombucha or actual brett ) , black cherry , dried peaches , honey , and cider . it 's one of the most distinct and delicious smelling beers i 've come across in a while . it 's clever enough to inspire analysis , while still being relatively drinkable , in spite of the co2 struggles .  mouthfeel is creamy and crisp .

) , 2011 scorched crimson brown color ; fairly dark . the head does recede but retention is solid and there is a good bit of lace .  the mouthfeel is moderately thick and full for a pilsner and has a creamy texture . the citrusy hops create a crisp bite towards the end .

s : fragrant yeast character , a lot of banana , sweet malt . t : light caramel hits at first and then melds into a lot of banana , with hints of molasses .  this is a medium bodied , well carbonated beer .
