pours a murky borwn with some red hue with absolutely no head to speak of here but was expected , great aromas of cocoa some sugar cookie dough and orange with some noticable nuttieness.a real sipping brew here and fruity to the hilt big orange flavors along with some sour cherry and i have to say it does have this vodka and cranberry flavor to it the first i have ever experienced that in a beer , as the beer warms a real nutty presence come out as well.a nice before bed beer very enjoyable and exremely complex .  the body is nice and thick , with a flavorful malt profile : sweet medium caramel malts with a bit of roast character . hops , by the way , are almost nonexistent , which would n't be bad if not for the oxidation , which makes the faint floral flavor seem dull . overall not bad , but has the same type of oxidized or maybe just oversparged flavor common to other corporate breweries like gordon-biersch .
s - very lovely . a nice mix of sweet citrus fruits and hops . nice .  the body is somewhere between medium and full , with a creamy mouthfeel .

roasty , some coffee and chocolate . decadent .  the body is on the full side , though not quite as much as most stouts ( i suppose increased attenuation should have been expected with the switch in yeast strain ) , and has a solidly low key carbonation .
came out of the tap a deep brown , almost black color .  m - solid and full , with good carbonation .

a- pours a creamy 2 finger tan head over a black body . if this was labeled nut brown , i 'd be thrilled .  the aftertaste lingers nicely , and the mouthfeel is firm . full bodied and smooth , but lacking an extra punch .

the first impression i got when i took a long deep breathe in the the glass was sweet malt and chocolate , oh my god , chocolate ! it seems as though i was sniffing a fresh glass of dark chocolate milk . it just smells creamy and smooth . the taste was roasted malt and grains combined with the chocolate .  a - opaque black color with a small head that disappears quickly s - rich chocolate-like aroma , mild yeast esters , some smokiness , no hop perceived t - roasted malt flavor dominates , some yeasty esters and mild hop flavors take a secondary role , very gentle mild hop finish with some lingering smokiness m - smooth creamy medium body with moderately low carbonation d - this is a decent enough oatmeal stout . the head and retention is disappointing , but the smell , taste and mouthfeel are acceptable .

4.5 s : bourbon and maple come through most prominently . oak and vanilla next . as i sort of expected , most of the wheat gets lost in the previously mentioned powers . i say the bourbon level is just right . 3.0 t : again , maple and bourbon dominate only this time it may be too forceful .  mouthfeel was nice - weizenbock like . bananas , black beans , chile peppers and/or pepper jack cheese with some creamyness amidst the carbonation . interesting , no doubt , and worth seeking out if you want something really different .

longneck into a cascazilla pint glass purchased at the brewery : ( a very cool glass with some red hops on it ) a - copper/red hue with about a 1/2 inch head that quickly died down to an outer ring and no lacing - maybe it was the glass ' fault s - straight up pine and citrus from the hops , also some malt sweetness in there t - a burst of hops to start with . taste like west coast hops , and not too bitter , probably lots of late mid/late hop additions and dry-hopping , as there is a great hop flavor and aroma to this beer without too much bitterness . good supporting role by the malt to keep the hops in check . awesome job combining the characteristics of a red ale and an ipa .  the mouthfeel is very light bodied and good for the class .

s. plenty going on here in this one . d. a very good porter from left hand . the combination of aromas is brilliant . the taste is lighter than its 5.8 % abv .  mouthfeel good . creamy and subtle carbonation . cant complain about this .

a quick swirl brings nice crimson flashes to the glass , quite amazing ... the aroma flows to my nostrils from feet away .  the mouthfeel was good , but the drinkability hass to be chopped down due to the smell and the taste of this beer .

the aroma is strong thick sweet and syrupy . including pine , alcohol , vanilla and oak . overall it 's very nice , i 'd like to see how it would do with another year or two to tame the hops down .  mouth is no complaints , it 's low-medium body with relatively high carbonation .

frickin ' a beautiful . deep and black , medium head of nice and tight dark tan bubbles . no effort required to get it and even going vigorously on the pour it seems like there 's not a crazy amount of head . beautiful .  soft prickly carbonation does cleans the pallet , of this light to medium body beer with moderate astringency and warming alcohol .

nose is fantastic ! uniquely fruity , like a cranberry-mango chutney . hops are detectable and make this a complex sniffer , probably the best smelling tripel i have ever laid nostrils upon . fruit levels take on the best from belgium , impressive . very nice brew , might be my favorite that i have had so far from the bruery .  m : creamy and sticks to the mouth for awhile .
the beer smells or peat and smoke with a hint of chocolate and molasses . it tastes and smells delicious and really is a good example of a scotish ale .  m - it was very crisp and sharp .

pours a deep black with a seriously dark finger of head , may be the darkest head i have seen ... the nose is interesting to say the least ... not what i expected .  medium mouhfeel with some carbonation . smooth and buttery feel . pretty dry finish .

s : great smelling beer . c-hops and american malts . potent nose . d : great beer , absolutely delicious , with the delicate touch of a masterful brewer .  the mouth is pretty nice , feels rich but easy to drink .
this beer pours a very bright yellow sundrenched tint that just beckons to be drunk .  m - tongue ripping bitterness . medium to full body and tingly carbonation to go with it . good .

poured the 22 oz bottle smells amazing , looks great , with good carbination the flavor let me down , the initial impression was stellar but followed by a light bodied lingering hop flavor that doesnt seem to justify the body style of the beer .  taste is mild but the mouthfeel is full pleasantly full and quite nice .

aroma is very inviting with apple , pear , and an awesome yeastiness . the taste is n't as fruity and glorious as the incredible aroma but it is nice and earthy . there is a great toastiness to it and great caramel , bread and diacetyl butter flavor .  mouthfeel : full-bodied with a strong , expressive carbonation .

the aroma was amazing , especially for a beer of such humble stature . chocolatey rich to the extreme . steaming hot fudge instantly came to mind . sweet and creamy with strong notes of vanilla and a touch of oak . dark chocolate came through strong up front . black coffee was noticeable in the center . this was a smooth and tasty beer with an aroma that was to die for . at 5.7 % abv , this porter was surprisingly drinkable .  light body with good carbonation .

absolutely wonderful ! t : unfortunately , does n't quite live up to the aroma .  bottled under license by the cheval blanc in montreal . light golden ale witha medium head that did not disapear too quickly . the honey taste is very discreet . i could recognize the usual taste of malt from the cheval blanc . enjoyable but not exceptionnal
this beer is beautiful . red/amber color with a thick rocky head that clings to the side of the glass . head disappears fast though .  m - pretty thick , smooth and a bit refreshing .

smells great . big , overripe tropical fruit and citrus with a little bit of grass underneath . i actually coughed and spilled some while pouring and thought , `` man , that smells awesome ! '' while cleaning it up . still good , just a letdown after the nose .  nice lively mouthfeel .

lovely sugary sweetness , rich chocolate , and coffee nose & # 8230 ; the bouquet shows excellent depth , very inviting . the palate is less enthusiastic . fairly complex & # 8230 ; excellent hops influences at the finish , it builds on the coffee flavors nicely .  ) and is a deep rich molasses s : once again , may have been too cold for phenols to waft up t : slightly sweet really tasty m : nice and cold d : pour me another

smell : smell is impressive to say the least . huge oaky brandy smells , with rasberry , chocolate and an imposing roasted malt presence . taste : everything good about the smell is in the taste , although unfortunately it still has a bit of a raw bite to it .  the mouthfeel is good ; slightly thick and very smooth . however , it is a little bubble and will sting the recesses of your mouth .
very nice start of a semi-grainy and fully malted pilsner barley . delicious .  m : smooth and medium bodied .
it had a great smoky aroma of smoked wood , smoked malts , olives , dark chocolate , roasted coffee beans , and just the slightest touch of caramel at the finish .  m : a nice , medium body .
the smell has dark roasted coffee beans , figs , dates , madiera and some yeast .  it is medium bodied and smooth in the mouth .

my first impression was that it was surprisingly bitter for a beer that advertises `` creamy and smooth '' . the colour is auburn ( tetley 's tea , anyone ? ) , with a creamy head .  served in a pint glass mug a : pours a clear bronze color with about an inch of thick head s : a smell provides a nice rye scent with a very sweet undertone contributed by the honey addition t : very nice smooth tasting beer , has a slight hint of honey and perhaps a slight rye note but other than that there isnt much to comment on , smooth and slightly sweet but thats about it m : very smooth in the mouth with a slight bite on the tongue as it is drank d : high level of drinkability , very subdued taste that is great for a hot summer day but leaves the drinking looking for more otherwise .

subsequent sips bring forth strong chocolate notes mixed with a nice bitterness.the aroma a each sip is truly fantastic . finished nice and creamy with a strong bitter note present .  medium mouthfeel .

s : a rich citrus , piney hop aroma is released when you open the bottle and once in the glass that 's all you can smell . sweet grapefruit - fantastic smell . t : unfortunately the smell seems more powerful than the taste which seems a bit on the light side .  mouthfeel is nice , actually - light bodied , spritzy carbonation .

nose is quite complex with some really nice notes of oak , vanilla , chocolate , roasted malt , and some light coffee . the taste does n't mix these together quite as well , but is still tasty . great feel coming from all different directions and quite drinkable for the big beer that it is .  velvety . good amount of carbonation .
not very much in the way of hops , nothing really stands out . i loved the nose , but the taste let me down just a bit .  good carbonation .

thought this beer had a really nice color . an excellent color . i 'm thinking mahogony , but i 'm not sure exactly what color that ... but i 'm thinking like a deep deep wood varnish color ... really nice .  m- decent carbonation , light and airy .

this pours out the same deep orange color as the last one with the same solid fluffy head , lacing , etc . as appearance goes , there is nothing left to improve upon .  could be a bit less carbonated .

a clear , dark amber , dark caramel colored beer emerges and is topped by a super creamy , white head . lacing is so dense i can barely see through the glass .  m : felt good going down had a nice thick feel to it .
has a nice aroma of sweet carmely malt and spicey hops .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

very nice . i was frightened from all the soy sauce talk , but the aroma really sucked me in and eased my fear .  all right taste , almost neutral , with a bit of skunkiness . goes down very smoothly .

a nice blend is dominated by spices and finishes with a pumpkin quality . overall a great blend of scents . mostly spice flavor with only a minor pumpkin quality .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel was pretty good overall .

bottle : poured a medium amber color ale with super big foamy head with great retention and good lacing .  i 'm not sure what a `` baltic '' porter is supposed to taste like ; but this one is quite different from most porters i 've had . sweet molasses aroma that is greater than any chocolate or mocha that might be found . a strong level of metal present also . sweet , almost like brandy . reminds me far more of a double bock than a porter . i can not detect any hops at all . too sweet for me , making it more one-dimensional without any complexity .
very nice aroma . hmm , not sure about the taste .  decent carbonation , neither too intrusive nor too laid back .
pours a golden orange with lots of suspended floaties . it has a huge spongy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  m- medium bodied with a decent carbonation level .
it has a wonderful smell of yeast and citrus .  m/d : a medium body with good carbonation .

s : i found the strong tart raspberry with a faint mandarin-orange nose to be both unique and satisfying . not overpowering , like some over-the-top fruit beers .  the mouthfeel is slightly creamy and very enjoyable . this drinks nicely . there is a lot going for this though , the mouthfeel in particular .
there is a strong , heavy caramel smell to the beer .  it had a medium bodied with good carbonation .
a : dark black , thick brown head that dissipates slowly .  feels right in body , but the taste is just off .

drank it on draft at legacy and at reading country club i have also had three cases of it made for them by the lion in bottles it is smooth favorful light and not biteing , nice head great smell very refreshing to drink it is a amazing product that they have made it is very nice to just sit and drink again and again .  m : pretty creamy and lightly carbonated . easy to swallow a mouthful .
the nose on this thing is awesome . complex sweet fruits , sultanas and figs , some ginger , brown sugar , earth and alcohol .  m : good mouthfeel .

smell : this is an outstanding smelling beer . floral , hoppy and piney with a hint of grapefruit and orange . overall : if this beer tasted as good as it smelled and felt as good as it looked it would be one of the best in the world . it is still pretty good , but not what it could have been .  being of fan of bocks , i was fully prepared to love this ubiquitous doppelbock . it was kind of sweet and malty , smelled great , felt nice going down -- quite satisfying . there was a slightly funky smell to it , and an even funkier taste . i thought that was more common in highly hopped beers . at $ 10 for the four pack , i hate to try it again for fear of wasting my hard-earned beer money .

many thanks to drweizen for sending this in his shipment of holiday beers ... the beer is quite carbonated ( with a slow pour , i got half head ! ) and leaves a gorgeous lace pattern on my glass .  this beer has noticeable viscosity and a big thick feel . minimal carbonation .

the smell came off fruity , flowery , and hoppy . great aromas ! !  t : slight sweet taste , but does not taste much like anything actually , fairly bland m : smooth , light on carbonation . d : mouthfeel was nice , went down easily enough just did n't care for the smell or taste of the beer .

great theatre watching the tall head overtaken by the liquid and the color is near black and near opaque .  recommended by bert from bert 's better beers . smells like dark chocolate , burn caramel , and vanilla -- sort of like an chocolate chip oatmeal cookie . smooth roast malt , dare i say a tad burnt . there 's a mild pharmaceutical character in back that i 'm not a fan of . i drank half this bottle one night and the second half the following afternoon .

the fluid is dark caramelly clear with a huge three finger head of off white , which eventually receded to a half finger width with lacing still attached to the glass .  m - lighter side of heavy , pretty smooth .
the smell is truly incredible , and the taste is malty and pleasant .  medium mouthfeel .

appearance : light yellow in color with a large soapy head that stays around the whole time . the head on this beer is remarkable and deserves recognition . at first the beer was fairly clear but later i swirled some yeast in and the beer became cloudy .  m - full bodied and chewy with a moderately dry finish with some alcohol noticeable .
an extremely pretty looking beer . dark brown in color , close to black .  pleasantly carbonated on the palate , with a dry finish .

& raspberry , great if weird scents going on here ... t : raspberry , plums , figs , & strawberry jam verging om pop tart filling , very weird , plus leafy hops up front .  the flavor is a bit better as the taste of both a good belgian tripple and a solid ipa can both be percieved ; however , the flavors compete for dominance instead of blending harmoniously . i think the problem here is that tripple is a big , expressinve beer . with exit 4 the subtle flavors are masked behind a second layer of bold expressiveness . i love the brewery for pushing the envelope and i look forward to buying the next release in the series . with innovation like this , flying fish is sure to hit a huge winner sooner than later .
appearance : hazy golden orange . effervescent body with a thick pillowy , white head that just wo n't quite .  m=fairly thin , a little medium . watery .
pours a dark brown black with a large creamy brown head that retains well and laces the glass .  body is extremely light and spritzy ; refreshing and very inoffensive in character .

looks like a perfect ris : pitch black with barely no brown around the edges , even when held up to a bright light . an incredibly creamy , frothy and sticky dark khaki head forms and sticks around for quite a bit . impeccable .  the mouthfeel is medium-light bodied with a watery texture , and a little too much carbonation .

liquid is a dark amber topped with a thick finger of brown foam and dense and substantial lacing . carbonation is also very prevalent , making this model stand out much more than previous years . visually stunning .  a bit bland for the style . body is a bit like soda water , and fades really fast .

served in a pilsner glass a : pours a deep mahogany color that looks thick . pours with very thick white head and leaves considerable lacing s : very sweet smelling brew possibly of cherries .  lack of carbonation , and this beer 's thin , watery mouthfeel combine to make a less-than-awesome drinking experience .
great retention , and lace as one might expect from a northwest ipa .  the carbonation sort of ruins the mouthfeel from the can and hides the taste .

pours a luscious peach/dark gold color with a substantial , fluffy , two-finger head that exhibits excellent retention and lacing .  m : thin and watery , very little carbonation , too thin to be cloying , but i 'd rather this beer be full bodied .

a- pours an absolutely crystal clear light orange with a one finger white head .  was excited to see this one.. but again newcastle has let me down again ... on the bottle it says `` blood red ale '' .. it pours a reddish-brown color.. smells a little funky ... way too carbonated for my liking .
pours a two finger , cream head that slowly fades to a thin layer leaving a good lace . clear deep amber color .  carbonation a bit high . fails on this point . d- easy going macro lager .

sterling scarlet brown under a large canopy of tan .  the most negative parts of this beer include the smell and mouthfeel . the smell is pretty bland , not giving any info on the beer itself and the mouthfeel seems watered down after witnessing the color of the beer .
pours a glowing hazy golden with a thick creamy head that retains well and laces the glass .  3.0 m thin .

pours into 't hofbrouwerijke chalice a deep dark chocolate brown with a huge , i mean huge , light brown head . this is a head that just wo n't quit . it 's stunning .  the flavor was both too light and 'way too bitter for a pils . it was watery and lacking in aroma . not much foam - what there was disappeared quickly . the word i 'd use to describe this beer is `` insubstantial . ''
pours golden orange with a thick white head , impressive retention , good lace .  m : thin , watery , light-bodied , not something you 'd expect with the smell .
pours black as night with a brown head . definitely looks the part of a big ris .  m : water thin , light side of champagne-like carbonation .

dark brown head over a black body . there were tons of good stouts opened at the tasting , but this rose to the top of the heap . lovely stuff  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a fizzy carbonation .

on tap stone brew co. escondido , ca a dark , hazy orange with golden yellow edges and a small white cap atop . messy , spiderweb lacing around the glass . a very beautiful glass of beer !  caramel , coffee and cocoa are there , but overall balance is towards the dry and bitter mouthfeel - 2.0 lightly carbonated , bordering on flat and a little watery .
poured into a large wine glass , very dark , giant creamy brown head ( very enticing ) .  m - light bodied , very thin feeling , and very little carbonation o - not too impressed with this beer .
the color is a deep , very pretty dark amber . this is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel on both is not much , just clear water with a bit of beer bubbles .

beer is a dark , dark color , with just the slightest hints of ruby at the edges and a coffee colored head . beautiful to look at , and almost as nice to drink .  mouthfeel is similar to that of water , not much to it .
jet black in color with a large milk chocolate head .  mouthfeel : thin and watery ( or slim-bodied , which sounds more positive ) , medium-low carbonation ( too low for the style ) .

a : pours a hazy golden with a thick bubbly white head that slowly faded into a thick film that lasted the whole beer through and left an incredible fuzzy sheet of solid lacing down the glass . beautiful .  the body was light and very watery .

once cracked it pours a deep , impenetrable black with a thick , high , pillowy light tan head that leaves intricate webs of lacing .  perhaps age will remedy.. m : explosive mouthfeel upon drinking , but the body is very light , with the alcohol evident .
this beer poured black with a large tan creamy head , that lasted through out the beer .  m : this was the most dissapointing . aside from the lingering dry finish this was a very thin porter .

could n't get too aggressive with the pour b/c it has some major head on it . nice gold , perfect clarity , big puffy white head .  mouthfeel : pretty thin , with sharp carbonation and a watery finish .
this beer pours with a thick and foamy head . wonderful active bubbles slowly float to the top to form a thick white head .  m- thin highly carbonated .
thick foamy off-white head with excellent retention and lacing .  couple hints of charcoal & burnt toast - but just hints the whole bottle was thin and watery , and the harshness lasted throughout .

a giant , rocky , off-white head explodes out of the bottle , leaving strata-like rings on the glass as it settles , which is a good amount of time .  the mouthfeel is syrupy and shows none of the carbonation that the pour hinted at .

pours a hazy amber colour with one of the most impressive head i have ever seen . a frothy rocky mountain large off white head .  the mouth is super thin . the thinnest mouth i 've ever had on an ipa . d= the thin mouth makes me go for sips more often and the flavor does n't linger long ... great flavor on this one no doubt .
a nice two fingered head forms quickly and had great retention .  3.0 m too thin for my taste and my experience with better scottish ales ( like oskar blues ) .
lovely auburn red color blows me away .  really thin for an imperial stout .

copious carbonation visible throughout . head is a dense , small-celled foam that swarms out of the pour vigorously , and stays for ages , fading to a mottled cap .  very complex and interesting m : disappointing ! very thin for a barley wine .
the chocolate yeti has perfect color in both the body of the beer and the frothy dark brown head .  m - thin , watery , overly carbonated .

served up a breathtaking deep copper amber that is crystal clear . the head is slightly off-white and looks superb with tightly packed , shiny bubbles that stick around forever and leave near perfect lace . if this beer tastes nearly as good as it looks i will be most happy .  mouthfeel/ drinkability : the carbonation isnt stinging and seems appropriate . the body of the beer seems far too thin .

it pours a thick , viscous black with a large dark tan hea that slowly recedes .  feels very watery , not overly carbonated , but bubbles hard in your stomach , not letting you drink too many of these .
appears pitch black with a thick light brown head .  the problem is that the beverage is thin and flat on the palate and leaves a really unpleasant metallic aftertaste .

black with a nice brown head that leaves good lace rings .  no attempt whatsoever to hide the alcohol and the addition of the heavy acidic espresso taste and a watery mouthfeel make this hard to down .

when pored from the nitrous can , this beer has a wonderful black appearance with a one inch thick layer of tan head .  a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher

a careful pour into a tulip glass evokes a billowing , explosive cloud of soft white foam , decorated by a tiny glowing golden body alive with bubbles . the head is continually fed by a steady stream of bubbles , and holds at over two fingers throughout the drink , lacing the glass in a fashion not unlike shaving cream .  m - light and fizzy , thin bodied .
my first 5 for appearance , and it 's well deserved .  mouthfeel is painfully carbonated . light bodied , way way to much carbonation .
pours a nice red amber with a towering white creamy head ... just like every other nitro beer .  the mouthfeel is surprisingly flat .

bright yellow and unfiltered with a full white head that leaves nice lace .  flavor is rather plain , roasty , sweet , a bit of coffee and coco , the hops seem to be hiding somewhere , i detect little to none , little carbonation , short finish , with a bit of dark bread , and rasins , very thin body.drinkable but not very memoriable .
a- light copper body with a creamy white head that laces and stays to the last drop . d- highly drinkable .  ( btw the mouthfeel matches ) .

impressive thick , dark brown , almost red head . intimidating looking , with an enormous presence in the glass . fantastic appearance .  mouthfeel feels thin and weak ; this is my only real complaint with this beer .

this beer pours a golden color , with a thick and fluffy white head . the head fades slowly , leaving a nice lacing .  flavor is of arange , and body is highly carbonated . prickly mouthfeel , and a bit boring overall
the beer pours a dark amber with an impressive frothy head . the retention is excellent and lacing is glass coating .  sweet crackery finish , m - thin with very low carbonation .
this one is jet black with an enormous off white / light tan head . this head is quite frothy and laces incredibly .  m : thin body with almost no carbonation at all .
it basically looks very impressive ... fantastic .  mouthfeel : medium to light treading dangerously close to watery .

a- bright , vibrant copper/gold with a huge active head . this beer has sea foam on it . clumps of foam stuck to the top as i drink down .  the body is very thin -- like there was a lot of adjuncts added .
this one certainly fits the bill . appearance is nice at a dark brown near black with deep crimson hues and a thin tan head .  mouthfeel is very thin .

appearance : very , very deep clear gold , head on this one is one for the ages , really spectacular . huge , dense , pure white and a bit slick ; looks a bit like whipped egg whites .  has a malty aroma , enticing , maybe some wheat too ? fizzy palate , mallty taste , fruity , not very lingering . thirst-quenching .
first off , this is easily the coolest looking beer can ever . awesome retention and lacing .  m- spritzy , carbonation fills your mouth swelling your cheeks slightly . rough , bubbly and thin .

a- glourious golden yellow with a fluffy and foamy white head that retains well in the tulip glass . dies to a fluffy ring and nice cloud that leaves thick lace all along the glass .  i picked up a carton of this pretty cheap the only downfall its in cans anyways it pours a golden amber see thru colour with nice carbonation that leaves a bubbly two finger head and sporadic lacing , the aroma is pretty macro with grains and a feint bubblegum aroma , it has a thin mouthfeel with a rather grainy taste and isnt nothing to write home about , its definately better than the macroswill that sells for much more and easier to down but its not a beer that i would drink if i wanted a nice beer with character .
dark brown with good clarity , this beer has a dense , light brown head with excellent retention and lacing .  i will admit that i did not like the mouthfeel very much . too bubbly .

called the skellig irish red on the chalkboard , but confirmed with watch city that it is their shillelagh irish red . magnificent , bulbous cream of head that frankly amazes with its ocean of white and a knifes edge cut ; huge stick and lace . dark red hue with a dead quiet calm and plenty of crystal clarity .  the body was very thin and the beer lacked substance .

appearance : an aggressive pour gives me an inch head of fluffy off white foam on top of a mostly clear pale yellow orange beer .  it tastes ok. kind of watered down . cant taste any malt or hops . it was too bubbly , seemed over-carbonated .
a - only a sliver of red around the edge . tall very tight light brown head leaving considerable lacing .  the mouthfeel , as mentioned , is very watery and razor thin .

a gorgeous beer , this pours a rich , hazed , honey amber with a killer head of eggshell puff that forms stiff rocky peaks and deposits thick clumps of lace .  m- this is precisely the opposite mouthfeel that i want . it feels like it wants to be sweet and sticky , but it really just falls watery on the tongue .
a : bright straw body with an enormous rocky head of great retention .  mouthfeel : very carbonated with a thin , almost watery feeling .

( a great place ) poured a wonderfully rich yellow color . it was cloudy with a half inch of creamy white head . nice lacing with this beer .  thin , harsh , and astringent- the mouthfeel is where the beer suffers the most .

reviewed 1/8/2008 ( bottle ) : pours a golden somewhat cloudy yellowish color . big foamy frothy white head with good lacing .  not much to say about natural ice other than that it is cheap . little taste that i could discern , but nothing abhorrent at that . maybe some sweetness , a bit more complex than some of its stablemates . of course , it is highly drinkable , which is the point . pressed for cash and desirous of a little buzz ? you could definitely do worse .
bomber bought at total wine a - dark black , 2 fingered head , dissipates slow and leaves a nice lacing .  a : it 's still carbonated , that 's something at least . too fizzy .

a solid five fingers tall , the head falls slowly , leaving behind a cragy , mountainous blanket over top of the glass with massive amounts of lacing . best looking head i 've ever seen .  it actually smells more like a belgian dubbel . it does n't have much complexity and it drinks very watery . this is by far the thinnest quad i 've ever come across .

fantastic lacing & head retention is als really good , a peresitent film hugs the orval goblet all the way down s : slight hints of choclate , cherry & oak barrels t : choclate & oakyness up front .  the mouthfeel is watery with medium carbonation .

on to the beer : little is wrong with the appearance . the head is thick and sports plenty of its original self , peach colored body has the `` glowing '' illusion at some spots . it 's just one bitter mess with some soap and soft waves of phenols ( more specifically , pllastic ) that do n't belong and the beer becomes even more unpleasant .  feel : active , assaulting carbonation and a light , watery body .

anyway , it had a great head , probably because of the nitro , but it was large , white , creamy and fluffy . great lacing to boot . kind of milky , gauzy .  tasting it my first impression was how thin the body was for an english porter , compared to , for instance , the excellent fuller 's london porter or young 's double chocolate .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass the beer poured a crystal clear , deep , orangey-amber color . a two-plus finger tall crop of light beige froth topped the liquid . the head had excellent lasting power and it deposited a thick , drippy blanket of lacing along the top half of the glass .  not much at all going on except for some sweetness and a very slight bitterness that gives way to a watery finish . not the worst macro lager by any means .

appearance : beautiful deep gold color , a lushous two-fingered layer of white foam , lots of rising bubbles , good head retention , flecks of lace aroma : dusty , cinnamony , malty , honey-like sweetness , floral hops , plummy fruitiness , perfumy ( sage and roses ?  the body is thin and watery ; one hardly notices the beer until it is gone .
nice white , foamy head with great retention .  mouthfeel is thin for the style .

appearance this one poured a beautiful , hazy orange in color with a monster head that i had to control at the pour . it came down pitting , leaving a whitish film all along the inside of my glass .  the body of this is way too light for a porter .

drank on-tap at miracle of science bar & grill , cambridge , ma poured a gorgeous , crystal clear , dark orangey-amber with a clingy , off white , one-finger head that lasted the duration of the beer .  m : taste was below average for me , but the mouthfeel is even worse . super thin . light carbonation and no body make this almost watery .
oysters ... hmmm ... pours a blackish black with a black interior and black edging . nice looking bubbling dark brown foam . really attractive .  md - thin and not much of a body to it .
poured a deep thick black with a nice dark tan head that dissipated quickly .  mouthfeel is boring and watery .
pours a perfect cloudy gold with a big fluffy head .  thin , watery mouthfeel .
it has the perfect color for a lager , dark but not to dark .  body is thin and flat .
appearance : clear orange in color with a 2 '' head that slowly falls . some mild lacing develops .  the body is light and really deters the taste .
looks beautiful in the glass , with rich crystalline red color and a nice head .  mouthfeel is thin for a ris , almost watery .
baltika # 6 porter is nearly black in colour but has a slightly red hue when held to the light . a handsome porter .  mouthfeel is thin , almost no carbonation .

a- pretty close to opaque brown/black . head is thick and tan , stays frim at one finger . a couple wisps of lacing . o- it 's a tasty beer but it 's a bit too sweet , yet light , for me to think of it as much above average in the styke .  mouthfeel is thin and syrupy .

2009 vintage a- deep violet , crimson red just a beautiful awe-inspiring color and massive towering head that seems to be independent of the beer and an entity all onto itself .  the presence of tannin explains how , while quite watery , satan red is also quite drying .
a : pitch-black , a thick , frothy tan head very slowly settles , on top of lively carbonation . looking very good indeed .  tastes like someone put artificial flavoring in carbonated water .
pours very golden , pretty clear looking . great head that sticks around and some nice lacing .  mouthfeel is almost cloying from the sweetness and really is the only category this beer suffers .
a - deep beautiful red transparent body with a tight small head .  m- not a lot of carbonation , kind of syrupy actually . i feel if it would have been carbonated more it would have helped a lot .
this has a great exploding head and looks great . it has a dirty deep amber-and slightly ruby brown color .  m : flat . way too sweet for the ( non-existant ) level of carbonation .
1-fingered extremely light tan head with very impressive retention , leaves rings of lace all the way down the glass .  carbonation is way too high .

a : a stunning deep brown near black with cranberry highlights . a inch of toasted head comes after a medium pour . the head slowly fades to an impressive 1/3 inch . lacing on a dark beer ?  mouthfeel : a bit on the fizzy side - really scrubs the tongue .
terrific retention and lots of lace . stunning .  skimpy in body , vapidly dextrinous and approaching watery in mouthfeel .

pours a deep , deep garnet , with a big , three finger tan head .  it does n't taste bad or good , kind of like water . it tastes like bubble water with a hint of sweetness . it 's for getting your swill on , and nothing else . too bad this is what most americans think of , when they think of australian beer .

it looks like a very refreshing and tasty beer . crystal clear straw colored beer , again looks very refreshing .  starts with fruit taste , looses interest with a thin mouthfeel and water middle although helped by a supporting co2 texture and some tartness ( carbondated water ) ending with lactic acid and dry pucker on the back of the tongue and esophagus .

the bottle popped furiously , and poured with a full head and glowing color .  m : dammit , i hate porters like this . light , watery body , slightly oily , and slick on the palate . this would have been so much better with more body to it .
perfect looking beer .  2.5 m very light , i am not impressed . it is very close to water in feel .
pours a very pretty amber/copper with a persisting light tan head .  too thin .
a - black is right . the head is a medium brown and standing about three-quarter inches tall before slowly fading to bumpy and frothy top .  thin mouthfeel .

app- a nice dark brown which looked alot like maple syrup .  very pale straw yellow color , hazy but filtered look no aroma noted water like very light bodied taste and looks like water ... . however better than most would give credit to seeing how its bud .

has a lovely appearance . produces about two and a have fingers thick of light tan head that has perfect retention . the body of the brew is cleanly filtered and is dark copper/ruby red in color .  mouthfeel was pretty watery and went down quickly .

pours black with a long lasting brown head that leaves plenty of lacing .  above average taste for an adunct lager , but not great by any measure . this is definately better than budweiser , coors or miller , but not exactly to die for . foster 's price point is right about miller/bud level , but always slightly higher . it 's worth the extra coins if you 're on a budget . much more enjoyable than the run-of-the-mill macros .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a perfect pint glass . the bubbles slowly dissipated down to a 1/4 '' layer that left behind tons and tons of lace . this one fine looking offering ... the nose is solid ... piney hops with an earthy aroma mix with a sweet , bready backbone ... seems like this one will have some balance .  mouthfeel is overly carbonated .

cloudier than the surface of jupiter . a great looking , one finger head , sticks around for quite a while .  better than expected , but as someone who despises ab products + light beer i was n't expecting much trouble is , within the same can it tasted like lemonade in some sips , water in others . giving it a 4 on drinkability because it 's light , so one could drink a lot of these if they chose to .
a : i love the color ; a hazy gradient of orange and red hues that is literally shining in my glass , it would make a perfect sunset . beautiful .  mouthfeel - one of the most water beers i 've had .

a - extremely dark brown body with a dark brown head to go along with it . the thick and frothy head started out at about 4 inches and ever so slowly faded down leaving a thick humocky topography .  mouthfeel is thin and weak .

poured into tulip glass from 12oz bottle ... a- bright crystal clear gold . large two finger fluffy white head . one of most beautiful dipa i 've seen .  mouthfeel is very thin and overly carbonated .
a : yellow , straw hues , slightly hazy , enormous whipped meringue head , long lasting retention , nice lacing .  fizzy ... gross . m- watery , thin , minimal carbonation , and nothing lingering .
very good lacing & head retention smell : slight malt hints taste : slight caramel followed by malt & fruiityness .  very light in body with a slick mouthfeel at first that becomes almost slimy .
great streaks of lacing that never disappear .  the mouthfeel leans toward the thin and watery side .
a - deep cherry red with a pretty pink head that left a really nice lacing .  my big complaint is the mouthfeel . this stuff had some serious astringency to it leaving my mouth prickly and dry .

as the beer was going down in the glass , it left an incredible , thick creamy lacing all over the glass . appearance was pretty cloudy , light copper color .  body is very thin , drinkability is ok , but there 's not very much to this beer .

real dark brown . nice big dark tan head that retained throughout the beer and laced the glass nicely .  mouthfeel is very thin with low carbonation , almost watery , drinkability is poor , huge bitterness and watery mouthfeel is a disappointment .

delicious and only $ 7/pint..hells yes please . angry and black it pours with a dark brown head , roast and alcohol dominate with some hop aroma , very faded , a little smoke , a little coffee .  flavor : then , i drank some & everything went downhill . it was watery & disappointing .
this tyranena offering pours a beautiful semi hazed flourescent copper color with a medium to large sized foamy slight tan head . looks awesome . quite a hoppy , resiny smell .  m = thin . thats it .
pours a lovely shiny ruby colour , rich and clear . head is beige , nice and dense and retaining thin crown . lace is good and sticky . looks wonderful .  m : thin body with not much carbonation .

black hole is the visual m.o . the head is mammoth and very interesting . dark mocha color around the bottom near the liquid and a lighter tan color up top . very cool .  the body is a bit thin and feels too bubbly .
the head is fluffy and impressive with a slightly off white color and nice staying power . it leaves pretty average lace .  mouthfeel - very light and dry .

pours a chocolate brown color with a massive invincible head that lasts to the bitter end and gobs and gobs of lace .  tragically the mouthfeel is watery and the carbonation ( which others had noted ) , distracts from the overall experience .

a : amazing head on top of a dark yellow body launches up to the top of the glass and hangs out forever , ending its long life in a spiderweb of beauty . glass is soapy all the way down . this beer could not look any more inviting .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and very watery .
a : ca n't really take anything away from this one , perfect tan head on top of a pitch black body .  very thin , and watery . lower carbonation .

a : bright red with an even keel of carbonation rising to fluffy beige head . gorgeous head does n't waver for a moment .  has a bit of a sweet maltiness and maple flavor does come out more as it warms m : very thin feel for a porter and leaves an odd buttery coating d : nothing really appauling , and nothing overpowering so it is drinkable , but i probably wo n't get another
2011 bottle poured into a tulip glass . a - an inch of dense cream-colored foam sits atop a beautiful ruby colored ale .  the body is too full and filling .

the appearance is the best part about this beer . pours badass and the head stays with it the whole time of drinking .  mouthfeel - pretty astringent . almost watery except for the stickiness of the body .
this one pours a beautiful orange copper color with 3/4 '' off-white head .  very thin , and barely any head .

epic 's version has a great scent , faint spices , with a slight smokiness . it 's definitely much more bitter , with an almost a lemon pucker factor . the alcohol content also seems to add a bit more 'warmth ' than the dc brau version , which is n't entirely a negative .  m - watery and sticky . its almost a thin beer .

served at a few degrees below fridge tempeature in a tulip glass . the color is a gleaming orange , and the lacing is setting up with unbelievable sticky cling . superb ! smell- a bold metallic smell booms out from the glass , incredibly phenolic and overpowering the malts and hops .  mouthfeel is disappointing , wet , but not substantial .
great `` belgian '' lacing & very good head retention smell : sourness & then woody , lactic notes .  mouthfeel : not much carbonation and the body is kind of watery .

bottle courtesy of bu11zeye : poured a slightly cloudy bright yellow color ale with a super huge foamy pure white head with great retention and great lacing .  one thing about this beer is it feels extremely watery .
poured very nicely with a substantial head ( which receded faster than i expected ) and left lovely lacing down my pint glass .  mouthfeel was much too thin to be of any merit .

bottled in july 2011 poured into a tulip glass . still manages to create a creamy , thick-looking head , quite impressive . head fades gradually to a thin ring around the glass with some islands , leaving lots of lacing .  i am dissapionted in the carbination as it is nearly flat with a medium/light feel .
a - clear golden yellow with average ultra white head . moderate retention and good lacing .  feels watery with a sweet burn on the way down . soapy .
poured into a dokel with a deep copper hue and a thick head that stays like a film on the top of the beer , slight lacing .  it feels more watery than i 'd like my porter , however .
poured a beautiful mahogany with a creamy half inch of foam that never fully subsided .  mouthfeel : seltzer drinkability : would be good but the mouthfeel sucks .

this beer pours a gorgeous clear deep orange amber color with a 3 finger ( on an easy pour ) of offwhite/tannish thick sudsy head . the head retention on this was ridiculous !  mouthfeel is very thin , again very soda like .

pours pitch black like guinness . smells extremely strong of caramel and a hint of mint ( i 'm thinking of mint chocolate chip ice cream ) .  alcohol is very well masked for a 6.5 % way too much carbonation for my liking .
poured a nice pumpkin orange with a big frothy white head that left spots of lacing here and there .  mouthfeel is very flat .
amazing looking beer .  body was light and feel was watery .

on tap at ebenezer 's 2/13/11 a : pitch black and completely opaque . massive 2 finger mocha colored foamy and rocky head that was there to the finish . i ca n't recall many big stouts with such an impressive looking head .  overall , feels unbalanced , too much carbonation and a little too dull .

a : dark caramel ale with a finger of whipped toasted cream foam . this sticks around for quite some time before barely retreating to a quilt of the same . sheet lace . excellent clarity .  it 's watery on the palate , surprisingly so - i 've had beers of 3 to 4 % alcohol that had more body . the finish is lightly astringent and bitter .
pours a beautiful dark orange/copper color with a good head retention and lacing . i love the color of this beer .  immediately upon entering the mouth it felt very watery and light for an 80/- .

sadly , this is another short 's beer that is a huge let down ... a medium copper pour with tons of head . great retention , nice lava stack on the top ... aroma is super disappointing , light with only a whisp of sweetness coming through .  the flavor was spicy and malty and the mouthfeel was tingly along with a burning sensation as it is swallowed .

i 've been avoiding this beer , but my wife bought me a sixer so here we go ... poured into a sa perfect pint glass , and it looks pretty good with mounds of soft and pillowy head , and a golden/slightly hazy body .  really fizzy ( like coca-cola fizzy ) on the tongue , with a metallic finish , not really what i was hoping for , dissapointing .

g : erdinger weizen glass a : dark chesnut bpdy , some light escapes around the edges of the glass . there is three fingers of thick creamy off-white head with good retention .  m : watery , very light-bodied , body of a light lager .

dark gold , lightly cloudy , with a very big creamy off-white head slowly shrinking to a puffy , rocky smaller head and foamy lace .  it tasted mostly like water with a very light toffee/sweet taste in the back of the tongue . that 's it . it was very drinkable in the same way water is drinkable . when a brewer wants you to chill his beer , there must be a issue with the flavor at cellar temps . i ca n't believe some people consider this to be the flagship for the style .

appearance- beautiful aroma- smells like raw dark chocolate and smokiness taste- bitter chocolate and smoke overpower at first . one of the less complex stouts i 've had .  the mouthfeel is pretty thin and watery .
pours honeyed orange with a big beige foamy head with tons of sticky foam caking the side .  mouthfeel is thin .

huge , mocha head forms and stays around for a long time , leaving copious amounts of lace down the side of the glass .  2.5 m thin , with only the grain tastes and the slightest stickiness keeping it from being water itself .

looks really nice s : light fruity smells , with a caramel malt , slight peppery notes from from the hops , maybe a slight metallic note .  the mouthfeel is very watered down like an american pale ale but i thought the pumpkin taste was enjoyable .

appearance- 3/4 inch full dirty brown head . dark brown , maybe and off black colored pour . full length lacing sheets plaster the glass . lovely sight .  i must say this beer is best on tap as everywhere i 've tried it otherwise all of its carbonation seems to be non-existant .
black color , pitch black .  pretty easy to drink with a light , watery mouthfeel .

a : this beer has the darkest head i have seen . i would describe the head as dirt brown .  mouthfeel is watery . this style needs more body - the maltiness is there , but there is very little roasted character & not enough creaminess .

this beer looks wonderful . a beautiful mahogany red , cloudy and rich topped with two and a half fingers of rich foam . the beer leaves textbook rings down the glass as you drink it ( rather quickly ) .  the mouthfeel is this beer 's weakest point . also , it feels a bit heavy on the palate and is almost syrupy .

22oz into nonic pint in the mid-forties . booming 4f of cream-colored head , over a clear but rich amber body - tons of carbonation present , and lots of sugary/sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel was flat and very dissapointing .

pours a beautiful deep red ( more red than amber ) with two fingers of soft light brown head . leaves a ton of lacing behind .  taste is weak , almost watery , has to be drank ice cold or has a taste like vomit . bottom line is compared to other cheap beers pbr excels in taste , quality , and conveniently the price , 7 bucks a 12 pack .

i must say from my experience , dark horse makes some great looking beers . this one pours a beautiful light hazy brown , which turns a hazy burnt orange in the light .  pretty nice . the body is as thin as water . that leads to a very drinkable beer , actually , since it goes down ... well , like water .
appearance & gt ; lovely golden amber hue . lively .  good for a lager , but way too much carbonation really throwing this beer off .

dark , but clear with ruby/purple highlights . fine beige foam , really sticky with sheets of bubbles coating the glass . good head retention too .  the mouthfeel was watery , the body medium/light and the carbonation average .
pours almost oil black which was a pleasant surprise . medium/thick lumpy head that reveals most of the aroma right off the bat .  mouthfeel was very watery and not smooth in the slightest .

appearance ; nice white head . dissipates slowly to a thick film , leaving quality lacing .  i 'm going to have to go against the gimmick and with the style here , the mouthfeel just is n't there . i 'm not impressed at all , it 's like a half flat beer that you 've left on your desk whilst reviewing a beer and forgotten about it only to come back to it 30 mins later . the shining point of this beer is it 's drinkability .

a- it looks really good poured in a glass .  the mouthfeel on this one fluctuates but it has one of the worst finishes i can recall in a beer . the thin body and soda-like carbonation ( and some wheaty texture ) save this some , but the finish is just harsh . artificial flavor , sticks to the teeth , chewing on cardboard , something is wrong here finish to the mouthfeel .
pours a deep black color with a half inch frothy head .  i 'm gon na have to say the mouthfeel is what keeps this from being very drinkable . it felt almost like flat soda .

pours a beautiful clear copper with a tight beige colored head of foam . the head sticks around , with good lacing on the glass .  water with a little spice and alcohol . the smell is the best part with mainly cinnamon . the taste is one dimensional cinnamon with a super light water taste on the back . no malt or pumpkin to be found . not a good beer nor a good pumpkin ale but if someone handed me one i would have no problem finishing it . also you could down 3 or 4 no problem and being $ 6 a 6 pack you ca n't beat that .
a - truly unique looking beer . a black beer almost dark purple looking at times .  the mouthfeel is way to under carbonated and watery for the style .

really nice looking brew , deep copper colored body with a creamy cap of head that lasts forever.very little aroma with only the slightest hint of spicy hop .  thin to medium mouthfeel with zero carbonation -- lifeless .
poured into a nonic . pitch black with two fingers of creamy off white , frothy head . looking good .  mouthfeel very thin , almost light-bodied , and lacking in bitterness .
one and a half fingers of super creamy off-white head . excellent retention and lots of lacing . awesome !  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and watery .

a : reddish brown with a half finger of lightish fizzy head , *excellent* retention . insane amounts of lacing remained on my glass thru the drink .  not so much the taste as it had a good belgian style wheatiness to it but the body was extremely thin and almost watery . i was looking for more in the way of the mouthfeel .

a- caramel amber beer , nice dark coloration , super huge head with sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel is disappointing with absolutely no carbonation and mild flavors lingering around . overall , i could have possibly gotten a flat beer but this beer had potential ( when carbonated ) but it didnt come through in my bottle .

when you crack the can open you can hear the tsss of the nitro kick in , then it pours a full pinto of nitro head which slowly ( but faster than on tap ) dissipates into the body . nose is a bit roasty and creamy , nice and smooth .  very watery . the mouthfeel was thin and watery as well .
pours a near black with a khaki colored that head that shows great retention and lots of body .  mouthfeel is thin , macro thin .

poured into a new belgium snifter a - a beautiful clear dusk sunset color , 2 finger head that lingered and lacing through and through and awesome tiny bubbles for days s - pine , citrus , malt , floral , cotton , sweet , grains and maybe a bit toasty t - very nice bitter sweet , pine , orange , melon , pineapple , very hoppy and yet super bitter sweet malty m - coats the mouth a bit with some super bitter sweet lingering .  m : bitter , almost no carbonation , light to medium body .
heading was awesome , big , white and fluffy , with many tiny air bubbles racing toward the head .  this is very much like corona . not as good as miller light .

appearance : crystal clear . white head . nice lacing smell : smells like a triple .  mouthfeel is also watery with not much body and no carbonation but essentially pretty drinkable due to the fact that is just resembles colored water .

a deep golden pour teams with a fluffy cream head . good head retention and great lacing . very sexy served in a tulip .  the lack of body really disappointed me . while surprisingly drinkable , this beer needs to be heavier to match the taste , so more body and more alcohol are needed .
really beautiful beer , pours a hazy golden color with a huge frothy white head that retains impressively and leaves nice lacing .  m - weak and thin . lifeless .

a : beautiful beer ! it 's a perfectly clear light amber color topped by a big-bubble , thin but foamy head . lacing is alright , but the beer looks so good it makes up for that in other areas .  a nice chocolatey finish that lingers for a while on the palate is the best part about this beer . m : poor .

new holland mad hatter ipa 12 oz bottle recent bottling , tumbled down the rabbit hole 10/06 medium pour in a tulip glass . poured a hazy copper orange with a frothy mostly lasting white head with excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is rather thin for a scotch ale .

this batch was amazing ! the color was orange and hazy .  it was ice cold thanks to the cooler and that made it tasty . watery but that 's alright because your not expecting anything but that from bud ice .

a - hazy , orangish yellow body topped by a huge , rocky head with the most spectacular retention i have ever seen .  appearance : dark amber color with a nice 1/2 '' off white head ... unfortunately this reminded me of a pop on the pour smell : pine , hops , citrus taste : kinda watery , slight citrus ( maybe cascade hops ) mouthfeel : thin drinkability : could do two in a night , but i 'd rather drink something that tastes better

gorgeous , classy looking beer .  for the level of alcohol , there is hardly any hotness at all and a bizarrely watery and light body for a barleywine . could also stand some more hops , as i could hardly detect any at all .
dark completely opaque black like a cloudless night just past 11 . an insanely large , brown head fills the glass .  mouthfeel is weak and watery .
( bottle into pint glass - sampled 4/5/10 ) picture perfect pour with a dark brown color and creamy off white head .  m : light carbonation with a very light watery body .
the color was a nice brown color , very little head and the aroma was no where to be found .  aside from that , the taste , like the smell , is unremarkable mouthfeel is borderline watery .
looks picture perfect . despite my allergies , i can actually smell floral hops .  no finish , the faintest body , texture is nil , nothing to recommend it at all .
charcoal black with an inch thick teddy bear brown head that quickly sinks to an eighth of an inch . excellent lacing persists for some time thereafter .  body is way too thick , sweet , and syrupy .
poured from bomber into my stone irs snifter ( 2010 ) a - pitch black with a big persistent dark tan head . the head is beautiful on this beer . what an appearance !  watery and flat in my mouth .
best before 26.09.05 appearance : awesome . poured with a nice long lasting beige head .  the mouthfeel is poor . it seems to lack enough carbonation .

a- poured a dark black , with a nice head that faded quickly . the head was chocolate brown in color that had minimal lacing . i was very excited to taste based on looks .  head falls into the liquid way too quickly and seems to look more like bubble bath suds that the typical beautiful belgian head . certainly is the high point of the beer . alcohol comes a little too strong on the palate and seems to take over the other flavors . flat on the tonque . outrageously overpriced and overrated .

30 cl brown bottle poured into a pint glass ( it 's the only glassware i own ) . a : super-thick , rich , creamy , mostly white foamy head . in fact , the head was so thick that this small 300 ml bottle would n't fit into my imperial pint glass without waiting for some of the head to thin out .  the mouthfeel is a lowlight , though , with a very thin , watery body being punctuated by small , prickly bubbles .

poured with a firm sturdy , foamed up head .  here we go : a - opaque reddish-brown , small head with minimal lacing s - malts , hint of hops , not much else t - much like the aroma , mildly sweet malts , faint hop bitterness with weak coffee m - thin , a bit too thin for a brown ale d - no problem putting down a few if i chose to , but i do n't think i would unless it was my only alternative to bmc lagers .

this beer poured slow , and was pitch black in color . the head was medium sized , but brown , with small bubbles . looked beautiful !  m - the body is vanishingly thin and i feel the carbonation is too high for an english porter .

*reviewed on 06.07.2005 starts off with a golden clear base , medium white fluffy head , head retention for all 60 minutes and impressive lacing effects . luckily it was n't a typcial belgian ale but a cheap bud-like lager .  taste is rich and sweet , slightly nutty , but this beer really sufferes from it 's thin and watery mouthfeel .

| 8.0 % abv | 2011 brewer : shmaltz brewing company ( he'brew ) style : american strong ale glass : crystal mug appearance : dazzling orange-amber under light , with a foamy , frothy head .  mouthfeel is disappointing ; thin and watery , with too much carbonation for my taste .

pours a amber ale color with a super looking coffee colored head with tight tiny bubbles that also remits some great lacing .  mouthfeel is where the beer suffers . it just feels wrong . a very tasty and aromatic beer , and if you can get past or prefer the super-low carbonation level .

brown/red/amber , on the clear side , nice head that lasts . maybe give it a touch more opacity . edit : if they just called it a winter warmer and dropped barleywine from the name , why , it would probably just be average and not bad .  i feel like i have now experienced the true port/lost abbey experience , this is the first one i 've had that is flat ... a : pours dark brown with caramel highlights , zero head even after stiff pour , some clarity s : nose is predominantly oak and vanilla , some char quality in there , stout base takes a back seat t : vanilla and bourbon again dominate , some ashy character in there along with light notes of leather and tobacco , a bit of of boozieness on the finish mf : low carbonation is an understatement , medium body o : good flavors here , the lack of carbonation takes away from the quality a bit , for the premium price tag , i would expect carbonation .
dark brown with hints of red , and a solid beige head .  getting some sweetness from the milk sugar too , but not a lot m- thin . flat .
bod : 11/17/10 pours a rusted mahoghany and settles jet metal black . a fingers worth of burnt caramel head sits for a short while .  over carbonated , watery .

almost impossible to open due to the stupid wax coating covering the whole swing top . lightly hazed bronze color with a nice full pillowy light beige head , nice active carbonation , and nice lace sheets .  the first thing i notice with this beer is the watery mouthfeel . the mouthfeel is terrible .
the pour results in a fluffy off-white head ; the ale is a nice golden hue . patchy head retention and good lacing on the glass .  m/d - weak and thin mouthfeel .

two fingers of light tan head forms and recedes slowly . the color of this beer is truly gorgeous ... smell is sweet and sugary upfront .  crisp to the point of being overdone , loads and loads of soda like carbonation . notes : ho hum , average , run of the mill , mediocre ... etc .

good head retention that fades to nice lacing down to the last swallow . nice nutty brown color , with visible carbonation .  body is a nip thin . a bit too still , but more carbonation would have blasted through the empty body of the beer , making it even less desirable .

poured into a tulip . billowing head , color to the amber side of golden and nicely hazed , outstanding lacing .  the beer was thin bodied and very easy to drink . for a faint tasting , macro lager it was n't too bad .

poured a clear deep golden with a light orange hue with a huge blooming foamy white head that slowly crept its way down but took quite some time for it to settle.aromas are clean i think to clean , a little caramel note and a light passing herbal note but it was faint.its a sessional style beer no doubt light toasted , caramel sweet malt but nothing overbearing finishing with a light lemon , herbalness.it is what it is a light bitter a good quaffer just very subtle flavors .  medium bodied , but watery .

appearance : pours with a massive amount of head , ca n't even pour the bottle in one try . awesome lacing . the beer itself is black as black can be , without even a hint of any other color around the edges . drinkability : this beer is a beautiful thing to behold , with amazing lacing .  mostly smells and tastes like a lager pretending to be an ale . that hint of lager ( as in yuengling lager ) sits there in the background , but then there 's a nice hit of hops in there too . it 's odd , but not necessarily bad ( although certainly not a good american pale in any sense of the word ... it 's a cheap beer masquerading as an american pale ) . not great , but one to try if you 're tired of lager as your cheap beer for the minute .

a big fluffy ice cream scoop of a head , eventually smooths out to about a quarter inch . for a lager this is a very good looking beer .  mouthfeel this one was clumsy and , worst of all , lacked the fluffy character of a good hefe weizen .
appearance : very much a rich dark brown color that lets no light through . great measure of head .  feel : very thin bodied and a bit too light in body for an ipa or even an apa .
kudos to these guys for making such a fine looking beer . great head , elegant lace , interesting to look at .  the body was water and medium light .

a beautiful appearance , two thick fingers of creamy light coco head with spectacular lacing coating the glass .  mouthfeel : body is thin and water and a little flat ; finsih is wet and is like drinking malt flavored water . the flavors are mild and meek , the body is super watery and does n't offer much , so i do n't feel i will be drinking this again .

simply beautiful cascading action that lasts for over a minute ! superb tan head retention that is not going away at all !  i was again surprised to find a very thin mouth feel dominated by carbonation which seemed to accent the minimal hops to make them more pronounced .

poured from a 11.6oz brown bottle with a white cap marked `` bottl 2006* 12 % '' into a tulip glass . easily one of the longest lasting , largest frothy heads of foam i have ever seen on any beer . appearance is a rusty yellowish orange color , cloudy and semi-translucent .  mouthfeel is overly fizzy , making an already light beer even fluffier . overall , this is an interesting beer that could be very refreshing if less carbonated .

a : i really like the appearance of this beer . it is a real nice crystal clear copper color , you can see every bubble in the glass . the head almost looks too heavy for the actual beer , a nice contrast .  m - syrupy , mouth coating body with an obnoxious amount of carbonation . carbonation is prickly and really too much as i feel like i ca n't taste everything because of it . it does get better the more you let it warm and let the carbonation die down .

poured a 355 ml bottle , dated 15 nov 2007 , into a tulip . a : poured a massive 1.5 fingered creamy head , in a tulip this appears huge . the color is a glorious tawny . the carbonation is rising nicely in the glass and it seems as if the head is hardly going anywhere .  very light bodied , an ok mouthfeel.. just way too watery and thin , not much for taste , just some lemon zest on the after taste .

pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest hint of lighter color when held to a light source . frothy 1.5 finger chocolate coffee colored head that quickly settles into a lasting ring .  appearance : golden with extremely high head with low head retention smell : sublte hop aroma , taste : light and refreshing , herbal with some decent hop flavor mouthfeel : light bodied , way too much carbonation , jeez ... drinkability : great flavor belgian pale but its overcarbonated .

appearance opaque brown/black with faint crimson edges when held up to the light . a small creamy tan head tops the beer for most of my drinking , slowly sinking to a hazy covering . lacing is a solid coating around most of the glass , impressive . i can not really taste the oysters or notice any effect they have on the beer .  m - way too much carbonation for my taste .
the head is big , small bubbles below , big ones in the middle and a nice cream dome on top .  t : cheap carbonated corn . m : if it werent for the bottle this beer would have sunk years ago .

the beer after its removal from the 12-ounce brown bottle resides in my glass a pitch-black color with a moderate sized creamy tan head and after its decomposition , the lace forms a thick and sticky sheet upon the glass .  mouthfeel is very flat and is not impressing at all .
poured into a glass stein and had an above average white head . it looked great in the stein .  m - very thin and watery with flat carbonation .
bottle : poured a clear deep back color stout with large light brown foamy head with good retention and some lacing .  the body is light and really lacking .
appearance : pours a perfectly clear , deep yellow body with a tall , bubbling , white head . looks nice .  mouthfeel : absolutely no carbonation .
this beer looks absolutely perfect .  mouthfeel is very , very light -- it goes down like nothing at all .
a- gorgeous . deep gold with hints of orange .  m - thin , a little harsh and a bit drying .

a : looking very decent and nice -- light amber hue , with a tight , foamy white beer head with extremely good retention and looking very fizzy ... s : light floral hop aroma arrives upfront , plus a flow of semi-sweet grainy flavour at the back -- the aroma reminds me of some belgian amber ale ?  the mouthfeel is flat , but predictable as there are virtually no bubbles in the glass after the first minute or so . as far as drinkability goes , i 'd save it for the hot summer days , the ballpark and the cheap 30 pack for the party .

12oz bottle , best by 04/29/12 ... a : a perfectly clear super deep ruby red brew with a humongous 2+ inch tan head that fades very slowly . very good .  nose was fruity apples , peaches , apricots , but the mouthfeel was watery and very sour ... not like the lead-in on a flemish sour ... just tartly sour .

pours a beautiful head of dough bread mass cloudy caramel color .  smells and tastes bland and grain like . almost stale . it is a good beer to party with if all your doin is playin beer pong or circle .
appearance 5/5 clear dark brown with a good dark tan colored head that stayed around , and left good lacing as well .  m- strange , slick mouthfeel with a semi dry finish .

poured with some mild carbonation that settled into a thick yellowish head . absolute best porter i have ever seen .  very sweet flavour , largely the same elements as in the aroma , but far too sugary and overwhelmingly sweet for me .
pours a nice dark brown/black with a quarter inch head , typical for founders stuff .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied and watery with almost no carbonation .

this was poured from the bottle into a consendonk tulip glass . a - clear light golden straw color with a thick foamy , ice cream-like head that is very well retained s - sweet malt and fruity yeast aroma with a slight hop spiciness t - like aroma , sweet malt up front with fruit-like notes and a very slight amount of hops on the finish m - medium body with high carbonation d - this is a decent , well-made beer .  the mouhfeel is weak , watery , thin .

this beer looks really , really nice .  m : despite its creamy appearance , the head feels thin on the palate . the brew itself is thin and watery , especially as it warms . the carbonation barely registers .
a - what a beautiful looking beer .  palate scraping astringency . the lack of carbonation particularly makes me wonder if i should have given this more time in the cellar to condition .
poured a beautiful amber color . wonderful lacing . just a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel was slightly thick and flat .

a : very dark brown with appealing 2-3 finger , rocky , off-white head with very good retention and abundant lacing in rings .  thin watery and light in body o - did not even reach moderate expectations of being a porter and tasting barrel aged , just not very good in my opinion .

it pours a rust-colored brown with a roasted 2-3 finger head . this looks as good as any of the big ipas made by stone , smuttynose and company .  a - light , clear , yellow color with a thick head that dissipated quickly s - beer , cheap beer t - beer from a can , cheap beer from a can m - thin , flat , not much d - went down smooth , probably because i 'd wisely iced it down with some ice and rock salt so it would get really cold .
this beer poured pitch black with a thick light brown head out of a 12 oz . this is how a stout beer is supposed to look !  mouth is thin and watery . too simple and too one dimensional and thin .

i really enjoyed this one . perfect copper looking beer .  where this beer falls off is the mouthfeel ; it was like coca-cola without the carbonation . drinkability would be pretty good i guess , if you can get pas the average flavors and thin mouthfeel .

pours out almost pitch black but some light shines through around the edges . a nice fluffy , off-white two finger head has nice retention and leaves heavy lace behind . a huge pillow stays on top of the beer .  mouthfeel is entirely too thin and watery .

out of a bomber this beer was a true , opaque black color . the retention was very good ; it soon became a fluffy cap that also left very good , consistent lacing .  the mouthfeel is light to medium bodied and just way too thin and watery for an oatmeal stout .

a- a perfect golden look in the glass . looks great .  good lacing down the glass s : coffee , sweet bready malts t : coffee , slight harsh maltiness also slight hint of chocolate m : light very thin bodied beer .

brett poured a beautiful slightly hazed golden-orange color producing a massive white head of assorted bubble sizes which was a bit hard to tame .  m - kind of flat on the palate with very little carbonation . hop profile caught me off guard and the mouthfeel is pretty weak .
pours a huge near glass full of pillowy head .  m : thin body and light carbonation .

a : this thing has a huge head . a perfect billowy light-tan colored head with so much fluff , it might as well be whipped cream . the beer is a darker shade of brown when poured , and nearly black in the glass .  thin and watery .

whoa ... a : freakin ' black as my heart with a big tan head and lots of lacing . i really do think dark beers are the nicest to behold .  the mouthfeel is pretty sad on this one . very watery and thin .

looks great . large , stark white head with plenty of lacing . it looked great in the glass but fell apart upon tasting .  the mouthfeel is unbalanced as if the carbonation and the liquid will not merge . for as much noise the carbonation made on opening the bottle , it seems quite on the palate .

brilliant gold with enthusiastic bubbles streaming up to meet the huge fluffy white head .  s. nonexistent . m. also nonexistent . just plain and unoffensive . light beer on amber side ? nothing to brag about but goes down like water . above average in it 's class .
12oz bottle into a goblet a : pours a clear amber color with a finger of white head . solid looking beer .  mouthfeel is too thin for me .

beautiful look on this .  not much depth at all m- lacking for a stout -- - no creaminess and it 's pretty thin overall d- wo n't seek this out again and i hope the rest of the breweries selections are better -- - really loses you in the mouthfeel

appearance : pours dark brown with a hint of red . the head is a nice frothy tan with good lacing .  the finish is lightly sweet rather than crisp , and the mouthfeel , which started out thin , ends on a watery , undercarbonated note . zywiec is an average epl , making it a below average beer in general .
a : very nice translucent amber color with a half finger of white head . good head retention .  mouthfeel is overyly fizzy and thin .

bottled on : ( should be on the bottom right hand side of the bottle but its just dots ) purchased through lakeview liquors , chicago , illinois price - $ 9.99/bomber appearance : pours pitch black with a creamy mocha colored head . with each swirl of the snifter another layer of froth reveals itself . looks tastey .  watery mouthfeel in terms of a stout .

one of the prettiest looking beers i 've seen , a reddish cloudy haze glows from within , with a pink thick bubbly head .  it drinks as a light beer ; it is very thin and weak , much unlike guinness .

the picture looks like the marlboro man . it pours a reddish orange that is very clear . nice white-ish head that has some nice retention and lacing .  high gravity beer , this one is king . drink alot of water when drinking or a major headache occurs . so drink with caution .
this one is dark apricot , almost orange , in color and quite hazy .  very carbonated ... .too much .

this bock pours perfectly with a tight forming bright white head that stays around for a good duration .  ( m ) thin mouthfeel with some bitterness loosely gripping at the tongue , barely holding on .
very pretty two-finger head .  horrible macro version of the style .

the color is dark like black coffee . i hesitate to say pitch black because there is some light shining through when held up to the light . the head is huge , maybe from a poor pour ? the head also sticks around for a long time and is sticking all over the side of the glass .  empty , chalky mouthfeel , not much going on here .

look : beautiful solid two finger cream white head ( looks like a solid thick layer of whipped cream ) , beautiful retention , light amber ( about a 14 srm ) , beautiful lacing .  the mouthfeel is astringent .
