it 's hard to make a stout i dont enjoy but i am not so sure about this one . the color is most excellent ( pure pitch black ) and it poured with a nice head but unfiortunately it did n't last and left very little lace on the glass .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied . it took much diligence to see my way to the end of this beer , and , were it not for the runaway carbonation , it could 've been far better . one to revisit , provided they clear up the carbonation issue .

a : dark burnt rose . it has the color of a setting sun on a cool fall day . the head starts 2 fingers high but quickly disappears to just a lacing across the top of this beautiful beer .  m - crisp start but the finish ends up being very watery .
pours a 1+ finger tan head over a brilliant bright gold liquid .  a thin mouthfeel and not a lot of carbonation .

12oz bottle to pint glass a : very creamy brown with a puffy tan head that has decent retention and some lacing . i think the look of guinness is my favorite ... does n't get much better .  mouthfeel is thin .

glassware - imperial pint appearance - dark amber/red in color , which makes sense . nice two finger white head that leaves a lot of really great lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is light and watery , not much substance . a very watered down dunkel , i would skip this in the future .

sam adams longshot old ale 12 oz bottle moderate pour in an english pint glass best before 06/07 , longed over 02/07 poured a dark copper brown with a huge foamy mostly lasting head with good lacing .  m : really unappealing .
strikingly bright gold with a dense , frothy latte-like head .  the mouthfeel was very thin for a stout .
deep amber 2 finger head .  m - medium-thin mouthfeel with low carbonation . a bit watery , the consistency of this beer is not what i wanted . too thin , not creamy enough for me .

gave it a great appearance rating because it totally looks like autumn ! perfect golden brown hue and the thin wispy head perfectly resembles those thin , drawn-out clouds in front of the moon on creepy fall nights .  the mouthfeel was flat leaving a watery feel in the mouth .

a- this one pouts out a pretty dark brown colored body with ruby red highlights that can be seen when it is held up to a light . a rather large head of khaki colored bubbles forms on top and sticks around for a while .  that being said i want to keep track of beers i have tried and will start to try reviewing beers i drink ) from a sampler pack found at specs liquor . tastes flat to me . no alcohol taste that i can tell of and not a whole lot of flavor . goes down easy and not much of an aftertaste .

tall , nearly white head with good retention and great lacing .  it 's piercing , almost . the nose lands itself squarely on the tongue , unadulterated . what you are left with is a diminished , pale , watery finish . this , fortunately , leads to high quaffability .

pours a translucent medium copper with some awesome bubbling and a thick doughy head .  feels thin and watery on the tongue with a low level of carbonation . bitterness is harsh and detracts from drinkability , mouthfeel is unsatisfying , and the flavors are n't interesting and complex enough to yield repeated enjoyment .

this pours a beautiful black with a one finger tan head with incredible retention and good lace .  very little mouthfeel , this beer is meant to be drank ice cold as implied with the cold indicator on the can unlike most beers that i drink .

plenty of bubbles could be observed rising through the body , in short , it looked great ! the head produced somegood laceing as the beer was consumed .  m : this feels fairly thin ; the flavors fall quickly off the tongue , resulting in a watery finish .

a : forms a nice 1.5 finger frothy head in my sa perfect pint glass with very good retention . it 's a crystal clear beer with varying colors , being auburn orange at the thinner parts and ruby red at the thicker , and a good amount of bubbles floating up from the etch at the bottom . perfect appearance at least .  mouthfeel : lacking . too light for the style .
looks very lively . this looks amazing and out of control .  very thin feel , little oily .
pours a deep deep dark brown with a monumental rocky khaki head ... . beautiful .  m - slick and watery .
it 's a hazy orange-red-brown with a 2 finger head of foam . a great looking brew .  very watery .

this is an impressive looking belgian , from a 355 ml bottle it pours a deep hazy apricot colour with a great deal of carbonation action , and a massive creamy head that gets chunky on the pour , rises above the rim of my chalice glass and holds its form . solid lacing down the side of the glass .  mouthfeel was light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

bought this one on a whim , the fz album cover made it too good to pass up . beer advocate describes this as a doppelbock . ) poured a beautishus deep copper , malty nose , and nice lacing as i emptied the glass .  it was flat on the tongue and mouthfeel was very weak .

poured a one finger white head that had good retention and lacing . the beer is a nice amber-orange color and is very clear .  the sweetness died out in the taste , however , which was flat and slightly watered-down . a weird bitterness gave an unpleasant mouthfeel but still not difficult to drink .
motor oil black with a head like you would see on a rootbeer float .  m - too thin , light body , fizzy carbonation . the mouthfeel on this beer is no good .
sharp , slightly tannic porter that pours a deep dark ruby-brown with minimal head .  m - the downfall of this beer . carbonation is way to high , almost makes the beer feel fuzzy .

poured into pints : appearance : pours a deep rusted brown and is cloudy with an immense 2 1/2 finger , off-white , foamy head that fades and retains at a skim .  mf : thin bodied and only moderate carbonation makes this beer a bit too watery .
pretty good lacing , and , overall , a stellar appearance . however , appearance is n't everything .  palate is watery with that adjuncty grain flavor , but not too offensive . easy drinking .
looks fantastic and inviting .  i thought that the mouthfeel was kind of watered down ... it needed more `` oommff '' .

my first `` imperial pilsner '' a- a very clear rich golden , maybe slight orange . well formed fluffy white head builds on top , a thin layer sticks around .  carbonation is minimal , almost flat . again understanding its aged but this beer is pretty sweet and without some degree of carbonation to clear out the palette at the end it becomes cloying .

448th review on ba bottle to snifter 750 ml c/c batch 2 2011-2 best by : 1/2013 bottle # 9711 app- a gorgeous garnet red with a huge two finger head . puddles sit on top of this brew .  medium body , almost non existent carbonation , sweet sticky syrupy mouthfeel . i think the lack of carbonation ruins the mouthfeel and makes this taste and smell overly sweet .

beautiful looking beer to be sure , dark , dark brown with a very attractive frothy tan head . just looks so good in the glass .  this is a drinkable brew that definatly packs a punch , but it 's kind of one dimensional and thin .
bottle , a : pours yellow-orange , with a very long-lasting white head , great lacing .  carbonation is too high .
great clarity , very active , amber color , with a finger of bubbly off white head that fades gradually .  the mouthfeel is way thin , but drinkability is ok .
crispy , clear , & vibrantly gold . an inch of thinning egg white froth .  flavor is good and somewhat spicy , but fades too quickly because body is too thin and watery .

750 ml bottle , procured at the pacific park market in aliso , a : pours a pretty much opaque burnt orange . huge frothy white head from the bottle conditioning , leaving lots of lace .  carbonation is way too strong .

almost one-finger of fluffy dark brown head over an almost perfectly clear orange-brown liquid .  the malt is lightly roasted , but mild with candisugar and syrupy cane sugar . add to that the thin body caused by a lot of sugar and it will add up to a c for me .

a-pours a dark copper color with two and a half fingers of off-white , dense head . d-very confused by this one ; everything about this beer , besides color , screams porter to me , not marzen .  m - watery . too thin , especially for a beer so strong , and meant to be malt-forward .

long trail ale poured copper ; clean & clear , topped by a nice , tall , dense white head .  cloying , sticky raspberry and malty sweetness combine with a major lack of carbonation and a very thin body to achieve complete unbalane in my opinion .
bottle poured into a glass a : a rich and frothy off white head with great lacing and retention .  it 's drinkable , but the body and carbonation are really lacking .

this poured out a rich golden color with a lovely red-orange glow that danced reflective light off my fingertips . a rush of tiny bubbles formed a thick white head that dissipated at an average pace , leaving foamy crystals that clung to the sides of my tulip glass . superb !  taste is that of a standard belgian wit , but the body was off-puttingly thin . it was watered down , far too light for my tastes of wit beers .
pours a clear deep red-brown with a big white head .  slightly watery body and bland carbonation .

pours black with virtually no light around the edges . towering cap of light brown foam that grew on the pour like one of those ash-growing snake things from a fireworks stand . retention is great , as is the lacing .  mouthfeel is very light and watery and it has a similar taste as many other bmc beers , however it does have some light maltiness to it that most macro lagers lack .

poured into my delirium tremens tulip . a : pours a slightly cloudy amber/copper color with 3 huge fingers of head that fade very slowly leaving tons of sticky lacing behind .  i really like a strong flavor from my beer ... or food for that matter m : watery . with the cloudy , opaque look of this stuff i was expecting ( and hoping for ) a little creamier or more substantial mouthfeel .
pours a promising nearly opaque with a brown creamy head .  this beer is incredibly watery and light on the palate .

a freind brought this brew over ... a : perfect look for a belgian ale . deep dark ruby color like an iced tea .  mouthfeel is lacking as was expected . all in all this one is a step above the macro light brews .

16 ounce can , best by sept. 29 , 2011 . pours extremely hazy orange amber color with a 1 finger fairly dense off white head with good retention that reduces to a thin lacing cap that lasts .  mouthfeel 2/5 mouthfeel got too watery as the beer warmed .

a - pours a dark , cloudy copper with an amazing two finger light brown head . the head on this beer was huge and crated with never ending retention and thick , gooey lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .
with that said ... nice look . chestnut brown , reddish tones . good , soft , dense head .  but the overall mouthfeel is unbalanced , with simply too much fizz against a generally thin texture .

from tower liquor a - a deep reddish-copper pour , slightly hazy , with a great fluffy , off-white head with good retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is confusing as it feels too thin for the amount of sweetness on the taste buds .
found this one at julios randomly ... a : awesome look .  thin and tingly mouthfeel .
multilayered rings everywhere - one of the best lace patterns i 've seen from a beer in a long while .  seemed flat and had a flat taste .
one of the best looking beers i 've seen , almost black with a creamy head that stays for a good while .  biting carbonation , was that a hint of roastiness ?
it poured the dark copper of an old penny with a massive creamy tan head .  chocolately , dark . dry chalky taste , sweet . some warming . watery porter-like .

appearance - black with murky auburn brown edges . nice semi tan head with great retention and lacing . super sticky on the sides , just beautiful .  taste : carbonated water , with hops and light malt thrown in . mouthfeel : light and quickly fading .
another beer from the sam adams mix six pack , black lager pours a deep ruby red black with a light brown head .  mouthfeel very flat for a belgian dubbel .

poured lighter than i was expecting for whatever reason - i somehow put strong and dark together . a shimmering gold , with a great and sticky foam head . looks wonderful .  mouthfeel is kind of thin and not very pleasant as the carbonation dies down and leaves a sort of flat cola sensation , without the stickiness .
appearance- dark brown almost black with tan head with decent lacing .  m - maybe i 've had too many rises recently , but this is thin , very very thin .
pours a deep golden yellow with an inch or so of resilient white foam . offers good retention and sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and a bit watery .

pours a deliciously cloudy , rich red with a nice thick & dark tan head .  mouthfeel : this is where the beer went south for me . the carbonation was almost non-existent , which was in stark contrast to the initial appearance .

nice head , rocky and just off-white . great lacing .  nose : it 's aroma is a little bit malty , a little bit citrusy flavor : the taste has some lemon/citrus notes w/ some hints of maltiness , but the big thing that you notice is how fizzy this beer is . it 's far too fizzy for me .

initially there was an encouraging fresh sugary smell when opened and it poured an appealing crystal brown colour with orangish highlights . big one inch plus thick head .  mouthfeel : way too carbonated .
) pours a beautiful glowing , hazy , golden color . really gorgeous and appealing appearance .  almost watery .
the imperial stout was very black in color with a dark brown head . very pretty .  thin and watery for a dark beer . little carbonation . needless to say , i was disapointed in this beer .
perfect deep burgundy in color with a large , creamy and dense head of light tan foam .  m : watery , high carbonation .

12 oz bottle into pilsner glass a : beautiful ! crystal clear yellow body topped off by one inch of white creamy foam .  it does bring vanilla to mind . the sweetness almost removes it from the style of beer . far to thin for a brown ale .

a - very dark murky brown pour , extremely large ( 4-finger ) head . really beautiful .  the mouthfeel is the downfall , it is watery with a dry finish , it just does n't convey the flavors to the tongue well enough .

it pours midnight black with a huge , dark coffee-with-milk mead that does n't die easily and when it does , it leaves lacing thicker than most beers have head .  the herbal hops will become medicinal with traces of alluminum and will become a bit less appealing as it goes from a zippy feel to rather stagnent . a flat and bitter hop flavor is the finish .

the appearence is exceptional . pours a stout lovers favorite color , motor oil black . less than a finger of head , but it is a very dark brown .  far too thin and light for a bock . carbonation was assertive , but the body just felt thin and watery .
pours a beautiful deep dark brown with a nice big everlasting tan head .  however , extremely thin for a beer , and not very carbonated either .

head is 2 fingers with very good retention eventually settling to a crown producing excellent lacing s- aroma does n't five much away .  mouthfeel is extremely thin- it felt like a porter rather than an ris .

it 's unfortunate that such an incredible looking beer would have so little else working for it . appearance - dark , brooding .  mouthfeel is flat and thin . medium bodied and watery in texture , this brew falls short of anything special on the palate .
a- looks awesome . pours a crytal clear light brassy orange , with a massive white oamy , fluffy head that slowly shrinks down leaving behind all kinds of webbing lace .  tingly , thin watery feel .
it is a beautiful orange/amber with a nice head .  mouthfeel was poor .

pours a thick , dense black with not so much as brown on the edges and a deep , thick tan head that rises above the lip of my snifter . this is as good of looking a stout as you will ever see . the head slowly recedes into a nice cream capping the beer leaving some nice lacing .  mouthfeel : the carbonation is very high , way too high , for a milk stout . the body is thin . drinkability : just an ok beer , the mouthfeel also hurts the drinkability .
poured into a pint glass , dark as midnight , one finger head ( dark clay in color ) that stuck around for the duration of the beer .  mouthfeel is very thin and weak .

a big frothy tan foam sits atop the brown liquid . reddish hues appear when held to the light , along some clarity . very nice .  the weak malt presence and light flavor really hasnt enough oomph to fire up the taste buds . this one lacks that definitive crisp and bitter roastiness of the traditional dry stout . or watering their beers down ? actually , this wasnt that bad - light , thin and watered down , but not terrible .

a - poured completely ink black . appears thick and viscous . a small amount of light brown head formed and receded quickly .  mouthfeel is all wrong . way too much carbonation and way too thin of a body .
pours a beautiful golden color with thick , frothy guinness-like white head .  the mouthfeel was a bit thin and watery .

there is something hypnotic about watching the beer cascade into a jet black liquid with a wonderful tan thick creamy head . to me , the head on this is the best of almost any beer , and has a unique look .  m : mild , almost weak or watery . does not have stout presence at all ; feels like flat cola , if anything .

pours a very deep brown from a 550ml bottle with a two finger head that retains . it 's opaque and pushes pitch black .  mouthfeel - super watery overall - the only thing this beer has going for it is the aroma which is misleading .
this beer was very dark and had a creamy head that lasted a long time .  as many others have said , i 'm not liking the extra carbonation .

dark golden yellow . thickish head . excellent lacing .  taste : decidedly like its nose , only more so ; large notes of bittersweet chocolate and espresso rule the roost , here ; not nearly as sweet as you might imagine ; total lack of carbonation left the impression of a somewhat light , thin mouthfeel .
looks great on a goblet . amazing retention and lacing .  it is very thin like any us macro , making it very drinkable like water .

slow pour with not alot of head . incredible color . just beautiful dark ruby . the sun shined through it and it almost looks like a red wine .  `` simple '' is the best word i can use to describe the taste , but it does deliver with scorched malts with a touch of lactose . my biggest complaint with this beer is the mouthfeel- it 's way too watery .

a : the beer is a medium orange in color with a 2 finger fluffy white head that has excellent retention and lacing . the beer has minimal haziness to it and is nearly 100 % translucent s : citrusy hops abound on the nose .  slightly watery body with adequate carbonation . mouthfeel is slick and thin with a metallic and astringent finish as it dries .

yeti pours out like the darkest of used motor oils , thick and smooth with a monstrous billowing head that never goes away .  heard great things about this , found it in buffalo bought a 96 vintage.started promising i liked the color and the nice head , after that all downhill.had little to no smell , the taste was peppery ( overpoweringly so ) and way to sour ! the beer was way to thin and watery to go along with that taste.didnt finish the bottle just to peppery and thin for me , waiste of six bucks .

pours a very clear budweiser gold , with a fluffy white head . in a big glass mug it actually looks refreshing . the can looks pretty cool .  the flavor echoes the aroma , but the mouthfeel is n't quite up to scratch - weirdly thin and watery , which does no favors to the toasty , nutty , tea-like , and hoppy notes that are all individually assertive but harmonious and balanced in tandem , like a good jazz band .

this beer pours a semi-cloudy pale orange color . the head is an impressive two and a half inches in height , and recedes very slowly into thick , chunky lacing .  thin mouthfeel with average macro carbonation . touch of caustic mouthfeel in the middle with the bitterness and petrol notes .

appearance = ridiculous amount of head - like 5 to 6 inches of thick milky white froth and foam . looks pretty darn good ; i just need this one to settle .  the mouthfeel needs work . it is n't creamy at all , it is just really watery and lacking carbonation .

pours a clear dark brown with superior side lacing and a copious tan head with very good retention . appearance is exceptional .  mouthfeel : thin and watery body , medium carbonation overall : highly overrated .

on tap @ varga bar look : deep ruby/brown color , creamy tan head with decent retention & lacing smell : malt , caramel taste : malt , brown sugar from beginning to end mouthfeel : medium body & carbonation , sticky drinkability : light flavors make this a good session beer overall impression : not as flavorful or as complex as the better german examples , but still a good local beer worth sampling .  fizzy carbonation and no body .

poured a hazy golden yellow with a three finger white head that remained throughout the glass and even continued to grow if left to sit for long . insane ! maintained phenomenal lacing throughout the glass . first off , the appearance on this one was ridiculous for the style .  mouthfeel is very watery w/ average crabonation .

22 oz bomber pours copper to orange with a 4 fingers+ offwhite head with effervesence . great lacing & head retention s : fruit & oak-like notes taste : apricot & oakey notes up front .  t- vanilla/cream soda , one-dimensional caramel malt . very vanilla . m- mouth is unrefined and rough in the way i would expect from good ol bmc . sweetness lingers in an unpleasant and sticky way .
appearance : pours a deep copper body with a lush , creamy-looking white head .  m- thin and watery this could be improved greatly , but then it would probably be too sweet .

this one turns from a flurry of cascading cream colored bubbles into a light coppery hue and makes a really thick and fluffy , dense , cream colored head .  the first part of the taste it quite strong and somewhat acidic but as you move to the middle and rear of your mouth the beer becomes very thin .

pours a very dark brown , black in the glass , with a nice tan head that maintains down the glass . excellent rings of lacing .  for a russian imperial this is even for 9.7 incredibly weak and watery it 's the first thing i notice . the mouthfeel on this is not good , it 's even weaker than most american stouts i 've had .

a- amazing head retention on the big , white head that is very sticky ; body is gold body with red tints .  it 's also crisp . for a beer that looked so terrible ( albeit , it was dark ) and had such a poor mouthfeel , it sure tasted good .

pours a very dark brown with a nice frothy one finger of off white head that sticks around a while .  carbonation appears low . beer is thin and boring , not much there at all . mild sweetness very water like . bummer .
the beer looks very nice . shows great retention and lacing .  it was very thin bodied as well .

draft at teresa 's in wayne , pa pours a very dark brown with foamy tan head that forms a lacing that lasts throught the whole glass .  m surprisingly watery for the body ; slightly carbonated with a light , watery finish . my major complaint is with the mouthfeel , the watery texture really detracts from its drinkability in my book .
poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glas 2 inch off white head on top of a deep coppery garnet , modestly carbonated .  mouthfeel is flat but this is the only disappointment .
pours bright copper with a lasting , creamy off-white head that leaves plenty of rings of lacing on the glass .  mf : too smooth and wet . watery even , but not creamy .
served in a wheat beer glass . beer is yellow and hazy , forms a big white head of small and medium bubbles that leaves some lacing on the glass . looks good .  the palate is thin .
